<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-ANightOut     06-02 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-A Night Out,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans Treated To A Night On The Town, Moscow Style</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagans did up the town, Moscow-style, on
their last night here, taking in the ballet at the opulent Bolshoi
Theater, dining with the Gorbachevs at a dacha owned by the
Communist Party and strolling through a moonlit Red Square.
   With summit business over, President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev seemed in good spirits Wednesday night, moving
their seats closer together in the ``Royal Box'' the Soviet and
American first couples shared at the Bolshoi and briefly clasping
one another's waists as they left the ballet.
   But their wives, who ruffled one another's feathers earlier in
the day during a visit to Moscow's Tretyakov Gallery, appeared cool
to one another and did not speak.
   After their private dinner at the Communist Party-owned country
home on the outskirts of western Moscow, the Reagans, holding
hands, made an impromptu stop at Red Square, walking on the
cobblestone plaza between St. Basil's Cathedral and the Kremlin.
   Reagan described his Soviet evening on the town as ``wonderful
... very warm and hospitable.''
   He said the couple stopped at Red Square ``because Nancy hasn't
seen it. We're leaving tomorrow and I didn't want her to miss it.''
   The Reagans leave this morning for London, where they will spend
a day before returning Friday to Washington.
   In the six-tiered, gold and red Bolshoi on Sverdlov Square, the
audience of about 2,000, most of them Soviets, applauded the
Reagans and the Gorbachevs both at the ballet's beginning and again
at its end. The dancers also ended their performance by clapping
for the leaders and their wives.
   Reagan and Gorbachev waved back at the audience, both grinning
broadly.
   The Reagans appeared to enjoy the hour and a half of ballet. It
was the first night of pure entertainment on their schedule, which
had previously included official dinners complete with political
toasts and journalists.
   But even the last evening included a touch of patriotism.
American and Soviet flags hung on either side of the ``Royal Box''
at the rear of the theater, and the orchestra played national
anthems from both countries before the ballet began.
   Reagan mouthed the words of the American anthem while Nancy
Reagan held her right hand at her heart.
   The Reagans and Raisa Gorbachev used opera glasses to watch the
Bolshoi Ballet perform excerpts from ``Sleeping Beauty,'' ``Swan
Lake'' and ``Romeo and Juliet.'' The last excerpt was performed by
Nine Ananiashvili and Andris Liepa, winners of a 1986 world ballet
competition in Jackson, Miss.
   The Bolshoi Theater, founded in 1776, was the first permanent
theater in Moscow, and its ballet and opera companies gained an
international reputation in the 1950s and 1960s.
   Tickets cost about three rubles (five dollars) but are nearly
impossible for Soviets to obtain without contacts in the theater or
luck enough to receive an allocation at their jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
