<1ST_LINE>r i PM-US-SovietBaseball     06-02 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet Baseball,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yanks Beat Reds, 15-2, in Historic Baseball Matchup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN FRIEDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a match marked more by good will than athletic
prowess, Johns Hopkins University capitalized on eight errors by a
team of Soviet engineers to take a 15-2 victory in the first
baseball showdown between the superpowers.
   Before the historic game, played at the Lenin Komsomol
Automobile Factory stadium, the Johns Hopkins team presented the
Soviets with souvenir T-shirts, and both sides clasped hands and
hugged as Western reporters in town for the summit meeting crowded
around. President Reagan, busy elsewhere, was unable to throw out
the first pitch.
   A public address announcer chattered away about the rules of
baseball, even during play, to a crowd just learning about the
sport. But the 300 or so fans still seemed to enjoy the game,
cheering lustily when the Soviet team from the D.I. Mendeleyev
Institute of Chemical Engineering did well and whistling in
derision when it botched a play.
   Johns Hopkins struck immediately in the first inning when
leadoff batter Tom Finegan doubled off the left field fence and
scored on two successive wild pitches by Alexei Koshivoy.
   The Blue Jays put the game out of reach in the third inning,
while leading 2-0, when first baseman Dan Durocher walked, advanced
to second on a Koshivoy wild pitch and scored on a single by second
baseman Andy Bernstein.
   After two successive errors loaded the bases, third baseman John
Horner hit a drive that eluded centerfielder Alexander
Krupenchenkov and Horner came all the way home to make the score
7-0.
   The Soviets didn't get a base runner until the fourth inning and
scored their runs in the fifth and seventh innings on errant
pickoff attempts.
   ``It was not our best game,'' said Leonid Korneyev, the Soviets'
third baseman.
   The Soviet Union began its baseball program in 1987, in
anticipation of baseball becoming an Olympic sport in 1992. A
national squad played a team from Nicaragua last summer, but lost
by scores of 22-0 and 30-2.
   Earlier this week, the Johns Hopkins players spent several
practice sessions teaching the Soviets the finer points of the
game, and although the Blue Jays praised their competitors' desire
and athletic abilities, they expected the game to be a bit of a
mismatch.
   ``They made some outstanding plays out there,'' said Johns
Hopkins Coach Bob Babb. ``But they still have problems with routine
ones.''
   Finegan, a senior from Garden City, N.Y., praised the Soviets'
athletic ability, but noted that ``baseball is a unique sport. You
need to have skills that are more refined. They also have not seen
pitchers that are more refined.''
   Johns Hopkins alumnus Max Flaxman, a Moscow-based businessman,
was responsible for bringing the Soviets together with the Blue
Jays, who had a 26-12 record this year. He had heard the Soviets
were seeking an American squad for some exhibition games, and
suggested the Johns Hopkins team.
   The Soviet media publicized the game, and several newspapers ran
stories that caught the spirit of good will.
   A front-page article in Tuesday's editions of the newspaper
Sovietsky Sport carried the headline: ``When the score doesn't
count.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
