<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-NoSecrets     06-02 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-No Secrets,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Agents Show Off Limos, Pool Guesses on Reagan Departure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>USOVO, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Music poured from the front-seat tape
deck. Anatoly Kalinin snapped his fingers to the beat, and his
friends passed around cigarettes and pictures of their wives for
the visiting Americans to see.
   This wasn't an impromptu gathering of youth on the Arbat
pedestrian mall, but an assemblage of the usually staid gray-suited
security agents who guard Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Relaxing during a two-and-a-half hour wait for President Reagan
and his wife to finish dinner at a Communist Party-owned dacha
outside Moscow, a dozen security men bantered with their American
counterparts, showing off the Zil limousines they travel in and
joining in an American betting pool on when the Reagans would
emerge from the walled compound.
   ``At exactly 12 midnight!'' contended an agent identified only
as Yevgeny, arguing with an American agent who insisted that Reagan
never stays out that late.
   ``I'm not just taking a guess, I'm providing you with
information,'' Yevgeny stated knowingly.
   The American stuck by his 11 p.m. estimate, challenging, ``We'll
see whose intelligence is better.''
   Some of the security detachment had accompanied Gorbachev to
Washington in December, but the agents who had never seen America
showed the most curiosity about life in the other superpower. They
compared housing costs, divorce rates and the vastly different
attitudes toward smoking in their countries.
   The Zil tour was impressive for the journalists, who acted as
translators between the security squads. The sleek black limos are
usually seen flashing past at 60 miles per hour on the broad avenue
that leads from this parklike estate to the Kremlin.
   ``This costs 100,000 rubles ($167,000 at the official exchange
rate) here,'' one of the Soviets offered with an aim to impress
that would rival any car salesman. ``It's got genuine Karelian
birchwood lining on the doors and all around the windows.''
   One of the Americans, who did not want to be identified, said
that the Soviets were a little tense on the first day of Reagan's
visit, but that the two groups quickly became accustomed to working
together on their nearly identical tasks of protecting the leader.
   ``Discipline is discipline and surveillance is surveillance,''
Yevgeny explained, when asked how the two teams worked together.
   The nattily dressed agents from both superpowers took turns
posing for souvenir pictures.
   Floodlights blinked and a telephone call to the guard shack
outside the compound at 10:40 p.m. alerted both teams to the
presidential party's intended departure, causing moans from the
bettors who had guessed the party would break up later.
   The agents instantly snapped to attention, with the Soviets
diving into the limousines and escort cars and the Americans
climbing into their wagons.
   The entourage got back to business so quickly that the head of
the American security detachment had no chance to collect his bet
winnings. His guess of 11 p.m. was only six seconds off the mark.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nancy     06-02 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nancy,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Reagan `Rolls With Punches' In Uncertainties Of Raisa
Relationship</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan has ``learned to roll with the
punches'' when dealing with the uncertainties of meeting Raisa
Gorbachev and has achieved more balance in their relationship, the
first lady's spokeswoman says.
   The clear impression left after the two strong-willed women
squared off in a Soviet art gallery Wednesday was that Mrs. Reagan
has become far more assertive in dealing with the outspoken Soviet
first lady.
   President Reagan and his wife fly to London today after wrapping
up their summit activities here with a farewell visit to the
Kremlin and a meeting with U.S. Embassy employees. They return home
Friday after the London stopover.
   For the first time, Mrs. Reagan acknowledged during a tour of
the Tretyakov Gallery's icons that the frosty relationship, the
focus of months of intense media scrutiny, is real.
   ``A Mexican standoff,'' the first lady said with a shrug, when
asked how the relationship stood.
   Elaine Crispen, the first lady's press secretary, later
observed, ``They are from two totally different worlds.''
   Under a veneer of politeness, the two first ladies engaged in an
intense competition for the spotlight.
   ``I want to say something. I want to say something now, OK?''
Mrs. Reagan insisted sharply one point as Mrs. Gorbachev attempted
to stop reporters from questioning the American first lady.
   Mrs. Gorbachev backed away, but pointedly looked at her watch as
the first lady chatted with members of the White House press corps.
   When Mrs. Gorbachev tried to break in again and start the
gallery tour, Mrs. Reagan rebuffed her and returned to her
conversation with reporters.
   On the surface, things were pleasant enough, but the delicately
arched eyebrows and strained smiles told a far different story.
   Instead of strolling hand-in-hand as they had at events earlier
this week, the two women apparently had decided to show more of
their true feelings.
   It brought to mind a similar encounter during the December
summit in Washington, when Mrs. Gorbachev dominated a White House
tour by seeking out the press with lengthy commentaries on history,
art and political life, as Mrs. Reagan was left trying to get her
long-planned tour under way.
   During Wednesday's session with reporters, Mrs. Gorbachev and
her Soviet aides kept changing the arrangements for the event,
White House aides said.
   Instead of meeting Mrs. Reagan as planned by the outside door of
the gallery, Mrs. Gorbachev had come to the special vault where
they were to view the art and talked at length with the press corps.
   Mrs. Reagan has learned to be flexible with the Soviets at Mrs.
Gorbachev's events, Mrs. Crispen said.
   ``She's learned to roll with the punches,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   Noting that Mrs. Reagan has spoken out more in Moscow than she
did at the December summit, Mrs. Crispen said she believed they now
had ``more balance'' and equality in their relationship.
   Not surprisingly, the first lady said that her five days of
exposure to the glories of Russian art and architecture won't
change her mind about the Soviet system.
   ``We have two different ways of living, two different
philosophies,'' she said. One day earlier, Mrs. Reagan had termed
the Soviet system a ``more controlled'' society than the United
States.
   Asked if she'd become a convert to communism during her stay
here, the first lady gave a hearty laugh, saying, ``Oh, no!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
