<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Refuseniks     06-02 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Refuseniks,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomatic Sources Say 28 Refusenik Cases Unresolved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Western diplomatic source says 28 refusenik
cases have not been resolved, contrary to information from Soviet
Jewish leaders that the cases were cleared for emigration as a
result of meetings between U.S. and Soviet officials.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Jewish
leaders had evidently misunderstood the situation.
   The confusion arose over a meeting between Assistant Secretary
of State Richard Schifter and a group of six refuseniks Wednesday
morning.
   Refusenik scientist Yuli Kosharovsky showed reporters a list of
400 names that he said had been submitted to Schifter on Saturday
for discussion with Soviet officials at meetings during the Moscow
summit.
   He said Schifter told the group that 28 of the cases had been
solved in the meetings taking place during the Moscow summit
between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   But the Western diplomatic source said later that no cases had
been solved.
   Other refusenik sources said more than a dozen families from
Moscow, Leningrad and Kiev had received permission to emigrate in
the past 10 days.
   Moscow refusenik Bella Gulko said the Boris Weinshtock and Iosif
Pilmenshtein families of Moscow had received permission to emigrate
this week.
   Refusenik Sergei Mkrtchyan, who demonstrated daily in downtown
Moscow with his wife and year-old daughter last week, said he was
summoned to the Moscow visa office on Saturday and was told he
could leave the country on Monday.
   Mkrtchyan said he knew of three Kiev families who also had
received permission to leave the country.
   About 40 other refuseniks, many of them accompanied by their
children, held a peaceful, half-hour demonstration Wednesday within
sight of the Kremlin, waving banners demanding that they be allowed
to emigrate.
   An agency helping Jewish emigres said in Geneva on Wednesday
that the number allowed to leave the Soviet Union reached 1,145 in
May, a seven-year high.
   The May figure was the fourth straight monthly increase and
brought the total for 1988 to 4,547, said the Intergovernmental
Committee for Migration.
   More than 8,000 Jews were permitted to emigrate in 1987, a sharp
increase from previous years but far below the peak of more than
51,000 in 1979.
</TEXT>
