<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Reagan-Thatcher Bjt   06-02 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Thatcher, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's First Post-Summit Stop: A Call on a Close Friend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The relationship has never been more special. So
it is only natural that President Reagan is visiting Margaret
Thatcher, his ideological soulmate and closest foreign ally, to
tell her about the Moscow summit.
   Reagan's two-day visit, another boost to the British prime
minister's prestige on the international stage, comes six months
after Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev stopped off to confer with
her en route to the Washington superpower summit.
   Today's is Reagan's third and probably last visit as president
to a prime minister of whom he said recently, ``We're very good
friends and it is a friendship I treasure very much.''
   He will confer with Mrs. Thatcher at her No. 10 Downing St.
residence, dine there tonight and make a speech Friday on East-West
relations before returning home.
   For Reagan, the British Conservative Party leader has been a
sometimes costly, occasionally reproving but super-loyal friend.
She rarely criticizes him.
   Asked in Parliament about revelations about astrology in the
White House, all she would say was: ``I come under Libra, which is
a very balanced sign.''
   The Anglo-American bond, rooted in a common language, heritage
and alliances in two world wars, is the cornerstone of her foreign
policy.
   She stood alone in backing the 1986 U.S. bombing raid on Libya;
followed Washington out of UNESCO in 1985; was the first to deploy
U.S. cruise missiles in Europe in 1983, and last year, when the
superpowers agreed to remove the missiles, she put aside her
reservations and gave the deal a ringing endorsement.
   When other European leaders in the 16-nation NATO alliance
sometimes grumble about U.S. domination, Mrs. Thatcher's response
is blunt.
   ``She's the largest, most prosperous nation in the world, and
let's be thankful she has taken a leadership role,'' Mrs. Thatcher
said in a radio interview in March. ``None of us can substitute for
it. We could all help with it.''
   Her U.S. policy draws opposition taunts of ``Reagan's poodle,''
to which she retorts: ``I don't think I would make a very good
poodle. I might be more a sort of bulldog.''
   However, some analysts see her as having subtly moved into a
prime role in NATO, using both her special influence with Reagan
and, more recently, her good relations with Gorbachev to exercise
power.
   Elected to office 18 months before Reagan and recently
re-elected for an unprecedented third consecutive term, 62-year-old
Mrs. Thatcher is the senior stateswoman of the Western world. She
shares Reagan's hostility to communism and belief in free markets.
   She fervently believes nuclear weapons are peacekeepers. After
Reagan flirted with the idea of a non-nuclear world at the 1986
summit at Reykjavik, Iceland, Mrs. Thatcher sped to Washington to
make sure he didn't carry disarmament too far _ without consulting
his allies.
   At her instigation, NATO leaders held a special summit before
Reagan's latest meeting in Moscow with Gorbachev. She said the aim
was to demonstrate Western unity and show ``that the president is
always seen consulting his NATO allies.''
   There have been some disagreements.
   In 1982, when Reagan sought to withhold U.S.-originated
technology from a Soviet natural gas pipeline, Mrs. Thatcher
ordered British companies to fulfill their contracts despite the
threat of U.S. sanctions. Reagan backed off, after Mrs. Thatcher
complained publicly she felt ``deeply wounded by a friend.''
   A year later, Mrs. Thatcher criticized the U.S.-led invasion of
Grenada to overthrow Marxist coup leaders in the former British
colony, saying ``You just don't walk into countries like that.''
   More recently, she has chided the United States about its budget
deficit, making disapproving comparisons with her own stringent
policies which have produced a budget surplus.
   But she has never shied away from backing the United States in a
crisis, even when it has left her isolated.
   She says she has never forgotten that Reagan put his entire
Latin American policy at risk to support Britain in the 1982
Falkland Islands war against Argentina.
   In April 1986 she braved uproar in Parliament for allowing
Washington to use British-based bombers in the raid on Libya, when
other European allies had refused to help.
   She declared, ``I believe friendship is two ways.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
