<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WeatherRadar     06-02 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weather Radar,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Radars Will Sharpen America's Weather Eye</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America will turn a sharper eye to the weather
in the next few years with the installation of a snazzy new radar
system jointly funded by a quartet of federal agencies.
   The new radar will allow meteorologists, for the first time, to
see the formation of tornadoes before they reach the ground. They
also will be better able to pinpoint the landing site of
hurricanes, predict floods and measure the flow of wind, weather
scientists say.
   The first Next Generation Weather Radar installation is under
way at Norman, Okla., with as many as 175 to follow by the
mid-1990s, officials of Unisys, the private company building the
system, reported Wednesday.
   The National Weather Service, Federal Aviation Administration,
Air Force Air Weather Service and Naval Oceanographic Office are
anteing up $450 million for the new system, dubbed NEXRAD.
   Under development for eight years, the first system was tested
at a Unisys facility in Connecticut before the Oklahoma
installation, expected to be operational in thefall.
   Oklahoma, one of the nation's leading areas for tornadoes, will
test the new radar's ``unique capability to identify rotating wind
patterns within storms,'' according to Kurt Merl of Unisys.
   While current radar detects only the amount of moisture in the
air, the new one can follow its movement.
   Thus, an operator seeing wind rushing away from him, right next
to a severe gust heading toward him, will recognize the signature
of a rotating movement, the first sign of tornado development, said
Les Lemon, a former National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
researcher now directing the radar development program for Unisys.
   Radar tests have shown that movement can be seen in mid-level
clouds, before the twister reaches down for the ground. This means
warning time could be expanded to ``tens of minutes,'' Lemon said.
   Currently the National Weather Service issues a tornado watch
when conditions exist which could spawn a tornado, but ground
spotters have to spot the tornadoes to issue actual warnings.
   The new system could cut false alarms in half, Lemon added.
   NEXRAD will replace a 30-year-old radar system that provides
only limited weather data.
   Merl said the NEXRAD installations also will be coupled with
on-ground rain gauges to measure precipitation for forecast areas
where flooding is likely, a system that should improve warnings in
flood-prone areas.
   In addition, Lemon noted that the system will be able to measure
the winds within hurricanes within its 145-mile range.
   With that information, meteorologists will be better able to
predict the course of hurricanes to give warnings about where they
will strike land, and also to estimate the wind and surge of sea
water being pushed ahead of the storm.
   The system's 28-foot radar dish, enclosed in a fiberglass dome,
draws a profile of the air from the surface up to 70,000 feet every
six minutes, Lemon explained, providing detailed information even
in clear air. Many radars cannot detect clear air movement, only
air with water vapor or dust or some other debris to reflect the
signal.
   The radar uses the Doppler effect, which depends on a change in
frequency in a radio wave. The pencil-thin wave is sent out at a
constant frequency, and bounces back off clouds, moving air, dust
or whatever it strikes. There is a subtle change of frequency in
signals bouncing off something coming toward the radar compared to
things moving away.
   It's the same principle that causes a police or ambulance siren
to have a slightly lower pitch when the vehicle is driving away
from listeners than it does when coming toward them.
   Merl also said research is under way for short-range Doppler
radar systems at airports to detect local wind shears, sudden
shifts in wind speed and direction that have caused several
airplane crashes in recent years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
