<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OliverNorth     06-02 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oliver North,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Marine Stumps for California GOP Congressional Hopeful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North brought his unabashedly
patriotic message to California on Wednesday, lending his
conservative star status to the congressional campaign of an old
White House buddy.
   North, the former Marine lieutenant colonel who faces federal
conspiracy charges for his role in the Iran-Contra affair, sounded
themes of freedom, military might and family values in urging
election of conservative Republican Dana Rohrabacher to the state's
42nd Congressional District.
   ``Freedom is not free, it must be won, preserved and defended,
again and again,'' North told a cheering crowd of about 100 at a
late-morning rally at a hangar at Long Beach Airport.
   He urged voters to return a conservative majority to Congress
that will support continued military spending, saying, ``Freedom is
only as strong as its defenders.''
   North, sporting his trademark crew cut and gap-toothed grin and
attired in a civilian gray suit, ignored about a dozen sign-toting
protesters who shouted at him as left the hangar and got into a
waiting car.
   was making his first campaign appearance ever and his second
formal public speech since the Iran-Contra hearings, said
   Rohrabacher spokesman Robert Rule said North was to attend
fund-raisers for Rohrabacher in Los Angeles and Pasadena, then
address a $250-a-person dinner for Rohrabacher at the Spruce Goose.
   Participants were invited to donate $1,000 to attend a reception
next door on the ocean liner Queen Mary and have a picture taken
with North.
   He was set to spend Thursday campaigning for Christopher Cox, a
candidate in the 40th Congressional District Republican primary.
Cox, 35, of Newport Beach, was senior associate counsel for
President Reagan from 1986 to this year, when he resigned to seek
election.
   The front-runner in the crowded 42nd District race, Orange
County supervisor Harriet Wieder, denounced North's visit as a
``mercenary'' effort on behalf of Rohrabacher, 40, whom North knew
as a special assistant and senior speechwriter for President Reagan
from 1981 to 1988.
   ``Rohrabacher is just snuggling up to Ollie and president,'' Ms.
Wieder said. ``What does Ollie North know about issues in this
congressional district?''
   At a news conference before North appeared Wednesday,
Rohrabacher rejected suggestions that voters might react negatively
to a man facing criminal charges. ``I think that if people in the
district consider that Ollie North is for me, maybe they should be
too,'' he said.
   The candidate said he doubted voters would object to support
from North, who was indicted by a federal grand jury on charges of
conspiracy to defraud the government for his role in selling arms
Iran and using the profits to support the Contra rebels in Marxist
Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
