<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Hurkos 1stLd-Writethru a0910 06-02 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Hurkos, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0910,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch Psychic Peter Hurkos Dead at 77</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Hurkos maintaining
Strangler's innocence, details on Manson case; picks up 6th graf:
`Hurkos reportedly ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch psychic detective Peter Hurkos, who
helped authorities seek clues in the Manson family murders and the
Boston Strangler case, died of a heart attack Wednesday, his
publicist said. He was 77.
   Hurkos, who had part of his cancerous right lung removed in
April, had just left his doctor's office when he was stricken in
the hallway of a medical complex near Cedars-Sinai Medical Center,
said publicist Barbara Silver.
   He was best known for helping authorities in the 1969 Manson
family murders of actress Sharon Tate and supermarket owner Leno
LaBianca and his wife, Rosemary.
   Hurkos reportedly told authorities the person responsible for
the murders was a bearded man named Charlie, according to ``The
Psychic World of Peter Hurkos'' by Norma Lee Browning, published in
1970.
   The book also detailed Hurkos' involvement in the Strangler case
of 1964, which later was made into a movie starring Tony Curtis.
   Hurkos refused to budge from his position that a man he picked
as the Boston Strangler was the killer and that confessed strangler
Albert DeSalvo was not, the author wrote.
   ``He was very helpful in any of the police things that he worked
on. Why did he go into it? Because he could felt that he probably
could contribute.'' Ms. Silver said.
   Hurkos reportedly became psychic in 1941 after falling from a
ladder and suffering a brain injury. On regaining consciousness, he
realized he had ``an ability to pierce the barriers that separate
the past, present and future,'' his biography states.
   Hurkos said he was able to see things by touching objects. ``I
see pictures in my mind like a television screen. When I touch
something, I can then tell what I see,'' he said.
   He made appearances on several television talk shows and
appeared in the motion pictures ``The Amazing World of Psychic
Phenomena,'' ``Mysterious Monsters,'' ``Now I Lay Me Down to
Sleep'' and ``The Boston Strangler.''
   He was the author of three books, ``Psychic,'' `The Psychic
World of Peter Hurkos'' and ``Peter Hurkos: I Have Many Lives.''
   Born in Dordrecht, Holland, he came to the United States in 1956
for psychic experiments, and lived in the Los Angeles area about 25
years.
   Surviving are his wife, Stephany Courtney; a daughter and six
children from a previous marriage.
</TEXT>
