<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LieDetectors     06-02 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lie Detectors,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Restricting Company Lie Detector Tests Clears House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation that would significantly reduce
the number of lie detector tests administered by private companies
now needs only Senate approval to go to the president for signature
into law.
   The House voted 251-120 on Wednesday in favor of the conference
report, a compromise version of differing bills passed earlier by
the two chambers. Senate approval would send the legislation to the
president.
   The Office of Technology Assessment estimated that about 2
million such tests were administered last year, and that 90 percent
were administered by private employers, mostly to job applicants
but also to workers under investigation.
   The accuracy of test results has been questioned, and so has the
competency of some examiners. Twenty-two states prohibit the tests
in the private sector, and 19 regulate their private use.
   The legislation would permit private sector testing of
applicants for only two types of jobs.
   Those applying for security guard positions could still be
tested, and so could prospective employees who would have direct
access to the manufacture, storage, distribution or sale of
controlled substances.
   The bill also has several provisions to protect the rights of
workers subject to tests.
   The bill would prohibit an employee from being discharged,
dismissed, disciplined, discriminated against, or denied employment
or promotion solely on the basis of the test, or solely for refusal
to take the test.
   To take action against the worker, an employer would have to
have additional supporting evidence.
   Questions on religious or political beliefs could not be asked,
and all questions would have to be submitted to the examinee in
writing before the examination. The examinee could end the test at
any time.
   An employer could test an employee during an investigation
involving economic loss or injury to the company.
   However, the employee would have to have had access to the
property that is the subject of the investigation, and the employer
would have to have a reasonable suspicion that the worker was
involved in the incident.
   Before the test began, the worker would have to be given
specific information about the incident under investigation.
   Only the federal government would be permitted to administer
tests to those employed by, assigned to, or detailed to the
nation's intelligence agencies and to FBI contract employees.
   Qualification standards would be set for examiners, who would
need a license granted by the state, if one was required. The
examiner also would have to maintain a $50,000 bond.
   The legislation would take effect six months after it became law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shipyards-Jobs     06-02 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shipyards-Jobs,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Forecasting Job Losses at Eight Public Shipyards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy is forecasting new job reductions at
its eight public shipyards, where employment already has dropped 9
percent since 1985.
   An unpublished naval planning document shows that the Navy is
projecting a 21 percent cutback in employment at the yards between
now and the end of fiscal 1991.
   The job figures are only estimates, and are subject to change
because of schedule shifts, new work or other factors.
   The May 11 document, obtained this week from congressional
sources, projects employment requirements based on ship repair and
modernization assignments for the 1989, 1990 and 1991 fiscal years.
The Naval Sea Systems Command document resulted from a recent ship
scheduling conference sponsored by the systems command, which
oversees the eight yards.
   Overall, employment in the yards would shrink from about 71,100
now to 64,050 in the fall of 1989. The workforce then would shrink
further to 57,150 the next year and 56,400 the year after that. The
current 71,100 figure includes about 4,000 temporary and part-time
employees.
   The systems command, in a statement in response to a reporter's
query, said the Navy has neither published employment projections
nor announced layoffs.
   ``However, shipyard employment figures are routinely reviewed
and working documents are prepared to determine what employment
levels are necessary to meet fleet operational requirements,'' the
statement said.
   ``Exact naval shipyard employment figures will not be determined
until the budget process is completed for fiscal year 1989 and
beyond,'' it said.
   The eight yards have already seen their collective workforce
trimmed by 7,000 from the 78,100 who were employed in January 1985.
The Navy said those reductions were prompted in part by a declining
number of ship overhauls.
   Some yards would see their workforce dip and then swell again,
under the projections of the May 11 document.
   For example, employment at the Puget Sound Naval Shipyard in
Bremerton, Wash., is estimated to dip from 11,400 to 8,500 by the
fall of 1990, before climbing back to 10,000 the following year.
   Puget Sound spokesman Bruce Andrae said that while he was not
familiar with the working document, the yard was ``pretty well
aware'' of its workload over the next few years.
   ``I think you'll find we're not the only shipyard where you'll
see some rather wide swings in manpower,'' Andrae said. ``You go
down for a couple of years and all of a sudden you've got to make a
dramatic increase. Skilled labor doesn't come easily, and that
presents some challenges.''
   A similar pattern was projected at the Norfolk Naval Shipyard in
Portsmouth, Va.
   Employment at Norfolk, whose 12,700 workers make it the largest
public yard, was forecast at 11,350 in the fall of 1989, 9,700 in
1990, and 10,900 in 1991.
   Employment at the Philadelphia Naval Shipyard, now at about
8,700, is projected to decline to 6,800. The yard likely would lay
off 749 temporary workers first, officials said.
   The Long Beach, Calif., shipyard would suffer the least
disruption to its workforce, with its employment remaining between
5,000 and 5,250 during the three years.
   The Mare Island yard in northern California would see its
workforce drop to 10,000 in the fall of 1989, followed by a loss of
another 3,800 workers and then a gain of 1,300 to bring it back up
to 7,500.
   Hawaii's Pearl Harbor Yard, which employs about 6,100 now, would
drop to 4,000.
   Among Eastern yards, Charleston, S.C., would go from about 8,600
to 6,200. The Portsmouth, N.H., yard would remain at about 8,000
workers until 1991, then dip to 5,800 at the end of 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UnusualBirth     06-02 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unusual Birth,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Bears Child From Frozen Embryo Conceived With Donated Egg
And Sperm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman has given birth to a healthy child
produced from a frozen embryo that was conceived in a laboratory
dish with sperm from her husband and an egg donated by her sister,
doctors said Wednesday.
   The birth in May at the University of Medicine and Dentistry of
New Jersey is believed to be the first of its kind in the Northeast
and one of 10 in the world, the doctors said.
   The procedure was used because the unidentified mother, a New
York City woman in her 30s, suffered premature ovarian failure and
was unable to become pregnant, said Dr. Cecilia Schmidt, director
of the Center for Fertility and Reproductive Technology.
   Doctors retrieved several of the sister's eggs using a new
ultrasound procedure that does not require surgery. The eggs were
fertilized in vitro with sperm from the woman's husband.
   After an initial pregnancy attempt failed, the remaining embryos
were frozen and kept at 190 degrees below zero Celsius. One embryo
was thawed three months later and implanted, producing the healthy
baby.
</TEXT>
