<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Interview     06-02 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Interview,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice President Shrugs Off Conservative Figures' Influence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said in a published
interview that two of the nation's well-known and outspoken
conservatives are fringe elements whose support isn't necessary for
victory in the presidential election.
   Bush, interviewed by The New York Times at his oceanside retreat
in Kennebunkport, Maine on Wednesday, shrugged off the influence of
Richard A. Viguerie, a writer and direct-mail specialist, and
Howard J. Phillips, head of the Conservative Caucus.
   ``There's only one or two that polarize, and Viguerie and Howie
Phillips are two of them; it doesn't matter in terms of total
vote,'' the vice president said in the interview, published in
Thursday's editions of the Times.
   ``There is only a handful of Richard Vigueries out there,'' said
Bush, the all-but certain Republican presidential nominee.
   Asked if he had to do business with Viguerie to win the
election, he said: ``I don't believe that.''
   ``The fact that he (Viguerie) doesn't agree with me on a lot of
things or has opposed me for many years, that doesn't bother me one
iota,'' said Bush. Viguerie, the vice president said, ``gets his
name in the paper by criticizing other Republicans all the time.''
   A Viguerie spokeswoman, Carolyn Melenick, said Wednesday night
that Viguerie would have no immediate comment on Bush's remarks.
Viguerie said last month that he would vote for Bush.
   Bush also told the newspaper he would be meeting soon with
Attorney General Edwin Meese. Bush said over the weekend that the
two had met recently, and Meese said he would not do anything to
harm Bush's presidential campaign.
   The attorney general is under investigation by an independent
counsel, and the Democrats have been using the issue to attack Bush.
   ``I think he's been made aware by the polls and by a lot of
public comment that there is the danger that this matter, if it
stays exactly the way it is, could not only adversely affect me,
but affect others as well,'' Bush said of Meese.
   Bush was also asked if he agreed with President Reagan's
contention, made at the superpower summit in Moscow, that Soviet
bureaucracy, rather than Kremlin policy, was apparently responsible
for delays in granting exit visas, or refusal to grant them at all.
   The newspaper said the vice president did not answer directly,
but said the United States and the Soviet Union have ``fundamental
differences'' on human rights.
   ``There is a long way to go before they have lived up to
provisions of the Helsinki final act,'' he said, adding that the
United States was committed to ``broad, objective standards on
human rights.''
</TEXT>
