<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Reagan-Fallout 1stLd-Writethru a0420 06-02 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Fallout, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0420,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans See a Bush Opportunity to Part Company from Reagan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS Bush comment in New York Times interview in grafs
9-10; picks up 9th graf pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican politicians say the Moscow summit
has presented Vice President George Bush with one of his best
chances yet to establish a more separate identity from President
Reagan and reassure conservatives in his own party.
   ``There comes a time and I would say to him this is the time,''
said Eddie Mahe, a GOP political consultant.
   Conservative Republicans were especially displeased with
Reagan's statement Wednesday that the Soviet bureaucracy _ and not
policies of the Soviet leadership _ may be the reason so many
Russian dissidents are barred from leaving the Soviet Union.
   ``I respectfully disagree with the president's statement,'' said
Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y. ``Human rights problems are endemic to the
Soviet system, not just the bureaucracy, but the fundamental nature
of government.''
   ``I think that Bush could reassure conservatives by
demonstrating that he is totally realistic about the Soviets,''
said Roger Stone, a consultant who worked on Reagan presidential
campaigns in 1980 and 1984, as well as on Kemp's unsuccessful bid
for the 1988 GOP presidential nomination.
   At a news conference in Moscow near the close of his summit with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Reagan suggested that problems
Soviet citizens are having getting exit visas were caused by the
bureaucracy rather than government policy.
   ``I just have to believe that in any government some of us do
find ourselves bound in by bureaucracy,'' said the president,
apparently at pains to avoid direct criticism of his Soviet hosts.
   Reagan said he thought Gorbachev was attempting to overcome
these bureaucratic barriers.
   Bush took a fairly neutral tack when he was asked about the
president's remarks. The New York Times, which interviewed him
Wednesday, asked him about it, and said in today's editions that
the vice president did not respond directly.
   Instead, he noted that the United States and the Soviet Union
have ``fundamental differences'' on human rights, and added:
``There is a long way to go before they have lived up to provisions
of the Helsinki final act.''
   But the Reagan comments brought quick reaction from human rights
observers as well as other politicians back home.
   ``It's really hard to know where Reagan was coming from on
that,'' said Dawn Mann, a fellow at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, an independent policy research institute.
``The fact that there still are several hundred prisoners of
conscience is not attributable to bureaucratic snafus.''
   Rep. Gus Yatron, D-Pa., chairman of the Human Rights
subcommittee of the House Foreign Affairs Committee, defended the
president and said he thought Reagan was trying to be polite.
   ``I can think of no one in Congress or the administration who
feels that Moscow's repressive policies are not the results of the
repressive nature of the Soviet government,'' he said. ``I would
want to give the president the benefit of the doubt.''
   Rep. Gerald Solomon of New York, the senior Republican on
Yatron's subcommittee, said he thought Reagan's approach could help
open the way for loosening of Soviet emigration policy.
   ``That gives wriggle for Gorbachev to react, and without
confrontational demands,'' he said. ``I'm confident that it will
work.''
   But within the political community, the Reagan comments were
viewed far differently.
   Extreme conservatives were apoplectic.
   ``He's certainly become America's No. 1 apologist for the Soviet
Union,'' said Richard Viguerie, who has taken to criticizing Reagan
for being soft toward the Soviets.
   ``Who is he kidding?'' asked Juliana Pilon of the conservative
Heritage Foundation. ``It just isn't true.''
   Mahe said of Reagan's comments, ``Those sentiments would not
really reflect George Bush's sentiments.'' He said they could give
Bush an opportunity to demonstrate to voters an area where he and
the president disagree.
   ``What this provides him is an opportunity to say, well, I
respect the president but I can't find myself in agreement on those
things,'' he said.
   ``I would tell him (Bush), the opportunity is at hand, let's
jump on it,'' added Mahe.
   ``Reagan's clearly trying to be kind to his hosts,'' said Stone.
``But it's an unrealistic position.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     06-02 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summer Doldrums Upon Networks As Audience Levels Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a poignant end to a fine series, but at
least ``St. Elsewhere'' got a polite sendoff in the Nielsen ratings
last week when it got its highest ranking ever, seventh.
   The highly publicized final episode ending with a surprise scene
revealing the whole six years of the series as only the imaginings
of an autistic child. But the ratings were real _ the episode got a
rating of 17.0, matching the rating of the season premiere last
fall, and a share of 29, according to the A.C. Nielsen Co.
   The conclusion of ABC's two-part movie ``Baby M'' improved on
the part one, making the top 10 at fifth with a rating of 17.6 and
a 27 share. Part one, included in the previous week's Nielsens,
ranked 17th.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   CBS got a top-10 performance out of the ``Miss Universe
Pageant,'' which ranked ninth with a 15.6 rating.
   The summer doldrums began to set in last week as the network
schedules filled with reruns. Viewers apparently eschewed
television for the outdoors and dropped the network share of the
audience to 63 from a season-to-date average of 70. Only four the
top 20 shows weren't reruns.
   NBC won the week that ended Sunday with a 12.8 rating, CBS had
10.9 and ABC 9.8. NBC's season-to-date average rating is 15.7, ABC
13.4 and CBS 13.2.
   ABC's ``World News Tonight'' continued a winning streak in news,
though the three networks apparently lost early evening viewers to
summer weather, and the race continued to be a virtual three-way
tie. ABC had an average rating of 9.0 and 19 share, the ``CBS
Evening News'' 8.5 and 19, the ``NBC Nightly News'' 8.2 and 18.
   The top 10 prime-time shows were: ``Cheers'' NBC, ``A Different
World'' NBC, ``The Cosby Show'' NBC, ``Night Court'' NBC, ``Baby M,
Part 2'' ABC, ``L.A. Law'' NBC, ``St. Elsewhere'' NBC, ``Golden
Girls'' NBC, ``Miss Universe Pagent'' CBS, ``Who's the Boss
Special'' ABC.
   NBC's made-for-TV movie, ``Desperado,'' came in 11th, the only
other non-repeat in the top 20.
   The lowest-rated shows of the week were: ``Bride of Boogedy,''
``West 57th,'' ``Tour of Duty,'' ``Ohara,'' ``High Mountain
Rangers,'' ``Hotel,'' ``Our House,'' ``Probe,'' ``Juarez'' and
``Omnibus.''
</TEXT>
