<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hutton-Libel 1stLd-Writethru a0432 06-02 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hutton-Libel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Attorney General Says He Was Suspicious Of High Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores dropped article ``a'' in 2nd graf, ``Bell, a...,''
and paraphrases quote in 3rd graf, ``While some...,'' for clarity.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Attorney General Griffin Bell says a
former E.F. Hutton branch manager didn't try to hide his
involvement in a check-kiting scheme that led to the company's
guilty plea to criminal charges in 1985.
   Bell, a defendant in a defamation suit filed by a former Hutton
branch manager criticized by the report he wrote, disputed the
plaintiff's claim that the check overdrafting was authorized by
company executives.
   While some branch managers said they were authorized by Hutton
superiors to overdraw accounts, plaintiff John M. Pearce never said
that anybody authorized him to do that, Bell testified Wednesday in
U.S. District Court.
   ``I asked him about paying a penalty. He said he didn't think he
should have to pay a penalty because he was a manager and not an
account executive,'' Bell said, recalling his interview with
Pearce, one of eight branch and regional executives cited for
wrongdoing in the former attorney general's report.
   He quoted Pearce as saying: ``Why don't you take it out of my
bonus.''
   Pearce claims that Bell, a private attorney in Atlanta who was
President Carter's first attorney general, negligently ignored
evidence that the check kiting scheme was approved by Hutton's top
management in New York.
   Pearce, who ran branches in Bethesda, Md., and St. Louis, claims
that Bell defamed him in the report and at a Sept. 5, 1985, press
conference held to discus the findings of the three-month
investigation.
   Bell was hired by Hutton after the firm pleaded guilty May 2,
1985, to 2,000 counts of mail and wire fraud stemming from the
check kiting scheme.
   The company, now part of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., agreed to
pay a $2 million fine and reimburse banks for millions of dollars
in interest lost when branch offices wrote checks against money
that had not been deposited in their checking accounts.
   Bell strongly defended his investigation, saying he didn't cite
any top officials for wrongdoing because all he could prove was
that senior executives didn't monitor the activities of branch and
regional offices.
   ``I thought I could catch a high person, but I never could,''
Bell said.
   Bell acknowledged that he was suspicious of high officials,
including former Hutton president George L. Ball. But there was no
evidence that any top Hutton official intentional sanctioned any
check writing practice that was later found to be illegal, he said.
   ``I'm not going to put my name on something charging somebody
with wrongdoing if they hadn't met the test _ if they did not have
the intent to do something wrong,'' Bell testified.
   ``I never found anybody on a high level at Hutton that knew what
was going on,'' Bell said.
   The problem was ``they didn't have any controls at all,'' Bell
said. Hutton ``just letting people go wild, doing whatever they
wanted to do.''
   He credited the investigations he and the Justice Department
conducted with changing overdraft procedures of major corporations.
   Bell's report recommended that Thomas P. Morley, Hutton's
``money mobilizer,'' be relieved of any duties involving the
company's banking activities.
   Thomas P. Lynch, a vice president whom Bell identified as the
chief financial officer, was also forced to resign for failing to
keep adequate controls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
