<1ST_LINE>u a AM-IndustrialFire 1stLd-Writethru a0403 06-02 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Industrial Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0403,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion, Fire Kill 1, Injure At Least 10 In Industrial Park</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 1 dead, two missing; picks
up 3rd graf pvs; SUBS 7th graf pvs, `Fire Lt. ... to UPDATE with
evacuees allowed to return home, editing to conform; ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH CHICAGO, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fire ripped through
an industrial park Wednesday, killing one person, injuring at least
10 and prompting 2,000 to flee before the blaze was brought under
control, authorities said.
   Two people were unaccounted for hours after the 3:30 p.m.
explosion at Traco Inc., a plastics manufacturer in this industrial
northern Chicago suburb, said Lt. Jack Jordan of the North Chicago
Fire Department. He said he suspected the two were Traco employees.
   The body was found about 11:30 p.m. in the rubble of the
explosion, Jordan said.
   One of the injured was listed in critical condition and four
were firefighters treated for heat exhaustion from battling the
fire.
   ``It shook City Hall, which is about two miles away,'' said
Mayor Bobby E. Thompson, who ordered a precautionary evacuation for
the 2,000 to 3,000 people who live near the Coleman Industrial
Complex, due to potentially toxic fumes.
   The fire was brought under control about 8:30 p.m., but toxic
chemicals burned in the fire included chlorine, polyvinyl chloride
and polystyrene, said Will Flowers, a spokesman for the Illinois
Environmental Protection Agency.
   Gregory Stevens, 27, of Antioch was hospitalized in critical
condition with facial burns, smoke inhalation and cuts on his head,
face and legs, said Joanne Johnson, spokeswoman at St. Therese
Medical Center in Waukegan.
   Thompson said authorities were asking people within a two-mile
area to close all doors and windows and turn off air conditioners
to avoid possible respiratory injuries.
   Jordan estimated that 2,000 people evacuated their homes but
were allowed to return late in the evening. They were advised to
kept doors and windows shut.
   The mayor said six to 10 businesses burned, but there was no
immediate estimate of damages. The cause of the explosion was not
immediately known.
   North Chicago, with a population of about 47,000, is about 35
miles north of downtown Chicago, and is the home of the Great Lakes
Naval Training Station.
</TEXT>
