<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     06-02 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DC, Baltimore Mayors Back National Debate on Drug
Decriminalization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayors of the nation's capital and nearby
Baltimore have renewed their call for a national debate on the
decriminalization of illegal drugs, with Baltimore's chief
executive saying that cutting out profits is the key to shutting
down drug dealers.
   ``As you look at our so-called war (on drugs), we're losing,''
said District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry Jr. during a live
television call-in show Wednesday night.
   ``I think there ought to be a full debate on what our options
are,'' said Barry.
   ``I'm not calling for a retreat on the war on drugs,'' said
Baltimore Mayor Kurt Schmoke, who touched off a firestorm of debate
several weeks ago when he first suggested the possibility of
decriminalization. ``I want to fight on the battlefield of the drug
dealers _ money.''
   Schmoke also said that Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., who chairs
the House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control, has
agreed to hold hearings on the decriminalization issue, probably in
September.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congress Urged To Regulate Test-Tube Baby Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One member of Congress is urging the
government to take an active role in protecting would-be parents
who seek help in having children from the nation's test-tube baby
industry.
   ``Frustrated couples, many at an emotional breaking point,
shouldn't also have to face those who would exploit their faith in
modern medicine,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore. at a hearing
Wednesday.
   Wyden, chairman of the House Small Business subcommittee on
regulation and business opportunities, cited a recent congressional
study that found more than half of the 169 clinics in the United
States performing in-vitro fertilization (IVF) last year never
produced a baby. A woman's chance of taking home a test-tube baby
is about 6 percent he said.
   The study for the congressional Office of Technology Assessment
also showed Americans spent $1 billion last year to combat
infertility.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Judge Strikes Down Ban On Secrecy Pledges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge says the Reagan administration
can require government workers to sign secrecy pledges.
   U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch, in a May 27 ruling made public
this week, struck down a congressional provision that would have
barred the administration's action taken during the first 10 months
of this year.
   Gasch said the provision contained in a spending resolution
passed by Congress last December unconstitutionally intruded on the
president's power to protect government secrets.
   ``With a tug of the purse strings section 630 (of the spending
resolution) establishes a precedent unrestrained by discernible
standards and intrudes dramatically upon presidential authority,''
Gasch said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Average Public School Salaries Reported in Survey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average public school teacher makes about
$28,000 annually, according to a recent survey by an education
research group.
   The annual survey, conducted by the Educational Research
Service, found average salaries this year ranged from $28,230 for
teachers to $68,147 for superintendents.
   The salary data, reported in last month's issue of ``Principal''
magazine, was gathered in a survey of teachers and administrators
in 1,000 public school districts.
</TEXT>
