<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MineExplosion-Scene     06-02 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mine Explosion-Scene,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miners' Wives And Relatives Hope For A Miracle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Mine Explosion, bjt
^By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Their faces red from weeping,
relatives of the victims of the Borken coal mine blast headed home
early today after waiting for hours for news that their loved ones
were alive.
   The news never came.
   By early today, rescue workers had pulled 31 bodies from the
mine after the explosion midday Wednesday, Hessiche Rundfunk radio
reported.
   Another 26 miners were still trapped 330 feet underground and
hopes were dimming that they would be found alive.
   Wives, children and parents of the missing miners gathered at a
mine company building Wednesday night to wait together.
   ``I don't see how anyone could have survived,'' said 60-year-old
Gerhard Hettmanczyk, whose son-in-law Alfred Wiremba was among the
missing. He headed home late Wednesday after waiting several hours
on the mine grounds.
   Others followed Hettmanczyk, weeping or trying to hold back
their sobs.
   At the mine, floodlights illuminated about 300 rescue workers,
who were handling large cables for drills used by teams of diggers
inside. The cables also powered ventilators that were pumping fresh
air into the mine shaft.
   The explosion blew the roofs off at least three company
buildings and kicking up a dark cloud of dust that lingered over
the landscape.
   Strewn over the site were heavy steel rollers from a conveyer
belt blown apart by the blast.
   ``The air is very bad in there,'' said Klaus Hausmann, a
blackened miner who was helping outside. ``Things do not look so
good _ everything is blocked off.''
   ``Naturally we knew that a miner's job can be dangerous. But we
never thought this would happen,'' said Werner Henke, an elderly
man who was waiting near the mine in the house of his son Dieter,
who was among the missing.
   ``Work will go on here after this over,'' said Otto Kraft, a
mine worker who was above ground when it happened. ``But we're
never going to be able to forget this horrible disaster.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
