<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BroadwaySeason 1stLd-Writethru a0476 06-02 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Broadway Season, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0476,0657</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS to having, sted have, in lede.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Record Season For Ticket Sales; Production Drops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theatergoers gave their regards to Broadway,
buying a record number of tickets during the 1987-88 season despite
having fewer productions to choose from.
   During the season, which ran June 1, 1987, to May 29, $253
million worth of tickets were sold to more than 8.1 million
theatergoers, the League of American Theaters and Producers said
Wednesday.
   The previous season, ticket sales were $209 million and
attendance hit 7 million for 40 Broadway productions. The 21
percent increase in ticket sales and 16 percent increase in
attendance occurred despite a drop in the number of productions to
32 during the 1987-88 season.
   ``This was a more balanced season between musicals and plays,''
said George Wachtel, the league's research director. ``Last season
we seemed to have three musical megahits _ `Me and My Girl,' `Les
Miserables' and `Starlight Express.' That focused attention on
Broadway and set us up for where we are now.''
   Twelve new musicals opened during the 1987-88 season compared
with 11 the previous year.
   ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' the Andrew Lloyd Webber musical
that opened with a record $19 million advance sale, gave the
biggest boost to the season.
   It was joined by several other strong musical shows including
``Sarafina!'', a surprise hit from South Africa; a revival of the
Cole Porter musical ``Anything Goes,'' and ``Chess,'' a big British
musical that is doing well at the box office despite mostly
negative reviews.
   ``There's a lot of choice on Broadway which is probably why
there are so many people going,'' said Wachtel.
   There were eight new plays on Broadway, down from 13 the
previous season, but of the eight, only one _ ``Serious Money'' _
closed quickly. Five others are still running, including the four
strong Tony nominees for best play _ ``A Walk in the Woods'' by Lee
Blessing, ``Joe Turner's Come and Gone'' by August Wilson, ``M.
Butterfly'' by David Henry Hwang and ``Speed-the-Plow'' by David
Mamet.
   ``The eight plays that have opened this year are the fewest
number in the entire history of the Broadway theater,'' said Rocco
Landesman, president of Jujamcyn Theaters, which owns five Broadway
theaters. ``Granted they are of a high quality. If you feel like I
do that the play is the lifeblood of the Broadway theater, that's a
very worrisome statistic.''
   If production was down, ticket prices were up. The $50 ticket
for a musical is now the norm rather than the exception. A $40 top
ticket for a play on weekend nights is also not unusual with such
productions as ``M. Butterfly,'' ``Macbeth'' and ``Broadway Bound''
charging that amount. The average paid admission, according to the
league, was $31.10, up from $29.86 for the previous season.
   Wachtel was optimistic about the 1988-89 season. Among the
possibilities are several big musicals including ``Legs Diamond''
starring Peter Allen and a revival of ``The Merry Widow'' starring
Cleo Laine, as well as two Neil Simon comedies.
   ``In terms of attendance, I think we will do very well because
the last three weeks have been extraordinary,'' Wachtel said. ``We
have the momentum to keep going. A lot of that may be tourism, the
weakness of the dollar. The pickup we usually get from tourism
during the summer is happening earlier.''
   Landesman said he wants to see theatergoers attending more than
just the big musical hits like ``Phantom'' or ``Les Miserables.''
   ``I'd like to see more people spread out among more
productions,'' said Landesman. ``Because the producing situation is
so tough now, a lot of things don't go to Broadway unless they are
proven or established. You want to have a situation where there are
a lot of things going on _ some good, some bad and some ugly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
