<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-02 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GADSDEN, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonard didn't stand tall when he patrolled
his owner's car lot office, but Reggie Roberts says the 7-foot-long
boa constrictor was the best guard he ever had.
   Somebody broke the office window Sunday, and Leonard is gone.
   ``I'm just 99 percent sure somebody stole my snake,'' Roberts
said Wednesday. ``I don't know why they did it.''
   Roberts, who owns T.R. Roberts Motors, is offering a $100 reward
for the return of his pet reptile.
   ``I won't ask any questions,'' he said. ``I just want my snake
back. I miss the little fellow.''
   He hopes Leonard will be found. The ``Beware! Guard Snake on
Duty'' sign remains posted on the business' door.
   Leonard was kept in a temperature-controlled glass showcase
during the day so as not to scare customers. But at night the
creature, which Roberts describes as ``just a big baby,'' was given
the run of the office.
   Roberts bought the snake, who is about 8 years old, when the
previous owner's landlady objected to Leonard as a tenant. He's had
the snake nearly a year.
   ``I've had him long enough to get good and attached to him,''
Roberts said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Cuties will take on convicts at
Waupun state prison, but the comedy softball team won't be playing
in drag, officials say.
   ``If they can't do it in men's clothing, in regular clothing,
then we should cancel it,'' state Division of Corrections
Administrator Stephen E. Bablitch said Wednesday.
   The Cuties, four men who usually dress in women's attire for a
seven-inning comedy game, are scheduled to play an inmate team June
15 at the maximum-security prison.
   However, convicted murderer Harlan C. Richards complained,
saying it was ``sick and disgusting'' to have ``transvestite
baseball players in here to entertain us.''
   Jess Palacios, part-owner of the Cuties, said the team would
play in men's clothes if necessary, but the humor would not be the
same.
   ``The comedy part is that they dress up in women's clothes,''
Palacios said. He said the show had no sexual overtones. ``It's
just a comedy show.''
</TEXT>
