<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--DeathPenalty-Poll     06-02 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Death Penalty-Poll,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmits a0481 to fix typo in summary line</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rhode Island Poll Finds Nearly Half Want Death For `Crack' Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Brown University poll found that
nearly half those surveyed believe dealers in ``crack'' cocaine
should be executed.
   About half of the 345 adults contacted in the telephone survey
this spring believed the death penalty would be appropriate for
certain situations.
   The percentages ranged from 47 percent support for the death
penalty for a drug dealer who sells crack to a user to 59 percent
for capital punishment for a person who kills seven people after
being fired from a job.
   Sixty-four percent said they approve of the death penalty, and
only 29 percent disapproved, compared with 43 percent approval and
51 percent disapproval in 1985.
   Rhode Island has no death penalty.
   The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</TEXT>
