<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0430EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EmergencyLanding     06-02 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Emergency Landing,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>747 Makes Safe Emergency Landing At Midway Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines jumbo jet with 200 people
aboard made a safe emergency landing at Midway Island after a fire
warning light malfunctioned, an airline spokesman said.
   The Boeing 747 jetliner landed Wednesday around 2:30 p.m. HST
(8:30 p.m. EDT) on a flight from Honolulu to Tokyo, said Douglas
Killian, Northwest's manager of public affairs in Tokyo.
   There was no fire and the problem was determined to be a faulty
fire indicator light for the cargo hold, Killian said in a
telephone interview.
   Midway Island, controlled by the U.S. Navy, is 1,150 miles
northwest of Honolulu.
   A mechanic was flying to Midway from Honolulu to install new
fire extinguishers, which were activated when the light went on,
Killian said.
   Flight 9's arrival at Narita Airport was expected to be delayed
by about 16 hours, he said. During the delay here, the 185
passengers and 15 crew members were being accomodated at the naval
station, Killian said.
</TEXT>
