<HEAD>Rep. William Gray To Head Up Democratic Platform-Drafting
Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic National Committee Chairman Paul Kirk
says Rep. William Gray of Pennsylvania has been named chairman of
the party's platform-drafting committee.
   Kirk announced Wednesday that Gray, the chairman of the House
Budget Committee and a supporter of Jesse Jackson, will head up the
15-member panel that will develop a working draft of the party's
presidential platform.
   ``Congressman Gray enjoys the respect of both the presidential
campaigns, all the members of Congress, and has proven ... to be a
man of commitment to principle,'' Kirk said.
   The draft will be considered at a final meeting of the full
platform committee June 25 in Denver, and will be presented before
the party on July 19 during its national convention, Kirk said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mrs. Dukakis At Hospital For Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis, will remain in a Boston hospital
for tests to determine whether she will need surgery to correct a
problem with her vertebrae.
   Mrs. Dukakis, the wife of Democratic presidential front-runner
Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, arrived in Boston shortly
before 9 p.m. EDT Wednesday and was transferred immediately to
Massachusetts General Hospital.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 53, wearing a neck brace, told reporters at Logan
International Airport she began to experience numbness in her hands
and fingers about a month ago and called a family doctor, whom she
did not identify.
   ``He and I felt at that time it was just stress,'' she said,
adding that her symptoms worsened in recent weeks.
   A preliminary diagnosis Mrs. Dukakis received in California last
week indicated she has two herniated cervical disks in the neck
area. She was in California campaigning for her husband.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mental Health Advocates Sue Dukakis, Say Budget Cuts
Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mental health advocates have filed suit against
Democratic presidential front-runner Gov. Michael Dukakis and his
top budget officer.
   The suit, filed Wednesday with the state Supreme Court by the
Alliance for the Mentally Ill contends that spending cuts ordered
to balance the state budget were unconstitutional and would delay
community placement of state hospital patients.
   Dukakis, whose state budget problems have become an issue in his
presidential campaign, has said the past three years have seen
``the most significant expansion in the history of the state'' in
spending for the mentally ill.
   No hearing date was set.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gore Says He Won't Try to Influence Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COOKEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., who suspended his
bid for the Democratic presidential nomination in April, says he
won't try to sway actions at the Democratic National Convention
next month.
   ``I would hope that the platform would reflect the kind of
approach I've recommended,'' Gore said Wednesday on a swing through
his home state.
   ``I think there has already been a shift toward the center on
the part of the other candidates (Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis and Jesse Jackson) as a result of our campaign.''
   Gore, 40, still holds a block of about 400 delegates to the
convention in Atlanta, which begins July 18.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>20 Oklahoma Delegates Switch Allegiance To Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the Oklahoma delegates previously
pledged to Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore say they will endorse
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   The wholesale shift of 20 of the 26 delegates previously pledged
to Gore was announced Wednesday at a news conference at the state
Capitol by Stratton Taylor, a state senator who is chairman of
Gore's Oklahoma campaign.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., also formerly a Gore supporter joined
the group's switch.
   ``He has clearly emerged as the strong front-runner for the
nomination and is now entitled to have consensus support from the
party as we move toward the national convention in Atlanta,'' said
Boren.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Grassley, Branstad Join Forces To Run Bush Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Terry Branstad and Sen. Charles
Grassley, often at odds with each other, say they will join forces
to run George Bush's Iowa presidential campaign.
   Branstad and Grassley formally announced their decision at a
Statehouse news conference Wednesday, saying that gives the vice
president a chance at carrying the state in November though ``we
know it won't be easy.''
   ``We can carry Iowa in November,'' Branstad said.
   ``There should be no doubt any more'' that the state's
Republican Party is united after an often-fractious campaign for
the Feb. 8 precinct caucuses, said Grassley.
   Grassley was a prominent backer of Kansas Sen. Bob Dole during
that caucus campaign, while Branstad was neutral.
</TEXT>
