<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Yeltsin     06-02 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Yeltsin Faces Review For Leadership Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev says his former protege,
Boris N. Yeltsin, will be summoned to explain why he criticized the
ruling Communist Party's No. 2 man, Yegor K. Ligachev, in
interviews with Western news media.
   ``We in the Central Committee must ask Comrade Yeltsin and
request explanations: what is he talking about and what is Comrade
Yeltsin after? It means his opinion differs from that of the
Central Committee of the party,'' the Soviet leader said Wednesday.
   Gorbachev's remarks continued an unprecedented public airing of
discord in the Soviet leadership, which tries its best to present a
unified image on domestic and foreign policy.
   The comments were a sensation not only for the foreign reporters
who solicited them at a news conference, but also for the millions
of Soviets who watched the session live on Soviet television and on
tape late at night.
   Asked about Yeltsin's call for Ligachev's resignation in a
British Broadcasting Corp. television interview Monday, Gorbachev
said:
   ``As for Comrade Ligachev and his resignation: no such problem
exists either in the Central Committee or in the Politburo, and
that's it. You may proceed from this assumption.''
   Yeltsin, 57, was ousted as Moscow party boss in November and
from the ruling Politburo in February after he made an angry speech
during a meeting of the party's 300-member policy-making Central
Committee.
   In an unexpected twist, Yeltsin told ABC News on Tuesday and CBS
News on Wednesday that he had not called for Ligachev's resignation.
   ``I simply said that in the style of work of Comrade Ligachev,
there are certain aspects with which I disagree,'' he told CBS.
``That is true particularly on the social problems. And that was
it. And there was no talk of his (Ligachev's) departure.''
   He added: ``Comrade Ligachev is in the Politburo and I'm
convinced he will stay in the Politburo, undoubtedly.''
   In the BBC interview, Yeltsin said Ligachev should step down
``because processes in the party are too slow, because the party is
still lagging behind, because the process of democratization is not
developing ... and Comrade Ligachev is the main person
responsible.''
   Gorbachev forcefully sought to quell rumors of friction between
himself and Ligachev, believed to head a conservative faction on
the Politburo. Ligachev, 67, oversees Communist Party ideology.
   Responding to a question from a British journalist, Gorbachev
said Wednesday that he had neither seen the interviews nor read a
text of them.
   ``We plan to talk with Comrade Yeltsin because he is a member of
the Central Committee of the Communist Party,'' he said.
   Gorbachev offered some details of the Oct. 21 Central Committee
meeting at which Yeltsin gave a speech leading to his ouster.
   Besides Yeltsin, 27 other committee members spoke, said
Gorbachev, and ``the opinion of all 27 speakers was that the
generalizations made by Comrade Yeltsin regarding the Central
Committee, its secretariarat and the Politburo were wrong, and his
statement was recognized as being politically erroneous.''
   The towering, white-haired man was fired Nov. 11 as Moscow party
chief, removed Feb. 18 as a candidate, or non-voting Politburo
member, and stripped May 4 of his job on the Presidium of the
Supreme Soviet, the country's parliament.
   His current post is first deputy chairman of the State Building
Committee.
</TEXT>
