<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Singapore-US     06-02 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Singapore-US,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Reaffirms U.S. Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew has offered to
apologize to Washington if an international forum determines that
an expelled U.S. diplomat was acting within diplomatic guidelines
when he met an opposition leader.
   Lee told Parliament on Wednesday that allegations the United
States meddled in Singapore politics should not be allowed to harm
long-term relations beween the two countries.
   He said his country was ``not condemning the criminal designs of
an enemy, but regretting the misdemeanors of a friend.''
   The tone of Lee's comments contrasted with the often strident
rhetoric in earlier Parliament sessions. Deputy Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong on Tuesday threatened to cut the number of diplomats in
the U.S. Embassy unless Washington mended its ways.
   Lee referred to E. Mason Hendrickson, former first secretary of
the embassy's political section, who the government asked to leave
early last month. Hendrickson was accused of encouraging several
lawyers to run against the governing People's Action Party in the
next general election.
   Washington rejected the allegations, insisting that
Hendrickson's actions were within accepted diplomatic bounds and in
turn expelled a Singapore diplomat of equivalent rank from the
United States.
   On Wednesday, Lee suggested a neutral committee of three experts
in international law be named to determine whether Hendrickson and
three State Department officials ``acted legitimately as diplomats
or whether they have interfered in the internal affairs of
Singapore.''
   If the committee determines that Hendrickson and the State
Department officials were acting with normal diplomatic guidelines,
Lee said ``Singapore will withdraw its protest and apologize to the
State Department.''
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Richard Gong declined to comment on Lee's
remarks.
   Lee said his country's senior diplomats in the United States say
that many State Department officials would prefer this island
republic of 2.6 million people ``move from what they consider to be
an authoritarian political system, based on consensus, to a
pluralistic democracy, based on a multi-party system as found in
the West.
   ``Therefore, State Department officials have criticized
Singapore as not moving forward in liberalizing and democratizing
as in Taiwan and Korea ... I am only too aware of how very
different we are from Korea and Taiwan. Singapore does not have one
race, one language, one culture and nearly one religion. We are
multiracial, even though our 75 percent Chinese were originally
from East Asia.''
   Lee said he took full responsibility for the re-arrests last
month of eight dissidents originally detained a year ago without
charge as well as the arrest of two lawyers involved in the
dissidents' cases, and the ouster of Hendrickson.
   Singapore alleged that Hendrickson and the State Department
officials had dealings with a lawyer, Francis Seow.
   Seow, 59, a former solicitor general and president of the Law
Society, was arrested on May 6. He had been representing several of
the dissidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
