<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WishFulfilled     06-02 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wish Fulfilled,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mom Sees Last Surviving Son Graduate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For years, Martha Chappel has had the desire
to see one of her four boys make it to graduation day.
   Her wish came true Wednesday night. Her only surviving son,
Willie Jackson, received his ``completion certificate'' from Cold
Spring School, a school for mentally and physically handicapped
children.
   A rare disease, Hunter's Syndrome, killed her three other sons
before they could graduate.
   ``I'm so excited I can hardly stand it,'' said Mrs. Chappel, who
swore never to send her children to an institution after she saw
the life her brother endured in one.
   The fatal, inherited disorder causes mental retardation and
physical abnormalities such as dwarfism, deafness, heart defects
and arthritic joint pain. There is no cure or therapy for the
disease, which affects only males.
   Willie, who also has the disease, is a dwarf, moderately
retarded and deaf in one ear.
   The life expectancy of children with Hunter's is 15 years.
Willie is 18.
   ``He's gone against the odds already. This boy has been so close
to death you could almost see it, but he's so strong,'' said his
stepfather, Waller Chappel.
   Mrs. Chappel's son Adrian died when he was 5 in 1976, followed
by Eddie in 1979 at age 15 and Ernie in 1981 at age 18.
   Graduation day was a big event at the Chappels' white frame
house on the city's west side.
   When Willie arrived home from school Wednesday, his main
interest was the graduation cake.
   ``I want the cake now,'' he repeatedly told his mother after
sitting on the couch, waiting patiently for almost two hours.
   Mrs. Chappel didn't know her first two boys had Hunter's until
after Willie was born.
   ``I kept thinking I'll have a girl and I'll tell her not to have
children. I've always wanted a lot of kids. That's been my goal
since I was little,'' she said.
   Mrs. Chappel is not bitter. She says she feels fortunate in many
ways to have been blessed with four loving boys and caring friends
and relatives.
   ``Willie hugs me and tells me he loves me. They all have taught
me so much,'' she said.
   Because of the disease, Willie has a small esophagus, which
causes difficulty in breathing. He tires easily and can walk only
about a half block at a time, so she sometimes must carry him.
   Willie's future might be brief, but Mrs. Chappel said she'll
continue doing everything she can to make him happy. ``He'll be
home with me until I die or he dies. Willie's time is my time.''
   She hopes he can enroll in a day adult program for the
handicapped so he can continue socializing and being around people.
</TEXT>
