<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BlantonFiles     06-02 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blanton Files,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Tennessee Gov. Files To Run For Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Ray Blanton, who served two
years in federal prison on conspiracy and extortion convictions,
moved to resurrect his political career by filing to run for
Congress.
   Blanton on Wednesday filed a qualifying petition for the 8th
Congressional District seat being vacated by Democratic Rep. Ed
Jones. Blanton became the fifth Democrat in the race.
   The qualifying deadline for all state candidates running in the
Aug. 4 primary or the Nov. 8 general election was noon today.
   Blanton, who represented much of the same west Tennessee area in
the old 7th Congressional District from 1967 to 1973, was governor
from 1975 to 1979.
   In 1981, he was convicted of conspiracy, extortion and mail
fraud in the issuance of 12 state liquor licenses while he was
governor in 1976. He was released from prison in 1986.
   Last October, his citizenship rights, including the right to run
for public office, were restored by state Circuit Judge Harry
Lester.
   U.S. Judge Bailey Brown of Memphis, an appellate judge who
presided at Blanton's trial, granted his December 1987 petition to
vacate the mail fraud counts against him. The former governor is
appealing the conspiracy and extortion counts.
   The other Democratic candidates are Mayor Bob Conger of Jackson,
Charles McCright of Dyersburg, Ivy Scarbrough of Humboldt and state
Rep. John Tanner of Union City. Republican candidates include Dan
Campbell of Memphis and Ed Bryant and Richard Jacobs, both of
Jackson.
</TEXT>
