<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Mull     06-02 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Mull,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comedian Atones For Putdown Of Indianapolis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Mull has sent a $75 check to Mayor
William H. Hudnut as atonement for a putdown of the Hoosier capital
attributed to the comedian in a magazine.
   The $75 was prorated from the $1,500 Mull received for the story
in Philip Morris magazine titled, ``Why Baseball is Better than
Football,'' in which the first of his 20 reasons was, ``I'll never
have to go to Indianapolis.''
   Mull, who appears in commercials for a downtown Indianapolis
shopping mall, later issued a tongue-in-cheek apology in which he
said he meant to say Annapolis, ``because who in their right mind
would want to go to Annapolis?''
   Dennis Callahan, mayor of Maryland's state capital, then
demanded an explanation from Melvin Simon & Associates, the
development company that owns Claypool Court mall and uses Mull in
its commercials.
   Simon said he was ``bewildered'' by Mull's statements, that the
comedian did not speak for the company and that his future use in
commercials was under review.
   Meanwhile, the check arrived in the mail Wednesday, and Hudnut
endorsed it to St. Nicholas Youth Center, an Indianapolis
organization favored by Simon.
   Indianapolis is home of the National Football League's Colts but
does not have a major league baseball franchise.
</TEXT>
