<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0452 06-02 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Criticizes Reagan Summit Comments, Plans Meeting With Gang
Members</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 8 grafs after pvs 6th graf bgng `` As a ...''; picks
up pvs 7th graf bgng ``Jackson was ...''; EDITS throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson kicked off his final campaign
swing through California with a visit to the Watts ghetto, where he
told a rally, ``I'm a man of the people.''
   ``Where you struggle I will struggle,'' Jackson said to a few
hundred people who gathered Wednesday in Will Rogers Park and
cheered his every phrase.
   In the face of his fading prospects to win the Democratic
presidential nomination, Jackson urged people to vote for him next
Tuesday, the last day of the primary season.
   But Jackson also leaned heavily on his anti-drug, anti-violence
message and themes of hope that go beyond his presidential campaign.
   Today, in what promised to be a dramatic encounter, Jackson was
meeting with members of the rival Crips and Bloods gangs. Campaign
aides said they believed it would be the first time the rival gang
leaders got together.
   ``As a grown man, I will never be afraid of children. I will
talk with you anywhere,'' Jackson told the Watts rally.
   In his speeches Wednesday, Jackson also criticized Reagan's
comments in the Soviet Union about American Indians in which the
president referred to the ``primitive'' conditions in which they
live and said some got rich off oil.
   Jackson called Reagan's remarks ill-informed and ``an affront to
all Americans.''
   Jackson said U.S. policy toward native Americans has lacked a
key ingredient of ``profound and sustained respect '' for them.
   Jackson also said President Reagan made a mistake in saying that
the lack of human rights in the Soviet Union is more a matter of
bureaucracy than policy.
   ``Mr. Reagan is caught up in the romance of Russia, not the
reality,'' Jackson said in response to a reporter's question about
Reagan's characterization of the human rights problem in the Soviet
Union during his fourth summit meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev.
   Jackson said that Reagan's assessment was ``an error in his
judgment.''
   ``The lack of human rights in the Soviet Union, the lack of
freedom of press, freedom of religion, freedom of immigration is a
matter of policy, it is not just a matter of bureacracy.''
   ``I hope Mr. Reagan will not make anymore errors of that
magnitude,` he told reporters.
   Jackson was spending the night with a single mother and her
three children who live in the Nickerson Gardens housing project of
Watts.
   `I'm going to stay in Nickerson Gardens tonight because I'm a
man of the people,` he said.
   But first he attended a Hollywood fund-raiser featuring Kris
Kristofferson, Willie Nelson, Martin Sheen, Helen Reddy, Rita
Coolidge and other performers.
   As Tuesday's primary nears, with California offering the largest
delegate prize in the country, the Jackson campaign is launching
its $700,000 TV ad blitz for the final days of the campaign,
featuring four Spanish-language ads and three English ads developed
for California.
   Some of the ads began airing Tuesday, others will start today.
   Campaign spokeswoman Pam Smith said the campaign has bought
$60,000 worth of TV and radio time for the Spanish ads, hoping to
cut into the popularity front-runner Michael Dukakis enjoys among
California's large Hispanic population.
   Polls in California have shown Jackson far behind Dukakis, who
is on the verge of sewing up the nomination, but Jackson insisted
Wednesday that he can win the state and urged voters not to be led
to thinking their vote won't count.
   Jackson also vowed to go to the Democratic convention in Atlanta
this summer and fight for his platform goals. He said some have
termed his proposals radical, but that ``I'm not going to change my
plan just because you put a label on it.''
   Jackson also said he had telephoned his rival with good wishes
for Kitty Dukakis, who entered a Boston hospital Wednesday night
for tests after a preliminary diagnosis of herniated discs in the
neck area.
   Jackson said he reached the governor instead of his wife, but
said they did not discuss the vice presidency or anything
politically significant.
</TEXT>
