<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Monkeys     06-02 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Monkeys,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Virus May Have Infected Human Ancestors 20 Million Years Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A predecessor of the AIDS virus could have
infected primitive human ancestors more than 20 million years ago
and evolved as modern humans evolved, researchers say.
   A determination of the entire genetic code, or sequence, of an
AIDS virus found in an African green monkey suggests that the virus
did not jump recently from monkeys to humans, the researchers said
in an article published today in Nature, the British scientific
journal.
   Some researchers have suggested that these monkeys may have been
the source of the human AIDS virus.
   A team led by Masanori Hayami of the University of Tokyo found
that the African green monkey AIDS virus differed from the two
known human AIDS viruses in several important respects.
   If the virus had jumped from monkeys to humans in recent times,
the viruses would be identical or nearly so, said Carel Mulder, a
biologist at the University of Massachusetts Medical School in
Worcester.
   ``It is impossible that humans were infected in any recent time
with this virus,'' Mulder said in a telephone interview.
   The Japanese researchers and Mulder say that the evidence now
suggests that each species could have its own version of the AIDS
virus.
   Two AIDS viruses have been identified in humans. They could have
evolved in isolated populations in different places, the Japanese
researchers reported.
   Humans and monkeys are descendants of primitive primates that
may have lived 20 million to 30 million years ago. The Japanese
researchers believe that an AIDS-like virus infected those
primitive primates.
   As those creatures evolved into humans and various species of
monkeys, the parent AIDS virus evolved into the different forms
seen today, the researchers speculated.
   No AIDS virus is known in apes, which are more closely related
to humans than are monkeys.
   Dr. Norman Letvin, a primate specialist at the Harvard Medical
School, said of the Japanese research, ``This is yet another piece
of data in support of what I think should now be accepted _ that a
jump of the virus did not occur.''
   Asked why the virus has only recently been observed to cause
disease, Letvin said that it could have existed for a long time
only in isolated populations, and that it might also have evolved
into its present disease-causing form in comparatively recent times.
   The virus that Hayami and his colleagues studied was isolated
from a wild African green monkey obtained in Kenya. Their
determination, or sequencing, of the virus's genetic code shows
that it lacks some genetic material carried by the human AIDS
viruses.
   The two human AIDS viruses are HIV-1, which is almost
exclusively responsible for the worldwide epidemic of acquired
immune deficiency syndrome, and HIV-2, which is mostly limited to
West Africa but is now slowly beginning to spread.
   Researchers disagree over whether HIV-2 causes disease.
   The African green monkey virus lacks the so-called ``R'' gene
present in HIV-1 and HIV-2, the Japanese researchers report. In
addition, the African green monkey virus does not appear to make
monkeys sick.
   Researchers are trying to determine the function of the R gene,
Mulder said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
