<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Summit-Proverb     06-02 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Proverb,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Invokes Obscure Proverb in Moscow Farewell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today invoked an obscure Russian
proverb in his farewell to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``Mr. General Secretary, if you will permit me just one more
proverb,'' Reagan said. ``I think a very old and popular saying you
have here about last Sunday, the day of our arrival, spoke to the
promise we have seen fulfilled at this summit in this Moscow
spring.''
   Then, in halting Russian, the president said, ``Troitsa _ ves
les postroitsya.''
   Literally, the proverb translates into English as ``Holiday of
the Trinity _ and the whole forest will blossom.''
   This is a reference to the old Russian Orthodox holiday of
Trinity, celebrated on the last Sunday in May, and the fact that
birch trees _ a symbol of Russia _ are green then, auguring a good
summer.
   Reagan arrived in Moscow on May 29, the last Sunday of the month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Transplants     06-02 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transplants,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidney-Sharing Successful, Essential, Doctors Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether they're shipped across town or across the
country, transplanted kidneys work equally well in patients
following surgery, dispelling arguments that widespread
organ-sharing deflates short-term success, experts say.
   ``The main gain is in the long term'' because of the ability to
provide better-matched kidneys for patients, said Dr. Paul
Terasaki, professor of surgery at the University of California, Los
Angeles.
   For patients extremely sensitive to donor organs, sharing is
their only hope for a successful kidney transplant, said Terasaki,
who keeps an international kidney transplant registry.
   ``You can't find a perfect match'' unless you have access to
numerous organs, he said Wednesday at the annual meeting of the
American Society of Transplant Physicians and the American Society
of Transplant Surgeons.
   Some transplant doctors say shipping donor kidneys to the best
possible candidate damages the organs because of the increased
amount of time outside the body. Others, including Terasaki,
contend all kidneys should be shared because of the vastly improved
results when the tissue of the donor and recipient is matched as
closely as possible.
   Since last fall, the nation's transplant centers and organ
procurement agencies have had to share kidneys in which all six
antigens, or genetic markers, have been identified and perfectly
matched with a potential recipient. The so-called ``six-antigen''
organs account, however, for only a tiny fraction of the total
number of kidneys donated.
   Terasaki said he analyzed 6,250 kidney transplants to determine
whether early success rates were compromised by how far the organs
were sent.
   Of the total, 2,338 organs remained in the hospital where they
were procured and 1,422 were shared within 50 miles, Terasaki said.
The remaining 2,490 were sent more than 50 miles away.
   The transplanted kidneys that were not transported at all
functioned immediately after surgery in 85.7 percent of the cases,
compared with 74.4 percent of those shared within 50 miles and 83.5
percent in those sent farther, Terasaki said.
   A year after surgery, the transplanted kidneys were functioning
in 79 percent of the cases that involved no sharing, Terasaki said.
Seventy-eight percent of the locally shared kidneys were working
properly, as well as 76 percent of the kidneys shared over greater
distances.
   Long-term success was considerably better in kidneys that were
shared and transplanted into the best-matched candidates than in
those that were not shared and poorly matched, according to
Terasaki.
   Dr. John McDonald, president of the American Society of
Transplant Surgeons, said Terasaki's findings hopefully will end
the debate over whether kidneys should be shared.
   ``I think the argument not to put kidneys in the patients who
are the best match gets weaker and weaker. I don't really think you
can support that very much longer on scientific grounds,'' McDonald
said.
   About 13,000 people are awaiting kidney transplants in the
United States. Virtually all awaiting are on dialysis.
   About half are considered highly sensitive to transplants
because of a previous transplant, pregnancy, blood transfusion or
other circumstances that result in an unusually large amount of
cytotoxic antibodies in the bloodstream, said Dr. Lawrence G.
Hunsicker, president of the American Society of Transplant
Physicians. The group includes twice as many women as men.
   As many as a fourth of the approximately 6,500 patients
considered sensitized, in fact, are not because of an antibody
known as IgM that sometimes is misidentified in blood tests as an
anti-transplant substance, Terasaki said. The patients consequently
are passed over for kidney transplants since doctors presume their
chances are poor.
   ``They're waiting unnecessarily,'' Terasaki said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
