<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-02 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tokyo Market Closes At Record High, Dollar Posts Moderate Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed at a record high on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange today, while the dollar posted a moderate gain
against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 165.45
points, or 0.59 percent, to close at 27,869.36. The previous high
for Tokyo's main economic barometer was set on May 17 when the
Nikkei closed at 27,819.98.
   The index skyrocketed in early trading, momentarily touching
27,930.58, but lost momentum after investors started selling shares
for profit-taking toward the end of the morning session, brokers
said.
   ``There is growing concern for inflation and rising interest
rates,'' said a broker at a major securities firm. ``The market
slowed down from late morning to the early afternoon session, but
it regained strength toward the end of the day's trading,'' he
added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Volume today totaled 1.9 billion shares, with 1.3 billion traded
this morning.
   Meanwhile, the dollar rose 0.33 yen from its 125.35-yen
Wednesday finish to close at 125.68 yen. It had started the day at
125.50 yen and traded mainly between 125.48-125.78 yen.
   Traders said bullishness prevailed in the market throughout the
day, but gains in the dollar for the past four days had investors
worried.
   They added that the U.S. currency's strength against the
Japanese yen has been fueled mainly through profit-taking by
investors.
   `Ahead of the unemployment rate release scheduled for tomorrow
(Friday) in the U.S., market players sold the yen at the current
favorable rate,'' said Hiroaki Shukuzawa of Sumitomo Bank.
</TEXT>
