<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SpyBook     06-02 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spy Book,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Loses `Spycatcher' Case _ And A Heap Of Money With It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government today lost a
two-year court battle to stop a former intelligence officer from
publishing his memoirs in Australia and was ordered to pay an
estimated $900,000 in legal costs.
   In a unanimous decision, the High Court of Australia finally
rejected the British government's attempt to stop publication of
the book ``Spycatcher'' by Peter Wright, a 20-year veteran of the
MI-5 counter-espionage service.
   Arguing that Britain's catch-all Official Secrets Act committed
Wright to life-long secrecy, Britain also sought to seize profits
from sales of the book.
   Unspecified legal costs, estimated by lawyers at more than
$900,000, were awarded to Wright's publisher by the Canberra court,
which upheld lower court decisions that had all favored the
publisher.
   Wright, 73, was delighted and planning a ``quiet celebration''
on his horse farm in Tasmania, said his lawyer, Malcolm Turnbull.
   Britain's deputy high commissioner in Canberra, Malcolm Dougal,
told Independent Radio News after the hearing: ``We still believe
that a crown servant has a duty of obligation, a duty of
confidentiality to the government. We are naturally disappointed.''
   Dougal told the British network that it was up to London to
consider whether to continue the fight in other countries.
   ``Spycatcher'' has been banned in Britain and colonial Hong Kong
by government legal action. Another hearing in the continuing fight
to maintain the ban in Britain takes place before House of Lords
judges on June 13.
   Despite the bans, the book has sold more than 1.4 million copies
worldwide and 250,000 copies in Australia.
   Carol Bennetto, spokeswoman for Octopus Publishing Group, which
controls Wright's publishers, Heinemann, said in London today:
   ``When this all started almost three years ago we were worried
that Peter would never see the fruit of his labors being published
because he has been so ill. It is delightful that he now can.''
   Wright's book, easily available in Britain in U.S.-published
copies, describes how the British intelligence community bugged and
burgled its way around London, snooping on individuals, politicians
and foreign embassies.
   It alleges that right-wing intelligence officers plotted in the
1970s to destabilize the Labor government of then Prime Minister
Harold Wilson.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher told the House of Commons that
the book threatened national security, but Wright said he hadn't
revealed any secrets jeopardizing Britain.
   In its ruling, the court said the British government had not
sought to enforce private rights or private interests in a foreign
state.
   It said Britain's primary interest had been to ensure the
continued secrecy of MI-5's operations and to protect national
security.
   The judges said it was tempting to suggest that because of the
close relationship between Britain and Australia an exception
should be made to enable Britain to enforce its law in Australian
courts.
   But, the court said, ``there are no manageable standards by
which courts can resolve such an issue and its determination would
inevitably present a risk of embarrassment in Australia's relations
with other countries.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
