<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PregnancyRates     06-02 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pregnancy Rates,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Pregnancy, Abortion Rates Higher Than Many Industrialized
Countries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. women have higher rates of unplanned
pregnancies and abortions than women in many other industrialized
countries, according to a study.
   The study by the Alan Guttmacher Institute, a New York-based
organization that examines fertility issues, also found that U.S.
women relied more on abortion and less on contraception to limit
births than women in most other Western nations.
   U.S. women of reproductive age averaged 2.56 pregnancies and
0.76 abortions, according to the study. Only Greece and Ireland
showed higher pregnancy rates, at 4.33 and 3.23, respectively,
among the nations studied.
   Greece also had a higher abortion rate, 2.24, as did Italy,
0.80. The study, of all countries in Western Europe plus Australia,
New Zealand, Canada and the United States, appears in the current
issue of the institute's Family Planning Perspectives.
   The lowest pregnancy rates were in West Germany, with 1.64, and
the Netherlands, with 1.68. The lowest abortion rates were in
Ireland, with 0.15, and the Netherlands, with 0.18.
   Abortion is outlawed in Ireland and Belgium, although abortions
are still relatively easy to to obtain in Belgium, the researchers
said.
   The study found that 51.2 percent of pregnancies in the United
States in 1983 were unplanned, compared with 31.8 percent in Great
Britain and 17 percent in the Netherlands.
   Many contraceptives used in Europe and elsewhere are not
approved for use in the United States, said Dr. Jacqueline D.
Forrest, vice president for research of the institute. The more
contraceptive choices available, the more likely a woman will find
one that she will use consistently, she said.
   In addition, the study found that U.S. women are less likely to
use birth control pills or intrauterine devices than women in other
developed countries, Ms. Forrest said. These are the most effective
forms of birth control.
   The researchers said some method of contraception was used in
1982 by 54 percent of U.S. women between ages 15 to 44. That level
ranked low, and was similar to that of Portugal and Spain.
   Birth control techniques used by 37 percent of U.S. women
included pills, IUD or male or female sterilization, a ``medium''
level compared with the other countries. That ranking is largely
due to the widespread use of sterilization in the United States for
women older than 30, the researchers said.
   The study used the most recent data available. The U.S. abortion
rates are 1983 figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
