<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HassledEmbassy 1stLd-Writethru a0407 06-02 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hassled Embassy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0407,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires, Bugs, Spy Dust and Glasnost Harrass This Embassy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New 1st graf with Reagan stop at embassy; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, ``Amid it xxx''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan stopped by one of America's most
hassled embassies today, saluting diplomats and staff who have
lived through a ``spy dust'' scare, Soviet bugging, alleged
security breaches by Marine guards and a fire.
   Amid it all, the blossoming of superpower relations and the
radical changes in Soviet society ushered in by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev have dramatically increased the workload of America's
official eyes and ears in the Soviet Union.
   An American diplomat said the embassy workers were grateful to
Reagan for taking the time to have breakfast with them and their
families.
   ``He has these embassy visits wherever he goes, but in Moscow in
particular he's certainly aware of the unusual difficulties we've
had,'' the diplomat said, speaking on condition he not be
identified.
   The biggest jolt to the comfort and convenience of the folks at
No. 19-23 Tchaikovsky Street came Oct. 22, 1986, when the Kremlin
retaliated for U.S. expulsions of Soviet diplomats. It ordered 260
Soviets to stop cooking, cleaning, driving, translating and
answering phones at the Moscow embassy and U.S. consulate in
Leningrad.
   Diplomats had to do their own driving, cleaning and other
chores. Donna Hartman, the wife of then-Ambassador Arthur Hartman,
took over the gardening at her residence.
   ``We did what we had to do. It wasn't heroic, but it is somewhat
satisfying in knowing we survived it,'' recalled one diplomat who
mopped floors and carried supplies around the embassy for six
months.
   Gradually the embassy has bounced back, becoming a more
efficient operation by necessity.
   The diplomatic staff was cut to make room for American staff
support under a Soviet-imposed personnel ceiling of 225. The
government brought in a Los Angeles-based company, Pacific
Architects and Engineers, to run the embassy. It now has 84 support
employees.
   The diplomat said the arrangement has worked well.
   ``The Pacific Architects and Engineers people meshed in very
well,'' she said.
   But some officials traveling with Reagan say privately that the
embassy diplomats remain overworked, and haven't been concentrating
enough on their main duties: filing cables back to Washington on
what's going on in the Soviet Union. They also complain that the
embassy didn't prepare well enough for the Reagan-Gorbachev summit.
   Embassy spokesman Richard Gilbert admits the staff is having
trouble coping.
   ``We need more hands. At a time when U.S.-Soviet contacts are
exploding, the number of hands is limited by other than the
personnel practices of the U.S. government,'' he said in reference
to the Soviet-imposed staff limit.
   The diplomats are feeling under extra pressure since Hartman was
succeeded by John Matlock, who is described by embassy press
officer Michael Hurley as a ``hard taskmaster.''
   The summit itself and the frequent visits by Secretary of State
George P. Shultz have been an extra load on the staff, Hurley said.
   ``These visits prevent us from doing what we're here for:
looking at Soviet society and explaining it to people back home,''
he said.
   In addition to the withdrawal of the Soviet employees, the
embassy has faced these problems in the recent years:
   _In 1985, the embassy annnounced it had found traces of a
chemical dubbed ``spy dust'' that Soviet agents were alleged to be
using to track American diplomats. It turned out the substance was
not believed to be hazardous.
   _Last spring, a scandal erupted over charges that U.S. Marine
guards had allowed Soviet agents inside secret areas of the
embassy. Many of the charges fizzled, but Marine Sgt. Clayton
Lonetree, an embassy guard in 1985 and 1986, was convicted of
espionage for giving the KGB the identities of CIA agents and the
floor plans to the U.S. embassies in Moscow and Vienna.
   _Also last spring, U.S. officials revealed that the uncompleted
$191 million new Moscow embassy office building was riddled with
hidden KGB listening devices. Government investigation panels have
recommended the top floors of the building be stripped off.
   _Fire broke out Feb. 17 in an unoccupied fifth-floor residential
section of the aging main office building. Two U.S. congressmen who
inspected the building in April of last year had called it a
``firetrap and unsafe by accepted standards for general working
conditions.''
   _And, off and on for 25 years, the Soviets have bombarded the
embassy with microwave radiation. Despite intense investigation, no
one in the American government is willing to say whether the
purpose is espionage, interference with U.S. intelligence-gathering
operations, or an attempt to affect the health, minds or behavior
of Americans working in the embassy. Low-power microwave signals
continue to be detected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
