<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BuildingCollapse     06-02 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Building Collapse,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Store Collapses around Owner's Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZANESVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of a clothing store owner was
trying to call her husband about cracks she'd noticed in the walls
and windows when the 136-year-old brick building collapsed around
her.
   Susan Wade, who was the only person in the four-story Larry Wade
Inc. building when it collapsed Wednesday evening, suffered only
bumps and bruises, authorities said. She escaped by crawling
through what had been a storefront display window.
   ``I was talking to my son on the phone, trying to find out where
Larry was when it happened,'' Mrs. Wade said.
   ``I thought I was dead; it's awful to think you're dead.''
   The collapse tore down power lines, sparking a fire that spewed
heavy smoke and forced the evacuation of more than 100 residents
within three blocks of the building in this east-central Ohio city
of 28,500 residents.
   The evacuees, many of whom were taken to an American Red Cross
center, were allowed to go home early this morning.
   Police today said the cause of the collapse had not been
determined.
   Before the collapse, bystanders heard glass breaking in the
building and told police, who notified Mrs. Wade.
   Darlene Massey, who was in a law office across the street, said
she saw Mrs. Wade enter the building.
   Just then, a tractor-trailer rig rolled past and the building
fell apart, Ms. Massey said. The sides of the structure and part of
the front crumbled, while the back wall remained standing.
   ``It's amazing that she's alive,'' Ms. Massey said.
   The clothing store building was built in 1852. There was no
immediate estimate of the cost of the damage. The building was
purchased in 1974 for $37,500, the family said.
   Steve Wade, son of the Wades, said the building contained
offices on the second floor and a basketball court on the fourth
floor. He said the third floor ``didn't have much of anything.''
</TEXT>
