<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolShootings     06-02 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shootings,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunwoman Was Being Treated With Experimental Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman who invaded a suburban school and
fatally shoot an 8-year-old boy dead and wounded six people was
being treated with an experimental drug used to control a
psychiatric disorder, blood tests found.
   Traces of the drug clomipramine _ known by the trade name
Anafrail _ were the only drug that turned up in tests performed in
conjunction with the autopsy on Laurie Dann, Cook County Medical
Examiner Robert Stein said Wednesday.
   It was unclear where she received the drug, but her psychiatrist
at the University of Wisconsin was authorized to dispense it, the
drug manufacturer said.
   On May 20, Ms. Dann, 30, walked into the Hubbard Woods
Elementary School in Winnetka, shot a boy in the bathroom and then
entered a 2nd-grade classroom and shot five other youngsters.
   She fled the school and entered a nearby home where she shot a
20-year-old man who tried to seize the gun. Later, as police
surrounded the house in the posh suburb, Ms. Dann killed herself.
   Gloria Martini, a spokeswoman for Ciba-Geigy Corp., the New
Jersey manufacturer of Anafrail, said tests of the drug were being
conducted with government approval on 1,300 adult patients at 21
centers around the country.
   The company has been selling the drug outside the United States
for treatment of people suffering from ``obsessive-compulsive
disorders,'' Ms. Martini said.
   ``Carried to the extreme, some people spend eight hours in the
shower,'' she said, noting the drug also is used to check
``repetitive thoughts of random violence.''
   Ms. Dann exhibited various symptoms of the disorder during the
last few years. Residents of an apartment complex in Madison, Wis.,
where she once lived said Ms. Dann often rode the elevator for
hours.
   Ms. Martini said the Madison psychiatrist who was treating Ms.
Dann, was participating in tests of the drug at a university clinic.
   She said the drug was effective during the first phase of
testing that ended in December, but statistical reports were still
being compiled.
</TEXT>
