<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Italian Journalist Freed From Prison After 6{ Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian journalist convicted of
espionage after entering Afghanistan with anti-communist guerrillas
was freed today after 6{ months in jail, an Italian Embassy staff
member said.
   Fausto Bililavo was granted clemency by President Najib after
President Francesco Cossiga of Italy appealed for the reporter's
freedom.
   Last week, Najib pardoned French photojournalist Alain Guillo
after receiving a similar appeal from President Francois Mitterrand
of France.
   Bilislavo, who worked for the tiny Albatross News Agency, and
Guillo, a free-lancer, entered Afghanistan separately last year
with guerrillas who are fighting the Afghan army and the Soviet
troops supporting the Najib government.
   Bilislavo left Kabul this morning in the company of an Italian
delegation that arrived in the Afghan capital earlier this week to
deliver Cossiga's letter, according to the embassy staff member,
who spoke on condtion of anonymity.
   The noncommercial Italian flight was headed directly to Rome.
The delegation was headed by Bruno Bottai, secretary-general of the
Italian foreign Ministry.
   Both Bilislavo and Guillo had been jailed at Kabul's
Pul-I-Charki prison after being found guilty of spying. Both men
denied the charges.
   Bilislavo, 24, was arrested Nov. 14. He was convicted in March
and sentenced to seven years in prison.
</TEXT>
