<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bosch-Parole     06-02 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bosch-Parole,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Parole for Anti-Castro Militant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge early today denied a request that
he release an anti-communist Cuban-American who was convicted in
this country as a terrorist but is considered a hero by opponents
of Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
   U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler rejected Orlando Bosch's
petition for parole after reviewing more than 700 classified and
unclassified documents.
   Hoeveler made no mention of his proposal Wednesday that Bosch be
released from jail and put under house arrest pending a government
decision on whether to expel him.
   The proposal drew immediate opposition from the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
   The judge said today that the government has a ``legitimate and
bona fide reason'' wanting to expel Bosch. ``The petitioner has
failed to demonstrate that the attorney general has acted in bad
faith,'' he ruled.
   Bosch has been in jail since February, when he returned to the
United States. He fled the country in 1974 while on probation for a
1968 bazooka attack on a Polish ship that had been involved in
trade with Cuba.
   His case now goes to the regional commissioner of the INS in
Dallas.
   Bosch's attorney, Hank Adorno, was expected to appeal Hoeveler's
order to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta.
   Bosch remained in custody today without bail at the federal
Metropolitan Correctional Center south of Miami.
   Last week, a chanting crowd of 200 Cuban-Americans gathered
outside the federal courthouse to demand his freedom.
   Hoeveler said Wednesday that his house-arrest proposal might
ensure ``domestic tranquility.''
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Patricia Kenny, representing the
INS, said releasing Bosch would ``send the wrong message to the
community.''
   ``Terrorism is terrorism, no matter how long ago it took
place,'' she said.
</TEXT>
