<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TexasStorms     06-02 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Storms,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Survey Damage From Heavy Rains And Dam-Burst</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COMANCHE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain-sodden residents began clearing muck
and debris and repairing flood damage to their homes after a
4{-foot wall of water burst through an earthen dam, forcing about
60 people to evacuate.
   The heavy thunderstorms dropped up to 14 inches of rain on
Comanche on Tuesday and early Wednesday, flooding the north-central
Texas town, briefly shutting down some highways and obliterating
the dam on 100-acre Lake Eanes.
   The town's 4,100 residents were told they could return to their
homes Wednesday morning. The sun came out Wednesday afternoon while
residents picked through the muddy debris.
   ``We've lived here 22 years, and it's never gotten this high
before,'' said Maida Godfrey, 40. ``It came up to the porch only
one other time.''
   The flood emergency was over by Wednesday night, said Hazel
Carouth of the Comanche County Sheriff's Department.
   Mrs. Godfrey pointed to grass and mud stains 4{ feet high on the
white wals of her home, which lies on Indian Creek downstream from
Lake Eanes. She estimated about $30,000 damage to her house.
   Mrs. Godfrey said she and her 18-year-old son, Sheridan, ran up
a hill to the home of Earl Wadelle, Lake Eanes' owner, around 3
a.m., near the flood's apex.
   About two hours later, she said, water surged through the middle
of the earthen dam, which was built in the 1930s. Lake Eanes was
completely drained.
   The dam on Lake Comanche, which is downstream from Lake Eanes,
held but water spilled over its lip, said Duane Ogle, a teacher at
Comanche High School where about 60 residents stayed until the
floodwaters subsided.
   Full damage estimates were not available. As much as $100,000 in
inventory at Comanche Carpet and Tile was ruined by the
floodwaters, said owner Randy Martin. ``I don't know what we're
going to do yet,'' Martin said.
   North along U.S. 377, the floodwaters blocked several
underpasses and bridges with logs and other debris. The driver of a
tractor-trailer rig reportedly swam to safety as floodwaters washed
his truck off the road.
</TEXT>
