<HEAD>Passenger On `Monkey Business' Selling Shoes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman Donna Rice claimed sold the infamous
picture of her perched on presidential hopeful Gary Hart's lap to a
supermarket tabloid a year ago says she's glad to be out of the
limelight.
   ``After a wild month of May last year, things have been quiet,''
said Lynn Armandt, who was on board the yacht ``Monkey Business''
with Hart and Rice when the photo was taken.
   ``That's in the past,'' she said, declining to talk about the
incident further. She said in an interview in today's Daily News
that she hasn't talked with Rice since then. ``I haven't talked to
Mr. Hart, either.''
   Armandt, who moved from Fort Lauderdale, Fla., to New York last
year, said she is selling shoes.
   ``Sometimes (customers) make the connection when I hand them my
card,'' she said.
