<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Order     06-02 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Order,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sex Offender Submits to Court-Ordered AIDS Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted sex offender could face a more severe
sentence if he tests positive for the AIDS virus after the state
Court of Appeals refused to overturn a lower court ruling requiring
the test, a prosecutor said.
   Steven G. Farmer, a 34-year-old former flight attendant, took
the test Wednesday. He was convicted in April of two counts of
patronizing a juvenile male prostitute and two counts of sexual
exploitation of a minor.
   Deputy Prosecutor Rebecca Roe contended that Farmer knew he had
tested positive for the virus when he had contact with the two
prostitutes, including sexual intercourse with one of them.
   Jurors who convicted Farmer were not told he was believed to
have the virus for acquired immune defiency syndrome, which attacks
the body's immune system and can be transmitted through sexual
intercourse.
   On Tuesday, Court of Appeals commissioner William Ellis upheld a
May 24 Superior Court ruling that Farmer submit to the test before
his sentencing Tuesday.
   Ellis said there was a legitimate concern that Farmer, who is on
court-supervised release, would continue to engage in the same
sexual conduct.
   Defense attorney Michael Iaria appealed Ellis' decision, but a
three-judge appeals panel later upheld the ruling.
   By court order, the test results will not be made public. But
Ms. Roe has said that if Farmer tests positive for the virus, she
would use that information to argue that Farmer's conduct is an
aggravating factor that warrants a 10-year sentence.
   The standard sentencing range is between two years, seven months
and three years, seven months.
   Iaria argued the test would violate a state law barring
mandatory tests for the AIDS virus.
   However, Ellis said the law limits health officials, not judges.
   Joining Iaria's attempt to block the order were the American
Civil Liberties Union of Washington and the Washington State
Privacy Lobby.
</TEXT>
