<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar posted modest gains in light European
trading trading today. Gold bullion fell.
   Foreign exchange traders cited improved U.S. trade performance
and firmer interest rates for the dollar's continued climb.
   Activity was muted, however, by the closing of West German
markets for a national holiday and by a scarcity of commercial
orders, they said.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.7287 West German marks, up from 1.7255
   _1.4425 Swiss francs, up from 1.4390
   _5.8470 French francs, up from 5.8270
   _1.9384 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9330
   _1,288.25 Italian lire, up from 1,282.50
   _1.2336 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2319
   The British pound continued its steady decline from highs
reached last month. It traded at $1.8165, down from $1.8220.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 125.68 Japanese yen, up from
Wednesday's close of 125.35 yen. In later London trading today, the
dollar reached 125.95 yen.
   Profit-taking on platinum's recent surge pushed gold lower.
   London's main bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $454.60 a troy ounce, down from $456.50 late
Wednesday.
   Gold was bid at $454.70 in Zurich, down from $457.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $455.38, down
from $458.55.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $6.75 a troy ounce,
down from $6.79.
