<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Strike     06-02 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Strike,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>130,000 Engineers And Technicians On Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's 130,000 unionized engineers,
technicians and humanities and social science graduates went on
strike today, disrupting the country's airports, industrial plants
and universities.
   Israel's state-run radio and television halted broadcasts and
the only station operating was Israel army radio.
   The 24-hour strike of the three unions was announced last week
and started as scheduled at midnight. The Finance Ministry
announced an accord with the unions in the early morning hours, but
the strike was already in motion.
   Some disruptions were reported at Ben Gurion International
airport near Tel Aviv, where airport director Motti Debbie said
``every passenger has to take into account that his departure may
be delayed.''
   The strike shut down plants of the government-run Aviation
Industry, military factories, the high technology industries and
some plants belonging to the Histadrut, the country's largest trade
union federation, army radio said.
   About 1,400 engineers and technicians at the national Electric
Company were on strike, too, said a company official, Rafi
Ben-Sira. He said electricity supply would be maintained.
   Also affected were the national telephone company and the post
service.
   At Tel Aviv University, about 500 engineers and administration
officials did not show up for work, shutting down laboratories and
computers, said spokeswoman Carol Cooke.
   Hebrew University reported a similar situation.
   At night, representatives of the trade unions signed an accord
outlining the framework for trade negotiations in 1988-1989, said
Finance Ministry spokesman Yitzhak Feinberg. He termed the accord
``a real breakthrough.''
   He said it stipulated a unified wage increase for all the
unions, which would then be free to decide how to distribute the
increase to their members. Several major trade unions have already
joined the agreement, he added. The rate of the increase would be
negotiated separately.
</TEXT>
