<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest     06-02 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protests Reported In Armenia, Government Cancels Reporters' Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenian activists have been protesting around the
clock in Armenia's capital and staging a general strike in a region
in neighboring Azerbaijan that they want annexed to their republic,
an organizer said.
   The Soviet government, meanwhile, canceled a state-sponsored
press trip to Armenia without giving a reason. The ethnic
strife-torn southern region is closed to foreigners.
   And in Geneva, the Intergovernmental Committee for Migration
reported that Armenian emigration from the Soviet Union is headed
for an all-time high in 1988 following a new sharp increase in May.
   Regina Boucault, spokeswoman for the committee, said 5,305
Armenians have been allowed to leave since January, including 1,501
in May alone.
   This compares with a total of 6,633 departures in 1980, the
highest total since 1977, when the committee began monitoring the
family reunification program financed by the United States.
   Former political prisoner Georgy Homizuri said by telephone from
Yerevan on Wednesday that demonstrators had for six days staged a
sit-in outside the city's Opera Theater. They are demanding that
Nagorno-Karabakh, an Armenian-dominated region in the neighboring
republic of Azerbaijan, be turned over to Armenia
   Ethnic Azeris are predominantly Moslem, while most Armenians are
Christian.
   ``They have been demonstrating day and night, rain or shine,''
said Homizuri, 46, who was released in February 1987 after spending
four years in a labor camp for his writings circulated in the
intellectual underground.
   Homizuri said the demonstrators want the parliament of Armenia,
the Supreme Soviet, to consider their demand at a June 15 meeting.
   In Stepanakert, the main city of Nagorno-Karabakh, a general
strike that has shut down mass transit and factories for about a
week continued, according to Homizuri.
   Intourist, the Soviet travel agency for foreigners, advertised a
special trip to Yerevan for reporters covering this week's summit
meeting between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   The trip, scheduled from Friday to Monday, was to have been the
first opportunity for foreign journalists to visit the troubled
region since demonstrations and rioting broke out.
   On Wednesday, the official news agency Tass carried a Foreign
Ministry announcement that said the trip was canceled. It gave no
reason.
   Strikes and street rallies began in the region in February and
broke out again recently.
   On Tuesday, Tass said the former party chief in the Azerbaijani
city of Sumgait, where ethnic rioting related to the territorial
dispute killed 32 people in February, had been expelled from the
Communist Party. Also dismissed from the organization was the
former party chief in Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost'' has brought more open
discussion of the Soviet Union's problems, but foreign reporters
frequently have found their access to troubled regions cut off,
either through disruption of telephone calls or travel bans.
</TEXT>
