<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0708EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LibelAppeal     06-02 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Libel Appeal,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Agrees Libel Suit Should Be Retried</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporters have an absolute right not to
reveal confidential sources during legal proceedings, the state
Supreme Court ruled in throwing out a $4.5 million libel judgment
against The Philadelphia Inquirer.
   The unanimous opinion filed Tuesday lets stand a Superior Court
ruling that reaffirmed Pennsylvania's Shield Law and reversed a
1983 verdict won by Richard A. Sprague, a lawyer and former first
assistant district attorney in Philadelphia.
   The Supreme Court upheld the lower court's ruling that Sprague's
libel suit against the Inquirer be retried.
   The suit involves several 1973 articles that reported
allegations of Sprague participating in an illegal wiretapping
scheme.
   Other articles raised questions about whether Sprague, as chief
of the homicide division of the district attorney's office in 1963,
extended preferential treatment to the son of former State Police
Commissioner Rocco Urella Sr. in a homicide case.
   Sprague denied both sets of allegations.
   During a six-week trial in 1983, Common Pleas Judge Charles A.
Lord ruled the jury had to disregard any evidence presented by the
Inquirer based on confidential sources.
   Rather than divulge the reporters' sources, the newspapers'
attorneys chose not to present the evidence.
   The Shield Law, enacted in 1937, states that no reporter ``shall
be required to disclose the source of any information procured or
obtained by such person, in any legal proceeding, trial or
investigation before any government unit.''
   The Superior Court ruled in 1986 that the Shield Law gave the
newspaper the statutory right to withhold the identity of its
sources, and ordered a new trial.
   Writing for the Supreme Court, Chief Justice Robert N.C. Nix Jr.
said the Shield Law's language ``is in no way ambiguous'' and
agreed with the Superior Court that Lord had committed an error by
barring the Inquirer's evidence.
   However, Nix differed with the Superior Court's broad
interpretation of the law, saying that just because evidence based
on confidential sources is admitted doesn't mean its reliability is
guaranteed.
   ``The plaintiff is free to introduce rebuttal evidence and-or
argue that the record does not disclose any evidence to support the
reliability of the information,'' Nix wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
