<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Typhoon     06-02 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Typhoon,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Typhoon Susan Pays Return Visit, One Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Susan swept across the
northern Philippines and Taiwan today, killing at least one person,
flooding rice paddies and driving families from their homes,
officials said.
   The Red Cross said a 5-year-old boy, Dexter Aquino, was killed
Wednesday in a landslide triggered by heavy rains in Olongapo City,
50 miles northwest of Manila in the Philippines.
   Typhoon Susan's 84-mph winds spawned a freak tornado in Cainta
district outside Manila that destroyed 18 houses today, Red Cross
spokeswoman Teresita Pena said.
   Nine-year-old Dahlia Mabalot fell into the nearby Kasibulan
River when her house was blown away, but she was rescued, Pena
said. He added that several families were also evacuated from three
coastal villages in Cavite province which borders Manila to the
south.
   The tropical depression developed within Philippine waters
Sunday and passed over Batanes province Tuesday. It came back as a
typhoon late Wednesday.
   A Philippines government weather bulletin said that as of this
afternoon, the typhoon's center was 192 miles north of Batanes, the
Philippines' northernmost province, moving toward Japan.
   In Taiwan, the typhoon swept through the southeastern part of
the country today, disrupting highway and rail traffic, flooding
rice paddies and causing power outages, officials said. No injuries
were reported.
   The state-run Taiwan Power Co. said power outages were reported
in 16,000 households in eastern Taitung, the hardest hit county,
where 12 inches of rain fell in a 14-hour period.
</TEXT>
