<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IndianAsbestos     06-02 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indian Asbestos,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Lung Disease Linked To Asbestos in Silver Making</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of asbestos to make silver jewelry and
whiten moccasins for ceremonial dances is responsible for an
outbreak of a rare form of lung cancer among New Mexican Indians,
doctors report today.
   Doctors from U.S. Public Health Service began an investigation
after finding that the incidence of malignant mesothelioma, a form
of lung cancer associated with asbestos, was 1,000 times higher
than expected at one Indian pueblo.
   Five people, all from the same village, had the disease between
1970 and 1985.
   Dr. Richard J. Driscoll and other researchers reported their
findings in the New England Journal of Medicine.
   Four of the victims were silversmiths. The researchers found
that they typically used asbestos mats, which they called pounding
boards, to insulate their work tables against the heat of torches
and molten metal.
   All five also participated in ceremonial dances. Before the
dances, the Indians used asbestos to whiten their buckskin leggings
and moccasins.
   The researchers said efforts have been made to educate Indians
about the hazards of asbestos and to find alternative materials for
silversmiths and ceremonial dancers.
</TEXT>
