<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SeabrookWithdrawal 1stLd-Writethru a0492 06-02 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seabrook Withdrawal, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0492,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Seabrook Investor Votes to Pull Out Of Stalled Nuke Plant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, `The action ...' to CORRECT that Shoreham
never went into commercial operation sted never generated
electricity.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUDLOW, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of the fourth-largest investor in
the Seabrook nuclear power plant have voted to pull out, and
opponents of the stalled project say that could spell its doom.
   A plant spokesman said he was confident the project would
survive Wednesday's decision by the board of directors of the
Massachusetts Municipal Wholesale Electric Co., which has an 11.6
percent stake in Seabrook.
   The electrical cooperative's eight-member board voted
unanimously to withhold its June 1 payment of $1.6 million toward
building and maintaining the New Hampshire project.
   The cooperative said the strain the project has put on relations
with Massachusetts has hurt customers. The cooperative comprises 34
municipal electric systems, and supplies power to 28 electric
departments in Massachusetts and eight in other Northeast states.
   The action came less than a week after New York state reached an
agreement with Long Island Lighting Co. to abandon the $5.3 billion
Shoreham nuclear plant, which also has never gone into commercial
operation.
   It ``reflects the bottom-line reality that Seabrook is a
teetering financial dinosaur about to become extinct,'' said Rep.
Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., a Seabrook opponent.
   ``I believe there's a major funding problem for the project and
it is so grossly uneconomic right now that this may be the end of
it,'' said Bob Backus, a lawyer for the Seacoast Anti-Pollution
League, which has fought the project since its inception.
   Seabrook spokesman Rob Williams disagreed. ``Our detractors have
said from the beginning that each hurdle we face has meant the end
of the project, and each time they have been wrong,'' he said.
``The rest of the owners remain committed and the bottom line
remains the plant is very much needed for New England.''
   However, Seabrook's top three owners indicated that they
wouldn't pick up the cooperative's share. One, Public Service
Company of New Hampshire, has filed for protection from its
creditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy law.
   Public Service Company has a 36 percent share. United
Illuminating of New Haven, Conn., has a 17.5 percent piece and
Eastern Utilities Associates of Rhode Island has 12 percent.
   Under a plan approved by the board, the Massachusetts
cooperative plans to ask the other owners to assume its
construction and maintenance costs or to buy its shares outright
under the joint ownership agreement.
   The matter could come to a head in eight months, when the grace
period for overdue bills is up and the other investors exhaust the
money the cooperative has deposited in a prepayment fund.
   General Manager Gary L. Hunt acknowledged that cooperative would
lose the $875 million it has already invested in the plant, which
cost $5.4 billion to build but lacks the approved evacuation plans
required for commercial operation.
   Hunt also acknowledged that the cooperative could be paying off
the bonds issued for the Seabrook investment for the next 30 years.
The cooperative will pay $91 million yearly for its long-term
Seabrook debt in 1989 and $15 million to $20 million annually to
support the idle plant.
   But he said the project was a losing business proposition even
if the plant's license is eventually approved.
   ``The alienation that Seabrook has caused between MMWEC and the
Commonwealth (of Massachusetts) has had adverse consequences for
Massachusetts public power electric consumers.''
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis has refused to authorize tax-exempt
financing for the project, Hunt said.
   Hunt predicted ``serious rate increases for some participants on
top of the participants' already high rate levels caused by
Seabrook.''
</TEXT>
