<2ND_LINE>PM-Phones At Last,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Full Telephone Service By Sunday In Suburban Chicago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HINSDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Full telephone service should be restored
Sunday to the suburban Chicago communities affected by a fire May 8
at an Illinois Bell Co. switching station, the utility said.
   Half of the 35,000 customers were back on line last Friday. The
rest will be able to make all local and long distance calls by
12:01 a.m. Sunday, said James Eibel, Illinois Bell vice president
for operations.
   The fire at the switching station here turned into a
communications crisis. Phones in all or part of seven communities
were dead for several days before Illinois Bell gradually restored
local then long distance dialing.
   Hundreds of laborers have worked at all hours to replace
fire-and water-damaged hardware.
   ``This extraordinary effort by all our people involved has
allowed us to move ... quickly to restore customer service
following the worst service outage in our history,'' Eibel said
Wednesday.
   Meanwhile, the Illinois Commerce Commission said it has hired
Forensic Technologies International Corp. of Annapolis, Md., to
investigate the fire beginning today.
   ``The staff felt there was a real need for an independent
investigation by a company with proven expertise to determine the
cause of the fire and steps that might be taken to prevent a
similar occurrence,'' said spokesman David Farrell.

</TEXT>
