<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Hurkos     06-02 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Hurkos,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch Psychic Dead at Age 77</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Hurkos, who claimed psychic powers
stemming from a brain injury and helped police investigate the
Boston Strangler case and the Manson family murders, has died of
heart failure at age 77.
   Hurkos was stricken Wednesday in a medical complex near
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center after a visit to his doctor, said
publicist Barbara Silver. He had had a portion of his cancerous
right lung removed in April, she said.
   Hurkos helped authorities investigate the 1969 murders of
actress Sharon Tate and supermarket owner Leno LaBianca and his
wife, who were among eight people killed by followers of Charles
Manson.
   Hurkos said he told authorities the person responsible for the
slayings was a bearded man named Charlie.
   Hurkos also worked on the Boston Strangler case, later made into
a movie starring Tony Curtis, and on murders of college students in
Ann Arbor, Mich., Mrs. Silver said.
   Even after Albert DeSalvo confessed to being the Strangler and
was convicted, Hurkos maintained that another man was the killer.
   Hurkos said he became psychic in 1941 after falling from a
ladder and suffering a brain injury. Upon regaining consciousness,
he realized he had ``an ability to pierce the barriers that
separate the past, present and future,'' according to his biography.
   Hurkos said he was able to see things by touching objects.
   ``I see pictures in my mind like a television screen. When I
touch something, I can then tell what I see,'' he said.
   He appeared in the movies ``The Amazing World of Psychic
Phenomena,'' ``Mysterious Monsters,'' ``Now I Lay Me Down to
Sleep'' and ``The Boston Strangler.''
   He was the author of three books, ``Psychic,'' ``The Psychic
World of Peter Hurkos'' and ``Peter Hurkos: I Have Many Lives.''
   Hurkos was born in Dordrecht, Holland, and came to the United
States in 1956 for psychic experiments and lived in the Los Angeles
area about 25 years.
   Survivors include his wife, Stephany Courtney, and seven
children.
</TEXT>
