<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0833EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-EuropeReact     06-02 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Europe React,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Europeans See Summit Success Despite Scant Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European newspapers today declared the Moscow
summit a success despite the absence of major advances on arms
control.
   Editorialists applauded President Reagan's performance and his
disavowal of his earlier characterization of the Soviet Union as
``an evil empire.''
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl sent a message of thanks to
Reagan after five days of summit talks with Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev.
   Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland said in a
statement:
   ``With this fourth summit and the signing of the INF
(intermediate-range nuclear missile) treaty, we are facing a
historic watershed in European and international postwar history.''
   ``We have ahead of us a radically changed picture, both in
dialogue and in climate, between the two superpowers. What has
happened now makes new breakthroughs possible in East-West
cooperation,'' Brundtland said.
   Sir Michael Howard, a senior Oxford University historian, wrote
of Reagan in the Times of London: ``It has been a brilliant
performance. ... He is truly a remarkable man, and his place in
history is certainly assured.''
   Also in London, the left-leaning Guardian commented: ``There's a
pretty durable foundation of contact in place.''
   It said: ``When Mr. Reagan, in another era, talks of evil
empires and builds policies based on fear and mistrust, then his
voters, to an extent, share that fear and mistrust, believe that
the Russians are coming to get them.
   ``Such beliefs can't easily be sustained when their front-parlor
screens are filled by those same Russians (not to mention the newly
converted Mr. Reagan) expressing quite other sentiments.''
   Italy's largest newspaper, left-leaning La Repubblica in Rome,
differed with the Guardian.
   ``Things did not go well for Mikhail Gorbachev. ... One could
clearly see he was disappointed, very disappointed. ... The
ideological disparity between the two camps surfaced more clearly
in Moscow than in the previous summits,'' it said.
   In Paris, the leftist daily Liberation said: ``Mikhail Gorbachev
and Ronald Reagan have but very thin concrete results to add to the
essential dossiers of disarmament and regional conflicts.''
   But it said, ``This `routine' summit was nevertheless not
ordinary. Reagan, who just several years ago could be imagined as
Saint George slaying the Red Dragon of the Evil Empire, made a
skillful crossing to Moscow which he was visiting for the first
time.
   ``... Reagan knew how to suppress his first-class anti-communist
image. ... (But) at the end of the summit, the Kremlin chief was
unable to hide the fact that he was waiting for more,'' Liberation
said.
   The conservative Le Figaro said: ``The success of the Moscow
summit is paradoxically that it did not have major results. ...
This rendezvous appears to have confirmed that American-Soviet
relations have found their cruising rhythm...''
   The Basler Zeitung, an independent Swiss paper, said: ``It
ushered in a new kind of coexistence which has deservedly been
celebrated in Moscow...
   ``The old coexistence was ... a highly unpredictable matter full
of political misunderstandings, full of nuclear risks. The new
coexistence is to be different: calculable, solid,
crisis-resistant.''
</TEXT>
