<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0840EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ExecutionSquad     06-02 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Execution Squad,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seattle-Area Man Denies Justice Department Accusation of War
Crimes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of serving in a pro-Nazi execution
squad that killed tens of thousands of Jews and other civilians in
Latvia during World War II says he will fight a move to strip him
of his U.S. citizenship.
   Valdis W. Didrichsons, 74, concealed his membership in the
Latvian Security Auxiliary Police when he applied for citizenship,
according to a Justice Department complaint filed in U.S. District
Court.
   Didrichsons refused to comment on the case Wednesday except to
describe himself as a retired civil engineer who moved here nine
years ago from Chicago and to say, ``I will fight.''
   His attorney, Peter Berzins, said he didn't know whether
Didrichsons was a member of Arajs Kommando, as the execution unit
was known.
   ``Membership and whether he participated or knew of activity are
two separate things,'' Berzins added.
   The unit, formed to assist in persecuting and killing people
considered racially undesirable or enemies of Nazi Germany,
murdered tens of thousands, said Neal Sher, director of the Justice
Department's Office of Special Investigations.
   The founder, Victor Arajs, died recently in West Germany while
serving a life term for mass murder.
   Assisting in persecution makes a person ineligible to immigrate
to the United States and requires revocation of citizenship. The
denaturalization case against Didrichsons is the first step in a
process that could lead to deportation.
   A native of Latvia, Didrichsons entered the United States in
1950 and became a U.S. citizen in 1956. Latvia is now part of the
Soviet Union.
   Doug Schwartz, manager of Didrichsons' apartment complex, said
Didrichsons lived alone, never caused problems, paid his rent on
time and was ``very gregarious.''
   Didrichsons recently underwent surgery for cancer, Berzins said,
adding that he was awaiting medical records to determine the
seriousness of the illness.
   Berzins said it is difficult to view Arajs Kommando in its
historical setting 45 years later. He noted that in 1941 and 1942,
the Soviet Union and Nazi Germany were fighting in what was then a
neutral country that had been occupied by the Soviets.
   ``People pull strings and jump or face execution themselves,''
he said. ``Certainly the free choice of a person at that time is
severely impacted.''
   Konrads Kalejs of Chicago, who is now on trial in a similar
proceeding, and Mikelis Kirsteins of Syracuse, N.Y., who is facing
trial, served with Didrichsons in the auxiliary police unit in
1941, the government said.
</TEXT>
