<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-RustPlane     06-02 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Rust Plane,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Wants To Sell Cessna That Landed In Red Square</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German company is seeking
to resell the Cessna airplane that pilot Mathias Rust landed in
Moscow's Red Square a year ago, a Hamburg sports flying club
official said today.
   Karlfriedrich Giesie, deputy manager of the Hamburg air club,
said Azuma Royal Cosmetics of Munich had placed advertisements for
the plane in various newspapers. The company had bought the plane
from the club for $88,000.
   The Soviets allowed the Hamburg air club to fly the plane back
to West Germany last October, and the club sold it to Azuma Royal.
   ``Now they (the company) are seeking a huge profit on it and
have advertised it for sale in various places,'' Giesie said in an
interview. He estimated Azuma Royal was asking between $150,000 and
$175,000 for the plane.
   The Associated Press tried repeatedly to contact Azuma Royal
officials by telephone today for comment, but no one answered the
phone. Today was an official holiday in Bavaria.
   Rust, now 20, flew unimpeded over Soviet territory from
Helsinki, Finland, and landed in Red Square on May 28, 1987.
   On Sept. 4, Rust was found guilty of illegal entry into the
Soviet Union, violating international flight regulations and
malicious rowdyism. He was sentenced to four years in a labor camp.
   Rust remains in a Moscow prison, where the Soviets have
permitted his parents and brother to visit him on several occasions.
   One advertisement, which appeared in the May 15 editions of the
Welt am Sonntag newspaper, read: ``Most Famous Airplane To Sell. Do
you want the only airplane to land on Red Place-Moscow on 28th May
1987? Mathias Rust's Cessna 172 will be sold in best conditions.''
   According to Giesie, the Cessna is now parked in a hangar at a
small airport near the city of Uetersen, 15 miles northwest of
Hamburg.
</TEXT>
