<2ND_LINE>PM-Arm Severed,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine-Hour Operation to Reattach Boy's Arm Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old whose right arm was torn off by
a farm conveyor belt remained in critical condition today after an
unsuccessful attempt to reatttach the limb, officials said.
   ``Regrettably, the injury was so severe, with so much
destruction of the tissue, that it was not possible to rejoin the
extremity,'' Dr. Thomas E. McKell, vice president of medical
affairs at Tampa General Hospital, said Wednesday. ``It's tragic
for this young boy and this family.''
   Fidencio Jaurequi of Dade City had gone to a barn at Singletary
Farms on Tuesday where his mother was working on a conveyor belt
that sorts cherry tomatoes, according to Earl Singletary, a
co-owner of the 75-acre farm.
   The boy stuck his arm in the machine and got it caught on a
roller, Singletary said.
   The limb was packed by paramedics in ice and a saline solution.
Fidencio and the arm were taken by helicopter to the hospital.
   Three surgeons from the University of South Florida College of
Medicine worked nine hours to reattach the limb before giving up
early Wednesday.
   The family, seasonal farm workers, has no insurance. The
hospital announced a fund was being set up for the boy at a bank.
