<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BicentennialPigs 1stLd-Writethru a0413 06-02 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bicentennial Pigs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0413,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controverisal Flying Pig Statues Unveiled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-10 pvs bgng `There were ...' to ADD that artist
was born in England and lives in Minneapolis.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sculptor unveiled his four bronze flying
pigs atop a city bicentennial monument, but to the relief of some,
they're a weathered green, not pink.
   ``I changed my mind,'' artist Andrew Leicester said.
   The green and lean pigs top the entrance sculpture at
Bicentennial Commons at Sawyer Point, a new park near downtown and
along the Ohio River.
   The pigs measure 4{ feet from tail to wing tip. They stand on
their hind legs on bright blue replicas of riverboat smokestacks.
Their wings are spread, and stomachs taut and slim.
   ``They're pigs of the '80s _ very trim,'' said Carol Scott, a
visitor from Connecticut who was among a small group of people to
watch Wednesday's unveiling.
   Three pigs covered with black cloth were lifted into place
Tuesday night by a mechanical lift. The fourth was flown in
Wednesday on a US. Coast Guard helicopter and lowered into place.
   ``There were many, many times I thought they would never make
it,'' said Dennis Barrie, director of the Contemporary Arts Center,
which commissioned the $600,000 sculpture.
   The artwork contains 17 elements depicting Cincinnati's history
and its river heritage. The pigs celebrate the city's heyday in the
1880s as ``Porkopolis,'' the Midwest's hog-butchering capital.
   Leicester originally planned to cover the bronze hogs with
copper plating to achieve a lifelike rosy color. But there wasn't
enough time, so he opted for bronze's natural patina of green, he
said.
   ``They're more subdued, more traditional _ much more
appropriate,'' said Leicester, who was born in England and lives in
Minneapolis. ``If you want pink pigs, go to a department store, not
an artist.''
   Pink pigs ``would have been too much,'' agreed Don Scott,
another Connecticut visitor and former Cincinnatian.
   Some Cincinnatians had complained the pigs would make the city
look foolish. They flooded local newspapers and City Council with
letters and calls of protest.
   The council tried to settle the dispute in January by conducting
a hearing to air the gripes. Council members donned plastic pig
snouts for the raucous gathering, and one woman even cradled a
piglet.
   But the mediation failed when the council's attorney said the
councilors were powerless because the sculpture already had been
properly approved.
</TEXT>
