<HEAD>Kentucky Man Credits Nicaraguan Patrol With Saving Sinking Yacht</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kentucky man whose yacht was
reported to have been rammed by gunboats was quoted as saying the
Nicaraguan coast guard saved his craft from sinking in a storm.
   Stoye Milburn, 53, a painter from Kentucky, was towed in his
yacht by a coast guard cutter to Puerto Sandino, 44 miles northwest
of Managua. He said he and his German shepherd dog were on a
pleasure trip to Costa Rica when he was caught in heavy seas and
rescued.
   ``I was treated like a member of the family (by the
Nicaraguans), like a brother, like a gentleman,'' Milburn said
Wednesday. His hometown was not available.
   He spoke in English in an interview at Puerto Sandino with AP
photographer Mario Tapia, and his words were translated into
Spanish by Nicaraguan navy Lt. Jose Vilchez, the port commander.
   Unconfirmed reports, mostly from radio operators who had
monitored his garbled distress calls, had said that Nicaraguan
gunboats had intercepted and rammed the yacht offshore and arrested
Milburn.
   The U.S. Embassy had asked the Nicaraguan government to
investigate.
   Milburn said the bow of the ship was dented in a collision with
the coast guard cutter during the rescue.
   He said he had left a Mexican port, which he did not specify, on
May 25 and the yacht was five times on the point of sinking when it
was caught in heavy storms. He said he had to send out a distress
call Monday and a Nicaraguan coast guard cutter located and rescued
him two miles off Puerto Sandino and later towed the yacht into
port.
   Milburn said he was waiting for the weather to improve so he
could continue his trip to Costa Rica.
</TEXT>
