<HEAD>Haldeman Named Florida Orchestra President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Haldeman, credited with turning around
the once-struggling Dallas Symphony Orchestra, has been named
president and executive director of the deficit-ridden Florida
Orchestra.
   Haldeman, 55, replaces Marshall Rousseau, who resigned in March.
   ``I see myself as a kind of orchestra rejuvenator,'' Haldeman
said Wednesday. ``The situation here is better than when I took
over Dallas.''
   The orchestra has a deficit of about $600,000 for this year and
an accumulated deficit of $800,000.
   As general manager of the Dallas orchestra from 1974-79,
Haldeman is credited with reviving the organization from
near-bankruptcy.
   Haldeman was general manager of the Cincinnati Symphony
Orchestra and May Festival, the orchestra's summer home, from
1963-71. He also was general manager of the Vancouver Symphony and
the Fresno Philharmonic Orchestra.
