<HEAD>Governor Takes to the Air To Promote Highway Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Deukmejian found more trouble
in the air than on the ground during a stint as a traffic reporter.
   Deukmejian took to the air Wednesday in an effort to promote his
highway-funding ballot measure with reports of gridlock horror.
   He had to cope with technical problems that included numerous
airwave silences when his helicopter lost contact with the nine
radio and TV stations receiving his reports. However, things moved
along smoothly below.
   ``Traffic is moving well on the nasty Nimitz,'' the governor's
voice crackled over radio stations.
   ``It looks pretty thin at the Bay Bridge toll plaza,'' he added.
   ``Trouble free,'' he muttered a few minutes later, over
Interstate 680 in Concord.
   ``I guess I've been able to work out all the congestion problems
today,'' Deukmejian joked. ``I think they must be aware of the fact
that I'm up here and I've been able to straighten all this
congestion out very quickly.''
   The governor said he still backs Proposition 74, a measure on
Tuesday's ballot that would raise $1 billion for new highways.
   Jeffrey Schaub of Traffic Central, a Hayward company that hires
out traffic reporters to broadcast stations, gave the governor good
reviews.
   ``He's become very proficient,'' Schaub said. ``We'd hire him.''
