<HEAD>Police: Arab Prostitute Kills Jewish Youth In Jerusalem</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with four Israelis convicted of
illegally meeting with PLO. Pick up 5th graf pvs, ``The Israeli
...'' EDITS thereafter to conform and trim.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Army, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age Arab prostitute shot and killed an
18-year-old Jewish seminary student with a pistol before dawn today
in a park near Israel's parliament building, authorities said.
   Police Chief Yossi Yehudai said the girl's motive was unclear.
The 17-year-old Israeli citizen was arrested later and confessed,
he said.
   In a landmark decision, a court in the city of Ramle convicted
four Israelis of violating a law that bars contacts with the PLO.
   The judges ruled that the four left-wing activists acted
illeglly when they met a 15-member PLO delegation in Costinesti,
Romania, in November 1986.
   Amnon Zichrony, an attorney for the four, told The Associated
Press they were the first people convicted of an Israeli law passed
in 1986 that bars ``unauthorized'' contacts with members of
terrorist groups. Israel considers the Palestine Liberation
Organization a terrorist group.
   Zichrony said his clients, Latif Dory, Yael Lotan, Reuven
Kaminer and Eliezer Feiler, would appeal the decision. They face a
maximum three-year sentence.
   Judge Avraham Baiser rejected defense arguments that the PLO was
not a terrorist organization, saying: ``The acts of terrorism have
not ceased although here and there we do hear some different talk.''
   The Jerusalem attack came a day after Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir warned Palestinian underground leaders to end their
6-month-old uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied lands.
   The Israeli killed today was the third since Arabs in the
territories revolted on Dec. 8. Army figures say 207 Palestinians
have been killed, 157 of them shot to death by soldiers.
   City police spokesman Rafi Levy described the shooting as a
terrorist attack, apparently related to the uprising in the lands
Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East war.
   However, he said other motives for the shooting were being
investigated, including insanity.
   Levy identified the victim as Eliezer Shlesinger, 18, a student
at Sha'arei Chesed, a religious seminary near the park where the
shooting occurred.
   The girl, whom police declined to identify because she is a
minor, went to the park with two clients at about 1:30 a.m., Levy
said.
   They encountered ``two seminary students who were there by
chance. She spoke to them and then suddenly took out a pistol and
fired,'' Levy added.
   Shlesinger was hit by five bullets and killed. The other student
was unhurt, but reportedly being treated for shock.
   Levy said a security officer who passed by the park and heard
the shots grabbed the girl as she fled the scene. She later
admitted to the shooting after questioning, he said.
   Yehudai said the girl lived in Jerusalem and spoke fluent Hebrew.
   A fellow student said Shlesinger went to the park with a friend
``to get fresh air after a long day of studying.''
   Shamir, head of the right-wing Likud bloc, was chosen Wednesday
to be his party's candidate to lead the country if Likud wins the
November general election.
   ``Do we still have to prove that we have the power to cut off
every hand that is raised against us? If we haven't proven it
already, we will have to increase the pressure,'' Shamir told party
delegates.
   Also Wednesday, a military source said the army had started to
negotiate with Arab village leaders in the occupied lands,
promising them rewards if they ensure calm.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin meanwhile met with four
Palestinians from the occupied Gaza Strip, his third such meeting
in a week, a defense official said.
   The participants discussed political issues, such as a final
settlement for the occupied territories, during the two-hour
meeting, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Authorities refused to name the Palestinians who participated in
the meeting, saying their lives might be in danger if the
information was disclosed.
   Israel Television said Army officials on Wednesday met with
leaders of several villages near the West Bank town of Jenin.
   The report said leaders of the village of Yamun reached a
cooperation agreement with the army. The report did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
