<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-SovietTV 1stLd-Writethru a0412 06-02 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Soviet TV, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0412,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Viewers Get Look at Soviet Version of the Evening News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 9th graf to delete reference to No-Doz, ``Vremya opened
xxx''
^By KATHRYN BAKER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greeting, comrades! Let's go to the videotape _
of the farm equipment?
   No, it's not the stuff that great Nielsen ratings are made of,
but it's good enough to pull in 150 million viewers a night in the
Soviet Union.
   ``Vremya,'' the Soviet news show, also picked up a few million
American viewers this week thanks to The Discovery Channel, which
ran it each night of the summit meeting between President Reagan
and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The Discovery Channel, available on cable in about 32 million
households, supplied a running translation with the newscast. The
show, ``As They See It: Soviet Nightly News,'' was introduced by
Hodding Carter.
   If American viewers were surprised by what they saw, quite
possibly so were Soviets.
   Though stodgy farm equipment stories and use of still
photographs instead of videotape illustrated a continuing lack of
sophistication in Soviet television, there were segments of Monday
night's edition of ``Vremya'' that suggested major changes in
Soviet TV coverage since the advent of glasnost, Gorbachev's policy
of openness.
   For instance, there was a report on a meeting between President
Reagan and dissidents. The fact that it was reported at all was
surprising, though it was described rather snidely by a commentator
as not ``objective.'' He added, however, that the Soviet Union
might learn something about human rights from the United States.
   Other segments included coverage of Nancy Reagan's meeting with
cute Moscow schoolchildren who sang ``It's a Small World After
All.'' The Soviet segment was hardly distinguishable from American
coverage of similar events, suggesting fluff is the same the world
over.
   ``Vremya'' opened with the biggest and seemingly dullest story
of the day, the status of arms negotiations, described by a
stylishly dressed anchorwoman in a droning official commentary.
   Much of the reporting on the Reagan-Gorbachev meetings was
traditional: the co-anchors _ the man and woman do not acknowledge
each other's existence _ read official communiques that included
long lists of those present at official events.
   It hardly was exciting television, but important to Soviets who
closely follow the rising and falling fortunes of various officials
as indicated by their public appearances or disappearances.
   There was virtually no contribution from reporters on the scene,
though there was videotape from a banquet the Gorbachevs threw for
the Reagans.
   Carter explained that much of the banquet coverage was cut
because ``Vremya'' ran 35 minutes longer than its usual 40 minutes
to include the speeches by Gorbachev and Reagan in their entirety.
American viewers would long since have switched to ``Wheel of
Fortune.''
   But in the past, Soviet TV cameras were forbidden to show such
scenes as the flower-decked tables at the Gorbachev banquet. And a
waiter could be seen carrying a bottle of wine, despite Gorbachev's
policy of anti-alcoholism.
   Before Gorbachev came to power, the wives of Soviet leaders were
rarely shown on television. But Raisa Gorbachev was seen
prominently sitting just in front of Reagan at the banquet, reading
from the text of his speech as he delivered his remarks. A later
segment treated her as an important Soviet official in her own
right as she dedicated a statue symbolizing peace.
   While the Soviet and American leaders talked, so did Vladimir
Posner and NBC anchor Tom Brokaw for ``Vremya.'' It is a small
world after all, because as every TV journalist, Soviet or
American, knows, when you're stuck with what is basically a no-news
event, what do you do?
   Interview each other.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
