<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SteerJeans     06-02 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steer Jeans,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Park District Approves Steer Dressing for Rodeo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVERMORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city has decided it's all right if
steers wear the pants at rodeos.
   Animal rights activists had asked the Livermore Area Recreation
and Park District Board to ban use of electric prods and the steer
dressing event at the Livermore Rodeo.
   ``Odd animal events are the main issue, not the rodeo,'' said
Paul Miller from the Peninsula Humane Society.
   But the board Wednesday decided to allow both the prods and the
steer dressing event, in which cowboys chase steers and try to
dress their hind legs in a pair of blue jeans.
   ``Many rodeo events don't represent what is done on the ranch''
and should be stopped, said Doll Stanley, a member of the Fund for
Animals.
   The standing-room-only crowd at the agency meeting included more
than 100 flag-waving rodeo fans and only a handful of animal rights
activists. The cowboys in the crowd greeted the decision with
cheers.
   ``If I'm ever reincarnated send me back as a rodeo animal,''
said Jack Roddy, a professional rodeo cowboy.
   Kim Baker, 18-year-old president of the California High School
Rodeo Association, said of the activists' efforts: ``This is the
first step and next year it will be something else. It seems
eventually rodeo is just going to die.''
   The two-day Livermore Rodeo opens June 11.
</TEXT>
