<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0554,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Hyundai Officials Charged In Kidnapping Of Labor Leader</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with student protest in Seoul,
ADDS titles of arrested officials and where Hyundai Engineering is
based. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two senior officials of Hyundai
Engineering and Construction Co. were charged today with hiring a
group of men to kidnap an employee who was trying to organize a
labor union.
   Earlier today, about a dozen radical students hurled rocks at
the headquarters of the giant Hyundai group in Seoul to protest the
kidnapping at the Hyundai subsidiary. No injuries were reported.
   Labor unrest continued at three other Hyundai subsidiaries in
southern Korea. The Hyundai group is one of the largest
conglomerates in South Korea.
   On Wednesday, management locked out 20,000 striking workers at
Hyundai Motor Co. in Ulsan and said there was little chance of
settling a strike for higher wages. The strike began Monday.
   At Hyundai Precision and Industry Co., which makes trains,
management and workers held two rounds of talks today but failed to
end a one-week strike at the company's plants in Ulsan and
Changwon. The talks were held one day after strikers freed one of
the 11 executives they took hostage on Friday.
   ``Punish the masterminds of the kidnapping,'' the students
shouted as tey hurled rocks at the Hyundai group's main building in
Seoul, breaking four windows. The students ran away before police
arrived.
   Hours after the attack, government prosecutors arrested two
Hyundai Engineering officials, executive board member Choi
Jae-dong, 47, and manager for general affairs Kang Myung-ku, 42,
and charged them with hiring several men to kidnap labor organizer
Suh Jung-ui, 34.
   The government prosecutors said they would expand the
investigation to find out whether other Hyundai officials were
involved in the kidnapping.
   Suh was kidnapped May 10 by a group of unidentified men as he
left a Seoul restaurant where he had met with some officials of the
huge construction company, which is based in Seoul.
   Suh, who worked at the company's Seoul headquarters, returned
home several days later and said he was released after he agreed to
write a letter of resignation addressed to the company.
   Hyundai Engineering denied involvement at the time.
   Details of the kidnapping emerged this week when some of the
alleged kidnappers surrendered to police or were arrested in Seoul
and other cities.
   Their leader told police Hyundai Engineering executives offered
him $27,000 to kidnap Suh and persuade him to drop his labor
organizing effort.
</TEXT>
