<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FugitiveCaught     06-02 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fugitive Caught,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Arrests Man Accused of Being Chicago Gang Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANTANA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed leader of a Chicago gang accused
of drug trafficking, extortion and murder has been arrested after a
year on the run.
   Jack Darrell Farmer, a convicted drug dealer placed on the FBI's
Most Wanted List this week, was captured along with his wife,
Pamela, on Wednesday at his home of three weeks, the FBI said.
   Farmer, 35, was wanted for racketeering activities. He is
accused of leading Chicago's Little Mafia, described by the FBI as
a gang of drug dealers, loan sharks and burglars tied to two
murders in Chicago.
   ``They were a vicious group,'' said Bob Long, FBI agent in
Chicago. ``They were well organized. They would set goals they
wanted. And they would use violence, kill somebody or use great
bodily harm if that's what they needed to accomplish their goal.''
   In April 1987, while in his attorney's custody to prepare for
trial, Farmer and his wife tied up and gagged the lawyer and
escaped, said William E. Wells, agent in charge of the FBI office
in Miami.
   Nine FBI agents and eight members of the police SWAT team
surrounded the house rented by Farmer after authorities received a
telephone tip from a co-worker, said FBI agent Lloyd Dean.
   Mrs. Farmer was arrested when she drove away from the house,
Dean said. Fifteen minutes later, Farmer ``bolted from the door
into the arms of waiting FBI agents,'' he said.
   Farmer had worked at a supermarket warehouse in Deerfield Beach
under the name Robert J. Neiwiadomski, authorities said.
   The couple were jailed for an appearance before a federal
magistrate Friday.
</TEXT>
