<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Military 3rdLd-Writethru a0588 06-02 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Military, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0588,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini Names Rafsanjani Armed Forces Commander</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to CLARIFY Khamenei's title. Pick up 8th
graf pvs: `A major...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini today
appointed Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani acting
commander-in-chief of Iran's armed forces, Iran's official media
reported.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the
move had been proposed by President Ali Khamenei, who is also
chairman of the Supreme Defense Council which determines Iran's
strategy in the war against Iraq.
   Khomeini has held the title of commander-in-chief, but overall
strategy has been determined by Khamenei, Rafsanjani, who is
Khomeini's respresentative on the Supreme Defense Council, and
other leaders.
   Khomeini's decision followed two serious Iranian defeats in the
7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war and major gains by radicals and militants
in two-stage parliamentary elections in April and May that
strengthened Rafsanjani.
   Tehran Radio, also monitored in Cyprus, said Khomeini's decree
said that Rafsanjani was taking over command of Iran's forces at a
time ``when imperialist America, in collaboration with East and
West and the reactionary states of the region, are trying to
confront Islam and Iran and prevent the victory of the Islamic
revolution.''
   The radio said Khomeini noted: ``I hereby want all the dear
people of Iran and military forces to be patient and resistant and
stand against the conspiracies of global arrogance.''
   ``Global arrogance'' is the phrase Iran uses to describe the
United States and its allies.
   Khomeini's move clearly strengthens Rafsanjani's position in the
government and indicates that Khamenei apparently has been edged
out.
   A major shake-up in Iran's military command had been expected
since the Iraqi army pushed the Iranians out of their important
bridgehead east of Iraq's southern port city of Basra in a
lightning assault on May 25.
   The Iraqis recaptured the Faw peninsula, south of Basra, in a
two-day assault April 16-18, driving the Iranians back across the
Shatt Al-Arab waterway two years after they seized the dusty finger
of land.
   Those defeats cost the Iranians their main footholds on Iraqi
soil and were seen as major military setbacks at a time of
political uncertainty in Tehran and apparent economic problems.
   After the loss of Faw, Khomeini replaced the armed forces chief
of staff, Brig. Gen. Ismael Sohrabi, with a little-known officer,
Col. Ali Shahbazi, and promoted him to brigadier general.
   Western military analysts said at the time that ``more heads are
expected to roll.''
   Shahbazi, 42, a regular army officer, has a background in
guerrilla warfare and has commanded armored units.
   Rafsanjani's appointment came as military analysts expected the
Tehran hierarchy to reassess its strategy of attrition against Iraq
following their twin defeats.
   The Iraqis had expected the fighting in both cases to take
several days. But to their surprise, the Faw assault took less than
36 hours and the Iranians were rolled back from their positions in
10 hours.
   Iran's official media has reported tens of thousands of
``basij,'' or volunteers, have been dispatched to the front in
recent days. But there was no clear evidence of any major single
buildup along the 730-mile war front.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs     06-02 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say 36 People Murdered in Golden Temple</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said today that Sikh extremists
killed at least 36 people in the Golden Temple before it was
besieged by police, the United News of India reported. Many of the
victims reportedly were tortured.
   Alos today, two more decomposed bodies were removed from the
temple complex, raising to 16 the number of corpses found around
the shrine since the radicals surrendered May 18, the Press Trust
of India news agency reported.
   Police continue to maintain a cordon around the shrine at
Amritsar to prevent militants from returning.
   UNI quoted unidentified senior police sources as saying police
were told of the killings by some of the 200 Sikh radicals and
sympathizers who surrendered during the siege.
   Many of the victims were tortured before they were killed, UNI
said. The extremists said the victims were beaten with iron rods
and whips and that salt was rubbed into their wounds. Electric
shocks also were used, UNI said.
   In some cases, the Sikh extremists extorted money from the
victims' families on the false promise that they would be freed.
The funds went to the Panthic Committee, one of a dozen Sikh
extremist groups operating in Punjab, to buy arms and ammunition,
the news agency said.
   There had been reports for months that people going into the
shrine for worship were being kidnapped and held by militants in
the complex, but the full extent of the problem did not come to
light until after the police action.
   Most of the bodies have been found in a dump next to the Akal
Takht, or the seat of temporal power of the Sikh faith.
   Militant Sikhs have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent homeland in Punjab since 1982. Amritsar is the capital
of Punjab.
   The Sikhs, who make up less than 2 percent of India's 800
million people, claim they are discriminated against by India's
majority Hindus. They form a majority in Punjab.
   The radicals have been blamed for killing more than 1,240 people
in hit-and-run attacks in Punjab state this year. In 1987, 1,030
people died.
   The siege of the temple was launched May 9 after militants
inside the complex fired on a police party outside its walls. At
least 46 people were killed in fighting during the 10-day siege,
most of them radicals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
