<DOCNO> AP880602-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-TreasureShip     06-02 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasure Ship,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Value Of Treasure Not Known Says Chief Ministers Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials today said they did not
know the value of a 16th century Portuguese war ship whose treasure
was found in the Straits of Malacca.
   They denied saying the vessel, sunk in 1512, carried $3 billion
in gold and precious stones.
   News reports had quoted the Chief Minister of Malacca state,
Abdul Rahim Thamby Chik, as saying the treasure aboard the ship was
worth about $3 billion.
   Contacted by telephone, an official in the Chief Minister's
office, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the chief
minister had not given any value for the treasure.
   The Star daily quoted the Chief Minister as saying, ``I never
stated the estimated value of the loot. How can we estimate things
we have never seen?''
   Earlier this week Rahim said a foreign marine group had found
the treasure in the Straits of Malacca and the state government was
contacting the federal government to negotiate for bringing up the
treasure of the Flor De La Mar.
   The ship was the flagship of Alfonso d'Albuquerque, who led an
800-strong armada that conquered Malacca in 1511.
   He was taking the booty back to Portugal when it sank.
   He managed to escape to another ship accompanying the Flor De La
Mar, but most of the treasure sank.
</TEXT>
