<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0527,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Violence Mars Provincial Elections Designed To Give Tamils More
Autonomy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with polls closing, estimated 50
percent turnout. Pick up 6th graf pvs, `The voting ...' Edits
thereafter to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant Sinhalese nationalists hurled
bombs and grenades at voters and polling places during provincial
elections today, killing a police officer, authorities said.
   Polls closed with less than half the eligible voters in two
provinces casting ballots, election officials estimated. An
opposition party immediately claimed fraud.
   The policeman was killed and six others wounded in two attacks
on polling places in the village of Mattugama, 35 miles southeast
of Colombo, police said.
   At Dullewa, 65 miles northeast of Colombo, gunmen jumped two
policeman who had been watching a polling place. The assailants
tied the officers to a tree and stole their automatic rifles but
did not harm them, a police spokesman said.
   Late Wednesday, an airman was killed by suspected Sinhalese
radicals who ambushed his car, the spokesman said on condition of
anonymity.
   The deputy elections commissioner, Lakshman Perera, told The
Associated Press that less than 50 percent of the 3.6 million
eligible voters in the Central and Western provinces cast ballots.
   Results were not expected until Friday.
   The voting for provincial councils, in its second round today,
was called for under last July's peace accord to end the 5-year-old
revolt by militant Tamil separatists.
   The nationalist Sinhalese Liberation Front insists the accord
makes too many concessions to the minority Tamils and opposes the
councils, which are designed to give more autonomy to the provinces.
   Tamils dominate the Northern and Eastern provinces, where
polling has been postponed because of fear of violence by Tamil
separatists.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindu, comprise 18 percent of this
island nation's 16 million people. They claim discrimination by the
mostly Buddhist Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the population.
   The rest are descendants of Christian colonialists or Moslem
traders.
   On Wednesday, nationalist Sinhalese gangs burned down more than
15 government buildings, torched six buses and three trains and
killed a policeman in a bid to disrupt today's balloting.
   They also put up posters threatening to kill anyone who voted
and any shopkeepers who opened their stores for the next 36 hours.
   The government responded by tightening security and ordering
security personnel to ``shoot on sight'' anyone ``engaged in the
destruction of public property.''
   The voters cast ballots today for 158 lawmakers from 585
candidates fielded by the governing United National Party, the
Liberal Party, Sri Lanka People's Party and Moslem Congress.
</TEXT>
