<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-Ship     06-02 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Ship,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Cruiser Watches Iranians Board, Escort Cypriot Vessel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. missile cruiser today watched an
Iranian navy frigate stop, board and then escort away a Cypriot
cargo ship apparently suspected of carrying war-related cargo for
Iraq.
   U.S. Navy officials who reported the incident in the southern
Persian Gulf said the Iranian ship, tentatively identified as the
1,540-ton frigate Alborz, was acting within maritime law that
allows for ``visit and search'' in international waters.
   There was no confrontation or exchange of radio messages between
the American warship, the 9,400-ton Vincennes, and either of the
other two vessels, according to Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke, a U.S.
Navy spokesman. Officials on the Vincennes watched the incident
from two miles away.
   The Cypriot ship, identified by gulf-based shipping executives
as the 10,000-ton cargo vessel Vevey, ``did not request assistance
and did not appear to be in any distress,'' Van Dyke said.
   However, he said it was the closest that any American and
Iranian warships have come to each other in the gulf since April
18, when U.S. ships and aircraft sank or disabled six Iranian craft
in a series of clashes in the southern gulf and the Strait of
Hormuz.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
   ``The Vincennes had the others in view as the Iranian frigate
stopped the Cypriot ship, launched a small boat that put a search
party on board and then escorted her off in a northeasterly
direction,'' Van Dyke said.
   Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit in London said the Vevey was
carrying Italian marble powder and chips to Kuwait and the Saudi
Arabian port of Jubail.
   Lloyd's said the Cypriot vessel ``apparently'' was boarded by
eight Iranians, and was being escorted to Bandar Abbas, a major
Iranian port and naval base in the Strait of Hormuz.
   Tehran considers both Saudi Arabia and Kuwait to be allies of
Iraq and frequently attacks ships bound to or from ports in those
countries. It also regularly stops and searches vessels that it
suspects of carrying war-related materiel and sometimes takes the
ships into detention.
   The Vincennes, a sophisticated electronics warfare ship and the
most powerful ever deployed by the United States to the gulf, was
on its first week of patrol duty in the area, some 25 miles
northeast of Dubai.
</TEXT>
