<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HarvardTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0575 06-02 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0575,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: Harvard Concealed Faculty Vote Switch in Discrimination
Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with attorney declining a
delay; PICKS UP 12th graf pvs, `At issue ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for a former professor suing to become
the fifth woman to receive tenure in Harvard Business School's
history pressed on with the trial today rather than accept a delay
to gather more evidence.
   U.S. District Judge Douglas P. Woodlock on Wednesday ruled that
Harvard withheld key documents in the sex-discrimination case, and
he recommended suspending the non-jury trial so the attorney for
Barbara Bund Jackson could question professors who abruptly
withdrew support for her tenure bid in 1981.
   ``My fundamental view is that cases should be decided on the
merits and evidence worth submitting when possible,'' Woodlock said
today.
   But the attorney, Evan T. Lawson, said today, ``We simply don't
have the emotional resources, let alone the financial resources, to
embark on what we see as being an extremely complicated and lengthy
procedure.''
   Closing arguments then began in the trial, now in its eighth
day. Jackson contends that she was denied tenure because of her sex
and that less-qualified men than her received tenure.
   During testimony, a professor said the school's faculty voted
47-7 to support her bid for tenure but two days later backed her by
only 29-27. Tenure decisions at Harvard are submitted to the
faculty to gauge support for the professor; the actual decision
rests with the university president.
   Lawson had filed a motion seeking to sanction Harvard for
failing to provide evidence about the vote under a court order
requiring that the university turn over all documents relating to
Jackson.
   He asked the judge to bar Harvard from using the second vote to
prove its contention that Jackson was denied tenure solely because
her academic performance was below standard. But the judge denied
the request today.
   Suspending the trial would have required testimony from
professors who switched their votes and would have pushed the case
well into the fall, attorneys for both sides said.
   Lawson maintained that testimony by a Harvard professor shows
that business school Dean John H. McArthur lobbied the faculty to
switch votes to oppose Jackson, who began teaching at the school in
1973.
   Jackson resigned in 1984 after she was denied tenure a second
time, in 1983.
   At issue is the question of academic privilege, the right of a
university to keep confidential the names of professors involved in
judging candidates for tenure.
   In recommending suspending the trial, Woodlock said: ``It's a
pattern of limitations placed on proof _ limitations by
destruction, limitations by late disclosure ... and limitations on
proof by this privilege.''
   In her suit, Jackson also alleges the school destroyed documents
requested by her to support her claim that less-qualified men
received tenure from 1974 to 1984. Harvard said the destruction was
inadvertent.
   Harvard attorney Allan A. Ryan Jr. indicated the school might
risk being held in contempt of court and refuse to provide the
names of the professors to preserve their academic privilege.
   The school claims that failing to provide the 1981 votes was an
oversight and that Lawson never specifically requested the results.
   Jackson, 44, now a private marketing consultant, first applied
for tenure in 1981.
   After failing to gain tenure, Jackson was given a three-year
extension on her appointment. She submitted new academic work for
review, but in 1983 was rebuffed again. She sued in 1984.
   Three of the business school's 90 tenured professors are women.
Four women have received tenure in the business school's 80-year
history, the first in 1961.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
