<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PolarTrek     06-02 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polar Trek,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet-Canadian Skiers Finish 91-Day Trek Across The North Pole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and Canadian skiers without vehicles or
sled dogs finished a three-month polar trek from Siberia to Canada
in sunshine and 30-degree temperatures. Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev today praised the skiers.
   A gala welcome awaits the team in Ottawa tonight.
   ``Your journey has added to trust, mutual understanding and good
neighborliness in this world,'' the official Tass news agency
quoted Gorbachev as saying.
   He praised the ``courage, true comradeship and mutual
assistance'' of the nine Soviets and four Canadians in completing
their 91-day, 1,075-mile journey across the North Pole on Wednesday.
   An expedition spokeswoman, Shirley Smyth, said the group sent a
short-wave message after leaving the shifting ice pack and reaching
Ward Hunt Island near Cape Columbia on Ellesmere Island, the
northernmost part of Canada.
   All 13 adventurers who set out March 3 from Severnaya Zemlya
Archipelago, the northernmost point in the Soviet Union, finished
the journey under the leadership of Moscow mathematician Dmitri
Shparo and Canadian mechanical engineer Richard Weber.
   Aided by good weather, they reached the North Pole on April 26
and completed the trek a few days earlier than expected, Ms. Smyth
said.
   Their worst problems were a frostbitten nose for Soviet member
Yuri Khmelevskiy and a toenail lost to the frost by Canadian Dr.
Max Buxton, who provided the emotional highlight of the trip by
proposing to his fiancee by radio message from the Arctic.
   Nancy Burton, a dental hygienist in Ottawa, accepted and will be
waiting for him in the Ellesmere settlement of Eureka.
   In a message to Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, the team
said: ``We thank you for your interest in our venture and hope it
has sparked an interest and openness in many Soviets and Canadians
in the unique northern relationship between our two countries.''
   Mulroney, through an emissary in Eureka, said the group
completed the trip in ``spectacular fashion.''
   Fresh supplies were dropped to the explorers five times during
the trip, and each member carried a backpack with essentials such
as a high-protein, high-fat diet of bacon and dried fish to
maintain energy and body heat.
   ``I'm sure they're celebrating now as they do final blood tests
and take final snow samples,'' said Ms. Smyth.
</TEXT>
