<1ST_LINE>u i Soviet-SecretSpeech     06-02 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Soviet-Secret Speech,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Official Calls For Publication of Khrushchev Speech on
Stalin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher of Marxism-Leninism today renewed calls
for the publication of Nikita S. Khrushchev's 1956 ``secret
speech'' denouncing Stalin and said it is a secret only from Soviet
Communists like himself.
   ``If the party is keeping secrets from Communists in the pages
of its history that are not state secrets, then it is clear that it
doesn't serve the unity of the party,'' said V. Rusakov, dean of
the Philosophy and Scientific Communism Department at Sverdlovsk
Agricultural Institute, and a member of the party.
   Rusakov's comments appeared in an article published in today's
editions of the Sovietskaya Kultura newspaper. It appeared to be
the latest example in the leadership's campaign to open up the
pages of Soviet history.
   Khrushchev's address to the 20th Party Congress, held three
years after the death of Josef V. Stalin in 1953, detailed the
dictator's actions in the 29 years he served as Soviet leader.
   Western historians estimate that 20 million Soviets were killed
in political purges carried out under Stalin and in the drive to
collectivize agriculture.
   Under Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
``glasnost,'' or greater openness on selected topics, Stalin's
crimes are no longer a taboo subject, and the name of Khrushchev,
who was ousted as leader in 1964, is appearing more frequently in
the press.
   The call by Rusakov to publish Khrushchev's denuncation of
Stalin is not the first. In October, prominent Soviet scientist
Vitaly I. Goldansky also said Khrushchev's report, known in the
West as his ``secret speech'' because it was delivered behind
closed doors, should be published.
   Rusakov said the text of Khrushchev's speech was leaked almost
immediately in the West.
   ``All the world a long time ago read the `secret' report by N.S.
Khrushchev ... but an overwhelming majority of Soviet Communists
don't know this document, which so radically changed the evaluation
of the development of the party and the state,'' the educator wrote.
</TEXT>
