<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0451 06-02 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Cancels Debate, Returning to Boston for Wife's Operation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis returning home in top 7 grafs, picking
up in 2nd graf pvs, Dukakis has; also deletes 11th graf pvs, The
two</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis canceled today's debate with Jesse Jackson and was
returning home to Boston to be with his wife who was to undergo
surgery, a spokesman said.
   Dukakis, who flew to California late Wednesday for campaign
appearances and then the debate in Los Angeles, hoped to resume his
schedule by Saturday, said campaign spokesman Mark Gearan.
   Gearan said Kitty Dukakis would be operated on Friday for two
herniated cervical disks in her neck.
   He said there were no other problems beyond the disks. He said
Mrs. Dukakis underwent tests recently while in California and her
doctors in Boston decided an operation was required after reviewing
the results.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 53, was admitted to Massachusetts General Hospital
Wednesday night. She told told reporters at Logan International
Airport as she arrived in town that she had begun to experience
numbness in her hands and fingers about a month ago and called a
family doctor.
   ``He and I felt at that time it was just stress,'' she said,
adding that her symptoms worsened in recent weeks.
   Her husband had resumed his California campaign earlier today,
five days before the state's big primary.
   Dukakis has been campaigning this week in New Jersey, which also
holds its primary on Tuesday, along with New Mexico and Montana.
   The Massachusetts governor is far ahead of Jackson in the
nationwide delegate tally, and is heavily favored to win the
primary here.
   In recent days, however, Dukakis has been engaged in a delicate
minuet with Jackson over his rival's role in the fall campaign.
   Dukakis, who says he won't pick a running mate until after the
final primaries June 7, lauded Jackson's strong campaign.
   ``He's somebody who has done a remarkable job, has great gifts
and great strengths. I respect and admire him a lot,'' Dukakis told
reporters in Boston.
   The Massachusetts governor was questioned about Jackson's role
one day after Jackson said in New Jersey that he felt he had
``earned consideration'' for the second spot on the ballot.
   Asked if that was so, Dukakis responded, ``Because he has done
so well, of course he does.''
   He added that all of the Democratic presidential candidates had
earned the standing within the party to be considered for the
ticket.
   But when asked if Jackson deserved any special consideration by
virtue of having compiled the second-highest number of delegates,
Dukakis answered with a blunt ``No.''
   In a speech on Wednesday, Dukakis stressed his commitment to
expanding opportunities for higher education, calling it a
prerequisite for full participation in the nation's economic future.
   ``We need a president who will end the annual assault on Pell
Grants and loans and programs for disadvantaged students,'' Dukakis
said. ``We need to put our smartest investment bankers and college
administrators to work helping states to create college opportunity
funds.''
   Speaking at the state's newest community college in Boston's
Roxbury section, the traditional core of the city's black
community, the governor called for a new nationwide college loan
program.
   ``We can develop an approach based on the same principles as
Social Security that will keep faith with the next generation,'' he
said.
   Dukakis said his program would provide tuition loans to needy
students. After graduation, students would repay the loans through
payroll withholding, thus ensuring that the governnment would not
be saddled with unpaid loans.
</TEXT>
