<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-SovietPR     06-02 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Soviet PR,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Gorbachev, Summit Was Public Relations Triumph</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If nothing else, the Moscow summit was a public
relations triumph for Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Although it produced little progress on arms control, the
Reagan-Gorbachev summit showed the Soviets at their best under the
intense scrutiny of 5,000 Soviet and foreign journalists who
crowded central Moscow.
   Soviet officials were accessible and doggedly spontaneous.
Ever-hovering KGB agents were usually young and well-dressed.
Streets were swept clean and restaurants offered two Moscow
rarities: attentive service and fresh vegetables.
   Even the weather cooperated. It didn't start raining until
President Reagan was ready to leave Vnukovo Airport.
   Veteran Moscow observers said the Soviets, in style if not in
substance, are increasingly emulating the West.
   One little-known reason why the new Soviet image appeals to
Americans is that Soviet officials have frequently but quietly
sought PR advice from Americans.
   U.S. image-makers responded with a variety of suggestions. They
said security agents should wear lighter, less drab colors, and
Soviet officials should favor open-collared shirts instead of ties
and try to be more accessible.
   They also suggested that Soviet analysts establish eye contact
because, as one public relations specialist explained, ``it
connotes trust.''
   ``The Soviets certainly don't want to give Americans the credit,
but there is no denying that some things went off very well because
of both our input and their observance of us at the previous three
summits,'' said John S. Kavulich, chairman of a Washington, D.C.,
marketing firm that has worked with the Soviets since 1986.
   ``Officials from Gorbachev on down weren't running away from the
television cameras, they were stepping up to them,'' Kavulich said.
``The Soviets usually carried off media events with a flair. And
they reinforced the idea that they have a sense of humor.''
   In a move clearly intended to appeal to Westerners, the official
Soviet news agency Tass sold summit T-shirts, buttons, records and
tapes for foreign currency. It was the first time that Tass had
lent its name to a commercial enterprise.
   Some observers suggested the Soviets might even have worked some
magic with the weather, using chemicals to disperse rain clouds as
they did in 1986 for the Goodwill Games and the 1985 opening of the
World Youth Festival.
   There were some glitches. Hours after President and Mrs. Reagan
arrived Sunday for the five-day summit, they took an unscheduled
stroll along Moscow's pedestrian mall on Arbat Street.
   Soviet agents obviously were unprepared for presidential
spontaneity. Forcing themselves between the Reagans and the Soviet
crowd, the agents jostled the president and the startled first lady
as well as journalists and passers-by.
   ``The Soviets knew the Reagans would have some spontaneous event
to match Gorbachev's walk along Connecticut Avenue'' during the
Washington summit in December, Kavulich said.
   ``Agents on the street were told to let the president approach a
crowd of Muscovites if he wants. But apparently, for the agents,
acting as a wedge between Soviets and foreigners was almost a
reflexive action,'' he said.
   Nevertheless, as one U.S. diplomat said privately, ``The Soviets
are probably patting themselves on the back. They went every night
into homes throughout America, and as each night passed, they
became more familiar and more welcome guests.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
