<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0465 06-02 0960</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Cancels Debate to Be With Wife</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis Flying Home, Canceling Debate in top 8
grafs, picking up in 6th graf pvs, Reagan has</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis cut short a California campaign trip
and canceled today's debate with Jesse Jackson to return to Boston
where his wife faced surgery to relieve neck pain. Jackson was
meeting today with juvenile gangs in Los Angeles while Republican
George Bush relaxed in Maine.
   Bush has been making few public appearances in recent days while
President Reagan has been at the summit in Moscow. However, Bush
did hint in an interview published today that embattled Attorney
General Edwin Meese III could be hurting his candidacy.
   Both Dukakis and Jackson had flown to California Wednesday night
for campaigning in the days leading up to next Tuesday's primary,
the last and biggest delegate prize of the long primary season.
   However, Dukakis was flying right back to Massachusetts after a
single morning campaign appearance today, said spokesman Mark
Gearan.
   Gearan said Kitty Dukakis would be operated on Friday for two
herniated cervical disks in her neck. She had felt pain and
numbness for about a month, he said, and doctors believed it was
``a degenerative condition'' rather than the result of a single
injury.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 53, was admitted to Massachusetts General Hospital
Wednesday night. She told told reporters her symptoms had worsened
in recent weeks.
   Bush was spending a final full day today at his oceanside
retreat in Kennebunkport, and the only order of business was having
his boat checked for safety by the Coast Guard.
   The vice president has been holding strategy sessions with
advisers all week, and one of the key topics has been possible
issues on which Bush will set himself apart from his popular boss.
   Reagan has given his full support to Meese, who is under
investigation by an independent counsel. But Bush, in an interview
with The New York Times, hinted that if Meese's woes continue, the
matter could be a campaign liability for him. The Democrats have
been using the issue for months to attack him.
   ``I think he's been made aware by the polls and by a lot of
public comment that there is the danger that this matter, if it
stays exactly the way it is, could not only adversely affect me,
but affect others as well,'' Bush said of Meese in the interview,
published today.
   Bush said over the weekend that he had met recently with Meese,
and the attorney general had promised not to do anything that would
harm his campaign. Meese said Monday in a Cable News Network
interview, however, that he believed the Justice Department's
record would be an asset to any Republican candidate.
   Bush told the Times he expected to meet with Meese again soon.
   Dukakis, who has an all-but insurmountable delegate lead, has
been beset by questions all week about Jackson's role in the fall
campaign. Both men have said Jackson will play a major but as yet
undetermined part in the expected race against Bush.
   Jackson, campaigning in New Jersey on Wednesday, asserted for a
second day in a row that he has earned consideration as a potential
running mate.
   Dukakis agreed with that, but balked when asked if Jackson, in
view of his demonstrated vote-getting ability, had any special
claim on the No. 2 spot.
   ``No,'' the Massachusetts governor said flatly. But he also said
of his rival: ``I respect and admire him a lot.''
   Jackson, who drew overwhelming black support in the primary
contests, has been stressing that the party needs him in order to
win the general election.
   Party officials appear mindful of that. Democratic National
Committee chairman Paul Kirk announced Wednesday that a 15-member
platform-drafting panel would be headed up by Rep. William Gray of
Pennsylvania, a Jackson supporter.
   However, Dukakis was predicting he could draw ``genuine and
deep'' black support in his own right.
   The governor, who started off the week by meeting with black
supporters, made a campaign-style visit on Wednesday to a community
college in the predominantly black Roxbury section of Boston.
There, he cited a groundswell of black backing for his candidacy.
   ``I sense it,'' he said.
   Jackson, meanwhile, was marching through the Los Angeles ghetto
of Watts, which was torn by riots in the 1960s. ``Where you
struggle I will struggle,'' he told cheering supporters Wednesday
night.
   Jackson was also meetig today with members of the rival Crips
and Bloods gangs. The bloody battles of Los Angeles gangs were
dramatized in the recent movie ``Colors.''
   Campaign aides said they believed it would be the first time the
rival gang leaders got together.
   While Dukakis and Jackson prepared for the primary finale, a
past Democratic presidential contender jumped into the race.
   Former Sen. Eugene McCarthy, whose campaign two decades ago was
a rallying point for opponents of the Vietnam War, announced his
candidacy on Wednesday in Philadelphia. McCarthy, 72, is running on
the Consumer Party ticket in his fourth presidential effort.
   He ran as a Democrat in 1968 and 1972 and as an independent in
1976.
   ``This year the one thing we have to do is shake up the
two-party system, and that's what I hope to do,'' he said.
   McCarthy dismissed the likely Republican and Democratic nominees.
   ``There are two kinds of people who don't make good presidents _
vice presidents and governors,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis' economic policies came under fire from the
Bush camp.
   Former deputy treasury secretary Richard Darman, who met with
the vice president on Wednesday, emerged to ridicule the
``Massachusetts miracle,'' the economic boom in his state that
Dukakis frequently cites on the campaign trail. Darman called it
the ``Massachusetts mirage.''
</TEXT>
