<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Art Attack,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attacker Of Da Vinci Drawing To Remain In Mental Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who fired a shotgun at a drawing by Leonardo
da Vinci at the National Gallery was ordered Thursday to remain
indefinitely in a high-security mental hospital.
   Robert Cambridge, 37, was sent to Broadmoor asylum last December
after being convicted of blasting the priceless artwork on July 17,
1987, in a social protest.
   Judge Richard Lowry of the Old Bailey Criminal Court said after
reviewing a psychiatrict report that Cambridge should remain at
Broadmoor because he was a danger to the public.
   Cambridge blasted a six-inch gash in Leonardo's 450-year-old
charcoal and chalk drawing of the Virgin Mary with the Infant Jesus
and two saints. It is undergoing restoration.
   He said he attacked to demonstrate his disgust with ``political,
social and economic conditions in Britain,'' according to testimony
at his trial.
</TEXT>
