<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   06-02 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador's Car Hit in Exchange of Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spelling of Alann in 11th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador John Kelly's car was hit
with one bullet during a brief exchange of gunfire between his
bodyguards and a Christian militia patrol in east Beirut on
Thursday, police reported.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said: ``The ambassador and all his escorts are fine.'' He refused
to elaborate.
   In another development, the Shiite Moslem Amal militia on
Thursday denied it has custody of three American professors and an
Indian professor kidnapped in 1987.
   A police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity in line
with regulations, said one bullet hit the hood of Kelly's
armor-plated dark blue Chevrolet in an ``accidental exchange of
automatic fire.''
   He said the gunfire occurred around noon when Kelly's Lebanese
and American bodyguards in two escort cars fired in the air with
automatic rifles ``apparently to make way for the ambassador's
convoy'' in a traffic-jammed street in the Sin Fil neighborhood.
   Kelly's motorcade was heading to the heavily guarded U.S.
Embassy compound in the suburb of Aukar, north of Beirut.
   The spokesman said a militia patrol from President Amin
Gemayel's rightist Phalange Party, which was in the area, ``opened
fire in the air too in an effort to stop Kelly's convoy to check
what was happening.''
   ``Kelly's bodyguards fired three bullets at the Phalangists in a
white Mercedes-Benz and the patrol fired back. No casualties were
reported among the Phalangist militiamen,'' he said.
   ``Kelly's car was hit with one bullet in the hood and the convoy
continued on its way to the embassy,'' the spokesman added. He did
not elaborate.
   Hassan Youssef, foreign relations spokesman for the
Syrian-backed Amal militia, said a report by The Times of London
that the four kidnapped professors were believed to be in Amal's
hands was ``untrue and totally baseless.''
   The four are Americans Robert Polhill, Jesse Turner and Alann
Steen, and Indian Mithileshwar Singh. They were kidnapped on the
campus of Beirut University College Jan. 24, 1987.
   The Times also said that Amal leader Nabih Berri had scheduled a
news conference for this week and that ``there is understandable
speculation that this may be to announce the hostages' release.''
   ``Amal's standard policy denounces kidnapping,'' Youssef said.
   An underground faction calling itself Islamic Jihad for the
Liberation of Palestine claimed to have abducted the four educators
and has demanded Israel free 400 Arab prisoners.
   Fourteen other foreigners are held hostage in Lebanon _ six
Americans, three Britons, a West German, an Italian, an Irishman
and two unidentified men. Most are believed to be held by Shiite
extremists.
   The longest held is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   In another development, police said three members of the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, were wounded in a brief
firefight with rival Shiite Moslem militiamen in south Beirut on
Wednesday night.
   Another police spokesman said the three Hezbollahis were injured
in a five-minute exchange of fire with members of the Amal militia
in south Beirut's Shiyah district. Syrian troops ``intervened and
brought the firefight to an end,'' the spokesman said.
   The clash was the first reported between the two sides since
Syria deployed 2,400 troops in south Beirut on Friday and Saturday,
ending three weeks of clashes between the two rival militias that
killed nearly 300 people and wounded 1,000.
   Amal, Arabic for Hope, accused Hezbollah of provoking the clash
and said the three wounded Shiite militiamen were armed with
silencer-equipped pistols.
   Hezbollah said Amal militiamen opened fire at the three
``unarmed'' Hezbollahis as they drove to Shiyah to check on their
apartments.
</TEXT>
