<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Sweden-Subs     06-02 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sweden-Subs,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Uses Depth Charges, Grenades Against Possible Intruder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Swedish navy detonated depth
charges and anti-submarine grenades off the southern Baltic Sea
coast Thursday in the second hunt this week for underwater prowlers.
   Per Brissman, a defense staff spokesman, said electronic
monitors picked up signs of ``foreign underwater activity'' during
a navy exercise outside Oxelosund, 60 miles south of Stockholm.
   He said the sub hunters exploded several depth charges and
Elma-grenades, a Swedish weapon designed to pierce a 1-inch hole in
a hull to cripple a vessel without destroying it.
   On Monday, the Swedish military set off a mine outside the Musko
naval base south of Stockholm after a warning system indicated a
possible intruder.
   Sweden has not identified the nationality of submarines the
military says have repeatedly snooped in Swedish waters. The last
submarine caught was a Soviet vessel that ran aground outside a
naval base in 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
