<DOCNO> AP880602-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BangladeshFlood     06-02 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh Flood,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>46 Familes Washed Away in Flash Flood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flash flood on the Kushiara River
washed away an entire village of more than 200 people, officials
reported Thursday.
   All 46 families were feared drowned when the rush of water swept
through Sengram village Tuesday, but rescue workers continued
searching the banks downstream, said officials in the Sylhet
district near the Indian border 100 miles northeast of Dhaka.
   Thousands of people in Sylhet and the neighboring Sunamganj
district have fled their homes in the past week because of floods
along the Brahmaputra River and its tributaries. Communication with
the region has been difficult because of disruptions in telephone
and rail service.
   Kazi Feroze Rashid, regional relief minister, visited the
affected areas earlier in the week and told Parliament on Wednesday
at least 16 people were known to have been killed.
   Rescue workers and others in the Sylhet area say they believe
nearly 50 people have died, not including residents of Sengram
village who may have drowned.
   Rashid said more than 300,000 people have been forced from their
homes and 400 square miles of crops damaged.
   Floods often occur at the start of the monsoon season in
Bangladesh, a nation of 105 million. Last year, the worst flooding
in 70 years killed at least 1,500 people and displaced about
one-quarter of the population.
</TEXT>
