<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRdp 1stLd-Writethru b0476 06-02 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0476,0586</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs final item, datelined WASHINGTON, in AM-Religion Rdp,
send June 1 as b0476, to CORRECT name of Bishop Chilstrom.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has rejected an appeal
against back taxes and penalties by the Church of Scientology,
leaving in place the 1967 revocation of its tax exemption.
   The high court declined to review lower court decisions
penalizing the group for tax deficiencies in 1970, 1971 and 1972,
holding that large amounts of its monies claimed as tax-exempt went
for private enrichment of Scientology's late founder L. Ron Hubbard
and his wife, Mary Sue Hubbard.
   The U.S. Tax Court had ruled that $3.5 million was deposited in
Swiss banks through a bogus trust in those years, much of it later
removed to a safe on a yacht, Apollo, on which the Hubbards had
taken up residence in the Mediterranean. He died in 1986.
   However, the group continues to function, pressing lawsuits
claiming its ``E-meter'' auditing is religious and exempt from
taxes levied against its income.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new religious prize, the $150,000 Louisvile
Grawemeyer Award, has been estalished to honor the world's most
significant contributions to religious and spiritual understanding.
   Funded by Charles Grawemeyer, it is to be given jointly by the
University of Louisville and the Louisville Presbyterian
Theological Seminary to recognize ``creative and seminal insights
into the relationship between human beings and the divine.''
   Grawemeyer, a 1934 graduate of the University of Louisville and
a member of the seminary's board of directors, previously has set
up three other $150,000 international prizes in music, education
and political science.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concerning Nancy Reagan's reported consulting of
an astrologer, the Rev. Richard J. Neuhaus, a noted Lutheran
scholar observes:
   ``Astrology, if taken seriously, is a deviation from biblical
authority. If not taken seriously, it is a dangerous dabbling in
things that ought to be taken seriously.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Methodist Church says sexually
violent pornography should be legally defined as ``obscene,''
removing it from protection of the First Admentment guarantees of
freedom of speech.
   At its conference here in early May, the church also said harm
is resulting from child pornography and its distributors ``should
be prosecuted to the full extent of the law.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Judaism's placement division for
cantors has reaffirmed its commitment to finding positions for
cantors regardless of their sex.
   The stand came in response to a decision by the all-male
Cantorial Assembly not to accept women in its ranks nor place them
as cantors, singers in Jewish worship services.
   Franklin D. Kreutzer, president of the United Synagogue of
America, said the cantor's assembly's position was contrary to that
of the Jewish Theological Seminary of America, which trains women
as cantors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protestant and Roman Catholic officials are
calling for comprehensive sanctions against South Africa as a way
of supporting forces seeking to change the country's apartheid
policies of racial separation.
   Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom, head of the Evangelical Lutheran
Church in America, told a U.S. Senate subcommitte that ``virtually
all other peaceful means of persuading the stubborn South African
government to change have been tried, except comprehsnive
sanctions.''
   Roman Catholic Auxiliary Bishop Emerson J. Moore of New York
told the subcommittee that the Catholic Church throughout the world
is ``united in its profound moral opposition to apartheid.''
</TEXT>
