<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ParallelParking     06-02 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parallel Parking,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Driver's Test With No Parallel Parking?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you can't park, you may still be able to
drive under new license rules being promulgated in Wisconsin.
   Parallel parking, that nemisis of beginning drivers, has been
removed on a trial basis from requirements for a license, but some
examiners are not pleased, said Dennis Nussbaum, district manager
with the state Division of Motor Vehicles.
   ``Road tests are a lot like mom, apple pie and Chevrolet, and
some people don't like to see changes,'' he said.
   The parallel parking change is one of several designed to ease
the job of license examiners and reduce waiting times for tests,
Nussbaum said. It became effective Wednesday.
   ``We don't think that any of this will affect safety,'' Nussbaum
added.
   Over the years, the state has instituted new tests that
officials say more accurately check skills at such things as
high-speed driving and lane-changing maneuvers.
   ``Most people don't even use parallel parking any more,''
Nussbaum said.
   Nussbaum said the changes would remain in effect at least
through the summer and were made ``because we are in the service
business.''
</TEXT>
