<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     06-02 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0922</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Being the ambassador of soul is just as good
as being an ambassador from Seoul, according to a lawyer for James
Brown's wife.
   Attorney Allen W. Johnson has asked a Richmond County State
Court judge to dismiss misdemeanor traffic charges on grounds that
Adrienne Brown has diplomatic immunity.
   Mrs. Brown, 38, was charged with driving under the influence of
drugs, speeding and criminal trespass Sept. 3, 1987.
   The motion is based on a statement U.S. Rep. D. Douglas Barnard
Jr. made two years ago on James Brown Appreciation Day.
   Quoth the congressman: ``James is indeed our No. 1 ambassador.''
   Said Johnson's motion: ``The accused's husband, James Brown, is
America's No. 1 ambassador and as such should have diplomatic
immunity and such immunity extends to his wife, the accused
herein.''
   Brown is more commonly known as the ``godfather of soul''
because of such hits as ``Poppa's Got A Brand New Bag,'' ``Sex
Machine'' and ``I Feel Good.'' Seoul is the capital of South Korea.
   The Browns have recently had several highly publicized fights.
Brown has said he plans to file for divorce.
   Mrs. Brown has pleaded innocent in the traffic case. In
explaining his motion, Johnson said he was working under a
court-imposed deadline and was trying to pursue every possible
avenue of defense.
   Diplomatic immunity is designed to protect officials of foreign
nations while they represent their countries in the United States
and would not generally apply to American citizens.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who wouldn't be disappointed if they had a
date with a teen-age rock star and she didn't show?
   You can certainly count Judge Richard Hubbell among the unhappy.
Tiffany, the 16-year-old singer who wants to be independent, just
couldn't make it to a Superior Court session on her guardianship
petition.
   You see, she was in Germany on a promotional tour. First things
first. So instead, she sent her lawyers.
   Well, Hubbell couldn't impose a curfew or cut her allowance, but
he did give her an order _ no more career or travel plans without
court approval.
   ``She simply can't ignore a valid court order,'' Hubbell told
the attorneys representing Tiffany, her mother Jane C. Williams,
and her aunt, Julie Abbas.
   Hubbell issued Tiffany a rain check for June 9, the day she's
scheduled to return from Europe. He set the same deadline for a
report by an independent attorney who is going over the teen-ager's
recording and management contracts.
   The MCA recording star, whose full name is Tiffany Renee
Darwish, ran away from home because she said Mrs. Williams was
hampering her career.
   She is seeking to free herself from her mother's legal custody,
and accused her mother in an emancipation request of ``hindering my
career and jeopardizing my future.''
   Mrs. Williams contended Tiffany's contracts unfairly award most
of $5 million in record royalties, concert proceeds and other
revenue to her manager, George Tobin.
   Wednesday's hearing was scheduled to determine whether Ms.
Abbas, Tiffany's temporary legal guardian, would be named permanent
guardian.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everybody at Eastside High School is going
batty over a movie about tough-guy Principal Joe Clark.
   Except Joe Clark. He's not sure actor Morgan Freeman is up to
the role.
   ``He's a good actor but I don't think anybody can fully portray
me,'' Clark said Wednesday. ``There's only one Joe Clark.''
   ``Lean on Me'' began filming Wednesday at the inner-city high
school Clark made famous. Students sought autographs, a teacher got
a part, and school bells interrupted filming.
   Clark, who gained national prominence by roaming the halls of
Eastside with a baseball bat and bullhorn, is being paid a small
part of the film's $10 million budget, but the exact amount was not
released.
   The movie is ``a vindication of what I stand for,'' Clark said.
He said his students are holding their ``heads high, their chests
are out and joy bells are ringing in their souls.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After all that Monkey Business last year, Lynn
Armandt has gotten down to business. She's selling shoes.
   ``Sometimes (customers) make the connection when I hand them my
card,'' Armandt said Wednesday.
   The connection involves a yacht trip Armandt took last year to
Bimini with Donna Rice and then presidential contender Gary Hart.
After that jaunt was revealed, Armandt moved here from Fort
Lauderdale, Fla.
   Hart probably wishes Armandt had moved a bit earlier _ Rice
claims Armandt sold a picture of Rice in Hart's lap to a
supermarket tabloid _ but Armandt didn't want to talk about all
that.
   ``That's in the past,'' she said. ``After a wild month of May
last year, things have been quiet.''
   She said she hasn't talked to Rice since. ``I haven't talked to
Mr. Hart, either,'' Armandt said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She didn't have to spend much time there, but
still, Princess Diana wasn't too happy behind bars.
   The princess, opening a new magistrate's court in Lewes, 50
miles south of London, seemed a bit uneasy when she toured a
cellblock designed to hold six prisoners.
   ``I got the impression she had not been in cells before,'' said
jailer Tom Dowse. ``She said it would be rather claustrophobic and
she would not like to be locked up.''
