<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug War, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0621,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manufacturer Still Considering Herbicide Use, Congressman Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3 grafs company comment for 4th graf pvs, Lilly, asked;
inserts 2 grafs further from English after 6th graf pvs, English's
statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eli Lilly & Co. has not closed the door to the
use of its herbicide ``spike'' in a State Department program to
spray South American coca bushes, a House subcommittee chairman
said today.
   Rep. Glenn English, whose House Government Operations panel is
reviewing the battle against illegal drugs, said he spoke to
company representatives after the State Department criticized the
company during a hearing Wednesday.
   He said Lilly officials have objected to use of the chemical
tebuthiuron, known as ``spike,'' because ``they have not done the
proper testing of application by air over a wide section of
countryside. They have no data. They have not seen data from (the)
State (Department), and cannot assume responsibility or liability.''
   Ted McKinney, a spokesman for the Indianapolis-based company,
had no immediate comment on English's statement.
   But he did say that the chemical is applied both by air and on
the ground in the United States.
   He described tebuthiuron as ``a broad-spectrum, soil-applied
herbicide for brush and weed control on non-cropland, pasture and
rangeland.'' The herbicide is ``approved for use in grazing lands,
wildlife openings along ditchbanks, and utility rights of way. It
is safe for humans, livestock, wildlife and the environment when
used according to label directions.''
   English, an Oklahoma Democrat, said:
   ``We will continue discussions. We need to acquire a herbicide
against coca bushes as quickly as possible. At this point, my own
perception is the door is open, discussions will continue, and
hopefully a solution can be found to this particular problem.''
   English's statement was toned down considerably from his comment
Wednesday that Lilly was ``a deserter'' in the war on drugs.
   The congressman later clarified his remarks to say there had not
been proper aerial testing in the coca-producing region of Peru,
where the chemical would be sprayed. He said the area has
considerable groundwater and therefore is much different from the
dry, brush areas where it is used in the United States.
   He added that the company also was concerned that the coca area
in Peru ``may not be in friendly hands, and you may not have a
pilot totally concentrating on the accuracy of spraying.''
   At Wednesday's hearing, Ann B. Wrobleski, assistant secretary of
state for international narcotics matters, criticized Lilly for
deciding to withhold the herbicide from the spraying program _ even
though it has been manufactured for more than 15 years, has been
proven safe by U.S. standards, is widely available in this country
and has been sold to the Interior Department.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Wednesday, ``We
think the short-term impact is serious.'' The department wanted to
test the chemical for use in eradicating the coca crop focused
mainly in Peru's Huallaga Valley, she said. The chemical is used in
the United States for clearing brush.
   Mrs. Oakley said Lilly apparently was worried about possible
retaliatory measures by ``traffickers or terrorists.'' The company
also came under pressure from environmentalists who were concerned
about the ecological impact of the herbicide.
   Meanwhile, the subcommittee was told by agencies fighting the
drug war on Wednesday that the effort is troubled by delayed
equipment and financial woes.
   The Coast Guard said its boats and planes often sit idle because
the agency is short of money.
   The Customs Service said the entire U.S. border with Mexico
remains a haven for airborne drug smugglers because of delays in
installing four of five radar balloons.
   Also, Coast Guard surveillance planes have cracks in their wings
and may be grounded this summer. New or modified planes authorized
by Congress have not yet been delivered. Construction of three new
command, control, communications and intelligence centers for the
drug war are behind schedule.
   English blamed the Customs Service for the delays in installing
the radar balloons along the Mexican border to detect airborne drug
smugglers. Only one of the five balloons, called aerostats, is in
operation.
   ``This is a terrible failure,'' he told William Rosenblatt, the
Customs Service enforcement chief. ``You are costing us dearly.
There's no sense of urgency about this. That's the problem.''
   Coast Guard Commandant Paul A. Yost said his new, fast patrol
boats and many of the agency's airplanes are operating at only 55
percent of last year's levels due to lack of money.
   He said it was ironic that Congress is ready to spend huge sums
for an escalation of the military's role in the drug war, but can't
find $60 million to get his vessels in the water and planes in the
air full time.
   ``Turn me loose and don't give my mission away,'' he told the
committee.
   Rosenblatt blamed the radar balloon delays on problems with site
selection, environmental concerns, competitive bidding and
bureaucratic roadblocks from other federal agencies.
   When he explained how he spent four months seeking competitive
bids for the balloons in an effort to save money, English said,
``In effect, you cost us a heck of a lot of money'' because Air
Force AWACS surveillance planes have had to patrol the Mexican
border to pick up the slack. English said that an AWACS costs
$7,500 an hour to operate.
</TEXT>
