<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Conservatives     06-02 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Conservatives,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New-Right Republicans Tell Bush: Attack Dukakis, Not Us</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican conservatives questioned Thursday
what Vice President George Bush hoped to gain politically by
attacking two new-right activists whom he called ``self-appointed
spokesmen'' who have been critical of him for years.
   The objects of Bush's attack _ Richard Viguerie and Howard
Phillips _ said they still hope he defeats Democrat Michael Dukakis
in the fall presidential election.
   ``With George so far down in the polls I was wondering why he
was wasting his time and energy shooting at me instead of shooting
at Mike Dukakis,'' said Phillips, chairman of the Conservative
Caucus.
   ``If he wants to go around attacking conservatives, he's going
to dig himself a deeper hole,'' said Viguerie, a conservative
fund-raiser and former publisher of Conservative Digest.
   Recent national polls have said Dukakis is leading Bush by
margins ranging from six points to 16 points among voters.
   Conservatives have urged the vice president to step up his
attacks on the Massachusetts governor and portray him as a liberal
out of step with the national mood.
   Viguerie and Phillips also have been sharply critical of
President Reagan since he took office more than seven years ago.
They have complained that Reagan has abandoned much of the
conservative agenda.
   Only Wednesday, Viguerie described Reagan as having ``taken
leave of his senses'' for suggesting in Moscow that the problems
Soviet citizens were having emigrating to the West were caused more
by bureaucratic problems than government policy.
   Interviewed by The New York Times at his summer home in
Kennebunkport, Maine, Bush said of Viguerie, ``The fact that he
doesn't agree with me on a lot of things or has opposed me for many
years, that doesn't bother me.
   ``There's only one or two that polarize, and Viguerie and Howie
Phillips are two of them. It doesn't matter in terms of total
vote.''
   When asked if he needed to court the two new-right activists,
Bush said, ``There are some people that are almost self-appointed
spokesmen that will make a claim for that. I don't feel that at
all.''
   Bush said Viguerie ``gets his name in the paper by criticizing
other Republicans all the time.''
   ``I think it's kind of sad,'' said Rep. Robert Dornan of
California, a conservative supporter of Bush. ``I was hoping he
wouldn't react to their earlier goading. ... I thought the whole
thing was calmed down and we'd all be pulling together on one
team.''
   Dornan said Viguerie was ``absolutely correct'' in urging Bush
to get tougher on Dukakis.
   ``If George doesn't paint Dukakis as the liberal that he is and
establish himself as a conservative then the electorate is going to
opt for a change,'' said Dornan.
   ``It doesn't serve George Bush any useful purpose to attack
people who have constituencies that might support him,'' said Lyn
Nofziger, former White House political director.
   At the same time, Nofziger noted that Phillips ``has been a
vicious attacker of Ronald Reagan over the last seven years.''
   ``He's not running against Dick Viguerie and he's not running
against Howie Phillips; he's running against probably Mike Dukakis
and you really ought to keep your eye on the ball,'' said Nofziger.
   Phillips, asked how much of a following he has, said Bush ``does
not have to worry about me, I only have one vote.'' He said
Conservative Caucus has several hundred thousand supporters.
   ``Even though I'm not a great fan of the vice president or his
policies, I genuinely hope he succeeds,'' said Phillips.
   ``I want all of us to unite behind him (Bush),'' said Viguerie,
who added that if Bush ``doesn't run a polarizing election, he's
history. ... If he doesn't run a campaign to polarize, that
polarizes the country along liberal and conservative lines then he
has no chance of winning.''
</TEXT>
