<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Future 1stLd-Writethru a0632 06-02 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Future, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0632,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit Produces `Sea Change in Atmospherics' For East-West Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 20th (lasts) graf bgng, He said, to restore dropped
matter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Image may have overwhelmed substance here this
week, but American officials believe the Moscow summit will be
remembered for building a foundation of openness and trust for
future U.S.-Soviet relations.
   ``Military issues are the most important and here, progress was
thin,'' said one American participant in five days of summit talks
between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   It was uncertain whether arms talks will result in agreement on
a new treaty drastically reducing strategic nuclear weapons before
Reagan leaves office in January. That is the two leaders' condition
for holding a fifth and final summit meeting this year.
   ``But there has been a sea change in atmospherics,'' the U.S.
official said privately. He noted that ``we are talking with them
across the board'' from missile cutbacks to cultural exchanges.
   ``If we are going to build a future relationship, these will be
the building blocks,'' he said.
   Another U.S. diplomat with years of experience in Soviet affairs
said the Americans are ``feeling more confident about the
relationship'' after the summit. He, too, spoke only on condition
he not be identified.
   Kremlin spokesmen made their own upbeat assessment of
glasnost-era summitry.
   ``If someone had told me three years ago that we would have such
relations with the United States, I would have said it was a
fantasy,'' said Georgy Arbatov, head of the U.S.A.-Canada Institute
in Moscow.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov said on a British
Broadcasting Corp. interview that ``we do have progress, but we
could have even more.''
   To television viewers, the summit may have seemed designed to
produce scenes of Reagan and Gorbachev clasping hands and grinning
at each other.
   There were some TV images unfavorable to the Soviets _ KGB
agents roughing up the White House press corps a few hours after
Reagan arrived; police sealing off the apartment of a Jewish
activist whom Reagan intended to visit.
   There also were favorable Soviet images _ an aging Reagan
alongside a bright-eyed Gorbachev more than 10 years his junior;
Gorbachev urging a faster pace in arms control negotiations while
Reagan counsels caution.
   Behind the images, U.S. and Soviet aides were busy bargaining
over a far wider range of issues than their predecessors during the
days of East-West detente in the 1970s.
   ``We are finding greater openness than we have in the past,''
said the American official.
   Negotiators made only marginal progress this week on a proposed
treaty to reduce U.S. and Soviet arsenals of long-range nuclear
weapons by as much as 50 percent. They talked, too, about two
lesser agreements that would tighten verification procedures under
a 1974 accord limiting nuclear explosions and require advance
notice of ballistic missile tests.
   The two sides also made little headway on resolving differences
over Afghanistan, Central America and other regional conflicts. But
they signed a handful of agreements on minor issues such as
maritime rescue and radar navigation.
   In all the talks, the U.S. official said, the Soviets blamed
past mistakes on ``old thinking'' and tried to use what they called
Gorbachev's ``new thinking'' to make things work.
   Among the summit's little-noticed achievements, in the view of
American participants, was overcoming initial Soviet objections to
a cultural agreement to exchange as many as 1,000 high school
students from each country.
   ``In the past, the Soviets had objected to allowing Soviet
students to stay in American homes and Americans to stay with
Soviet families,'' said one U.S. official.
   He said the exchange students could become of the next
generation of U.S. and Soviet foreign policy experts.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Bryan Brumley, a national security writer based
in Washington, was an Associated Press correspondent in Moscow in
1981-82 and has covered previous summits in Reykjavik, Iceland, and
Washington.
</TEXT>
