<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Justice-Dennis     06-02 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice-Dennis,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Justice Official Looks Forward to Report on Meese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new chief of the Justice Department's
criminal division said Thursday he looks forward to the release of
a report detailing Attorney General Edwin Meese's ties to
scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. and a $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline
project.
   ``I think it will be much better for all concerned when that
report is issued, the sooner the better, for the department and for
the attorney general,'' Edward S.G. Dennis Jr., the former U.S.
attorney in Philadelphia, told reporters.
   Independent counsel James McKay will conclude a year-long
invesitgation of Meese by filing a report in the next week of two
with three-judge federal appeals court panel, which is expected to
issue it publicly later this month.
   Dennis said issuing the report ``will be very good because right
now you just have a lot of speculation.'' He said making the report
public will give Meese an opportunity to respond to any allegations
in detail. Meese has said he wants to respond to all the
information in the report to ``clear the air.''
   Dennis, who is in his first week on the job as acting assistant
attorney general said morale in the criminal division is good
despite Meese's legal problems and a wave of departures from the
Justice Department in the past two months.
   ``It's not easy in a situation where you do have controversy and
uncertainty to be without someone to kind of keep the division's
oar in the water,'' said Dennis, a former chief of the narcotic and
dangerous drug section at the department.
   Dennis sidestepped when asked whether colleagues urged him not
to take his new assignment. ``My feeling is basically if there
weren't problems, there'd be no need for lawyers,'' he said.
``That's basically what we do, deal with controversy and problems.''
   Dennis said that since he already knows many people in the
criminal division and is ``a known commodity,'' his nomination
``has done a great deal to perhaps calm any concerns.''
   Dennis said he has spoken briefly to his predecessor, William
Weld, who quit in protest March 29 out of concern that Meese's
continued tenure was hurting the Justice Department's operations,
morale and public image.
   Dennis said he will probably have lunch with Weld soon. In a
recent conversation, he said, Weld didn't say why he resigned,
Dennis didn't ask him why and Weld didn't offer Dennis any advice.
   McKay's report is expected to raise questions about Meese's
ethical conduct that will be examined by the Justice Department's
Office of Professional Responsibility in the coming months, sources
familiar with McKay's investigation have said.
   McKay also has been examining Meese's meetings with regional
Bell Telephone company executives while holding $14,000 in phone
stock and has been delving into a Washington real estate family
providing funds for a job for Meese's wife Ursula and leasing
buildings to the Justice Department.
</TEXT>
