<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-US     06-02 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-US,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Broadcasting Company Says Dukakis Bows To Black Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state-run broadcasting
company charged Thursday that pressure by blacks prompted U.S.
presidential hopeful Michael Dukakis to accuse South Africa of
terrorism.
   The accusation by Dukakis, the likely Democratic nominee, had no
factual basis and ``was quite openly a capitulation to threats that
black voters' support would depend on his making such a
statement,'' said the South African Broadcasting Corp. in an
editorial.
   It was the latest in a wave of attacks by right-wing and
mainstream news media on U.S. politicians campaigning to toughen
sanctions against South Africa.
   Several commentators have suggested that South Africans should
shift attention to Europe and the Far East and abandon hope of any
constructive U.S. dealings.
   A Johannesburg brokerage firm, Davis Borkum Hare, reported
Thursday that one proposal in Congress would force the sale of $7
billion of U.S.-held shares in South Africa's mining companies. The
report said U.S. citizens held 14.2 percent of all South African
mining shares as of Jan. 1.
   South Africa has developed ``appropriate counter-strategies'' to
combat the African National Congress guerrilla movement, the
broadcast commentary said. A pro-goverment Johannesburg newspaper,
The Citizen, said South Africa ``will be in for a lot of trouble''
if the Massachusetts governor becomes president.
   ``Dukakis has been easily swayed by the likes of the Rev. Jesse
Jackson and Archbishop Desmond Tutu, and he will do everything he
can to try and strangle the South African economy,'' The Citizen
said in an editorial Wednesday.
   ``But this son of immigrant parents should know that South
Africans have deep-seated roots in this country that go back more
than three centuries and they will not give in to U.S. demands nor
submit to U.S. sanctions,'' it said.
   Dukakis has accused South Africa of terrorist acts but has not
called it a terrorist state, as Jackson has urged him to do.
   Tutu, leader of the Anglican church in southern Africa, praised
Dukakis during a recent U.S. trip and endorsed sanctions pending in
Congress.
   Pro-government media have denounced the black cleric, saying he
has no mandate and ignores the harm which sanctions might inflict
on blacks.
   An accurate assessment of black views on sanctions is difficult
to obtain because the 26 million blacks cannot vote in national
elections or referendums, and public advocacy of sanctions is
forbidden under emergency regulations.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   Business Day, a Johannesburg newspaper reflecting the views of
moderate business executives, has carried several articles
assailing the U.S. proposals. The sanctions would cut off virtually
all bilateral economic activity, except for trade in certain
strategic minerals.
   The newspaper reported that the proposals include a section that
says the United States should not provide advice to South Africa in
the event of a nuclear accident.
</TEXT>
