<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Deukmejian-Veep Bjt   06-02 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deukmejian-Veep, Bjt,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Governor Insists Vice Presidency Not Possible</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One in a series of occasional profiles on vice presidential
prospects</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California Gov. George Deukmejian has
said at least 100 times that he couldn't accept the Republican
nomination for vice president because he would have to turn over
his office to the Democratic lieutenant governor.
   The governor's protests notwithstanding, he remains an
attractive vice presidential prospect as George Bush tries to keep
California, with its 47 electoral votes, in the GOP column in
November.
   ``As I've said many times now,'' Deukmejian said of the vice
presidency a few weeks ago, ``I don't expect even to be asked, but
if I was asked, if I am asked, I cannot accept it.
   ``If I were on the (national) ticket and that ticket was to be
successful, it would mean turning over the entire executive branch
of California state government to the other party, which I'm not
about to do.''
   California voters, who cast separate ballots for governor and
lieutenant governor, have saddled Deukmejian with a Democrat in the
No. 2 spot in state government, Leo McCarthy. McCarthy, however, is
running this year for the U.S. Senate and would not necessarily be
Deukmejian's successor. But that doesn't ease the governor's
problem, because the next person in line is another Democrat, state
Senate President Pro Tem David Roberti.
   But Deukmejian continues to fan speculation with comments such
as these to a Texas GOP fundraiser: ``I'm still hoping that
somebody might come along and figure out a way I could be vice
president and at the same time (let) the Republicans hold onto
control of the statehouse in California.''
   The importance to Bush of winning California is enormous, and it
is clear that Bush needs help in the Golden State despite Ronald
Reagan's lasting popularity here. Although California has ended up
in the GOP column in eight of the last nine presidential elections,
a Californian has been on the Republican ticket, either for
president or vice president, in six of those races.
   The most recent presidential election in which there was not a
Californian on the GOP ticket was the 1976 race between Republican
Gerald Ford and Democrat Jimmy Carter, in which Ford carried
California by a scant 1.7 percent.
   Although the prospect of Deukmejian turning the California
statehouse over to a Democrat is strongly opposed by state
Republican party leaders, California voters have given pollsters
mixed signals that they would probably be more inclined to vote for
Bush if Deukmejian were on the ticket with him.
   In a late May survey, Mervin Field's California Poll reported
Bush trailing Dukakis by 53 percent to 40 percent. But Field said a
Bush-Deukmejian ticket narrowed that margin only to 51-41 against a
Dukakis-John Glenn ticket, and that a Bush-Deukmejian ticket led
Dukakis-Sam Nunn and Dukakis-Jesse Jackson tickets by 2 and 7
points respectively.
   On the positive side, Deukmejian is the son of immigrant parents
who arrived from Armenia nearly penniless at Ellis Island in the
early 1900s, a background that could help counter the ethnic appeal
of Democrat Michael Dukakis and add a humble background to balance
Bush's image of Eastern wealth and preppiness.
   The 59-year-old Deukmejian's other political assets include a
strongly favorable rating in his home state _ 61 percent positive
to 31 percent negative in a May survey. He has a scandal-free
reputation as a family man and hard-working administrator, and a
political image as a fiscal conservative and law-and-order former
attorney general.
   His most noteworthy achievement as governor was pulling the
state through the crisis of a $1.5 billion deficit inherited from
Democratic predecessor Jerry Brown without a general tax increase.
Deukmejian faces a similar crisis this year, a revenue shortfall
estimated at $2.3 billion over two years. He has been criticized
for his proposed solution, a package of spending cuts, dipping into
treasury reserves and $800 million in new state income tax revenues
that he insists are an ``adjustment'' or ``correction'' and not a
tax increase.
   His greatest liability may be what even his friends concede is a
bland speaking style and image, a problem that also plagues Bush.
   Altogether, Deukmejian, a native of Menards, N.Y., has spent 26
years in public office in California _ 16 in the state Legislature,
where he was Senate GOP floor leader for six years prior to his
1978 election as attorney general. He was elected governor by
93,000 votes in 1982 and re-elected by a landslide 1.7 million vote
margin in 1986.
</TEXT>
