<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gorbachev-SovietPress     06-02 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Soviet Press,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev's News Conference: Another Glasnost First</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev stood eyeball-to-eyeball this
week with Soviet journalists who tested the uncharted bounds of
glasnost, and he never blinked.
   Never had a Kremlin leader held a news conference on home
territory until Wednesday, when Gorbachev agreed to take questions
from 300 Soviet and foreign reporters and government officials here
for his summit talks with President Reagan.
   The five Soviet journalists chosen to ask questions were polite
and ideologically acceptable. But they raised issues that could
never have been addressed publicly by Soviet citizens only three
years ago.
   Articulate and in easy command of the occasion, Gorbachev deftly
handled such sensitive topics as war losses in Afghanistan, past
Soviet stubbornness at arms negotiations and the need for a greater
degree of democracy in Soviet society.
   By White House standards, Gorbachev's news conference was windy
_ it lasted two hours _ and disorganized. The order of the two
dozen questions was more random than under the White House formula,
which awards the first query to a wire service reporter at news
conferences that seldom last longer than a half-hour.
   Soviet journalists are still committed advocates of official
policy, but their reporting on the summit and the questions they
asked Gorbachev reflected a freer attitude.
   Gorbachev talked openly about the once-taboo subject of internal
disputes within the Kremlin leadership. He explained his problems
with foot-dragging conservatives until Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze whispered that the Soviet journalist was asking about
American factions that are hesitant about improving superpower
relations.
   ``You mean you're talking not about our conservatives but their
conservatives?'' Gorbachev asked magazine editor Valentin Berezhkov.
   The auditorium erupted in laughter.
   The reporters' questions and Gorbachev's responses would have
been unthinkable before the Soviet leader introduced his reforms in
early 1985.
   When a correspondent for the weekly newspaper Literaturnaya
Gazeta rose to ask Gorbachev about the fate of about 300 Soviet
soldiers reportedly seized by Afghan rebels and held captive in
Pakistan.
   Without a hint of discomfort, Gorbachev responded with the
sincerity of a concerned father that ``we will do everything so
that our people return home.''
   The most delicate queries were posed by foreign reporters, who
outnumbered their Soviet counterparts by at least 2-to-1 and were
allowed to ask the most questions.
   Gorbachev gave a self-assured response even to the most
sensitive questions about his relationship with KreqE@oO__oo@O@Wgor
K. Ligachev, who is reported to be challenging
Gorbachev over the pace of reforms, and the inflammatory remarks of
Boris N. Yeltsin, the ousted Moscow party chief who called Monday
for Ligachev's resignation.
   Gorbachev did not fully answer some questions, such as whether
the June 28 party conference could prove contentious, but he never
refused outright to respond to a query.
   Melor Sturua, a correspondent for the government newspaper
Izvestia who was expelled from Washington in a tit-for-tat exchange
in 1983, commented during one question that the Soviet side had
hampered negotiations over verification procedures during arms
talks at Geneva.
   The Soviet leader agreed with Sturua's assessment, but
attributed current difficulties to American intransigence.
   Gorbachev told the reporters he had enjoyed the opportunity to
talk with them, hinting that his first Moscow news conference might
not be his last.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Carol J. Williams has reported on Soviet affairs
and other issues for The Associated Press since 1984.
</TEXT>
