<2ND_LINE>PM-Tower Collapse, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0675,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Tower Collapses, At Least One Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to CORRECT height to 200 sted 20
stories. PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `I can't ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>COLONY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2,000-foot TV tower collapsed today,
killing two maintenance workers and apparently trapping a third in
the wreckage, police said.
   ``It's just a tangled pile of metal,'' said C.L. Harlan, a
dispatcher with the Missouri State Highway Patrol in Macon. ``They
are getting cutting torches in there to try and cut it out.''
   The maintenance crew was working at about 500 feet when the
tower as high as a 200-story building gave way around 10 a.m.,
authorities said.
   The bodies of two of the workers were found within an hour of
the collapse, the patrol said. Colony is about 25 miles from the
Iowa and Illinois borders and 200 miles northwest of St. Louis.
   The patrol said the cause of the accident was not immediately
known. Winds were calm when the tower belonging to KTVO in
Kirksville fell, said Kurt Sweeney, station news director.
   The transmission tower went up in September and was one of the
tallest in the nation, visible from more than 30 miles, authorities
said. Jerry Heilman, KTVO general manager, said the workers were
replacing more than 1,000 structural braces.
   ``I can't even venture a guess as to what happened,'' said
Heilman. ``At this point, I don't know why it fell. It was very
tragic that human life was lost.''
   Martha Huber, who lives about a quarter mile from the tower,
said she looked out her window and saw the structure falling. It
did not strike any homes in the mainly rural area but tore down
several trees, witnesses said.
   ``I heard it and it sounded like a jet taking off,'' said Ms.
Huber's sister, Elizabeth Huber.
   The workers were employees of Structural System Technology Inc.
of McLean, Va., and had been working in Colony for several weeks.
   KTVO was off the air following the collapse. An FM radio station
that also broadcast from the tower, KRXL in Kirksville, was working
on reduced power, authorities said.
   The tower was the maximum height allowed under Federal Aviation
Administration rules, said Sharon Scott, public service specialist
for the Federal Communications Commission in Kansas City.
</TEXT>
