<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Marijuana-Trauma     06-02 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marijuana-Trauma,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One-Third of Trauma Victims Used Marijuana Before Injury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than one-third of the patients at the
University of Maryland Shock Trauma Center used marijuana several
hours before sustaining their injuries, a study has found.
   Another third had been drinking alcohol before they were hurt,
and 16.5 percent had been both drinking and smoking marijuana,
according to the study appearing in the June issue of Archives of
Surgery.
   ``To me, it was rather startling to see that an illicit drug
matched in use a legal drug,'' said Carl A. Soderstrom, a surgeon
who headed the research team from the Maryland Institute for
Emergency Medical Systems.
   ``The suggestion is that the use of this drug alone and in
combination with alcohol may be the reason why they got hurt and
ended up hurting someone else,'' Soderstrom said.
   The study, based on leftover blood samples collected from July
29, 1985, to May 8, 1986, provided a ``phenomenally high number of
positives for marijuana,'' said Dr. Edward J. Cone of the Johns
Hopkins Addiction Research Center at Francis Scott Key Medical
Center.
   ``There's a common misconception that marijuana is a safe drug.
But the statistics coming out of that study clearly show that
people who are using marijuana are involved in accidents at a much
higher rate than you would expect,'' Cone said.
   Soderstrom said more studies need to be done, since the
marijuana use rate he detected was four to 10 times as great as the
rate reported in previous studies of car crash victims in Canada
and North Carolina.
   Soderstrom's study is based on blood samples from 1,023 patients
treated at the shock-trauma center. About two thirds had been
involved in car crashes, while the others suffered their injuries
in falls, assaults and accidents.
   About 73 percent were men and 58.4 percent were 30 or younger.
   The results showed 34.7 percent of the patients tested had used
marijuana and 33.5 percent were under the influence of alcohol.
   Soderstrom said that of 393 drivers admitted, 1 in 6 had both
marijuana and alcohol in their systems. More than three-quarters of
those who drank registered blood-alcohol levels equal to or higher
than the 0.1 level commonly used to determine drunkenness.
   Soderstrom said blood sample testing, or radioimmunoassay,
rarely registers positive levels more than four hours after use of
marijuana.

</TEXT>
