<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Airlines-Drugs     06-02 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airlines-Drugs,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Unions Claim Drug Testing Unnecessary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed mandatory drug-testing program for
airline workers prompted sharp criticism Thursday from airline
labor unions, which argued there is no evidence of a problem in the
industry to warrant it.
   The union officials were among witnesses who testified at a
public hearing on a proposed Federal Aviation Administration
regulation that would require a broad range of drug tests,
including random screening of tens of thousands of pilots, flight
attendants and other airline employees.
   Representatives of airline management backed the regulations, as
did administration officials.
   The drug-testing program ``is crucial in our effort to establish
a drug-free aviation system,'' said Transportation Secretary Jim
Burnley, who conducted the hearing with FAA Administrator Allan
McArtor.
   The proposed regulations call for pre-employment tests,
post-accident tests, tests if drug use is suspected and a system of
random tests of employees.
   Burnley and McArtor have repeatedly called for a drug-testing
program in aviation and last year began random testing of
Transportation Department employees in a variety of safety-related
jobs, including air traffic controllers.
   ``We are concerned ... that (the department) may ahve already
decided on the main elements of this proposal'' especially random
testing, said Raymond Woolfolk, representing the 40,000-member Air
Line Pilots Association.
   He said the union is ``uncompromisingly opposed to random drug
testing of pilots'' because no evidence has been shown that such
tests are needed or that they will be able to identify the small
number _ if any _ of drug users in the industry.
   ``To locate that one pilot, many thousands of tests would have
to be given,'' Woolfolk said. ``... Instead of eliminating drug
abuse, (the mandatory testing) will merely spawn resentment,
opposition and litigation.''
   Capt. C.R. Paty of the Allied Pilots Association, which
represents pilots at American Airlines, complained that commercial
aviators are being singled out while private pilots, in whom more
of a drug problem has been documented, are not subject to the
testing.
   ``Regulations are proposed to monitor our conduct, while pilots
in the general aviation sector whose statistics reveal some measure
of drug abuse, are left unregulated,'' Paty said in a written
statement.
   Representatives of flight attendants unions also opposed the
rule, as did groups representing private pilots and air taxi
operators.
   Society's drug problem ``should be dealt with by reasonable, not
intrusive means. Targeting specific, highly visible groups without
cause is not reasonable,'' said Brian Moreau, vice president of the
Independent Union of Flight Attendants.
   The pilot and flight attendant groups suggested that instead of
mandatory random testing, the FAA help the industry develop a
voluntary detection and rehabilitation program for drug abuse
similar to the program the industry for years has used to deal with
alcoholism.
   But the drug-testing regulation received the endorsement of the
Air Transport Association, the trade group for the major airlines.
   ``We support, as we have from the beginning, the goals of the
proposed (testing) rule. ... The justification clearly must be the
protection of public safety.'' said James Landry, the trade
association's general counsel.
   The FAA plans to hold further hearings on the drug-testing rule
in Denver on June 7 and San Francisco on June 9. A final rule is
likely before the end of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
