<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Jamaica-Manley     06-02 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jamaica-Manley,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Socialist Says His Next Government Would Be Different</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The return of Michael Manley to power in Jamaica
wouldn't mean a repeat of the tumultuous, pro-Cuba policies that
marked his leadership in the 1970s, the Socialist opposition leader
said during a Miami visit.
   Manley, 63, will lead his People's National Party in elections
this year against the Jamaican Labor Party of Prime Minister Edward
Seaga, an ally of President Reagan who has rebuilt the economy
around trade and tourism.
   Polls by Jamaican sociologist Carl Stone, who has accurately
predicted all island elections for 12 years, have consistently
given Manley a solid lead over Seaga, whose no-nonsense style has
overshadowed his economic recovery program.
   Seaga defeated Manley in 1980 with the economy deteriorated and
tensions high over the heavy involvement of Cuba and radicals in
the Manley government.
   But Manley, calling himself more mature and wiser after years of
analyzing his government's failings, has met in recent years with
Vice President George Bush, Secretary of State George Shultz, other
U.S. officials and Jamaican and international business leaders to
outline his plans for a new approach.
   ``I think that what happened then was that a situation was
allowed to escalate that should never have happened,'' Manley said
in an interview Tuesday.
   ``We're quite clear we would have diplomatic relations with Cuba
as part of the Third World, part of the hemisphere, part of the
region, etc. But we do not ever intend again to allow the
relationship with Cuba to become internally divisive or a source of
trouble with Washington.
   ``We've had many discussions about this with the State
Department, and I don't anticipate it's going to be a problem,''
said Manley, who blamed U.S. economic hostility and CIA activity
for undermining his government in his 1982 book: ``Jamaica:
Struggle In The Periphery.'' Seaga broke relations with Cuba.
   ``The main problem where Cuba was concerned was that as our
relationship developed and the pressure was put on us, we allowed
ourselves to become irritated and to become defiant,'' Manley said.
   Asked what Cuba can offer his nation, Manley replied: ``Nothing
in any direct sense. Their model of economic development is a
Marxist-Leninist model, and we're firmly rooted in parliamentary
democracy, human rights, rule of law and the private sector. These
are so vastly different it's hard to consider what one can
contribute to the other.''
   Seaga supporters warn that Manley's rhetoric covers up his
continued dedication to leftist principles and the influence of
radicals within his party.
   Manley, though, pointed to increased business investment in
Jamaica in the past year although ``it is almost universally
conceded that, short of a miracle, we will form the government.''
That, he said, shows the private sector is confident about his
commitment to working with it, an area he concedes he handled
poorly during his last government.
   Manley said his economic plan would promote national
self-reliance while ``shifting away from heavy taxation of the
productive side of the economy into the consumptive side; heavy
emphasis on creating new businesses, far more collaborative nature
between private sector and, importantly, revitalization of
Caricom,'' the Caribbean Community, a regional common market of the
former British West Indies.
   Elections are expected any time between July and November.
   Manley said he and Seaga have made progress in ``peace talks''
aimed at avoiding a repeat of the violence that left hundreds dead
in the 1980 election campaign.
</TEXT>
