<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-CatastrophicHealth     06-02 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Catastrophic Health,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Vote Sends Bill to Senate for Final Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today overwhelmingly approved and
sent to the Senate a catastrophic health insurance bill designed to
protect Medicare beneficiaries from the financial devastation of a
prolonged, acute illness.
   The bill, the most sweeping expansion of Medicare in its 23-year
history, includes the program's first-ever outpatient prescription
drug benefit.
   Approval by the Senate is likely after its Memorial Day recess.
Health and Human Services Secretary Otis R. Bowen has said he will
recommend that President Reagan sign the legislation despite
earlier administration misgivings that the bill is too broad.
   The House voted for the bill 328-72.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee, called the plan ``a good, reasonable and responsible
agreement'' and said he expected approval by the president.
   Under the legislation, the out-of-pocket deductible for doctor
bills covered by Medicare _ the amount paid by each recipient
before government aid takes over all costs _ will wind up somewhere
between $1,320 a year and $1,400.
   The hospital benefit is already set: full, 365 day-a-year
coverage after a one-day deductible that rises along with average
hospital costs. The 1988 deductible is $540.
   Once fully implemented in 1993, the new prescription drug
benefit will pay 80 percent of those costs after a $655 deductible.
   By contrast, Medicare now pays no more than 80 percent of doctor
bills no matter how high they climb and only 60 days of full
hospital coverage after a one-day deductible.
   The only prescription drugs now covered by Medicare are a
handful of particularly expensive ones such as anti-rejection
medication for organ transplant patients.
   All of the additional benefits are to be paid for by additional
charges to Medicare enrollees. The charges will be a blend of flat
monthly premium increases deducted from Social Security checks and
an additional, sliding-  scale supplemental premium charged the
estimated 40 percent of the elderly to be subject to federal income
taxes.
   The additional flat premium will start at about $4 a month in
1989, climbing to $10.20 in 1993.
   The so-called supplemental premium, tantamount to an income tax
surcharge, is expected to total an additional $22 a year for each
$150 of income tax owed in 1989, climbing to an additional $42 a
year on each $150 of tax liability by 1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
