<DOCNO> AP880602-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1536EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     06-02 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Policeman Killed, Nine Wounded During Local Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists killed a
policeman and wounded nine people in attacks on polling booths
Thursday in an unsuccessful effort to block local elections, police
said.
   Elections Commissioner Chandrananda de Silva said that despite
the violence, about half of the 3.6 million eligible voters cast
ballots in two District Council elections in western and central
Sri Lanka.
   Final results for the 158 seats were expected Friday.
   Opposition politicans charged voting irregularities, and
Chandrananda said the complaints were being investigated.
   The violence was blamed on the Peoples Liberation Front, a group
of nationalist extremists among the majority Sinhalese that
threatened to kill candidates and voters. The front opposes
concessions to minority Tamils fighting for autonomy on the island
nation.
   Police said the extremists killed a policeman and injured six
other lawmen in two attacks on an election site in the village of
Matugama, 35 miles southeast of Colombo.
   A bomb exploded in a polling station in the town of Nuwara
Eliya, 60 miles east of Colombo, wounding two voters and an
election official, said the police officials, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   Officials said armed members of the front also tied up two
policemen and took their rifles at a polling station at Dullewa, 60
miles northeast of the capital. The rebels burned paper ballots but
did not harm them, the officials said.
   The Sinhalese front also was blamed for attacks Wednesday in
which one policeman and an air force member were killed and more
than 15 government buildings were razed. Two Sinhalese extremists
also were killed Wednesday in a shootout with police.
   The violence occurred despite the deployment of an estimated
15,000 police and other security forces in the two districts.
   An Indian-sponsored peace accord called for the creation of the
councils. The accord, signed July 29, called for the minority
Tamils to end their five-year insurgency in exchange for more say
in government.
   The Sinhalese front, outlawed after a failed 1971 coup, contends
that the pact makes too many concessions to the Tamils and has
vowed to block it. It has been blamed for killing more than 300
people since July.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus and compose 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million population, claim they are discriminated against
by the island's majority Sinhalese Buddhists.
   A Tamil rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam,
rejected the accord. India has sent more than 50,000 soldiers to
the island to quell the Tamil rebellion.
   Four district councils were elected April 28. Another council
will be selected next week in the south. Elections in the north and
east have been delayed indefinitely because of the continuing Tamil
insurgency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
