<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ColumbiaDean     06-02 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Columbia Dean,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Konner Named Columbia J-School Dean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joan Konner, a producer who has worked on Bill
Moyers' programs for public television, has been named dean of the
Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism, the school
announced Thursday.
   Ms. Konner, 57, will become the fifth dean and first woman to
head the school. She succeeds Osborn Elliott, who stepped down two
years ago. Frederick Yu, a faculty member, has been acting dean.
   ``A thorough, national search was essential in filling this
important post but ... we found the excellence we sought close
by,'' said Columbia President Michael Sovern.
   A 1961 graduate of the school and a university trustee, Ms.
Konner joined The Record in Hackensack, N.J., in 1961 as a
reporter, and moved to television station WNET in New York in 1963.
She worked at NBC News from 1965 until 1977.
   She rejoined WNET in 1977, and was executive producer of ``Bill
Moyers' Journal'' from 1978 to 1981.
   Her programs have won nine Emmys, the Peabody Award and the
duPont-Columbia University Award in Broadcast Journalism.
   In 1986 Ms. Konner and Moyers formed Public Affairs Television
Inc., which produces all Moyers' programs. Moyers said Columbia
students will be ``as lucky to sit at her feet as I have been to
have her by my side.''
</TEXT>
