<DOCNO> AP880602-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-SecretSpeech     06-02 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Secret Speech,0504</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Party Official Calls For Publication of Khrushchev Speech on Stalin
^By BRIAN FRIEDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist Party member on Thursday called for
the publication of a ``secret speech'' Nikita S. Khrushchev gave in
1956 that detailed dictator Josef V. Stalin's crimes against
society.
   ``If the party is keeping secrets from Communists in the pages
of its history that are not state secrets, then it is clear that it
doesn't serve the unity of the party,'' said V. Rusakov, dean of
the Philosophy and Scientific Communism Department at Sverdlovsk
Agricultural Institute.
   The article by Rusakov, a teacher of Marxism-Leninism, was
published in Thursday's editions of the Sovietskaya Kultura
newspaper.
   It appeared to be the latest example in the leadership's
campaign to open up the pages of Soviet history and break down the
barriers erected by those who are clinging to the old policy of
guarding and controlling all information.
   Khrushchev's address to the 20th Party Congress, held three
years after the death of Josef V. Stalin in 1953, described the
dictator's crimes in the 29 years he served as Soviet leader.
   About 20 million Soviets were killed in political purges carried
out under Stalin and in the drive to collectivize agriculture,
according to estimates by Western historians.
   Under Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
``glasnost,'' or greater openness on selected topics, Stalin's
crimes are no longer a taboo subject. The name of Khrushchev, who
was ousted as leader in 1964, is appearing more frequently in the
press.
   The call by Rusakov to publish Khrushchev's denunciation of
Stalin is not the first. In October, prominent Soviet scientist
Vitaly I. Goldansky also said Khrushchev's report, known in the
West as his ``secret speech'' because it was delivered behind
closed doors, should be published.
   The withholding of the information from Soviets was
``ridiculous,'' Rusakov said, since the text of the speech was
leaked almost immediately in the West.
   ``All the world a long time ago read the `secret' report by N.S.
Khrushchev at the 20th Party Congress of the CPSU (Communist Party
of the Soviet Union), but an overwhelming majority of Soviet
Communists don't know this document, which so radically changed the
evaluation of the development of the party and the state,'' the
educator wrote.
   He said the whole nation, not just party members, awaits the
publication of Khrushchev's report, as well as the documents of all
party congresses, conferences and plenums.
   Rusakov said that was necessary for historical research, which
he said was a part of glasnost. He said the documents should also
be put before the public to overcome ``the stereotypes and myths
which were created and indoctrinated into the consciousness of the
people.''
   He called for an accounting of how people were politically
repressed and who was responsible.
   ``This is the sole means to avoid the gossip, rumors and
ill-intended falsification of the internal life and history of the
party,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
