<DOCNO> AP880602-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1823EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LostDies     06-02 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lost Dies,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dies for Gold Coins Missing, Mint Admits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dies used to strike the most valuable coin
minted by the government are missing, a Treasury Department
official acknowledged Thursday.
   The Secret Service is investigating the disappearance in January
of 24 dies for the obverse, or front, of 1-ounce gold bullion
Eagles, said Michael Brown, a spokesman for the U.S. Mint. They
were lost or stolen while en route between mints in San Francisco
and West Point, N.Y., he said.
   The Eagle has a face value of $50 but the sales price, currently
$460 to $470, fluctuates with the price of spot gold. The dies,
which are 5-inch-long cylinders the width of a coin, are worth
about $40 each, Brown said.
   He said the missing dies likely would be of little use to
counterfeiters because all were for one side of the coin.
   But Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the House Banking
subcommittee that oversees the Mint, branded the loss _ the second
such mishap in two years _ ``unpardonable.''
   In the first incident, 44 dies used to strike the $1 Statue of
Liberty commemorative coins disappeared in April 1986 on their way
to the Royal Canadian Mint in Ottawa. Only one was ever recovered.
It turned up last year in the possession of a Canadian coin dealer
at a coin show in Atlanta.
   After the 1986 incident, the Mint began hiring armored cars for
cross-border shipments but continued to use overnight mail services
for delivery within the United States.
   Normally employees of the delivery service sign for the dies at
each transfer point, but Brown said a clerk at the San Francisco
Mint apparently failed to complete a shipping form requiring that.
   ``They were shipped as ordinary freight, as if they were a crate
of oranges,'' Annunzio said in a recent speech on the House floor.
``Someone apparently figured out that a package going from one mint
to another mint would be valuable.''
   Annunzio said he would grill Mint officials on the subject at
budget hearings conducted by his subcommittee later this year.
   ``I intend to find out why security for dies was so deliberately
lax,'' he said. ``Losing dies once because of slack shipping
procedures is inexcusable; losing dies a second time is
unpardonable.''
   Brown said about 75,000 dies are shipped around the country each
year. They are made in Philadelphia and sent to regional mints,
depending on production schedules. Dies used to mint ``proof''
coins for collectors are sent to San Francisco for a special
polishing process.
   Beginning in late April, the Mint began using armored cars for
domestic, as well as cross-border shipments, he said.
   ``I think our record's pretty good. ... Obviously it was a
mistake and we don't like them to happen and we moved quickly to
make sure it doesn't happen again,'' he said.
   The clerk has not been disciplined, Brown said, but ``We're
working on that process right now.''
   However, Annunzio noted that the change in shipping procedures
came three months after the Eagle dies disappeared.
   ``The Mint's foot-dragging on switching to a secure method of
shipping dies is inexplicable,'' he said in the floor speech,
delivered May 25 and first reported in Thursday's editions of The
Washington Post.
   ``Was the Mint trying to pinch pennies? ... Quite frankly I do
not have the answers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1951EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Strike     06-02 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Strike,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineers And University Employees Stage 24-Hour Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 130,000 engineers, technicians and
university employees staged a 24-hour warning strike Thursday,
disrupting work at military industries, delaying flights and
slowing down work at government offices.
   The three unions called the strike to press wage demands in
stalled contract negotiations.
   A Tel Aviv labor court ordered the workers back to work, and
union leaders said they would comply at the end of the job action
scheduled for midnight Thursday.
   President Chaim Herzog said the strikers were ``fighting
professional struggles on the public's back, on the back of the
citizens.''
   ``I rise up against this norm, which has become entrenched in
Israel,'' Herzog said on Israel's army radio, the only radio
station operating Thursday.
   The strikers also shut down the government-run television
station. The Bezek telephone company did not make repairs, and the
electric company operated on a reduced weekend schedule, according
to the radio report.
   The strike virtually paralyzed the government-run aviation
industry, military factories, high technology industries and some
plants owned by the Histadrut, Israel's trade union federation, the
radio said.
   At Ben Gurion International Airport near Tel Aviv, some
disruptions, including flight delays, were reported.
   ``The automatic luggage distributor has failed, and of course
the technicians are not repairing it,'' union leader Moshe
Ben-David told the radio.
   At Tel Aviv University, about 500 engineers and administration
officials did not show up for work, shutting down laboratories and
computers, said university spokeswoman Carole Cook. Jerry Barach, a
spokesman for Jerusalem's Hebrew University, reported a similar
situation.
   Yitzhak Raz, head of the technicians union, said the strike was
a warning to the Finance Ministry to renew stalled wage
negotiations.
   Finance Minister Moshe Nissim, who has maintained strict price
and wage controls to keep Israel's high inflation in check,
responded by saying the strike did not damage to the economy.
   ``This is a one-day strike that was forced on the workers by the
professional unions, and I heard that many workers were
dissatisfied (with the strike call),'' he said.
   The strike came just after negotiations passed a major hurdle,
when unions agreed to end the linkage between wages and economic
indicators, said ministry spokesman Yitzhak Feinberg.
   Such linkages in the past have been blamed as contributing to
high inflation rates.
   The unions represent workers in variety of workplaces and salary
levels. They have not stated specific figures, but they want raises
of at least 10 percent. Monthly salaries now range from $435 to
$1,850.
   The government maintains the economy now is stable so even small
raises are unnecessary. Inflation last year was 20 percent, which
is low by Israeli standards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Summit-Allies     06-02 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Allies,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Briefs NATO, Allies Cheer Better East-West Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
told the NATO allies Thursday that the failure to reach a strategic
arms agreement at the Moscow summit was a blessing ``in a curious
way'' because it allowed more attention to be focused on human
rights and other issues.
   The allies, in turn, cheered what they called a broad
improvement in East-West relations.
   Shultz met with European foreign ministers and other alliance
officials for about two hours before flying to London to join
President Reagan. He plans to leave Friday on a new mission to the
Middle East to push his plan for Arab-Israeli peace talks.
   ``I certainly feel, and I believe all my fellow foreign
ministers felt, the outcome was a very good one,'' Shultz said at a
news conference.
   He said the two leaders had scored advances in numerous areas of
arms control, including negotiations to ban chemical weapons, cut
long-range nuclear missiles and reduce East-West conventional
forces.
   Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the West German foreign minister, told
reporters after meeting with Shultz that his government was pleased
with the summit results, despite the lack of a big breakthrough in
arms control.
   ``We share his opinion that it was a successful and substantial
summit,'' Genscher said. ``Through this summit the American-Soviet
relationship got a new stability, a new perspective.''
   Other alliance officials were equally upbeat.
   ``What is important is the judgment that Shultz gave that the
political climate of the meeting was a substantial success,''
Italian Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti told reporters.
   Lord Carrington, the NATO secretary general, underscored the
emphasis Reagan put on human rights issues during the summit, as
well as the progress reported in various areas of arms control.
   ``All these are elements of an increasingly stable relationship
between the United States and the Soviet Union which can only
benefit the alliance,'' Carrington said.
   In his news conference, Shultz discounted Gorbachev's comment on
Wednesday that the summit could have achieved more in arms control.
   ``Always it's possible to achieve more ... but it simply wasn't
possible to work through all of the difficult issues, and I think
we all recognize that,'' he said.
   Shultz said that absent a major arms control breakthrough, the
superpowers were able to give more attention to three other main
agenda items: human rights, bilateral relations and regional issues
such as the Angolan civil war.
   He called this a blessing ``in a curious way.''
   ``The absence of anything like that has caused people to reflect
on what may be the more important meaning of what the president,
the general secretary and others have managed to put together
here,'' Shultz said.
   ``People can see more clearly than otherwise that the
(superpower) relationship now proceeds on the basis of an
established, four-part agenda.''
   Shultz declined to rule out a U.S.-Soviet agreement on 30
percent to 50 percent reductions in strategic, or long-range,
nuclear weapons before Reagan leaves office next January. The main
stumbling block is Soviet objections to Reagan's Strategic Defense
Initiative for developing a space-based defense against ballistic
missiles.
   ``It's possible. We're going to work hard on it,'' Shultz said.
Negotiations are scheduled to resume in Geneva on July 12.
   Genscher said he told Shultz that the Europeans were
particularly eager to see a strategic arms accord, since the Soviet
long-range missiles can be targeted on European as well as American
territory.
   Andreotti said Shultz told the NATO meeting that Gorbachev had
demonstrated at the summit a determination ``to want to conclude
initiatives with this administration to the maximum extent
possible.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
