<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SummitEnvoys     06-02 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit Envoys,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top US Officials Embarking On Summit Briefing Tours</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's special arms control
adviser began an Asian trip Thursday to brief leaders on the
summit, and a top State Department official planned a similar visit
to two of Moscow's tightest adherents.
   Edward L. Rowny, the arms control official, told Japanese
Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno ``the summit was a triumph of
realism,'' according to an account issued by Rowny's office.
   Rowny, who in the past has been outspoken in his criticism of
Soviet motives, said progress on strategic disarmament was made at
the summit, but ``let's remember that the Soviet negotiators always
seek to cripple us in areas where they fear we might utilize our
comparative technological advantages.
   ``Whenever they move away from such positions and agree to truly
equitable measures, they are not being motivated by philanthropy.
Rather they are responding to patience, firmness and solidarity on
the part of the allies.''
   Rowny was scheduled to brief Chinese leaders on Saturday and
planned to go to Australia and South Korea for similar meetings.
   The State Department announced, meanwhile, that Deputy Secretary
John C. Whitehead will visit East Germany, Austria, Hungary,
Yugoslavia, West Germany and the Netherlands during a trip to
Europe beginning Friday, ``to review the results of the summit''
and discuss other issues.
   East Germany and Hungary are Soviet allies and provide troops to
the Warsaw Pact forces in Eastern Europe.
   Since Reagan first met Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in
Geneva in 1985, the United States has made a practice of sending
top-level officials on post-summit trips to Eastern Europe, to make
sure the Soviets' allies get the U.S. perspective on how the
meetings went.
   There are no plans for Whitehead to meet Kurt Waldheim, the
president of neutral Austria, during talks in Vienna. Waldheim has
been barred from entry to the United States because of his
activities as an officer in the German army in World War II and
U.S. diplomats are under orders to avoid contacts with the Austrian
president.
</TEXT>
