<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Spycatcher 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spycatcher, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0723,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Government Loses `Spycatcher' Battle in Australia</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with three grafs to move up references to Thatcher's
campaign and press freedom. Pick up 3rd pvs, `The judges...' SUBS
7th pvs, `Prime Minister...' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
Thursday lost a three-year court battle to block Australian
publication of a former intelligence agent's memoirs.
   Mrs. Thatcher's expensive crusade against Peter Wright's
``Spycatcher'' had prompted protests that the government was
infringing on freedom of the press.
   Australia's highest court, the seven-judge High Court in the
capital of Canberra, ruled against Britain in its final bid to
suppress the book.
   The judges accepted Britain's contention that Wright was bound
by a lifetime oath of silence about his 25 years with the MI5
counterespionage agency, but they said Australian courts had no
jurisdiction to enforce a British security regulation.
   They unanimously rejected the British government's attempt to
seize all profits from ``Spycatcher'' to prevent further
publication of the book in Australia.
   About 240,000 copies of the book had been sold in Australia
after lower courts ruled in Wright's favor, and publishers William
Heinemann released 200,000 paperback copies immediately after
Thursday's verdict.
   The judgment also releases nearly $3.6 million in royalties to
the 73-year-old Wright, who lives on a horse farm in Tasmania and
is said to be in poor health.
   The publicity from Mrs. Thatcher's campaign against the book
accounts for much of the book's stunning commercial success.
   More than 1.4 million copies have been sold in 40 countries,
including the United States, despite the government's continued ban
in Britain and Hong Kong.
   The British taxpayer is left with an legal bill estimated at
$3.6 million. In the Australian case alone, the government was
ordered to pay an estimated $900,000 in legal costs.
   Wright's book, frequently smuggled into Britain by tourists and
Britons returning from overseas, describes his 20-year career in
the MI5 counterespionage service.
   It alleges that the security service eavesdropped on foreign
embassies, burgled offices, stole documents, plotted assassination
attempts and discussed how to bring down Harold Wilson's Labor
Party government in the 1970s.
   Mrs. Thatcher's attempt to suppress the memoirs dates from
September 1985 when an Australian court granted a temporary
injunction against the book.
   The subsequent hearings prompted newspapers in Britain to
publish extracts of ``Spycatcher,'' and the government immediately
clamped down, creating a confrontation over press freedom.
   The government maintains it has pursued the case to uphold the
principle that former security officers are bound by a lifetime
oath of silence about their work. To relax the rule, officials
argue, would seriously undermine national security.
   Lawmaker Tam Dalyell of the opposition Labor Party said the
government was squandering public money on its legal challenges.
   ``It was obvious to many lawyers and politicians many moons ago
that this (Australian decision) would happen,'' Dalyell said.
   ``It was political obstinacy and stupidity on behalf of the
government. ... The government must now abandon all other
proceedings relating to this book around the world.''
   The government still hopes to block ``Spycatcher'' in Britain,
where it has banned the book and brought a half-dozen court cases
to prevent newspapers from publishing extracts.
   On June 13, the nation's highest court, the five-judge Law Lords
of the House of Lords, is to decide whether to overturn a ban
imposed on publication of extracts from ``Spycatcher'' in three
newspapers, The Sunday Times, The Observer and The Guardian.
   Conservative Michael Mates said the principle confidentiality on
which the government based its case should be defended to the last.
   ``And I think the government has been entirely right to do that,
difficult and embarrassing as it has been,'' he said in an
interview with Independent Television News.
</TEXT>
