<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BethesdaProcedures     06-02 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bethesda Procedures,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Shows Credentialing Failure at Bethesda Naval
Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two years after its chief heart surgeon was
court-martialed, the Bethesda Naval Hospital has come under new
criticism for failing to follow physician credentialing procedures,
officials said Thursday.
   An internal investigation has concluded the latest problem did
not jeopardize patient care, and the competence of any doctors
never was called into question at the Maryland facility, the
officials added.
   But the finding that there was a procedural failure in the
hiring and credentialing of a physician at the Navy's premiere
hospital nonetheless has ``attracted high-level attention,'' one of
the officials said.
   The criticism is contained in an interim audit report by the
Navy's inspector general. The report was prompted by a complaint
from the current head of Bethesda's cardio-thoracic unit.
   The Navy said Thursday it would not release the interim audit
report, but several officials agreed to discuss the matter on
condition they not be identified.
   The issue is a particularly sensitive one for Bethesda because
of the case of Dr. Donal M. Billig, the former chief heart surgeon.
   Billig was court-martialed and convicted in 1986 of involuntary
manslaughter and negligence in the deaths of three patients. That
conviction was overturned in April by an appeals court, however,
and Billig received an honorable discharge.
   One of the key issues raised by prosecutors during the
court-martial was that Billig hid a visual handicap from his
superiors and that military recruiters failed to investigate his
background adequately.
   In the latest case, the sources said the inspector general found
the Navy failed to adequately review the patient survival record of
a heart surgeon who was returning to Bethesda after five years in
private practice as the head of the Howard University Hospital
cardio-thoracic unit.
   Ironically, the surgeon involved _ Dr. Reginald Peniston _ was a
prosecution witness against Billig.
   The officials said Thursday that Peniston's credentials were not
reviewed formally by a new panel of naval officers before his
appointment to the hospital. Peniston's appointment was finalized
in February with orders given to him to report for duty in March.
   Peniston, who was assigned temporarily to the cardio-thoracic
unit at Walter Reed Army Medical Center early in May, did not
return a phone call Thursday to discuss the matter.
   The inspector general launched the investigation after a
complaint was filed by Cmdr. Edward Woods, the current head of the
Bethesda cardio-thoracic unit.
</TEXT>
