<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Miro,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Stolen Miro Paintings Returned To Barcelona Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Thursday they recovered six
paintings by Joan Miro and arrested eight suspects in a theft two
months ago from the Fundacion Miro Museum in Barcelona.
   A painting believed to be the work of 19th century French artist
Henri Toulouse-Lautrec also was recovered, police chief Enrique de
Federico told reporters.
   Ferran Cardenal, civil governor of Barcelona, returned the Miro
paintings to the museum.
   On Wednesday, police in Milan, Italy, arrested Antonio Jorge
Carrancio of Spain in connection with the April 5 museum break-in.
   De Federico said Carrancio, 32, was in Italy seeking buyers for
the Miro works, which included gouaches, pastels and oils from the
Spanish artist's early period.
   Also on Wednesday, police arrested a 36-year-old Uruguayan, Luis
Anibal Medina, 36, and two suspects in Barcelona.
   Police found three Miro paintings and the work attributed to
Toulouse-Lautrec in a sealed tube buried near a cottage outside the
city. De Federico said authorities did not know where the fourth
painting had come from.
   The other three paintings were in a hollow wall in a fruit
warehouse owned by Carrancio's parents in the northern city of
Palencia, the police chief said, and parents and two Carrancio
brothers had wee arrested.
   Investigators began following Carrancio and Medina the day after
the theft, when a witness provided the license number of a van
registered to one of them, de Federico said.
   Carrancio set off an alarm when he broke into museum but escaped
because the lone, unarmed night watchman called police instead of
confronting the thief, police said. Medina allegedly was waiting
outside in the van.
   According to de Federico, both men have police records and are
not specialists in art theft.
</TEXT>
