<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DuarteChronology     06-02 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Duarte Chronology,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Life of Salvadoran President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Duarte</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a partial chronology of
the life and career of President Jose Napoleon Duarte of El
Salvador, who is being treated in Washington for gastric cancer.
   Nov. 23, 1925: Born in San Salvador.
   May 1948: Graduates as civil engineer from Notre Dame, South
Bend, Ind.
   Aug. 14, 1949: Marries childhood friend Ines Duran. They
eventually have six children.
   November 1960: Co-founder of Christian Democratic Party.
   March 1964: Elected to first of three terms as mayor of San
Salvador.
   Feb. 20, 1972: As he is winning the presidential election, the
vote count is stopped by the military. Duarte is arrested, severely
beaten and expelled from the country.
   October 1979: Returns from exile after coup by reformist-minded
military officers.
   March 3, 1980: Named member of third military-civilian junta,
after two previous juntas disbanded amid discord.
   Dec. 13, 1980: Named president of fourth junta. U.S. aid _ cut
off by Carter administration 10 days earlier because of human
rights abuses _ is reinstated.
   March 25, 1984: Wins plurality in presidential elections.
   May 6, 1984: Wins presidential runoff against rightist candidate
Roberto d'Aubuisson.
   June 1, 1984: Assumes presidency.
   Oct. 15, 1984: First round of peace talks with leftist rebels
held in the northern town of La Palma.
   March 31, 1985: Christian Democrats win majority in legislative
elections.
   Sept. 10, 1985: His daughter Ines, 35, is kidnapped by leftist
guerrillas.
   Oct. 24, 1985: Ines Duarte and 23 kidnapped mayors are released
in exchange for 22 rebels imprisoned by government and 100 wounded
guerrillas given safe conduct out of country.
   June 1, 1986: Proposes fresh peace talks with rebels. Proposal
accepted.
   Sept. 14, 1986: Travels to town of Sesori in northeast El
Salvador for talks with guerrillas. Rebels, saying government
forces have militarized the town, refuse to attend. Duarte says
insurgents don't want peace.
   Oct. 10, 1986: Major earthquake devastates San Salvador. An
estimated 1,500 people killed, scores of thousands left homeless.
   Oct. 14, 1987: During White House ceremony, Duarte leaves
speakers platform to kiss U.S. flag. Though applauded in
Washington, he is criticized at home for subservient attitude.
   March 20, 1988: Christian Democrats defeated by rightist
Republican Nationalist Alliance in legislative and municipal
elections.
   May 27: Government says he is suffering from bleeding ulcer,
will go to United States for treatment.
   May 31: Duarte, before leaving for Washington, says his ailment
is ``of a malignant nature.'' Delegates presidency to Vice
President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount.
   June 1: Castillo confirms that Duarte has stomach and liver
cancer. Calls him a ``man on the verge of death.''
   June 2: Duarte vows to fight his cancer and urges countrymen to
``never lose the liberty they have now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-QualityofCare     06-02 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quality of Care,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Study Cites Need To Find Way To Evaluate Doctors,
Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers lack adequate information to
evaluate the quality of care from doctors and hospitals, according
to a congressional study released Thursday.
   The study by the Office of Technology Assessment, prepared at
the request of Rep. James Scheuer, D-N.Y., said there now is no
single source readily available to the consumer to evaluate the
quality of care, and what little information is available is
difficult to collect and understand.
   Such evaluations could be created, the report said, if congress
would act to require the data to be collected and released to the
public.
   ``We have all kinds of high-tech medical equipment now, but when
it comes to information for consumers on the quality of medical
care, we are still in the ice age,'' Scheuer said in releasing the
report. ``What information is available is inadquate and frequently
incomprehensible.''
   Scheuer said he will conduct hearings to determine the best way
to evaluate the qualilty of work by doctors and hospitals and then
will push for a legislation requiring that this information be
distributed to consumers.
   ``We're trying to develop a system to give consumers information
that they need,'' he said. ``We know now that there are valid
indicators to assess both hospitals and doctors.''
   The OTA report said quality of care information could be used
not only by individual consumers, but also by companies and labor
unions that are selecting hospitals, physician groups and health
maintenance organizations.
   Doctors could find the information on other doctors useful in
deciding on referrals and in hiring staff physicians at hospitals
or HMOs.
   For now, the report said consumers rely mostly on the
suggestions and experiences of friends and families to select
doctors and hospitals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
