<HEAD>Newspaper Groups to Encourage `Readathons'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two newspaper groups said Thursday they will
encourage newspaper ``readathons'' and other activities on Sept. 8
as part of what they are calling National Newspaper Literacy Day.
   The American Newspaper Publishers Association Foundation and the
American Society of Newspaper Editors declared the special day to
coincide with the International Reading Association's celebration
of International Literacy Day.
   John Seigenthaler, editor and publisher of the Nashville
Tennessean and president of ASNE, said in announcing the joint
effort, ``National Newspaper Literacy Day focuses our attention on
the urgent need to eliminate illiteracy in America.''
   Sandra C. Hardy, vice president of Calkins Newspapers of
Levittown, Pa., and chairman of the ANPA Foundation, said, ``At
least 21 million adults cannot read at a survival level; up to 40
million cannot read bus schedules, job applications or the local
newspaper.''
   The newspaper associations' activities on that day _ the
Thursday after Labor Day _ include a National Literacy Symposium in
Washington on adult literacy programs; newspaper readathons in
shopping malls with the help of volunteers from the American
Association of Retired Persons and other organizations; and efforts
to encourage readers to share newspapers and magazines with people
who do not have print material at home.
