<DOCNO> AP880602-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Neuharth     06-02 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Neuharth,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gannett Chairman Says Castro, Botha Mistreated By U.S. Reporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allen H. Neuharth, chairman of Gannett Co.,
Inc., said Thursday that world leaders such as Cuba's Fidel Castro
and South Africa's P.W. Botha have been mistreated by U.S.
reporters whom many heads of state now view as the new ugly
Americans.
   Neuharth, answering questions after a speech at the National
Press Club, said that although he has no sympathy with Cuban
communism or with South African racism, leaders such as Castro and
Botha have a legitimate complaint.
   ``Botha and Castro have been mistreated by the press'' because
reporters have not let them be heard fairly, he said.
   All world leaders ``have the right to present their point of
view without some reporter, especially a reporter from this
country, acting like judge and jury, confronting and convicting and
then spreading news of that conviction,'' said the 64-year-old
chairman and founder of the internationally circulated newspaper
USA Today.
   Since February, Neuharth has visited 19 countries and
interviewed 15 heads of state in the newspaper's ``JetCapade''
reporting venture.
   Neuharth, who is midway in the tour with members of his staff
who fly aboard a private jetliner, said he believes he has gained
access to a wide variety of world leaders, including Castro and
Botha, because his newspaper is ``informational rather than
confrontational.''
   ``In the eyes of some leaders, the `ugly American' is no longer
the wealthy camera-laden tourist in Bermuda shorts. He or she is
the arrogant Nikon-carrying reporter from a big U.S.A. newspaper,''
Neuharth said.
   ``I hope we will not be tempted to start or stop wars, dethrone
presidents or kings or elect them. I don't think that's our role,''
he said, in announcing that 5-year-old USA Today would once again
not endorse a U.S. presidential candidate.
   He said, however, he has ``no quarrel'' with the newspaper's
editorial board decision to call for the resignation of Attorney
General Edwin Meese III.
   Neuharth said attempts to curtail press freedom are unfortunate,
``but they go with the territory as the U.S.A. press exerts greater
influence around the world.''
   ``Unless we are sensitive to different political systems and
philosophies, unless we try to report international issues from al
perspectives, not just ours, we run the risk of perpetuating
worldwide the same image of arrogance some of us suffer from here
in the U.S.A.,'' he said.
   ``Worldwide, I think it's extremely important that the media
from the U.S.A. practice informational journalism, not
confrontational journalism. We should inform, not indict ...,'' he
said.
   ``If we do that, foreign leaders and their people will talk to
us and share their problems and their hopes. If we don't, they'll
resent us and try to shut us out.''
   Neuharth said USA Today's circulation and advertising revenue
are at an all-time high, with average daily paid circulaton of 1.6
million, more than 105 ad pages published last week and weekly
revenues of $3.7 million.
   He predicted that the newspaper, which had its first profitable
quarter at the end of 1987, would either show a profit or a
marginal loss for all of 1988.
   Gannett owns and operates 90 daily newspapers, 35 non-dailies,
10 television stations, 16 radio stations, and the largest outdoor
advertising operation in North America, according to a company news
release.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1829EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WishFulfilled     06-02 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wish Fulfilled,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mom Sees Last Surviving Son Graduate
^Eds: Waller cq in 8th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANK LOWENKRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martha Chappel's sole surviving son has just
graduated from high school even though he suffers from the
congenital illness that killed his three brothers, becoming the
first of her children to live long enough to reach that goal.
   ``God has not given me children to keep forever,'' she said
Thursday. ``He gave them to me to love and care for, they are a
loan.''
   Willie Jackson, 18, graduated this week from Cold Spring School,
a public school for mentally and physically handicapped children.
   One son, Adrian, died when he was 5 in 1976, followed by Eddie
in 1979 at 15 and Ernie in 1981 at 18.
   The cause each time was a rare, inherited disorder known as
Hunter's syndrome, which causes mental retardation and physical
abnormalities. There is no cure or therapy for the disease, which
strikes only males and can cause dwarfism, deafness, heart defects
and arthritic joint pain.
   ``He knew all his brothers and that they died in the hospital
and he becomes very upset when we go to a hospital,'' said Mrs.
Chappel.
   The life expectancy of children with Hunter's is 15 years.
Willie is a dwarf and is moderately retarded and deaf in one ear.
   ``This boy has been so close to death you could almost see it,
but he's so strong,'' said his stepfather, Waller Chappel.
   Mrs. Chappel didn't know her first two boys had Hunter's until
after the third, Willie, was born.
   ``In the beginning, it was like a shock to me. I cried for
days,'' Mrs. Chappel said. ``I kept thinking I'll have a girl and
I'll tell her not to have children. I've always wanted a lot of
kids. That's been my goal since I was little.''
   ``There have been times when I've been frustrated, but whenever
things got rough I had friends and relatives to help me over the
hump,'' Mrs. Chappel said.
   Because of the disease, Willie has a small esophagus and
difficulty breathing. He tires easily and can walk only about a
half block at a time.
   ``For the last six or seven months we've been spending about
$500-to-$600 a month for his medical expenses. We have to have
oxygen and had to get a wheelchair. We've had to struggle, but the
time with Willie and the other boys has been worth it,'' Mrs.
Chappel said.
   The graduation was ``one of the highlights of my life,'' said
Mrs. Chappel. ``He's the first to live long enough to accomplish
it.''
   She hopes to enroll Willie in a day adult program for the
handicapped so he can continue associating with other youngsters.
   ``He knew something exciting was going on (at the graduation),
all the people and receiving a certificate. He knew there was some
sort of special conglomeration taking place. But, I think he'll be
kind of sad when he learns what it means, that he won't be seeing
the teachers and children every day,'' Mrs. Chappel said. ``He's
always looked forward to the bus rides to school.''
</TEXT>
