<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Earthquake     06-02 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Earthquake,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Shakes Greek Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake shook the western
island of Cephalonia Thursday for the third time in two weeks but
there were no reports of damage or injuries, police said.
   The Athens Seismological Institute said the tremor measured 5 on
the Richter scale. Its epicenter was in the Ionian seabed off
Cephalonia, about 195 miles from Athens.
   ``We felt the tremor around lunchtime but people didn't bother
to leave their homes and there were no damage reports,'' said a
police officer on Cephalonia, speaking on condition of anoymity.
   Tremors measuring 5.8 and 5.3 on the Richter scale shook the
island on May 18 and May 21 but caused no damage.
   Buildings on Cephalonia have been constructed to withstand
tremors of 7 on the Richter scale ever since the Ionian islands off
western Greece were hit by a devastating quake in 1953.
   The Richter scale is a measure of the energy released by an
earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   A quake measuring 5 on the Richter quake can cause considerable
damage and quake measuring 6 can cause severe damage.
</TEXT>
