<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SeveredArm     06-02 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Severed Arm,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Condition Upgraded for 5-Year-old Who Lost Arm in Farm Machine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condition of a 5-year-old boy whose arm
was ripped off in a farm machine stabilized Thursday, and he was
taken off the critical list at Tampa General Hospital.
   ``He is serious but stable, which shows he is improving and
that's good news,'' said Emily Stehle, hospital spokeswoman.
   A team of three doctors gave up Wednesday after nine hours of
surgery to try to reattach Fidencio Jaurequi's limb. His right arm
was ripped from its socket Tuesday when he poked his hand into a
machine that sorts tomatoes at Singletary Farms in Dade City, where
his mother works.
   The boy's father, Salvador Jaurequi, is a carpenter who moved to
Florida from Guadalajara, Mexico, 10 years ago.
   His mother, Eustolia Jaurequi, brought her son to work Tuesday
because there was no one home to care for him, said Dora Jaurequi,
sister-in-law of the boy's father. Fidencio finished a preschool
program last month.
   Mrs. Jaurequi told investigators that Fidencio asked for money
to buy a snow cone just after lunch. He returned to where his
mother stood sorting tomatoes and began trying to touch a rolling
conveyor belt. Mrs. Jaurequi told him to stay away, but when turned
her back for a moment, the accident occurred.
   Earl Singletary, co-owner of the farm, said the machine has a
safety switch, but ``when it happened, it happened. It was done.''
   Officials from the Tampa office of the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration have begun an investigation, said Lawrence
Falck, area director.
   ``Our jursidiction is related only to the employees,'' he said.
``But from the description of the accident it sounds like there may
be hazards to employees there.''
   Singletary said Mrs. Jaurequi and some relatives have worked on
and off at the farm for about seven years.
   Dora Jaurequi said her nephew, who was born in Dade City, is a
``very happy boy.'' School officials agreed, describing him as
``delightful'' and well-mannered.''
</TEXT>
