<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PoliticalPrisoners 1stLd-Writethru a0734mittee. 06-02
0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Prisoners, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0734,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Women Held in Kentucky Federal Prison Were Mistreated</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 4th graf, Deutsch appeared, with Bureau
of Prisons rebuttal; picks up 5th graf pvs, Last week</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A half-dozen women prisoners, held in an
isolation unit in an underground Kentucky federal prison, are being
treated so inhumanely that they may be permanently psychologically
harmed, a federal judge was told Thursday.
   A lawyer argued that the women, all serving long terms in the
Federal Correctional Institution in Lexington, Ky., had to disrobe
in rooms visible to guards, shower in stalls without curtains, did
not have recreation equipment in the exercise yard, went without
heat in freezing weather and were shackled hands and feet whenever
they were taken out of their unit.
   Attorney Michael Deutsch said most of the five women he
represents had been placed in the special unit because of their
political beliefs, not for their prison behavior, and that the
purpose was ``to destroy these women.''
   Deutsch appeared before U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker
seeking to have the women removed from the high security unit and
to have it closed. The Bureau of Prisons has said it intends to
shut down the unit in July when a new medium- and high-security
facility for women will be opened in Marianna, Fla.
   John C. Cleary, representing the Bureau of Prisons, said that
the women were transferred into the unit because they posed ``a
risk of external assault on the prison.'' He said there is no
medical evidence to support an accusation that they have suffered
psychological harm.
   ``There is no question that it's constitutional to prevent
prison escapes,'' he told the judge. ``At no time were the
political beliefs of these women taken into account in transferring
them to the high security unit.''
   The arguments will continue next Tuesday.
   Last week, the Soviet news agency Trud said that the FBI was
conducting experiments on female political prisoners at the
Kentucky institution and ``exerting psychological pressures aimed
at breaking the will of the prisoners.''
   There was no reference to such activity in Deutsch's
presentation.
   But he said, the women ``are suffering from restricted
environment syndrome, from sensory deprivation, free-floating
anxiety and depression.''
   One inmate, Susan Rosenberg, was in court. She is serving a
58-year term for possessing weapons and explosives in connection
with a 1985 police raid in New Jersey and is one of seven recently
indicted in the 1983 bombing of the U.S. Capitol.
   Another of the inmates is Sylvia Baraldini, convicted of
racketeering and conspiracy in aiding a $1.6 million Brink's
armored car heist in Nyack, N.Y. that left a guard and two police
officers dead. Ms. Rosenberg was linked by law enforcement officers
to the same bungled Brink's robbery.
   Deutsch said that Ms. Baraldini had been in prison for more than
four years with only one minor infraction _ that of cutting to the
wrong side of a food line _ on her record.
   He said she was sent from prison in Pleasanton, Calif., to the
newly opened isolation unit in Kentucky in 1986 without being told
why. As for Ms. Rosenberg, he said, her status as a sympathizer
with terrorist groups was inexplicably elevated to that of member
in letter exchanges between prision officials.
   ``There is no need to have these women in this unit,'' Deutsch
said. ``There is no evidence they were involved in any escape
attempt or that they were plotting to escape.''
   Deutsch told Parker that the women were sent there after ``a
call for bodies to fill this unit.''
   The unit can house 16 women but has not had more than six, he
said, adding: ``What has happened is this: They realize they are
running an unconstitutional unit and they are closing it down.''
</TEXT>
