<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NuclearTest     06-02 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Test,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third Test in Three Weeks at Nevada Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States conducted its third
nuclear test in less than three weeks Thursday, just hours after
the conclusion of the Moscow summit.
   Nuclear testing was one of the issues addressed in Moscow, with
the Soviet Union and the United States formally agreeing to monitor
each other's tests this summer in joint verification experiments.
   The test shook the Nevada desert and registered on seismic
equipment atop hotels and casinos here, 110 miles from ground zero.
The blast measured 5.3 on the Richter scale of ground motion at the
National Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo.
   Soviet scientists who are setting up monitoring equipment at the
Nevada Test Site were at Mercury, Nev., 52 miles from ground zero,
at the time of Thursday's blast. The Soviet scientists also were on
hand for two previous tests, May 13 and May 21.
   The test was the fifth announced blast this year, and the 680th
announced test since the program moved to the Nevada desert in
January 1951.
   The nuclear device was buried 2,000 feet beneath the surface of
Pahute Mesa, a rocky patch of desert in the far northwest corner of
the 1,350-square-mile test site.
   The blast had an explosive force of up to 150 kilotons. The
atomic bomb that destroyed Hiroshima had an explosive yield of 13
kilotons. All tests are listed as less than 20 kilotons or 20 to
150 kilotons, with advance notice given for tests at or near the
upper limits. Such a notice was issued Tuesday.
   The force of the blast produced a gentle swaying motion at the
Regency Towers high-rise condominiums in Las Vegas, according to
Energy Department spokeswoman Barbara Yoerg.
   ``Everything appears normal,'' Ms. Yoerg said as she monitored
the blast from a control point 31 miles from ground zero. ``Nothing
is coming out of the ground.''
   The success of underground tests is measured, in part, by the
ability to prevent radiation from leaking into the atmosphere.
   Ms. Yoerg said she did not feel any ground motion at the control
point. DOE personnel monitoring such blasts often experience a
rocking motion following detonation.
   DOE seismic equipment atop the Golden Nugget and Mint hotels in
downtown Las Vegas and the El Rancho Hotel on the Las Vegas Strip
recorded the blast ``distinctly,'' according to Ms. Yoerg. A
similar reading was obtained at Scotty's Castle in Death Valley, 60
miles from ground zero.
</TEXT>
