<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Poll-Texas     06-02 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Poll-Texas,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Lead Narrow Over Hypothetical Dukakis-Bentsen Democratic
Ticket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush could face a close
race in Texas this fall, particularly if paired against a
Democratic ticket of Michael Dukakis and Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas, according to a newspaper poll released Thursday.
   Bush, the all-but-sure Republican nominee, held a roughly
seven-point lead over the Massachusetts governor when voters were
asked to consider only the two candidates, according to the poll
conducted for the Houston Chronicle.
   The poll, conducted between May 13-28, showed 48 percent of the
785 voters surveyed preferring Bush if the presidential election
were held the day they were contacted. Forty-one percent said they
would vote for Dukakis.
   However, when the Democratic front-runner was paired with
Bentsen as his running mate, Bush led Dukakis by only two
percentage points, 43 percent to 41 percent, falling within the
poll's three-point margin of error.
