<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bosch     06-02 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bosch,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Bosch Parole, Family Blames Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Thursday refused to release
convicted anti-Castro terrorist Orlando Bosch while he appeals an
immigration service order expelling him from the country.
   U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler reviewed 700 documents,
many of them classified intelligence reports linking Bosch, 61, to
two violent anticommunist groups, before denying bond.
   Bosch returned to the United States in February after spending
11 years in Venezuelan jails successfully fighting charges he blew
up a Cuban jetliner in 1976, killing all 73 aboard. He had fled
Florida in 1974 while on probation for a 1968 Miami bazooka attack
on a Polish ship that had previously stopped in Cuba.
   The federal parole commission, saying it had no objection to
Bosch's being freed, turned his case over to the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
   Bsch's attorney, Hank Adorno, said he had a right to live in
Miami's exile community, where he has received strong support from
many anti-Castro Cubans, ``in light of the fact that he has
renounced his ways of fighting communism and fighting Castro.''
   But the INS started proceedings to deport him, calling him an
undesirable alien with terrorist connections. The agency said he
would not be sent to Cuba, but did not specify a country where he
would go.
   The agency said Bosch has ``a history of leadership and
involvement in terrorist groups and activities,'' including a role
in two groups responsible for more than 50 bombings in the United
States and Latin America.
   ``Terrorism is terrorism, no matter how long ago it took
place,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Patricia Kenny, representing
the INS. Freeing Bosch would ``send the wrong message'' to
terrorists, she said.
   Bosch is being held at the federal Metropolitan Correctional
Center south of Miami.
   Bosch's daughter Myriam lashed out at the decision to keep her
father in custody, blaming it on the Reagan administration's desire
to reach a global accommodation with the Soviet Union and its
allies.
   ``Cuba does not want him free,'' she said. ``That is why my
father is behind bars.''
   Attorneys for Bosch said they planned to appeal to the federal
appeals court in Atlanta, but his daughter said the judge had been
the family's last hope.
   ``He's going to die in jail,'' Ms. Bosch said bitterly. ``Why
don't they just send him back to Cuba?''
   Early Thursday, Hoeveler abandoned a compromise that he had
proposed earlier to allow Bosch to remain under house arrest while
appealing his expulsion.
   Hoeveler made no reference to that proposal in his eight-page
order rejecting the petition for parole. The order said the
government has a ``legitimate and bona fide reason'' for wanting to
expel Bosch.
   Under federal law, the INS can hold an alien pending disposition
of deportation proceedings provided it is acting in good faith.
   ``The petitioner has failed to demonstrate that the attorney
general has acted in bad faith,'' the judge said, therefore he had
no power to overrule the INS decision to keep Bosch in custody.
   His deportation case now goes to the regional commissioner of
the INS in Dallas for a recommendation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
