<DOCNO> AP880602-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PhonesAtLast     06-02 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phones At Last,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phone Service is Returning to Chicago Suburbs as Costs Mount</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HINSDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The six Chicago suburbs that lost all or
part of their telephone service in a May 8 switching station fire
should have service restored by this weekend, officials said
Thursday.
   About 35,000 Illinois Bell customers had their service disrupted
when the station, which houses computerized equipment that connects
local and long distance calls, was damaged in the blaze.
   The costs of the outage continued rising _ not only for
businesses whose phone service was cut off, but also for local
governments forced to pay for overtime and emergency equipment.
   ``I've gotten very close to Illinois Bell officials over the
past few weeks,'' said Hinsdale Village Manager Ronald Ruskey.
``I'm learning about the telephone business.''
   The fire also disrupted service at several automatic teller
machines, Sears, Roebuck and Co.'s catalog sales phones and
off-track betting parlors. Crews at the Federal Aviation
Administration's control center in Aurora were forced to go to a
backup phone system, delaying some flights to Chicago's O'Hare
International Airport by two hours.
   The total cost to communities and businesses could exceed $100
million, officials said, and they said Bell would be asked to help
pay for it.
   Bell spokeswoman Laura Littel said the phone service should be
restored for customers by 12:01 a.m. Sunday, more than a week ahead
of schedule. About half the 35,000 customers were switched over to
the new system last Friday.
   ``There may be a few bugs, but we're hoping for the best,'' Ms.
Littel said.
   For governments, the fire meant extra overtime and equipment to
connect emergency services. The estimated costs ranged from $13,000
at Burr Ridge to $65,000 at Clarendon Hills.
   Ms. Littel said the exact cause of the fire is still being
investigated. The Illinois Commerce Commission hired an Annapolis,
Md., firm, Forensic Technologies International Corp., to
investigate.
   ``We do know that it's possibly electrical in nature,'' she said.
   Bell, which has promised customer rebates for the disrupted
service, is facing lawsuits from several businesses. The businesses
contend Bell was negligent in unstaffing the Hinsdale station and
for having no direct telephone link with the local fire department
at the time of the fire.
   In addition, Illinois Attorney General Neil Hartigan has filed a
complaint with the ICC, asking the comission to order Bell to pay
for financial losses.
</TEXT>
