<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AirForce-Radon     06-02 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Force-Radon,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unacceptably High Radon Levels Found at AF Academy, Colorado Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force said Thursday a new program of
testing its bases for the natural radioactive gas radon had turned
up two facilities inside the United States and three outside with
unacceptably high readings.
   Both of the bases inside the United States are located near
Colorado Springs, Colo. _ the U.S. Air Force Academy and Peterson
Air Force Base.
   One of the three bases outside the country is Andersen Air Force
Base on the island of Guam. The Air Force said it would not
identify the other two overseas bases until it had notified the
host country's government.
   The service said in a statement it was launching a more
extensive radon survey of all habitable structures and preparing to
take ``quick corrective action'' at the academy and Peterson and
Andersen bases because of radon readings above the level of 20
picoCuries per liter of air.
   ``The Environmental Protection Agency considers radon levels of
four picoCuries or less per liter of air acceptable,'' the Air
Force said. ``For a level of radon (above 20 picoCuries), the EPA
recommends that corrective action be taken within several months.''
   The service said that at 49 other bases around the world, it had
discovered one or more structures with radon levels between four
and 20 picoCuries per liter. In those cases, every habitable
building at the bases will be screened for the next year to
determine which ones need repair work to reduce radon levels below
the four picoCurie standard.
   The Air Force said 33 of those 49 bases were located in the
United States. The other 16 are located in foreign countries and
will be publicly identified ``in the near future following
notification of host countries.''
   All told, the Air Force said it had taken 4,404 air samples at
135 major bases and found 211, or 4.8 percent, at a level above
four picoCuries.
   ``The EPA has found levels above four picoCuries per liter in 14
percent to 20 percent of the houses they have tested nationwide,''
it added.
   The service declined to speculate on why the radon levels at the
two Colorado facilities and on Guam were unacceptably high.
   The Air Force became the first of the military services last
December to launch a test program for radon. The Army has since
followed suit and the Navy and Marine Corps are considering such a
move.
   Radon is a colorless, odorless natural product of decaying
uranium in the soil. Medical research has indicated that exposure
to high levels of radon over extended periods may increase the risk
of lung cancer.
   ``Results of commercial testing in communities throughout the
United States, coupled with concern about the health of Air Force
members and their families, prompted the decision to test,'' the
service said last year in announcing the program.
   The Air Force has said it will launch a ``mitigation program''
for those buildings where radon levels exceed the recommended EPA
standards, sealing foundation cracks or installing new ventilation
systems.
   The service estimated last year it would spend up to $2.6
million on the testing and up to $30 million on repair work. The
Air Force said Thursday it now appeared those figures would be
overstated, but added it did not have new estimates available.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
