<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AgingPlanes-Boeing     06-02 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aging Planes-Boeing,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Spokesman Says Company Would Oppose Mandatory Airplane
Retirement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes would oppose any
effort to set a mandatory retirement age for jetliners even though
such a requirement could boost sales of new planes, a company
spokesman said Thursday.
   ``It would be arbitrary and we don't think it would be
necessary,'' Jack Gamble, a spokesman for the Seattle-based
aerospace company, said during a break in a Federal Aviation
Administration-sponsored conference on aging aircraft.
   On Wednesday, FAA Administrator Allan McArtor raised the
possibility of mandatory airplane retirement. But Gamble said
Boeing and other aircraft manufacturers have found nothing to
suggest that jetliners can't fly safely for years if they are
properly maintained.
   ``We could be selfish and say it would be good for us,'' Gamble
said of mandatory aircraft retirement. ``But it is good equipment.''
   ``Mandatory retirement just wouldn't make any sense,'' he said.
   The average age of the world airline fleet has increased from
eight years in 1980 to nearly 12 years in 1988, said Gamble. By
2005 the average age of jetliners is expected to be 15 years.
   Gamble said that Boeing's commercial planes are built to provide
at least 20 years of ``economical'' service.
   The FAA called the three-day conference as a result of increased
concern about the safety of older jetliners since the in-flight
breakup of a 19-year-old Aloha Airlines Boeing 737 in April.
   A 20-foot section of the plane tore away and a flight attendant
was swept to her death, although pilots were able to land the
aircraft safely.
   Gamble said that even before the Aloha incident there was
increasing industry interest in aging plans and that Boeing began
looking at the problems as early as 1983.
   Since January 1987, Gamble said, Boeing has been conducting an
informal survey of 50 of its older planes owned by 33 airlines in
19 countries.
   ``There have been no surprises,'' he said of a preliminary
analysis of the survey.
   In addition, Boeing recently put a 737 it purchased from
Piedmont Airlines after an accident through an extensive series of
tests that simulated more than 200,000 takeoffs and landings.
   ``We didn't find anything unexpected,'' said Gamble, adding that
some small cracks were found in the airplane after the test, but
they were easily fixed.
   The Aloha plane involved in the recent accident had undergone
about 90,000 landings and takeoffs.
</TEXT>
