<HEAD>14 Share Honors As High School Class Valedictorian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEFONTAINE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's crowded at the top, at least at
Bellefontaine High School.
   When diplomas are passed out Sunday to 185 seniors, the school
will honor 14 valedictorians, each of whom managed a perfect 4.0
grade point average.
   ``It makes us look like we're grading on a very easy kind of
basis. But these are the same standards that we've always had. This
is an extremely unusual group of kids who just happen to be in the
same class,'' said Principal George Harris.
   Harris said the 14 valedictorians had shown their academic
prowess on college admission and scholarship tests as well as in
class. They earned more than $52,000 in scholarships, and three of
them are National Merit Scholarship winners.
   Average ACT college exam scores for the 14 seniors was 28.6,
placing them at the 95-plus percentile of all students taking the
exam across the nation.
   Tammy Watson, class secretary and one of the valedictorians,
credits the harmony of the class for its scholastic achievement.
   ``I think the strength of our class is achieving what we want
through a tremendous unity,'' Watson said. ``We work together and
help each other to reach higher goals.''
   But valedictorian Elizabeth Hendershod said she believes
competition was critical.
   ``The fact that there were 13 other candidates helped to
motivate us. We would say to ourselves, `I'm not gonna allow that
other person to get it and leave me out. If that person can get it,
I can too,' '' she said.
