<HEAD>Italian Journalist Returns Home From Afghan Jail</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th `Asked to' with further quotes.
PICKS up 5th pvs bgng, The journalist... </NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian journalist who was jailed in Afghanistan
for 6{ months on espionage charges returned home Thursday and said
he was whipped after being caught entering Afghanistan with
insurgents.
   Fausto Biloslavo, 26, told reporters he spent three or four
months in jail near the Afghan capital of Kabul before receiving
the first of two letters from his family.
   Biloslavo, who looked weary but healthy, said he would describe
his time in captivity at a news conference on Friday.
   Asked to confirm news reports that he was whipped after his
arrest in November, the journalist said: ``Yes, it happened when I
was first taken prisoner about 100 kilometers (60 miles) from
Kabul.''
   ``They put a gun to my head, made me put my hands on my head and
an officer whipped me,'' Biloslavo said, then added: ``I will
continue to work in this profession, and I will ask for a visa to
return to Kabul.''
   The journalist smiled broadly when he stepped off a special
private plane at Rome's Ciampino airport after a flight from Kabul.
   Biloslavo, who worked for the tiny Trieste-based Albatross news
agency, was greeted by his mother Grazia who hugged and kissed him.
   A crowd of well-wishers, including former Socialist Premier
Bettino Craxi, welcomed the journalist when he got off the Falcon
50 aircraft.
   Also present was Bruno Bottai, secretary general of the Italian
Foreign Ministry, who had delivered a plea for clemency to Afghan
President Najib from Italian President Francesco Cossiga. The
request was granted on Wednesday.
   ``I want to thank President Cossiga and Mr. Bottai, who
literally came to pull me out of the prison,'' said Biloslavo, who
was wearing a blue T-shirt, gray jeans and sneakers.
   Biloslavo was arrested Nov. 14 while traveling with Moslem
guerrillas battling the Soviet-backed Afghan government. He was
convicted in March of espionage and sentenced to seven years in
prison.
   He shared a jail cell with French free-lance photographer Alain
Guillo, who was freed last week after an appeal from French
President Francois Mitterrand.
   Bilislavo left Kabul early Thursday in the company of an Italian
delegation headed by Bottai. Bilislavo and Guillo were held at
Kabul's Pul-I-Charki prison after being found guilty of spying.
Both men denied the charges.
