<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0733,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Cruiser Watches Iranians Board, Escort Cypriot Vessel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf ``There was...'' with one graf to fix typo.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most powerful U.S. warship in the
Persian Gulf stood by on Thursday when Iran's navy stopped, boarded
and escorted away a Cypriot freighter apparently suspected of
carrying war-related cargo for Iraq.
   U.S. Navy officials said the guided missile cruiser Vincennes
was two miles away and did not get an appeal for aid that could
have caused the first direct confrontation with Iran since April
18. Six Iranian vessels were knocked out that day, including two
sister ships of the frigate involved in Thursday's incident.
   It also was the closest brush since the United States adopted a
new policy allowing Navy ships to intervene in attacks on neutral
commercial ships flying flags of other nations. The rule requires a
victim to be a non-belligerent in international waters that
requests assistance.
   Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke, a Navy spokesman, said the Iranian ship
was tentatively identified as the 1,540-ton frigate Alborz and
acted within maritime law that allows for ``visit and search'' in
international waters.
   It halted the Cypriot motor vessel Vevey in the southern gulf at
about 9:30 a.m. Van Dyke said the Cypriot ship ``did not request
assistance and did not appear to be in any distress.''
   He said the 9,400-ton Vincennes remained two miles away and had
no radio exchanges with either vessel.
   ``The Vincennes had the others in view as the Iranian frigate
stopped the Cypriot ship, launched a small boat that put a search
party on board and then escorted her off in a northeasterly
direction,'' Van Dyke said.
   There was ``no communication between the merchant and the U.S.
warship'' and no indication the Vevey tried to make contact during
the incident 25 miles northeast of Dubai, he said.
   Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit in London said eight Iranian
naval personnel boarded the 10,000-ton freighter and it was taken
to the Iranian port and naval base at Bandar Abbas in the Strait of
Hormuz.
   Its listed cargo was Italian marble chips and powder, bound for
Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, the report said.
   Iran considers Saudi Arabia and Kuwait to be allies of Iraq,
with which Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's regime has been at war
since September 1980. Most commercial ships it has attacked were
traveling to or from those countries.
   Iranian gunboats regularly stop and search merchant vessels to
search for war-related cargo that could be bound for Iraq.
   The Vincennes, based in San Diego, arrived in the gulf last
weekend on the first assignment to the gulf of an Aegis-type
cruiser, equipped with advanced long range radar surveillance and
missile systems.
   Three other U.S. warships left the gulf Thursday home ports on
the East Coast. The missile cruiser Wainwright and missile frigates
Jack Williams and Simpson all played prominent roles in ``Operation
Praying Mantis'' April 18.
   Staying behind in a Dubai drydock is the missile frigate Samuel
B. Roberts, which struck a mine April 14. That incident led to the
retaliation four days later.
   The Iranian frigate involved in Thursday's incident was one of
two believed operational after the April 18 encounters. The frigate
Sahand was sunk by American bombs and missiles and the fourth,
Sabalan, was severely damaged.
</TEXT>
