<2ND_LINE>AM-Aborted Takeoff, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0747,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jumbo Jet Aborts Takeoff, Captain Praised for Precautionary
Measure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with pilot aborting takeoff because he thought a
just-landed plane was still on the runway, although FAA says jet
was on taxiway. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Continental Airlines DC-10 aborted its
takeoff at Los Angeles International Airport Thursday because the
pilot thought a just-landed jet had not cleared the runway,
officials said.
   The DC-10's tires automatically deflated but no one was hurt
when Continental Flight 43 to Honolulu, carrying 148 passengers and
about 15 crewmembers, came to a stop, said airline spokesman Ned
Walker in Houston.
   Walker said the pilot felt a Delta Air Lines jet hadn't
adequately cleared the runway, but Federal Aviation Administration
spokeswoman Elly Brekke said the Delta plane was off the runway and
had come to a stop on a taxiway.
   Ms. Brekke said the Continental pilot ``took the extra margin of
safety'' in the 9:55 a.m. incident. Passengers deplaned on a
taxiway but did not use emergency exits or equipment.
   Neither Walker nor Ms. Brekke knew how far into the takeoff the
airliner had gotten before the abort, but the FAA spokeswoman said
the jet had reached at least 100 knots, or 115 mph. They did not
know the actual distance between the planes.
   ``Captain did a good job in reacting quickly when he saw the
other aircraft,'' said Walker, who would not release the names of
the crew.
   Ms. Brekke initially reported that four of the DC-10's tires
blew after the abort, but later she and Walker explained that the
tires have a safety plug that melts when heated to a certain
temperature, letting the tires deflate rather than explode.
</TEXT>
