<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ComputerCo-pilot     06-02 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Co-pilot,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Artificial Intelligence in the Cockpit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wouldn't have the lovable personality of
R2D2, but an artificial intelligence system being developed for the
Air Force would perform many of its tasks, including alerting a
pilot to key points in an air battle.
   The ``pilot's associate'' program, a version of which was
demonstrated Thursday at Lockheed Aeronautical Systems Co., was
initiated by the Air Force because of the proliferation of
high-speed, high-tech weapons and aircraft systems, said Maj. Ron
Van Der Weert, director of the program.
   Today's pilot is inundated with information about his plane,
other planes, radar installations hoping to hit him with
surface-to-air missiles and other threats.
   ``In the heat of battle, there's a tendency to get overloaded
with everything that's taking place,'' said Van Der Weert, a
graduate of the Flight Weapons School, the Air Force version of the
Navy's ``Top Gun'' school.
   Lockheed and McDonnell Aircraft Co., working independently under
Air Force contracts, hope to take advantage of advances in
artificial intelligence to produce a computer that would focus the
pilot's attention on the most critical decisions while handling
lower priority matters itself, like the vacuum cleaner-shaped
sidekick of ``Star Wars'' hero Luke Skywalker.
   For example, in a Central European battle scenario demonstrated
Thursday, the ``pilot's associate'' copes with an overheating radar
system while the pilot is firing missiles at an enemy bomber. All
the while, the computer is giving the pilot a display of the
missile ranges of the most threatening enemy fighters.
   Major new threats prompt the computer to talk aloud _ Lockheed's
model, in fact, sounds like a woman with a Southern accent.
   The ability to pick out the biggest threats is made possible by
artificial intelligence. The computer considers the pilot's planned
flight path and the capabilities and behavior of enemy aircraft and
draws conclusions. It may suggest avoiding some planes or attacking
them, depending on the orders for each mission.
   And instead of merely telling the pilot that fuel has been lost,
the computer would indicate whether the plane has enough to carry
out the original mission and suggest a new flight path if
necessary. That flight path would take into account the delicate
task of weaving among enemy ground radars to prevent them from
gaining a good enough fix to launch a missile.
   Van Der Weert said that would replace educated guesswork by the
pilot.
   But Van Der Weert emphasized the ``pilot's associate'' would
replace neither the pilot nor, on two-seat planes, the navigator.
   The pilot could overrule any action proposed by the computer, in
some cases simply by ignoring it. Martin Broadwell, Lockheed's
program manager, noted that the computer would adjust to the
pilot's rejection, going to work on new proposals consistent with
the pilot's decisions.
   As smart as the new system is, it must overcome the
``notoriously slow'' characteristics of artificial intelligence
computers, said Lockheed program manager Jack Barnette.
   The 30-minute simulated flight replayed on video monitors for
reporters Thursday actually took nearly three hours for the system
to process, but Broadwell said that meets the goal for this point
in the system's development.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1747EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0767 06-02 0837</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0767,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Meets LA Gang Members; Dukakis Goes Home for Wife's
Surgery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with new word on Mrs. Dukakis, more delegates for
Dukakis, inserting new 2nd graf and subbing 5 grafs for grafs 10-12
pvs, Dukakis canceled ... New Mexico.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson met with members of Los Angeles street gangs in an
extraordinary campaign spectacle on Thursday, while fellow Democrat
Michael Dukakis cut short a California campaign trip to be at his
ailing wife's side.
   Dukakis canceled a debate with Jackson and flew home to be with
his wife, Kitty, for surgery that one of her doctors described as
``not emergency but urgent.'' Dr. James R. Lehrich said surgeons
would remove two herniated discs that are pressing dangerously on
her spinal cord and could, if left untreated, cause paralysis.
   Vice President George Bush pronounced himself a ``refurbished
candidate'' after four days of skull sessions with aides and
outside advisers in Kennebunkport, Maine, and said he won't change
tactics just because he trails Dukakis in the polls.
   ``I've never felt more relaxed, never felt more convinced that
we're on the right track,'' Bush said at his vacation home after a
Coast Guard check of his powerboat. He said he would make his
differences plain with his likely Democratic opponent after the
Democratic convention in July.
   With his armed Secret Service guards in attendance, Jackson met
privately with members of the Bloods and an affiliated group, the
Bounty Hunters. Later, Jackson told reporters that the gang members
talked of how they could buy any type of weapon.
   ``They can buy the very latest guns, no ID,'' Jackson said.
``The combination of drugs, guns and money creates a kind of unholy
alliance.''
   Jackson said he hoped the meeting would be the first of many
aimed at ending gang violence, which killed 205 people in Los
Angeles last year. ``It's not a matter of signing papers,'' he said.
   Jackson has finished second in more than 30 primary and caucus
contests this year, and one of the prime topics of speculation in
Democratic circles is whether he is owed special consideration when
it comes time for Dukakis to select a running mate.
   Dukakis himself said no to that question on Wednesday, and party
chairman Paul Kirk seconded the idea in a speech in Milwaukee on
Thursday. Kirk said Jackson is entitled to ``fair consideration''
but no more.
   At the same time, he praised Jackson for running a
`'constructive campaign. ... I think it will help in November.''
   Dukakis canceled his California schedule and left for Boston to
be with his wife, saying, ``This is obviously the most important
thing.''
   At Massachusetts General Hospital, where her surgery is to be
performed, Dr. Lehrich said it was not certain what caused Mrs.
Dukakis' problems. ``We have seen no trauma, unless you consider
that she has been a dancer and moved her neck a lot.''
   Mrs. Dukakis, 53, has been a student and teacher of modern dance
for three decades.
   Lehrich said Mrs. Dukakis has suffered numbness and altered
sensations in her hands and feet.
   Dukakis, who said he might resume campaigning over the weekend
if his wife's operation went smoothly, picked up 21 additional
delegates during the day, bringing his total to 1,768 in the
Associated Press count. He is expected to achieve a nominating
majority of 2,081 by the time the votes are counted Tuesday night
in the final Democratic primaries of the year in California, New
Jersey, Montana and New Mexico. Jackson has fewer than 1,000.
   The Massachusetts governor's campaign announced the beginning of
a television advertising campaign in California, with a commercial
seemingly designed more for the general election campaign than the
primary battle with Jackson. It claims striking achievement in
Dukakis' drive to reduce crime in Massachusetts, and said the
governor ``did it with hard work, integrity, leadership. We could
use some of that...in the White House.''
   Bush tried to explain his comments in a New York Times interview
in which he assailed two new right activists who have been critical
of him.
   ``That's a longstanding feud with two individuals who don't have
any following,'' Bush said. ``The fact that I have been constantly
attacked by two individuals doesn't have anything to do with votes.
If it did, I wouldn't be the likely nominee of the Republican
Party.''
   But some conservatives questioned the vice president's tactics.
   ``He's not running against Dick Viguerie and he's not running
against Howie Phillips. He's running against probably Mike Dukakis
and you really ought to keep your eye on the ball,'' said Lyn
Nofziger, a former political aide to President Reagan.
   In the New York Times interview, Bush criticized Viguerie, a new
right fund-raiser, and Phillips, chairman of the Conservative
Caucus, as polarizing influences on the party.
   When asked if he needed to court the two new-right activists,
Bush said, ``There are some people that are almost self-appointed
spokesmen that will make a claim for that. I don't feel that at
all.''
</TEXT>
