<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EducationResearch     06-02 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Education Research,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Education Department's Research Budget Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Education Department's budget for research
and development fell by 33 percent after inflation between 1980 and
1987, the General Accounting Office said Thursday.
   At the same time, the federal government's overall spending on
research and development rose 24 percent, the agency said in a
report to a House education subcommittee.
   But most of the growth was in the Pentagon budget, where R&D
expenditures shot up 81 percent during the 1980s, the GAO said.
   The Education Department spent $132 million on research and
development in 1980 and $124 million in 1987. The latter figure,
taking inflation into account, was the equivalent of $88 million in
1980 dollars, the GAO said.
   Defense expenditures on R&D rose from $13.9 billion to $36.1
billion. The 1987 figure was the equivalent of $25.2 billion in
1980 dollars.
   The government's overall R&D spending rose from $31.7 billion in
1980 to $56.1 billion in 1987, or in terms of 1980 dollars, to
$39.4 billion, the GAO said.
   Such departments and agencies as Health and Human Services, the
National Science Foundation, the Veterans Administration and the
Agency for International Development registered real increases, but
R&D spending fell at the departments of Agriculture (down 2
percent), Commerce (down 16 percent), Energy (down 29 percent),
Interior (down 35 percent), and Transportation (down 39 percent) as
well as the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (down 47
percent).
   The report said that Education's Center for Education Statistics
has experienced a cut of 34 percent in constant dollars since 1980
and more than 50 percent since 1978.
   The report was prepared at the request of Rep. Major Owens,
D-N.Y., chairman of the House Education and Labor subcommittee on
select education.
</TEXT>
