<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Teamsters     06-02 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Teamsters,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney Blasts Any Federal Attempt To Supervise Teamsters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters attorney John Climaco said Thursday
any scaled-down plan for government supervision of the union would
be just as unacceptable as a straight takeover contemplated earlier.
   Federal law enforcement sources said Rudolph Giuliani, the U.S.
attorney for the Southern District of New York, was considering
modifying plans to seek a takeover following a failed attempt by
federal prosecutors to convict Teamsters officials of corruption.
   Giuliani initially wanted to force Teamsters leaders out of
office and put the union under court trusteeship.
   Instead, he likely will file suit seeking a court-appointed
monitor to oversee some organization activities, according to the
sources, who spoke only on condition they not be named. Such a
lawsuit still could seek removal of some members of the union's
executive board, the sources said.
   The sources were confirming a story in the Los Angeles Times.
   Giuliani plans to forward recommendations soon to acting
Associate Attorney General Francis A. Keating on how to proceed
against the Teamsters.
   ``Whether you call it a monitor or a trusteeship, it's still an
undemocratic attempt by the government to become involved in the
supervision of a free trade union,'' Climaco said. ``It doesn't
appear to me to be any change; it's still business as usual.
   ``The Reagan administration started with the air traffic
controllers and it appears they want to end with the Teamsters,''
Climaco added. President Reagan fired striking air traffic
controllers in 1981.
   On May 4 a U.S. District Court jury in New York aquitted Anthony
``Fat Tony'' Salerno and eight associates of charges they rigged
the elections of Roy L. Williams in 1981, and Jackie Presser in
1983, as Teamsters presidents.
   Although acquitted of the election-rigging charges, Salerno and
six others were found guilty by the same jury of rigging
multimillion-dollar bids in the New York construction industry.
   Presser, who recently underwent surgery for brain cancer, is
awaiting trial on criminal charges in Cleveland that he allegedly
misappropriated $700,000 by keeping non-working ``ghost employees''
on the union payroll.
</TEXT>
