<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Marines-Homosexual     06-02 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marines-Homosexual,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court-Martial Ordered for Woman Marine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARRIS ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court-martial has been ordered for
the first of five women charged in a crackdown on alleged
homosexuality at the Marine Corps' Parris Island Recruit Depot,
officials said Thursday.
   A date for the court-martial of Cpl. Barbara J. Baum will be set
next week. The proceeding was ordered by the base commander, Major
Gen. Joseph P. Hoar.
   An Article 32 hearing, similar to a civilian preliminary
hearing, was held in April after Ms. Baum was charged March 28
under the Uniform Code of Military Justice, said depot spokesman
Maj. Robert McLean.
   Ms. Baum, 23, of Mishawaka, Ind., is charged with conspiracy to
obstruct justice, sodomy, indecent acts, obstruction of justice and
communicating a threat, McLean said.
   ``After a thorough investigation and review by the Article 32
investigating officer, and a recommendation by Baum's commanding
officer, charges were referred to court-martial on Wednesday,''
McLean said.
   Ms. Baum, if convicted on all charges, would face a maximum of
38 years confinement, a dishonorable discharge, reduction to
private and a forfeiture of all pay and allowances, McLean said.
   Ms. Baum, who is single, entered the service in May 1985 and
arrived at Parris Island in December 1985, McLean said. She had
been a military policewoman but is assigned to administrative duty,
the spokesman said.
   ``The other four women also had Article 32 hearings, and we are
presently awaiting results of that. ... This is the first of those
to come to fruition,'' McLean said.
   He also said the Naval Investigative Service review is
continuing.
</TEXT>
