<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1901EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SummitRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0823 06-02 1036</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0823,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Advanced, Gorbachev and Reagan Agree; the President Heads
Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 2-3, Thatcher calls Reagan among the greatest;
edits to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev parted company Thursday expressing confidence they had
advanced the cause of peace during five days of a ``Moscow
spring.'' En route home, Reagan stopped overnight in London for a
sentimental visit with a steady ally.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher honored Reagan with a
dinner for 19 at No. 10 Downing Street. She told him the summit was
a ``tremendous success'' heralding ``a new era in East-West
relations.''
   She told told her guests that Reagan ``will take his place in
history as one of the greatest U.S. presidents.''
   At a Kremlin farewell, Gorbachev said he and Reagan could have
accomplished more, although they did manage to ``divert the train
of U.S.-Soviet relations from a dangerous track to a safer one.''
   Reagan replied that he and Nancy ``for all our days'' will
remember the people of Russia _ ``the faces of hope, hope for a new
era in human history, an era of peace between our nations and our
peoples.''
   ``We think of you as friends,'' he told the Kremlin leader.
   And thus ended the first presidential trip to the Soviet Union
in 14 years.
   Asked later about Gorbachev's criticism of the pace of
negotiations, Reagan replied, ``I'd like to speed them up.'' He
offered no elaboration.
   The Geneva negotiators are scheduled to resume talks, but not
until July 12.
   Just hours after Reagan departed, Gorbachev told several hundred
peace activists that Reagan's human rights campaign would not
change Soviet policy. He said the Russians don't need ``advice on
how we run our affairs.''
   Meantime, the British turned on the pomp.
   When the president came to her 285-year-old palace for tea,
Queen Elizabeth II greeted him with a simple handshake and a ``Nice
to see you again. How are you, Mr. President?''
   A band played the tunes of 100-year-old American songwriter
Irving Berlin when Reagan met Mrs. Thatcher, who has been her
steadiest supporter in the West. He grasped her warmly by the elbow.
   There was also a parade outside No. 10 Downing Street, an annual
event in ceremonies leading up to the queen's birthday. The parade,
dating back to 1727, included 406 musicians and 61 horsemen.
   Reagan invited Mrs. Thatcher to visit Washington after the
November election, and she promptly accepted. White House press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said it was assumed she would also meet
the president-elect.
   A senior British government official, briefing reporters on
condition he not be identified, said Mrs. Thatcher was
``gratified'' that Reagan had mingled among Muscovites. She told
Reagan ``the Russian people would find it difficult now to see the
United States as a threat,'' he said.
   Reagan planned to meet Friday with Japanese Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita and deliver a speech on the state of East-West
relations before returning to Washington.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who made a side trip to
Brussels, gave the NATO allies an upbeat summit assessment and said
``it's certainly possible'' that the superpowers could agree on
deep nuclear cuts before Reagan leaves office in January.
   ``We share his opinion that it was a successful and substantial
summit,'' said Hans-Dietrich Genscher, West German foreign
minister, after meeting with Shultz. ``Through this summit the
American-Soviet relationship got a new stability, a new
perspective.''
   Reagan and Gorbachev had hoped to find the formula for a 30 to
50 percent slash in strategic weapons. That goal evaded them, but
they agreed on two ``confidence building'' treaties and established
a personal warmth.
   Reagan took pleasure in the outcome. He said ``this summit in
this Moscow spring'' had fulfilled its promise.
   A less-than-euphoric tone was struck by Edward L. Rowny,
Reagan's special adviser for arms control matters. Rowny returned
to Washington where, his staff said, he told Japanese Foreign
Minister Sousuke Uno that progress on strategic disarment was made,
but cautioned: ``Let's remember that the Soviet negotiators always
seek to cripple us in areas where they fear we might utilize our
comparative technological advantages.''
   By stopping here to brief Mrs. Thatcher, Reagan was
demonstrating his esteem for the woman whose nine years in office
have made her the Western alliance's senior leader.
   The trip to London was likely to be Reagan's last as president,
although the pair will meet again in Toronto later this month for
the seven-nation economic summit.
   The Reagans looked drawn and tired as they left Moscow in a
downpour. ``He is tired, I guess he looks tired. We're all tired,''
acknowledged White House Chief of Staff Howard Baker.
   Baker, talking to reporters aboard Air Force One en route to
London, said Reagan and Gorbachev were ``going at it pretty heavy
until the end'' and disagreed over whether a communique should
embrace the concept of ``peaceful coexistence'' _ a term coined by
the Soviets that became part of their Cold War jargon.
   Gorbachev, speaking a farewell to Reagan, seemed to agree that
the talks were not always smooth.
   ``Our dialogue has not been easy,'' the Soviet leader said,
``but we mustered enough realism and political will to overcome
obstacles and divert the train of U.S. Soviet relations from a
dangerous track to a safer one.
   ``It is, however, so far, been moving much more slowly than is
required by the real situation, both in our two countries and in
the whole world,'' he said.
   He added: ``Over the past three years, our two nations have come
to know each other better. They have now taken a really good look
in each other's eyes and have a keener sense of the need to learn
to live together on this beautiful planet Earth.''
   Reagan noted that their parting was occuring in a Kremlin hall
named for the Order of St. George and said, ``I would like to think
that our efforts during these past few days have slayed a few
dragons and advanced the struggle against the evils that threaten
mankind ... And I would like to hope that like St. George, with
God's help, peace and freedom can prevail.''
</TEXT>
