<DOCNO> AP880602-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ABC-Stoddard     06-02 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ABC-Stoddard,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC's `Slap Maxwell' Scuttled Over Actor-Producer Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC dropped ``The Slap Maxwell Story'' after
its star, Dabney Coleman, and producer and creator, Jay Tarses,
refused to continue working together, the president of ABC
Entertainment said Thursday.
   ``We never really had an opportunity to renew the show or cancel
it,'' Brandon Stoddard said at an informal meeting with newsmen in
his office.
   ``The way it was presented to us was that if Dabney continued
with the show, Jay wouldn't do it. And if Jay stayed with the show,
Dabney wouldn't do it. It just went its way.''
   Stoddard said he did not know what caused the conflict between
Coleman and Tarses, neither of whom was available for comment.
Tarses was in New York, and Coleman was working on a movie for NBC
called ``Sooner or Later.''
   The show, with Coleman as an acerbic sports writer, did poorly
in the ratings and had particular trouble reaching women viewers.
Stoddard said he felt it was essentially a variation of ``Buffalo
Bill,'' which Coleman and Tarses did for NBC several years ago.
   ``We felt the show had problems with women,'' said Stoddard.
``They had trouble caring about that character. But Jay runs his
show, very clearly. We talked to him and made suggestions, but he
does what he wants to do.''
   Tarses was also the creator and producer of ``Days and Nights of
Molly Dodd,'' which was canceled by NBC.
   Stoddard met with newsmen to discuss the new schedule and ABC's
plans for the future, although he avoided answering questions about
contingency plans for fall programming should the writers strike
continue.
   Although ABC finished last season in second place in the
ratings, ahead of CBS, he said he still considered ABC the third
network because it took second on the basis of the Winter Olympics,
World Series and the Super Bowl.
   ``We think the quality of our programming continues to move
forward,'' he said. ``We have a long way to go in that direction
but we are committed to quality programming. We were lucky this
spring that some of our tryout shows caught on with the public,
like `The Wonder Years,' `The Ten of Us' and `China Beach.'''
   ABC's biggest problem show appears to be ``Moonlighting,'' which
irked many viewers this past season with numerous reruns. Another
problem was that Cybill Shepherd, who co-stars with Bruce Willis,
was pregnant.
   ``We're making some headway against the problem of repeats,''
Stoddard said. ``That is a serious problem but we look for more
original shows. The writers strike is causing creative problems at
this time, but in the future I'd like to see a greater balance in
the stories.
   ``We want `Moonlighting' to return to being a detective show and
to put less emphasis on the relationships. We want it to get back
to being a detective show. We have great writers and a great cast
and I don't think that'll be too difficult.''
   Stoddard said he expected ABC's 30-hour miniseries ``War and
Remembrance,'' a sequel to ``The Winds of War,'' to begin in
February. He said a final decision on how to schedule the series
would be made soon. The series, based on the book by Herman Wouk,
could not be scheduled in the fall because of NBC's coverage of the
Olympics ``which has tied up all the advertising money.''
   ``I've seen 18 hours of this show,'' he said, ``and you ain't
never seen anything like this! Not ever! I think this show is going
to bring people back to television who haven't watched in years.
And it's not just one show. It's 30 hours long.''
   The final scenes for ``War and Remembrance,'' including a tank
battle and miniatures for the Battle of Midway, are now being
filmed. Stoddard said a 26-foot submarine miniature had its front
end blown off during filming when two torpedoes were fired at the
same time and exploded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
