<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TransplantBias     06-02 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transplant Bias,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disparity in Kidney Transplant Rates Found, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White men suffering from kidney failure are more
likely to get a kidney transplant than are women or minorities, a
new study says, but an transplant expert says that the statistical
differences aren't the result of bias on the part of doctors.
   A study in the June issue of the American Medical Association's
Archives of Internal Medicine showed 31 percent of U.S. men who had
undergone long-term dialysis received a transplant, compared with
21 percent of the women.
   Among minority patients, 20 percent received a transplant after
long-term dialysis compared with 30 percent of white patients, said
the report, based on national statistics dating to 1983.
   Dr. Carl M. Kjellstrand said the imbalance his report found does
not prove ``actual bias.''
   ``However, the most favored recipient of a transplant is similar
to the physicians who make the final decision: a young, white
man,'' said Kjellstrand, a Swedish doctor who spent several years
doing research in the United States.
   In certain age groups, the difference in transplant rates
between races or sexes was even greater than the 3-to-2 ratio found
overall. Minority long-term dialysis patients age 21 to 45 were
half as likely to undergo the surgery as white patients of the same
age and sex.
   And women of any race age 46 to 60 were less than half as likely
to receiving a donor kidney as men of the same race and age,
according to the report.
   Dr. Lawrence G. Hunsicker, former president of the American
Society of Transplant Physicians, said that for various reasons,
white men are more likely to seek transplants.
   A recent change in the method used to allocate donor kidneys to
people on waiting lists, ordered by the government, ensures against
bias based on age, sex or race, he said.
   But women and non-whites who have had kidney failures are much
less likely to be on those lists than white men, Hunsicker said in
a telephone interview Thursday.
   Hunsicker said blacks might be less eager than whites for
transplants, because they typically do not do as well after
receiving a donor kidney. But they also do not do as well on
dialysis because of specialized health problems, he said.
   ``To get a kidney transplant, your doctors or you must get you
on the list, and black patients (and doctors) may not take the
initiative,'' said Dr. Arthur J. Matas, a kidney-transplant surgeon
at the University of Minnesota.
   About 5 percent of the women who qualify for kidney transplants
may have trouble being matched to a donor organ, Hunsicker said.
Women who have been pregnant several times can develop antibodies
that would reject the organ, a problem that can be detected in
pre-transplant tests, he said.
   But that 5 percent does not nearly justify the disparity between
the number of women and men on dialysis who receive transplants, he
said.
   Hunsicker also said women may hesitate to get transplants
because ``by and large, in our society, men tend to be more
aggressive and risk-taking.''
   In November 1987, the United States instituted a new policy for
allocating donor kidneys based on objective criteria, Hunsicker
said. The government enforces the system by denying hospitals
Medicare if they fail to report all patients on waiting lists, all
donor kidneys and all recipients.
   Even before the law was passed, Hunsicker said, ``there is no
reason to believe there was any bias anywhere with regards to race
or sex. Age is a different matter.''
   He said some hospitals may have used age as a criterion before
the new policy was instituted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
