<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Violence     06-02 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Violence,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Forces Kill 23 Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces killed 23 leftist guerrillas
in the Andes and eastern jungle, and in Lima rebels assassinated a
lawyer who was recovering from an earlier attempt on her life,
official sources said Thursday.
   Guerrillas of the Shining Path, a Maoist group, ambushed a
military patrol Wednesday and 12 rebels died in a 15-minute battle
with troops, the military said.
   A brief statement said the fighting occurred in the rural
highlands of Ayacucho state near Huanta, 230 miles southeast of
Lima. There was no mention of army casualties.
   La Cronica, the government newspaper, said 11 Shining Path
gunmen were slain Wednesday in a fight with paramilitary police on
the outskirts of Uchiza, a center of the cocaine trade 260 miles
northeast of Lima. Police accuse the Maoist rebels of cooperating
with narcotics traffickers.
   The regions around Uchiza and Huanta are under a state of
emergency because of the Shining Path, which began an insurgency
eight years ago that has cost more than 10,000 lives.
   In Lima, police said two men carrying concealed guns entered a
hospital Wednesday and killed Carmen Rosa Cuzquen, 32, an alleged
former member of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement.
   She was recovering from an attack two months ago by the
guerrillas, who have accused her of being a government informant.
   The Tupac Amaru movement, named for the leader of an Indian
revolt in 1780, began operating in 1984. It favors a Cuban-style
Marxism.
</TEXT>
