<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Mars     06-02 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Mars,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cosmonaut Says Arms Money Should Go for Mars Mission With US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cosmonaut Alexei Leonov suggested Thursday that
the superpowers spend money saved by disarmament to finance joint
missions to Mars and beyond.
   In an interview with the Soviet weekly Nedelya translated by the
Tass news agency, Leonov said that would be an ideal use for money
previously spent on intermediate-range missiles, which United
States and Soviet Union have agreed to scrap.
   ``The funds released can be diverted to the implementation of
large-scale peaceful projects, specifically to manned flights to
Mars and the exploration of the universe,'' said Leonov, who flew
on the joint Soyuz-Apollo mission in the 1970s. He estimated the
cost of a Mars mission at $30 billion.
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed
ratification instruments Wednesday for a treaty eliminating the
missiles. The Soviet Union has said some transportation devices
used for its missiles were being converted into construction cranes
and civilian uses were being found for other missile hardware.
   Washington has been lukewarm to Soviet proposals for a joint
manned mission to Mars because of the cost. Gorbachev first
broached the idea in an interview last month with the Washington
Post and Newsweek magazine.
