<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     06-02 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Attack Guerrilla Meeting, 33 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers attacked a gathering of two
leftist guerrilla groups who were discussing joint operations and
25 guerrillas and eight troopers were killed in the battle, the
Defense Ministry said Thursday.
   In Bogota and other Colombian cities Thursday, people honked car
horns, waved flags and white handkerchiefs and sang the national
anthem in an appeal to kidnappers to free former presidential
candidate Alvaro Gomez Hurtado.
   The shootout between soldiers and guerrillas occurred Sunday
near San Pedro de Uraba, a town in the northern banana-growing
region.
   A report Thursday in the El Mundo newspaper of Medellin, a
northwestern city known as the center of Colombia's cocaine trade,
said 60 guerrillas had been killed in the initial fighting and in
daily running battles since.
   According to the ministry statement, the guerrillas involved
were from the Popular Liberation Army, a Maoist group, and the
Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces, a Moscow-line organization.
   During the nationwide demonstration, which lasted 10 minutes
beginning at 11 a.m., about 1,000 people assembled in a park
outside the Bogota apartment building where Gomez lives. Gomez was
kidnapped last Sunday as he left a church two blocks away.
   ``Colombians today have expressed the utmost unity for the
immediate release of Alvaro Gomez Hurtado,'' acting President Cesar
Gaviria Trujillo said after the demonstration.
   Gaviria is minister of government. He is tanding in for
President Virgilio Barco, who is on an official trip to Europe and
the United States.
   Radio stations have received several telephone calls allegedly
from the abductors, but police say they are not sure any are
legitimate.
   Some callers claimed responsibilities for drug traffickers,
others for leftist guerrillas. One said Gomez had died of bullet
wounds.
   Dozens of Colombians have been kidnapped by leftist guerrillas
and several have been seized by narcotics traffickers who demand
that the government stop extraditing Colombian drug suspects to the
United States.
   Colombia has not extradited anyone on drug charges in 15 months.
   Gomez, publisher of the daily El Siglo, ran for president twice
and has said in many editorials he wants to see Colombia free of
leftist guerrillas.
</TEXT>
