<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Demonstration     06-02 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Demonstration,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Students Demonstrate Over Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 students from Beijing University
marched to the city's main square Thursday night to protest the
death of a fellow student in a brawl.
   Foreign sources said the demonstration developed spontaneously
at about 11 p.m. after students read a poster on campus describing
the death earlier in the day of Cai Jinfang, a 22-year-old
geophysics student.
   Students said Cai was beaten to death by ``hooligans'' while
buying liquor outside the campus.
   It was the largest demonstration since huge pro-democracy
rallies in December 1986 and January 1987 that led to shakeups in
the government and a conservative backlash against ``bourgeois
liberalization.''
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
students arrived at about 4 a.m. at Tiananmen Square, the large
plaza in central Beijing, passed through it and stopped at a police
office to present a list of demands.
   About 700 students completed the 10-mile walk from the campus in
northwest Beijing to the square, linking arms and shouting for
``justice and human rights.'' One banner read ``pay back the blood
debt.''
   Police watched the march but did not interfere.
   In their petition to police, students demanded the arrest of the
assailants, a public trial, better security around the campus and
reports of in the official media.
   Yuan Liben, a Beijing Communist Party official, told the
students at the police office that two of the attackers had been
arrested, but demonstrators shouted him down with complaints about
``bureaucracy,'' the sources reported.
   About 1,000 students from the University of Foreign Economic
Relations in Beijing demonstrated in December about a similar
incident, in which a student was knifed to death. One of the
attackers, a 22-year-old man, was executed.
</TEXT>
