<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0811 06-02 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0811,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Meets With Gang Members</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 5 grafs with comment after City Hall meeting</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate Jesse Jackson met with
gang members in a violence-ravaged ghetto Thursday and said he
wants to end the cycle of ``desperation...hopelessness'' that
plagues their lives.
   ``A combination of drugs and guns and money creates a kind of
unholy alliance that has left the South Central Los Angeles
residents feeling they have no way out,'' Jackson said.
   He said he hoped the meeting would be the first of many such
talking sessions between officials and the young gang members,
beginning with one that afternoon with Mayor Tom Bradley at City
Hall.
   He talked to reporters as gang members and other residents of
the Nickerson Gardens housing project milled around in the
courtyard outside a two-bedroom apartment where Jackson had spent
the night with a projects family.
   Jackson's closed session with more than 100 community
representatives and gang members in the Watts housing project had
been billed as a meeting of both Bloods and Crips, rival gangs in a
city that saw 205 gang-related deaths last year.
   But the few dozen gang members on hand were all from the Bounty
Hunters gang that dominates that area or their affiliate groups.
Many sported the red colors, hats or shirts, that mark the the
Bloods.
   Gang members and police officers said they doubted anyone could
get the gang rivals to sit down together peacefully.
   ``I'd be surprised if they both got in there and didn't start
anything,'' said Officer Victor Rocha, who patrols the South
Central Los Angeles region where Watts is located.
   Jackson emerged from the meeting to announce to reporters that a
meeting had been arranged later in the day at City Hall for
himself, gang members Mayor Tom Bradley and other officials.
   Initially, Jackson's schedule included an afternoon debate with
front-runner Michael Dukakis, but Dukakis canceled it Thursday
morning because his wife was to undergo surgery on Friday. He flew
back to Boston to be with her.
   Jackson said the City Hall meeting would include discussion of
ways to more effectively target resources, social programs and job
efforts in the communities plauged by gang and drug problems.
   He described gangs as groups of people ``who form a reaction of
desperation to hopelessness.''
   It was unclear what else was acheieved at the morning meeting
which was closed to reporters.
   Some local residents _ many of whom have lost friends and
relatives to gang shootings _ expressed hope at the attention
Jackson brought to their concerns, but also skepticism that any
changes could be achieved.
   ``I don't know, I doubt it,'' said James Tapla, 17, who
described himself as aa Bounty Hunter ``marked'' by rival gangs.
   ``You can't go nowhere without somebody wanting to beat you down
or shoot you. I lost three close friends'' to gang violence, he
said. ``I'm tired of it. It's time for this to stop.''
   Another youth, John Thomas, 25, said he once shot someone in a
gang feud and didn't stay around to see if the person died.
   ``It's no big deal. Life in South Central LA is tough,'' he
said. But he said ``deep down inside'' many gang members don't want
to be involved in violence.
   He and others said virtually everyone in their community has a
gun.
   ``It's better to be caught by the police with it, than by some
other fool without it,'' said Kevin Johnson, 25.
   Later Thursday, at City Hall, before Jackson and Bradley met
with several county and city representatives and six gang members,
Bradley praised Jackson's ``thoroughly remarkable campaign.''
   ``I commend you for what you have done in showing what is
possible for this country,'' the mayor told the candidate.
   However, when questioned by reporters, he declined to directly
endorse Jackson.
   ``Jesse Jackson hasn't needed anybody to endorse him. He's done
it on his own,'' Bradley said. He credited Jackson with
``energizing millions of people across the country.''
   When the two emerged from a private meeting, Bradley turned
aside questions as to why it took a Jackson visit to spark the
meeting between officials and gang members. Jackson ``in his most
unique way has been able to make an appeal'' to gang members, the
mayor said.
</TEXT>
