<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0692,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Prostitute Kills Jewish Seminary Student; Shamir Rejects
Soviet Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Shamir reax to Gorbachev
offer to resume relations; Arafat calling for another year of
uprising. PICKS up 4th graf pvs bgng, The killing... Minor editing
throughout to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age Arab prostitute fatally shot an
18-year-old Jewish seminary student Thursday after telling him she
was tired of life and wanted to commit suicide, police and an
Israeli news agency reported.
   Spokesman Rafi Levy said Jerusalem police were investigating
whether the killing was linked to the Palestinian rebellion that
began Dec. 8 in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Also Thursday, a court convicted four left-wing Israelis who met
with PLO officials of breaking a law against contacts with members
of terrorist groups. Israel calls the Palestine Liberation
Organization a terrorist group and refuses to negotiate with it.
   Prime Minister Yitzak Shamir on Thursday reiterated his
opposition to holding an international Middle East peace
conference. Shamir was reacting to Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's statement Wednesday that he would be willing to renew
relations with Israel if such a conference took place.
   Shamir told army radio that Gorbachev's remarks ``will not
change my views. ... I don't think we should pay a heavy price for
renewing relations with the Soviet Union.''
   The Soviets broke diplomatic ties with Israel during the 1967
Middle East war, when Israel captured the West Bank and Gaza Strip
from Jordan and Egypt.
   In the United Arab Emirates, PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat said the
Arab uprising in the occupied territories will continue until
Palestinians have an independent homeland.
   ``We need another year of continuous uprising,'' Arafat told a
gathering of Palestinians at the emirate's presidential guest
palace Wednesday night.
   The killing in Jerusalem was the second recent attack on a
seminarian in the Holy City, which has 340,000 Jewish and 130,000
Palestinian residents. The first occurred May 26, when an Arab
stabbed and wounded a Jewish student in the Arab quarter.
   The latest victim, Eliezer Schlesinger, was a student at the
Sha'arei Chesed seminary in the Rehavia quarter, near where he was
shot.
   Itim, the Israeli news agency, said Schlesinger and another
student took a break from studies at 1:30 a.m. and walked through
Sacher Park.
   Schlesinger's companion, who was not identified, said they
encountered a young woman who told them in fluent Hebrew: ``I'm
tired of life. I want to commit suicide,'' Itim reported.
   He said they talked about two minutes, then the men walked away
and the woman drew a pistol and opened fire, hitting Schlesinger
five times in the back and head.
   She fled but was caught by a security officer who heard the
shots. Levy said the woman confessed and described the shooting,
but her name was not released because she is a minor.
   An Israeli soldier and a teen-age Jewish settler have been slain
in the West Bank during the Palestinian uprising. At least 199
Palestinians also have been killed, according to U.N. figures.
   Arab east Jerusalem was taken from Jordan along with the West
Bank, but Israel has formally annexed it.
   On Thursday, the army retracted figures published earlier this
week that put the Palestinian death toll at 207.
   Col. Raanan Gissin, an military spokesman, said the army was
certain of only 152 deaths, all at the hands of Israeli soldiers.
``All the rest are unclear and we are not going to relate to
them,'' he said.
   The court convicted the four Israelis after rejecting defense
arguments that the PLO was not a terrorist group and the 2-year-old
law against meetings with such organizations did not apply.
   Latif Dory, Yael Lotan, Reuven Kaminer and Eliezer Failer held
talks with a 15-member PLO delegation in Romania in November 1986,
soon after the law was passed. They said at the time they
considered the meeting a test of the law.
   Dory called the statute ``a terrorist law against a peace
dialogue'' and declared: ``We shall continue to fight it until it
is revoked.''
   At Rafah in the Gaza Strip, soldiers prevented students from
entering a junior high school. Itim said the army closed the school
for two weeks, accusing students of throwing rocks at Israelis who
drove by.
   Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, military commander in the West Bank,
said soldiers no longer will force Arab merchants to open stores
during hours set by the army. Underground leaders of the rebellion
have ordered shopkeepers to close in the afternoon.
</TEXT>
