<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SupernovaStar 1stLd-Writethru a0841 06-02 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Supernova Star, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0841,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Waiting for Neutron Star To Show Itself</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st, 3rd grafs pvs to read Supernova 1987A sted
Supernova '87; SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT to University of
California, Santa Cruz sted Santa Clara; Picks up 4th graf pvs
bgng, ``It was ....''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supernova 1987A, the closest star to explode
in 400 years, has provided a feast of many courses for an
international army of scientists. Now the researchers are waiting
for dessert: a look at a neutron star in its infancy.
   ``We've never before observed a supernova evolve through to the
birth of a neutron star,'' Stan Woosley, a University of
California, Santa Cruz, astrophysicist said at a National
Aeronautics and Space Administration news conference Thursday.
``Now the egg is about to hatch.''
   Supernova 1987A was first detected on Feb. 24, 1987. The burst
of light and radiation was located in the Large Magellanic Cloud, a
galaxy near the Milky Way, and some 160,000 light years away.
   It was the first exploding star in four centuries that was close
enough to be seen with the unaided eye _ but only in the Southern
Hemisphere _ and scientists all over the world immediately turned
powerful instruments toward the object.
   Since then, the progress of the explosion has been charted in
minute detail as light and other radiation streamed away and were
detected by instruments onboard airplanes and satellites, or
carried aloft by balloons and sounding rockets, or housed in
ground-based observatories.
   ``It has been the most completely studied phenomenon outside the
solar system in history,'' Woosley said. ``It has been a grand
event, as it should be since something like doesn't happen but
every 30 generations.''
   The scientists actually are studying an event that occurred
160,000 years ago. But the star is so far away, some 960,000
trillion miles, that it has taken all of those centuries for the
light to reach Earth.
   Visible light from the explosion has declined slowly, but data
is still being collected in other parts of the radiation spectrum.
   At Thursday's NASA news conference, scientists said the studies
have confirmed some basic theories about the life cycle of stars
and about the formation of fundamental elements in the universe,
but Supernova '87 also has created mysteries that are yet to be
explained.
   Among the findings reported Thursday:
   _Gamma ray studies show that as the star exploded, a small
amount of matter in its helium core evolved into radioactive
nickel, which decayed to cobalt and finally to the stable isotope
iron-56. This confirmed theories of the evolution of matter from
stars.
   ``We have seen for the first time the creation of new matter in
the universe,'' said David Helfand, a Columbia University scientist.
   _Data from emissions of the explosion, which give indications of
the star's composition, show the star had a puzzling lifetime
before its explosion. Woosley said it apparently spent about 9
billion years as a blue sequence star, changed its composition to a
red super giant star for a million years through the loss of
material equal to about four suns, and then evolved back to a blue
star. He said there is no general explanation for this.
   _Early in its life, the star that exploded was about 20 times
more massive than the sun. It's explosion came about through a
gravitational collapse of shells of surrounding the core of helium.
   _Light streaming from the star has been the result of
radioactive decay. The light has declined and will continue to do
so until energy from an evolving neutron star causes the level of
light to become steady.
   It is this event, Woosley said, that astronomers are awaiting.
   Detection of the neutron star could come in a year, as some
believe, or it could take many years.
   A neutron star is the final stage in the life of a star. It is
composed of neutrons and compressed to the density of about a
thousand million million times that of water. Its density is only
10 percent less than that of a black hole, which is so dense that
not even light can escape its gravitational field.
   ``If a sugar cube was dropped on a neutron star, it would hit
with a megaton of force,'' Woosley said. ``That's the energy in
such a force of gravity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
