<HEAD>Former Temptations Singer Gets Probation For Cocaine Use
Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Temptations lead singer David Ruffin was
sentenced Thursday to two years probation and 50 days of community
service after being convicted of using cocaine.
   Ruffin also was ordered to remain drug free during his probation
in the sentencing at Detroit Recorders Court, authorities said.
   Ruffin was convicted May 19 of using cocaine after Judge John
O'Brien ruled there was not enough evidence to convict him of a
cocaine possession charge.
   Ruffin, who sang with the Temptations from 1963 to 1968, was
found in the basement of a Detroit house authorities raided for
drugs. A bag containing cocaine residue was found with his personal
papers in the raid July 28, 1987.
   Ruffin said he went to the home to find a friend, not to buy
drugs. A co-defendant in the trial, Marvin Hicks, testified Ruffin
was among seven people who pitched in to buy 42 grams of crack
cocaine.
   Ruffin, who has been touring with former Temptations singer
Eddie Kendricks, is in a hospital drug treatment program in Saline
and will remain there until he is discharged, according to a court
official.
