<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HarvardTrial     06-02 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harvard Trial,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sees `No Smoking Gun' In Sex Discrimination Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is no ``smoking gun'' in the Harvard
Business School faculty's vote for a former professor who claims
she was denied tenure at the school because of her sex, a federal
judge said Thursday.
   Whether Barbara Bund Jackson should become the fifth tenured
woman in the school's 80-year history hinges on whether the
evidence showed discrimination when she was denied tenure in 1981
and 1983, U.S. District Judge Douglas P. Woodlock said Thursday.
   Jackson, 44, now a private marketing consultant, began teaching
at Harvard in 1973. She was promoted to associate professor in 1977
and applied for tenure in 1981. She sued the university in 1984.
   The judge, who is expected to rule in the case next week, heard
closing arguments in the eight-day trial came after attorney Evan
T. Lawson refused the judge's recommendation to suspend the trial
to question 56 professors involved a key 1981 faculty vote.
   Lawson said he did not have the resources to embark on ``an
extremely complicated and lengthy procedure.''
   ``I think you will concede that there is no smoking gun here,''
Woodlock said. ``What I'm interested in finding out is not whether
or not her tenure review case was unfair but whether it was unfair
because she is a woman.''
   In closing arguments, Lawson maintained he had compiled ``a
multiplicity of little things that put together add up to an evil.''
   Harvard attorney Allan A. Ryan Jr. maintained ``not one shred of
evidence'' linked Jackson's tenure denial to sex bias.
   During testimony, Harvard admitted that documents existed
showing the school's faculty voted 47-7 to support Jackson's tenure
bid but two days later backed her by 29-27. But Ryan said there was
no evidence that McArthur used Jackson's sex in lobbying professors
to switch their votes in 1981.
   Tenure decisions at Harvard are submitted to the faculty to
gauge support for the professor; the actual decision rests with the
university president.
   Lawson's argument cited a number of factors which he contends
prove that Jackson was a victim of sex discrimination, including:
   _Business school dean John H. McArthur, a co-defendant with the
university, once said the only way to get more women on the
school's faculty would be to impose quotas.
   _At least four men who had less favorable reviews and faculty
support than Jackson received tenure from 1977 to 1984.
   _A marketing expert from outside Harvard who backed Jackson was
specifically asked whether his recommendation had anything to do
with affirmative action.
   Lawson claimed the school's tenure standards were applied
unfairly to Jackson, who after being denied tenure in 1981 was
given a three-year extension and asked to demonstrate excellence in
marketing.
   Ryan contended that Jackson's case was ``a long train of
perceived slights ... but it is wholly bereft of any evidence that
a man would have been treated any differently than her.''
</TEXT>
