<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Hildreth     06-02 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Hildreth,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Maine Governor, U.S. Ambassador to Pakistan Dies at Age 85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horace A. Hildreth, whose career as
lawyer, broadcast executive, college president and two-term
governor of Maine was capped with four years' service as a U.S.
ambassador, died Thursday. He was 85.
   Hildreth suffered a heart attack while at Maine Medical Center
undergoing an examination for a blood pressure problem, said his
son, Horace Jr.
   In 1953, President Dwight D. Eisenhower named Hildreth
ambassador to Pakistan, the Moslem country carved out of India in
1947. At that time, Hildreth had been president of Bucknell
University for four years.
   Hildreth was governor from 1945-49. In 1948, he ran for the U.S.
Senate seat, finishing second to Sen. Margaret Chase Smith in a
four-way Republican primary contest. Ten years later he lost a bid
for a third term as governor.
   Hildreth, a Gardiner native, was a graduate of Bowdoin College
and Harvard Law School. He practiced law in Portland and began his
Hildreth Network of Maine radio and TV stations before entering
politics.
   In 1940 he was elected to the Maine House and later that same
year he won promotion to the state Senate, where he became
president in 1943.
   The Hildreth Network included the state's first commercial radio
station, Bangor's WABI and television stations WABI in Bangor and
WAGM Presque Isle.
   In 1977 Hildreth merged his network with W. Russel Brace's
newspaper and publishing interests to form Diversified
Communications Inc. He served as its chairman until 1980 and as a
director thereafter.
   In addition to his son, Hildreth is survived by his wife,
Katherine, and three daughters.
</TEXT>
