<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama Cocaine,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Soldier Linked to Drug Ring That Used U.S. Bases in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former U.S. soldier who was caught with 18
pounds of cocaine during a traffic stop was part of a
drug-smuggling ring that used bogus military IDs to operate through
U.S. bases in Panama, federal drug authorities said Thursday.
   Members of the ring got false Army identification papers, forged
requests to board military aircraft and pretended to be active duty
servicemen returning home on leave, said Cornelius Dougherty, a
spokesman for the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration in
Washington.
   The members carried cocaine in luggage on flights from Howard
Air Base in Panama and shipped cocaine in Army mail from Fort
Kobbe, also in Panama, said Robert Feldkamp, another DEA spokesman.
   DEA officials said Thursday that Jackie Lee Bigelow, 27, of
Moultrie, was a central figure in the ring.
   Bigelow was taken into custody last week after being stopped by
a state trooper in nearby Colquitt County. He admitted he was
carrying cocaine and agreed to cooperate with police, said Sheriff
Gene Beard.
   Information supplied by Bigelow led to the arrests of five women
and one man in the past week. More arrests were expected, said FBI
agent David Parker.
   Each woman is charged with conspiracy to possess cocaine with
intent to distribute. If convicted, they could each face a maximum
sentence of life in prison and a $4 million fine. A bond hearing is
scheduled for Friday in Albany.
   At an initial hearing Wednesday, U.S. Magistrate Nathan Davis
appointed lawyers to represent Maxine Williams, 24; Brenda McGee,
25; and Betty Howard, 31, all of Colquitt County, and Regina
Carmela Smith and Julia Thom, both of New York City. Ms. Smith's
husband, Oscar, has been arrested in New York on the same charge
and is being held there, said U.S. Attorney Edgar W. Ennis Jr. of
Macon.
   An FBI affidavit released Wednesday said Bigelow told
investigators he traveled to Panama twice this year to meet with
two members of the drug operation. He said he arranged for cocaine
packages to be mailed to the three Georgia women.
   Investigators seized two packages of cocaine last week that were
mailed to Moultrie from a military post office in Panama. One was
an 18-pound package taken from Bigelow's car on May 24 after he was
stopped for having a suspended license and the other was a 29-pound
package seized Friday at the Moultrie post office.
   Army spokeswoman Paige Eversole said military investigators were
trying to determine if any active-duty personnel were involved.
</TEXT>
