<1ST_LINE>r i AM-TropicalWeather     06-02 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tropical Weather,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Kills 14, Six Missing in Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains from the first tropical
depression of the year killed at least 14 people and drove many
thousands from their homes in central Cuba, the Cuban government
news agency Prensa Latina reported Thursday.
   The 3-day-old storm seriously damaged homes, bridges, roads and
railroad tracks and cut off electric power and communications to
several areas, said the agency, monitored in Mexico City.
   It said a tornado touched down early Thursday at an airport in
Camaguey city, destroying five Soviet-built MiG-21 fighter planes
and several buildings.
   Authorities ordered the evacuation of 65,000 people in five
central provinces whose homes were threatened by flooding. Prensa
Latina said rescue crews using helicopters and amphibious vehicles
evacuated at least 10,000 from their homes Wednesday and carried
them to higher ground.
   The U.S. National Hurricane Center in Miami said Thursday the
storm was downgraded to a foul-weather system and was drifting
northeast from Cuba at between 5 and 10 mph.
   The official Agency of National Information said six people
drowned and three were electrocuted, Prensa Latina reported, with
seven of the dead in Cienfuegos province and one each in Villa
Clara and Sancti Spiritus.
   It did not give details on the five other deaths.
   The depression was the first of the 1988 Atlantic hurricane
season, which began Wednesday and ends Nov. 30. A typical season
sees 10 named tropical storms with winds exceeding 39 mph. Six
become hurricanes with winds over 74 mph.
   Tropical depressions can become tropical storms if their
circulating winds reach 39 mph. Storms become hurricanes if those
winds hit 74 mph.
   In 1987 there were three hurricanes and four tropical storms in
the Atlantic.
</TEXT>
