<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SpellingBee 3rdLd-Writethru a0836 06-02 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spelling Bee, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0836,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Youngster Wins Spelling Bee</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``I'm really ...'' to fix typo in
name.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rageshree Ramachandran, a 13-year-old
eighth-grader from Fair Oaks, Calif., won the 61st National
Spelling Bee on Thursday, scoring her victory with the word
elegiacal, a form of couplets in a poem.
   Rageshree, the Indian-born daughter of statistics professors at
the University of California at Sacramento, defeated Victor C.
Wang, 14, of Camarillo, Calif., after a prolonged head-to head
match. She had placed 36th in the 1986 bee.
   Victor stumbled on the word stertorous, an adjective meaning
characterized by a harsh snoring or gasping sound. Rageshree
spelled the word correctly, then sealed her victory by correctly
spelling elegiacal.
   The winner won $1,500 and other prizes from the sponsoring
Scripps Howard newspapers, the runner-up $1,000.
   ``I'm really happy,'' said Rageshree, known to her friends as
Raga. ``I have been studying hard since January, at least a couple
of hours a day.''
   Asked if she had any coaches, she laughed and replied, ``My mom
and my dad. Also, my little sister. She's just 6, but she likes to
ask words, too.''
   Rageshree, who was sponsored by the Sacramento Bee, said she was
not surprised that Victor had misspelled six in the final round and
she five. ``There are always words that anyone can miss,'' she said.
   For Victor, it also was his second appearance at the national
bee. He placed 34th in the 1985 contest. He was sponsored by the
Ventura County Star-Free Press.
   Earlier, Iris Liu, 8, of Muncie, Ind., the youngest member of
the record 200-youngster field, made it to the fifth round in the
annual competition.
   But ``waywiser'' _ an instrument that measures distance _ proved
to be the instrument of her downfall. She spelled it
``weighweiser.''
   The pace of attrition escalated dramatically in the fifth round,
with 78 dropouts, more than five times as many as the round before.
The day had started with 144 survivors from Wednesday's competition.
   As the stakes got higher, the spellers increasingly requested
definitions, illustrative sentences, word origins and repetitions,
hoping for a magic moment of revelation.
   Antonia Seesink, 13, of Bangor, Pa., wrote frenetically on her
arm with a finger, a trick that saved her Wednesday with
``pontificalibus.'' But it didn't work Thursday with
``multipotent.''
   Some contestants who fluffed their words left the stage
tearfully. Others saved their reactions for the privacy of the
restroom or a special comfort room equipped with soft drinks and
soft couches.
   There were a few light moments. As the contest began its second
day Thursday, Robin Covey, 12, of Detroit, had barely repeated his
word _ ``eschatological'' _ when the disqualifying bell sounded.
   ''What's the matter, did I pronounce it wrong?'' Robin asked
with a grin. He went on to spell it correctly.
   Vasilios Stavrou, 13, of Dracut, Mass., fell victim to
``isepiptesis,'' a line on a map that shows the path of a migratory
bird. He spelled it ``isepatesis.''
   And ``klinotaxis'' _ bending in the direction of a stimulus _
proved fatal to Ana Gordan, 12, of Manchester, N.H. Her version:
``clinataccis.''
   Robert Pryor, 11, of Washington, D.C., who struggled heroically
through Day One on Wednesday with a stomach virus, returned
Thursday only to be stymied by ``fidgetiness.'' He spelled it as
``fidgitinous.''
   Contest officials estimate that 8 million to 9 million children
competed in local tournament that produced the 200 hopefuls who
traveled to Washington for the finals.
   The event offered $1,500 and other prizes to the winner.
   Scripps Howard also gave $1,000 to the second-place finisher,
$750 for third place, $500 for fourth, $400 for fifth, $300 for
sixth, $200 each for seventh through 10th, $100 each for 11th
through 20th, and $50 to each of the other 180 entrants.
</TEXT>
