<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Djilas     06-02 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Djilas,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Speaks To Students; Protests Over Arrested Journalist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident Milovan Djilas told an
enthusiastic student audience on Thursday in the increasingly
liberal republic of Slovenia, ``Yugoslavia can prosper only as a
democratic confederation,'' sources said.
   They said Djilas praised the West European pluralistic political
system.
   The sources said the noted author and former vice president of
Yugoslavia, once heir-apparent to the late President Josip Broz
Tito, talked to students in the Slovenian city of Maribor, in
northern Yugoslavia near the Austrian border.
   About 300 students loudly applauded him when he entered a hall
in their dormitory and during and after his address, according to
the sources, who spoke on condition their names not be used.
   Although the anti-communist themes Djilas expressed were typical
of him, the fact that he was allowed to voice them was considered
an event in itself.
   Djilas, a former comrade-in-arms of Tito, the founder of
communist Yugoslavia, spent about three years in royalist jails in
Yugoslavia before World War II and nine years in communist jails
after becoming one of the strongest critics of communism.
   He was given back his passport in January 1987, for the first
time since 1969, and began traveling widely, giving lectures.
   Slovenia is Yugoslavia's most developed region and is strongly
influenced by Italy and Austria, on its western and northern
borders.
   In another development Thursday, the arrest of Janez Jansa, an
outspoken journalist and Slovenian youth leader, led to sharp
public criticism in Slovenia.
   Jansa, one of four candidates for president of Slovenia's
official Socialist Youth organization, was arrested on Tuesday in
Ljubljana, a city 62 miles southeast of Maribor, on what police
said was ``suspicion of revealing a military secret.''
   He had published articles in Slovenian youth periodicals
critical of Yugoslav army policies and leaders. He also reported on
alleged plans for a military coup in Solvenia.
   ``We are embittered by Jansa's arrest and we are worried about
the freedom of public speech,'' said a statement released Thursday,
signed by 88 leading Slovenian intellectuals. ``We feel this is an
act of intimidation,''
   Police said earlier that authorities found ``a secret military
document'' in a Ljubljana software company where Jansa works.
   The document allegedly represents the minutes of a top-level
closed Communist Party meeting at which a plan for a possible
military intervention in Slovenia was discussed, Jansa's friends
said.
   They said the same document was published by the Mladina youth
magazine in May, but authorities immediately banned the periodical,
saying it contained state secrets.
   Last month, Slovenian youth publications said the military was
planning a coup in Slovenia and intended to arrest intellectuals,
journalists and others to quell dissent in the republic.
   A communique issued last week by the Presidency of Yugoslavia
denied plans for a military takeover and called the articles a
``slanderous campaign.''
   Bojan Korsika, a journalist friend of Jansa, told The Associated
Press, that Jansa's whereabouts were unknown since and that the
military said he would be allowed only an official army attorney.
   Korsika said several youth organizations around Slovenia have
held meetings protesting Jansa's arrest and demanding his release.
</TEXT>
