<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Kapoor     06-02 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Kapoor,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Film Star Raj Kapoor Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Film star Raj Kapoor, known as ``the
Charlie Chaplin of India'' for his comedy roles, died Thursday
after a month in the hospital following an asthma attack, state
television reported. He was 64.
   Kapoor was stricken on May 2 during a film awards ceremony at
which he was given India's highest movie honor, the Dada Saheb
Phalke Award. He was already in such weakened physical condition
that Indian President Ramaswami Venkataraman had come down from the
stage to give him the trophy.
   The actor later was carried from the auditorium and hospitalized.
   Kapoor acted in 60 films and produced or directed 18 others over
a career that spanned four decades. Almost all his movies were hits
in India, and he was perhaps the most popular Indian film actor
abroad with followers in the Soviet Union, the Middle East and
China.
   Among his best-known films was ``Awara'' (The Vagabond), in
which he borrowed from Chaplin and played the part with trousers
riding high above his ankles and a perpetual forlorn look on his
face.
   A semi-biographical film, ``Mera Naam Joker'' (My Name is
Joker), filled 25 reels and allowed the audience two intermissions
in its four-hour-plus showing.
   Kapoor's father, the late Prithvi Raj Kapoor, was a stage and
screen actor and three of Kapoor's sons _ Randhir, Rishi and Rajeev
_ are popular actors. Kapoor's two younger brothers, Shammi and
Shashi, also are screen stars.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi issued a statement mourning the
death, calling Kapoor, ``a person who became a legend in his
lifetime.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
