<HEAD>Mormon Leadership Appoints New President of Twelve Apostles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former California corporate lawyer on
Thursday was appointed president of the Mormon Church's Council of
the Twelve, a position held by the apostle next in line to be
church president.
   Howard W. Hunter, 80, was ``set apart'' by church President Ezra
Taft Benson during a meeting of high officials of The Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in the Salt Lake Temple,
according to a church statement.
   By tradition, the president and most senior member of the Twelve
becomes church president at the death of the faith's leader.
   Hunter succeeds Marion G. Romney, who died May 20 after a long
illness. Hunter had been acting president of the Twelve since
October 1985 and an apostle since 1959.
   A native of Boise, Idaho, Hunter practiced corporate law in
California until his appointment as an apostle in the 6.5
million-member church.
