<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0779 06-02 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0779,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, ``Refurbished'' By Week in Maine, Says He Won't Change
Tactics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Moves up final 6 grafs pvs on summit to after 4th graf;
CORRECTS quote in final and penultimate grafs pvs, now grafs 6 and
7, to read `we've' sted `they've</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush declared himself a
``refurbished candidate'' on Thursday after a week of rest and
strategy talks but said he won't change his tactics just because
he's trailing in the polls.
   The vice president spoke with reporters at his seaside vacation
home after a Coast Guard safety check of his powerboat.
   ``I've never felt more relaxed, never felt more convinced that
we're on the right track,'' he said. ``And I'm not going to be
stampeded by polls that don't mean anything.''
   Recent public opinion polls have shown Bush trailing Democrat
Michael Dukakis by 10 or more points.
   On another subject, Bush moved slightly away from President
Reagan, stressing more forcefully than Reagan did the U.S.-Soviet
differences on human rights.
   ``I think we have very different views on human rights than the
Soviet Union,'' he said. ``I would suggest that Soviet retaliation
against us, saying we've got human rights problems, is mixing
apples and oranges.''
   ``We've got some problems, but they're not problems of human
rights. I think the Soviet Union should adhere to these high
standards the president is talking about,'' said the vice president.
   But Bush sidestepped questions about Reagan's suggestion that
Soviet bureaucracy, not Kremlin policy, was to blame for delays in
issuing exit visas, or refusing them outright.
   He said he was pleased with the overall outcome of the summit,
saying: ``I don't think anyone expected a significant
breakthrough'' on a new treaty.
   ``When I get back (to Washington) I'll get a much better inside
assessemnt of what went on. But I think, generally speaking, it's
been very positive,'' he said.
   On another subject, Bush said he has ``great respect for the
conservative movement'' and believes he has its support despite a
public disagreement with two of its more outspoken members.
   One day earlier, in a New York Times interview, he had taken aim
at Richard Viguerie, a new right fund-raiser, and Howard Phillips,
chairman of the Conservative Caucus. He said in the interview,
``There's only one or two that polarize, and Viguerie and Howie
Phillips are two of them.''
   ``That's a longstanding feud with two individuals who don't have
any following,'' Bush said Thursday. ``The fact that I have been
constantly attacked by two individuals doesn't have anything to do
with votes. If it did, I wouldn't be the likely nominee of the
Republican Party.''
   Bush clinched the GOP nomination in April.
   The vice president returns to Washington on Friday after an
eight-day sojourn at his vacation retreat, during which he met with
domestic policy and economic advisers and held strategy sessions
with top aides.
   Asked by a reporter if a ``new Bush'' would emerge, he said:
``You're going to see a refurbished candidate because I come here
and I feel good. I get a little bit rested. But you're not going to
see any drastic change in campaign plans.''
   Some Republican consultants have urged Bush to put more distance
between himself and the Reagan administration and to step up his
attacks on Dukakis. But while Bush has moved a little bit in that
direction in recent days, he told reporters: ``We've got a game
plan. We're staying with it. It will be effective.''
   He said he planned to hold most of his fire against Dukakis
until after the Democrats formally nominate their candidate.
   Then, he said, ``you will see me doing much more to put
differences in focus. ... And that will be easy to do because we
fundamentally differ on so many issues.''
   Bush invited reporters to his house to watch his 28-foot
powerboat, ``Fidelity,'' get a safety check from the Coast Guard
auxiliary. It passed.
   He was presented an inspection sticker by John Murray, chief of
staff for the regional Coast Guard Auxiliary, who noted that it was
Safe Boating Week.
   Next, Bush took a group of reporters for a boat ride as the
Coast Guard officials looked on.
   ``Should I make a dramatic exit?'' he asked. He gunned the two
185-horsepower engines on his modified Cigarette racing boat and
turned the boat in a fast circle in the cove next to his dock,
sending up a wall of spray, before rocketing out into the Atlantic
Ocean.
   Was that a safe-boating manuever, Murray, the Coast Guard
inspector, was asked by reporters?
   ``It's his cove,'' Murray responded.
   Bush said that he ``learned a lot'' from economists who had
briefed him on Tuesday and Wednesday.
   He want on to attack Democrats for ``pessimism and negativism''
about the economy.
</TEXT>
