<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Disarmament     06-02 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Disarmament,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>France To Keep Up Nuclear Tests; China Warns of Nuclear Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France said Thursday it will continue
nuclear tests in the South Pacific and rebuffed a Third World
campaign for nuclear disarmament, saying that fighting poverty and
hunger are just as important.
   France told the U.N. special session on disarmament not to adopt
Utopian declarations on total nuclear disarmament. It called for
realistic measures to reduce conventional arms, especially in
Europe, and a ban on chemical weapons.
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas told the 159-member General
Assembly it was paradoxical ``to lavish so much effort on
disarmament talks while displaying only resignation and sometimes
even indifference when tragic problems of poverty, hunger and debt
are broached.''
   China's minister of foreign affairs, Qian Quichen, congratulated
the United States and the Soviet Union for recognizing their
special responsibility to reduce their enormous nuclear arsenals,
and on their treaty to scrap medium- and shorter-range nuclear
missiles.
   He called on the superpowers to cut their arsenals further,
while cautioning against false complacency:
   Qian said that ``even if they do cut by half the number of their
nuclear weapons, their nuclear arsenals will still account for
approximately 90 percent of the world's total ... sufficient to
destroy all life on earth many times over.''
   He said ``people should be on guard against an important change
which is taking place in the superpower arms race.'' Even with a
reduction in the number of nuclear weapons, he asked, ``will
qualitative development of more and newer types of armaments make
the world safer and peace more secure?''
   President George Vassiliou of Cyprus called again for
demilitarization of his divided Mediterranean island, saying the
money saved could promote economic development of Turkish Cypriots.
   Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot
areas since Turkey invaded the island in 1974, saying it was to
protect the Turkish Cypriot minority after a brief but unsuccessful
coup there fostered by the Greek military government then in power.
   Vassiliou said ``no lasting solution is attainable unless
Turkish occupation forces and settlers are withdrawn from the
island.''
   The special session meets through June 25. The United States and
its Western allies hope for a concrete, modest U.N. document on
disarmament that will not impose on national defense policies and
bilateral disarmament efforts.
   Most of the 12 speakers at the opening session Wednesday issued
sweeping calls for total disarmament, a comprehensive nuclear test
ban and a supervisory, verification and monitoring role for the
United Nations. The United States is mainly opposed to the measures.
   Dumas said Thursday that France will not stop nuclear testing in
the Mururoa Atoll in the South Pacific but announced that the
government for the first time would make an annual statement on the
number of tests in the preceding 12 months.
   France refuses to ratify the Rarotonga Treaty instituting a
nuclear-free zone in the region and Dumas reaffirmed that decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MotherTeresa'sInmate     06-02 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mother Teresa's Inmate,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate Arranges Prison Visit for Mother Teresa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALPOLE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Franciscan monk serving an 18- to
20-year prison term here for assault and battery has persuaded
Mother Teresa to visit three of the state's prisons after
corresponding with her for two years.
   Donald Ouimet, 47, will be greeting Mother Teresa when the
77-year-old nun visits three state prisons, including Walpole, on
Saturday. Ouimet said he invited Mother Teresa last year and he
hopes she will spread ``the healing warmth of love'' among the
inmates.
   ``Walpole prison has been recognized as a holding pen for the
lowest of the low,'' said Ouimet at a prison news conference
Thursday afternoon. ``But every now and then a ray of hope shines.
I hope this Saturday a ray of hope will shine when a little nun
from India comes.''
   Walpole inmates will present Mother Teresa with a pen drawing of
her against a background of a comment she once made: ``We are like
a pencil in God's hands, even though the instrument is imperfect,
the writing is beautiful.''
   The unlikely acquaintance of Ouimet and the Nobel Peace Prize
winner began in 1986 when Ouimet, encouraged by a prison chaplain
and a nun in New York City, decided to write to her.
   Since then, he has written to her and has received four letters
from her.
   Ouimet, who grew up in the working-class western Massachusetts
town of Holyoke. After graduating from Sacred Heart High School in
Holyoke, he became a Capuchine Franciscan monk and joined the St.
Pius X Friary in Middletown, Conn., as a lay brother.
   After four years in the monastery, Ouimet left. He said he's
still not sure why he decided to leave.
   ``It was springtime and the birds were singing and I wanted to
live the good life,'' said Ouimet, addressing reporters with the
aplomb of a celebrity accustomed to the spotlight. ``Little did I
know the good life would lead to the good life behind bars.''
   In 1965, a few years after leaving the monastery, Ouimet was
convicted of aggravated assault. He served nine years at Walpole
before his release in 1974, then returned to western Massachusetts
and held odd jobs, mostly as a cook.
   Around 1985, he said, he was arrested for four separate
incidents of aggravated assault. Ouimet said he assaulted both a
man and a woman in the course of the incidents, but he did not
provide any details.
   ``That's not the issue,'' he said. ``What's here and now is the
issue. I have nothing, no life in the streets. My life is in here.''
   Walpole, properly known as the Massachusetts Correctional
Institution-Cedar Junction, is the state's only maximum-security
prison and is known as a tough institution. But Ouimet says he
likes prison life and doesn't want to leave.
   Though he is eligible for parole in 10 years, Ouimet said he
would prefer to stay inside, describing himself as an ``old-time
con, part of the furniture here.'' He said he even likes the food.
   ``I prefer it here, there's security, I don't have to pay rent,
don't have to pay for lights,'' he said. ``I'm comfortable here.''
   Ouimet said he plans to continue his correspondence with Mother
Teresa after her visit, adding that it has ``broadened'' his
outlook. He hopes his fellow inmates will have the same experience
when they meet her Saturday.
   ``We are poor in spirit, poor in emotion and poor in material
possessions but in the eyes of our Father we have a great
dignity,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
