<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     06-02 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Make Campus Arrests Following Clashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police in armored vehicles swept onto a
Lima university campus Wednesday and arrested about 100 people
protesting the death of a campus demonstrator, officials said.
   Earlier, police fired buckshot and tear gas to disperse
students, some wearing masks and shouting leftist guerrilla
slogans, who lobbed dynamite sticks at police and burned bonfires
in nearby streets, according to reporters on the scene.
   Demonstration leaders at San Marcos, about four miles west of
downtown, told reporters that six students were wounded by buckshot.
   Police said the Mao-inspired Shining Path guerrilla group
fomented the San Marcos violence, but refused to confirm the
reports of injury.
   Violent demonstrations also erupted at two universities
downtown. Tear gas fired by police wafted through the city during
evening rush hour, forcing thousands of pedestrians to cover their
faces or seek shelter.
   The campus strife, which began Monday to protest the alleged
killing of highland peasants by soldiers and against recent fee
increases, intensified Wednesday, a day after a student was slain.
   Protest supporters charge the student was killed by a tear gas
cannister fired by police. Officials have not confirmed the cause
of the death.
   Demonstrations, held throughout the day, culminated late
Wednesday afternoon as dozens of heavily-armed police, in five
armored vehicles and in vans, rolled into San Marcos, police said.
   Officials said 100 university protesters were arrested, among
them students in the campus cafeteria.
   Television news reports showed footage of police smashing a
life-sized campus statue of Ernesto ``Che'' Guevara, the deceased
hero of Cuba's Marxist revolution.
   It was the second time in 16 months that police entered the San
Marcos campus, which the government charges serves as a planning
site for small pockets of leftist guerrillas.
   University campuses in Peru, as elsewhere in Latin America, are
considered autonomous and traditionally off limits to government
forces.
   A San Marcos police raid in February 1987, during which about
800 students were briefly arrested, sparked intense criticism by
left-wing politicians against the government.
</TEXT>
