<HEAD>Federal Judge Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Judge Clement F. Haynesworth Jr.
was in satisfactory condition Wednesday after being hospitalized
for chest pains, a spokesman said.
   Haynsworth, 75, went to the hospital Tuesday with an irregular
heartbeat, said Greenville Memorial Hospital spokesman Dave
Partridge. Haynsworth did not have a heart attack, but was kept for
observation, he said.
   Haynsworth, a member of the 4th Circuit Court of Appeals since
1957 and its chief judge for more than 16 years, officially retired
as chief judge in 1981, but continues to work as a senior judge.
   Haynsworth was nominated to the U.S. Supreme Court by President
Richard Nixon in 1969, but the Senate rejected the nomination
55-45. It was the first time in 39 years that the Senate rejected a
president's nominee for the court.
