<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MedicaidCondoms     06-02 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medicaid Condoms,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few Condoms Given Away In Distribution Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Medicaid program offered free condoms
to its clients for the first time Wednesday, but an unscientific
survey of pharmacies found there were few takers.
   Michigan's Department of Social Services is allowing Medicaid
recipients to receive up to 24 free condoms at a time from
pharmacies in an effort to promote birth control and curb the
spread of acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   By early afternoon, the response at Perry's Drug Store in Battle
Creek was ``absolutely zero,'' said Arch Kane, the store's
pharmacist.
   At a Perry's Drug Store in Detroit, five people requested free
condoms by early afternoon. ``Give them a week. Word will spread
quickly,'' said the store's pharmacist, who declined to give his
name.
   The program, approved by the Legislature in December 1987, is
believed to be the first of its kind in the nation and officials
are uncertain how strong demand will be, said Chuck Peller, DSS
spokesman.
   The DSS plans to put a limit on the giveaway when it compiles
statistics on average use, Peller said. Recipients who ask for
condoms must register their Medicaid number to prevent from abusing
the offer, he added.
   Most of the cost of the program should be reimbursed by the
federal government, which pays for 90 percent of the costs of
family planning services, Peller said.
   The state will reimburse drug stores, giving them a 47-cent
profit on each condom, but that isn't as large as the margin on
condom sales, Kane said.
   ``Condoms are the highest gross-margin product in the store,''
Kane said.
   At Snyder's Drug Store in Marquette, there were no takers by
early afternoon, pharmacist Pam Pyle said.
   ``I never notice anyone being hesitant to ask for condoms,''
Pyle said, but she said most of the store's Medicaid patients
already use some type of birth control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
