<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DigestBriefs     06-02 1083</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Digest Briefs,1128</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: This package does not contain the following items from the
News Digest: LONDON _ Summit Rdp; MOSCOW _ Summit-Future; LONDON _
Britain-Reagan; JERUSALEM _ Israel; WASH _ Texas Air; WASH _
Catastrophic Health; WASH _ AIDS Commission; UNDATED _ Political
Rdp; SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Deukmejian-Veep; BORKEN, West Germany _
Mine Explosion; PHOENIX, Ariz. _ Mecham; SAN FRANCISCO _ Janitors
Strike; WASH _ Spelling Bee.
^By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev stressed
Thursday there will be no changes in his country's human rights
policies despite President Reagan's emphasis on this issue during
the Moscow summit.
   Hours after Reagan left Moscow at the end of the five-day
summit, Gorbachev told several hundred peace activists the Soviet
Union ``will not accept any advice on how we run our affairs.''
   ``We do not need anyone else's model. We do not need anyone
else's values,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on Thursday
appointed Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani acting
commander-in-chief of Iran's armed forces after major military
defeats on land and sea.
   The appointment increased the political power of the man
Iranians call ``the shark.'' Iran's official media, monitored in
Nicosia, reported that Khomeini, who has held the title of
commander-in-chief, gave Rafsanjani ``full authority'' to take over
control of military affairs.
   Rafsanjani's appointment followed a disastrous confrontation
with the U.S. Navy in the Persian Gulf and two defeats on the
battlefield in which the Iraqis drove the Iranians out of their two
main footholds inside Iraq.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most powerful U.S. warship in the
Persian Gulf stood by on Thursday when Iran's navy stopped, boarded
and escorted away a Cypriot freighter apparently suspected of
carrying war-related cargo for Iraq.
   U.S. Navy officials said the guided missile cruiser Vincennes
was two miles away and did not get an appeal for aid that could
have caused the first direct confrontation with Iran since April
18. Six Iranian vessels were knocked out that day, including two
sister ships of the frigate involved in Thursday's incident.
   It also was the closest brush since the United States adopted a
new policy allowing Navy ships to intervene in attacks on neutral
commercial ships flying flags of other nations. The rule requires a
victim to be a non-belligerent in international waters that
requests assistance.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``This absolutely blew my mind,'' Dr. James C.
Caillouette said. ``I thought something awful was happening to me.
Everytime I went into an examining room, I had a patient with
ovarian cyst.''
   Eventually, the Los Angeles gynecologist said, ``the lights
began to go on'' and he concluded there was a connection between an
outbreak of functional _ or non-cancerous _ cysts among his
patients and a new type birth control pill he had been prescribing
for them.
   Sold by three of the six major U.S. pharmaceutical companies
that make birth control pills, the so-called multiphasic pills that
went on the market in 1984 actually were not new chemical
formulations, but rather new packaging of existing drugs in various
strengths.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors should be cautious in prescribing aspirin
as a preventer of heart attacks until more research supports its
value, the Food and Drug Administration says.
   Taking aspirin to prevent heart attacks may increase some
people's chances of dying of other things, especially hemorrhagic
strokes, the agency said in a commentary in Friday's Journal of the
American Medical Association.
   The FDA persuaded aspirin makers in March to refrain from
promoting aspirin as a preventer of first heart attacks, at least
for now.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 80 percent of U.S. physicians favor
withdrawing life-support systems from hopelessly ill or
irreversibly comatose patients if the patients or their families
request it, according to a survey.
   ``From the day they enter medical school, physicians are taught
to cherish and preserve life,'' said Dr. James H. Sammons,
executive vice president of the American Medical Association, which
conducted the survey.
   ``However, there comes the time with the terminally ill or
irreversibly comatose patient that the physician must step back
and, at the patient's or the family's request, allow the patient to
die with dignity.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have identified the precise
target where the AIDS virus latches onto cells it destroys, another
step toward a drug to combat the fatal disease.
   ``For the first time, we have fairly precisely defined the
structure on the cell surface to which a virus binds. This is a
primary step in the infective process,'' said protein chemist
Stephen B.H. Kent, research team leader at the California Institute
of Technology.
   Once the virus' target, called a ``binding site,'' was
identified by Caltech molecular biologist Bradford Jameson, the
study's chief author, he and his colleagues manufactured crude
synthetic copies of the binding site.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheila Shea was just trying for a last
laugh, but some officials say the cemetery that's the final resting
place of Louisa May Alcott is no place for a tombstone that reads:
``Who The Hell Is Sheila Shea.''
   Shea, who died a year and a half ago at age 43, is buried in the
historic Sleepy Hollow Cemetery, in whose ``Authors' Row'' are
buried Alcott and 19th-century luminaries Ralph Waldo Emerson and
Henry David Thoreau.
   The disagreement over the 3{-foot, gray granite headstone
recently surfaced at the Concord Cemetery Committee, which labeled
the inscription ``obscene.'' Some members of the committee, an
advisory body to the town's department of public works, pushed for
legal action to have the headstone removed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
Thursday lost a three-year court battle to block Australian
publication of a former intelligence agent's memoirs.
   Mrs. Thatcher's expensive crusade against Peter Wright's
``Spycatcher'' had prompted protests that the government was
infringing on freedom of the press.
   Australia's highest court, the seven-judge High Court in the
capital of Canberra, ruled against Britain in its final bid to
suppress the book.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 capitalists converged Thursday on
Beijing for a weekend of caviar on the Great Wall, boat rides on an
imperial pleasure lake and a display of opulence not seen in this
spartan socialist capital since 1949.
   The participants, from 21 countries, are spending $4,300 each to
enjoy such Western luxuries as a masked ball and champagne
breakfast at sites of past Chinese imperial glory.
   For $5,200 more, 100 of them will spend 10 days touring China's
most famous scenic spots.
</TEXT>
