<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BlackMormons-Overseas Adv06   06-02 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Mormons-Overseas, Adv 06,0766</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Priesthood Revelation Sparks Growth in Africa, Caribbean</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Black Mormons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Mormon missionaries to Nigeria and Ghana were greeted
by whole congregations of converts awaiting baptism into a church
that for more than a century had refused to ordain blacks to its
priesthood.
   ``They came to us,'' said former missionary Reed Clegg. ``We
could have baptized thousands. They were living the gospel, paying
tithing, holding meetings, before we arrived.''
   When the late Mormon Church President Spencer W. Kimball ended
the 130-year exclusion of blacks from the church's all-male
priesthood on June 9, 1978, he paved the way for one of the most
extraordinary episodes in the faith's long history of missionary
work.
   Blacks have also converted by the thousands in many
predominantly black Caribbean countries and in Brazil, where many
of the church's 250,000 members claim black ancestors.
   But the story of Mormon growth in Africa stands apart. For
decades, thousands in Nigeria and Ghana who had read Mormon books
and tracts implored the church to send missionaries to baptize
them. But it wasn't until the doctrine forbidding black priests was
abolished that African governments would grant visas to Mormon
missionaries.
   In one year, the first missionaries _ two elderly couples _
baptized nearly 2,000 converts. A decade later, Nigeria has 8,500
church members, Ghana 5,000, with membership growing by about 4,000
a year in the two combined.
   Missionaries returning from African service tell of villagers
walking more than 50 miles round trip to attend church meetings, of
baptismal services lasting for hours to accommodate all the
converts and communities where religion in general was of urgent
concern.
   Church leaders assert they could multiply by many times the rate
of growth in Africa if they wished. But they are moving slowly to
build a solid base of black leadership, and they say the strategy
is paying off.
   In May, visiting officials from Salt Lake City ordained the
first black African stake president, a lay leader who presides over
several congregations, in the Nigerian city of Aba.
   In South Africa, controlled by the apartheid system of racial
separation, the number of black converts is also on the rise.
   The church could not estimate their number because its
membership records do not note race, but blacks attend Sunday
meetings and worship in the Johannesburg Temple alongside whites,
said Elder Neal A. Maxwell, who supervises church activities in
Africa.
   Black Africans are aware of the church's old policy of denying
priesthood membership to blacks, but it appears to have made little
difference to them.
   ``They are not as interested in it as we are. For them, that's
that. They are grateful for (the change), but their eyes are on the
future and they don't seem quite as caught up in it. It's not a big
thing for them,'' said Maxwell.
   Despite the success, prosyletizing in Africa has raised new
challenges to a church long acquainted with missionary work in
far-away places. Among the more difficult is the popular tradition
of polygamy.
   Scores of potential converts have been denied baptism because of
plural marriage, a practice the Mormons themselves once embraced
but officially dropped in 1890 as a prerequisite to statehood for
Utah.
   Rendell Mabey, who led the first missionary contingent, said the
problem arose on a grand scale in a congregation organized years
before the missionaries arrived. When Mabey went to the village to
baptize the people, he learned about half were polygamists.
   The monogamists initially refused to be baptized unless the
others could be as well. But after meeting privately, local leaders
decided that those who were monogamous would be baptized and the
polygamists would continue to attend as non-members.
   A cultural barrier of a different type _ the practice of voodoo
_ confronts missionaries in the West Indies. A folk religion with
African origins, voodoo involves the belief that the dead live in a
spirit world from which they can be recalled to bless or curse the
living. Those who practice it are refused baptism, said David King,
a former Utah congressman who now directs the church's missionary
effort in Haiti.
   But King said adherents usually are not attracted to Mormonism.
   ``I rarely hear it discussed, although I'm aware it is very much
a part of the Haitian culture,'' King said. ``We can hear the
voodoo drums going into the night.''
   End Adv for Mon PMs, June 6
</TEXT>
</DOC>
