<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0657EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BlackMormons-InnerCity Adv06   06-02 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Mormons-Inner City, Adv 06,0802</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, June 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mormon Ward Struggles to Accommodate Black Culture</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Cleeretta is cq in 1st graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Black Mormons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cleeretta Smiley says she's ``free at last''
in the Mormon Church's new Washington, D.C., Second Ward, but her
25-year-old son, a Sunday School teacher, wishes the church had
more appeal for young blacks.
   A decade after the church began admitting blacks to priesthood,
the sole urban Mormon congregation in Washington, which is 70
percent black, is mostly white and struggling to convert and keep
black members.
   Ward leaders could think of only two black families who attend
church together. Most members are singles or couples and few stay
in the ward long. The 400-member congregation is about 40 percent
black, but at a recent Sunday service with 100 people, only about
one-fourth were black.
   Yet officials of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints
say some of the black members, particularly more-recent immigrants,
are faithful members, and they are having a subtle impact on
traditional Mormon services.
   A former Nigerian legislator, Rufus Olumba, teaches in his
native ``agbada'' robes and headdress to a mostly white priesthood
class. The lessons are out of the church manual, but Olumba adds
unique phraseology and experience to Mormon doctrine.
   Mrs. Smiley, the ward's public communications director, has
heard the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. quoted in church.
   ``What this church has given me is such a high level of freedom.
I'm free, I'm free at last in that ward,'' she said, consciously
echoing King's words.
   Mrs. Smiley, whose husband left her and won custody of two of
their four children after she joined the church three years before
the ban on black priests was lifted, said she and other black
Mormons tried for years to get an inner-city ward, which was
finally established in May 1987.
   Before that, the city had been divided like a wagon wheel, with
its wards radiating out into the suburbs along the lines of the
spokes. That scattered the few black members among the suburban
wards.
   Beverly Campbell, a Washington-based church spokeswoman, said
the church earlier avoided having a city ward because it didn't
want the appearance of segregating church members.
   Now, although the gleaming Mormon temple in Kensington, Md., is
a suburban landmark, the city's Mormons have no chapel.
   On Sundays, the church leases part of the National Press Club,
turning the modern downtown center into a not-so-typical Mormon
wardhouse, with bishops conferences in a 13th-floor lounge
overlooking the city, Sunday School classes in rooms named for
famous journalists and sacrament services in a hall where the
nation's newsmakers address the Washington press.
   Campbell acknowledged the church faces a challenge in attracting
black Americans.
   ``The gospel is ever true and ever the same. It does not
change,'' she said. ``And yet, the people of other cultures must
feel a spiritual and emotional binding with the spiritual message.
That is sometimes missing.''
   But in a church that now prides itself in attracting all races
and nationalities, there aren't enough active black members to
raise the issue of segregation.
   Mrs. Smiley's son Robert said the church has little appeal to
inner-city blacks, who still view it as a white, racist institution.
   ``The church has the basic principles,'' he said, ``but it has
to change with the times.'' A graduate in industrial technology, he
said one of his major complaints about the church is the dullness
of its music.
   At a recent service, the congregation sang several traditional,
slow Mormon hymns _ a sharp contrast to the lively gospel music of
Washington's predominantly black Protestant churches.
   A member of the bishopric, Mark Sykes, said he knew of no
incidents of racial prejudice among Mormons in the area but pointed
to other problems.
   Church members assigned to make monthly visits to members' homes
have been mugged in tough inner-city neighborhoods, he said.
   Ward leaders try hard to make black members more active in the
congregation and to make them leaders, he said, but many are from
homes where they are the only Mormons. They face pressure to leave
the church from their families and friends and from actively
anti-Mormon Protestant ministers, he said.
   Sykes, a 26-year-old financial analyst with the Marriott Corp.,
said he believes full acceptance of the church by blacks may have
to come with the generation who are now children.
   ``The children ... should be able to reconcile their black
heritage and their Mormon heritage,'' he said. ``Maybe only then
can there be a happy marriage of Mormonism and the black American.''
   End Adv for Mon PMs, June 6
</TEXT>
</DOC>
