<2ND_LINE>PM-Surfing Pets, Adv 10,0810</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, June 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pet Peeve of Hawaiian Humane Society: Surfing Animals</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Professional surfer Rell Kapoliokaehukai Sunn
figured she and her dog, Shane, had the ``Wet Pet'' division of a
recent surfing contest all wrapped up. Then the pig with the
sunscreen showed up.
   Brian Keaulana, another pro surfer, and his 4-month-old pig
``Chop Chop'' sent the 2,000 spectators and five judges at Makaha
Beach on Leeward Oahu hog wild, beating a dozen other human
competitors who rode their boards tandem with everything from a
baby goose to saltwater fish in a bowl.
   ``Shane is the surfing dog of Makaha, the kids love him,'' Sunn
said of her 2-year-old mutt. ``But Brian really did some moves on
the board with that pig, Chop Chop. Shane just sort of sits there.''
   But Sunn, who is 37 and works as a lifeguard, said winning was
not important. She was happy that the first ``Wet Pet'' contest,
part of the 11th Annual Rell Sunn Menehune Surfing Championships,
was a hit.
   ``The kids out there were going crazy. Everybody just loved
it,'' she said.
   Not everybody.
   The Hawaiian Humane Society received numerous phone calls
protesting the event and wants to prevent similar contests in the
future, according to Bob Spencer, public relations and fund
development director.
   The society is not impressed by surfing animals.
   ``We are against putting animals in unnatural or dangerous
situations,'' Spencer said. ``And there is nothing more unnatural
than a pig on a surfboard.''
   Further, Spencer said, delicate pink pig skin is prone to
sunburn, and not all owners are as considerate at Keaulana, who
covered Chop Chop's ears and snout with multicolored zinc oxide.
   ``People thought the pig was in distress because it was green,''
Spencer said. ``They didn't know it was covered with colored suntan
lotion.''
   Sunn's ``Wet Pet'' contest is the first one Spencer has heard of
in the islands, but he's worried the idea might catch on.
   ``It might look fun, but whose entertainment is it?'' he asked.
``It's certainly not entertaining or fun for the animals.''
   Sunn disagreed, but acknowledged Spencer had a point.
   ``Shane loves being in the water. He loves to surf and he loves
the attention,'' she said. ``But some animals might not like it,
and their owners shouldn't push them just to show off.''
   Sunn said she refused to let one inexperienced surfer enter the
``Wet Pet'' competition after she saw the woman practicing with her
dog.
   ``She wiped out and had attached the dog's leash to the board so
it really got knocked around in the waves. That dog could have
drowned or broken its neck,'' Sunn said.
   Spencer said the Humane Society ``isn't declaring war on these
people, we just want to educate them,'' noting that animals are
prohibited on state beaches, and that regulation could be more
strictly enforced.
   Sunn said she plans to hold the competition again next year, but
will regulate who can enter.
   ``We're only going to have people who we know surf with their
animals, who we've seen out before,'' she said. Meanwhile, she says
she'll keep surfing with Shane.
   ``He loves it and I don't think anybody should tell me what to
do with my dog,'' she said. ``I don't force him. I just put the
board on the beach, he jumps on the nose and we paddle out
together.''
   ``I only take him out in gentle surf. He likes small waves,
nothing bigger than 5 feet.''
   Rob Burns agreed: ``You know how certain dogs really like to
hang their heads out of car windows? Well, it's like that, some
pets just really take to the waves.''
   Burns owns Local Motion, a Honolulu-based water sports equipment
and clothing store with nationwide distribution, which sponsored a
surfing contest in the waves off Waikiki on Memorial Day and wanted
to include a ``Wet Pet'' division this year.
   ``I've heard of pigs out in Waianae that bodysurf all by
themselves and one gal has a pet rabbit that follows her to the
beach,'' he said.
   But after talking it over with the Humane Society, Burns
scrapped his plan.
   ``They let us know they were against it and that is was illegal
to have animals on the beach,'' Burns said. ``It looked like it was
going to cause a big stink, when it was supposed to be all in fun,
so we just decided to drop it.''
   Burns ``was very sensible about it and understood our point of
view,'' said Spencer. ``Some people aren't so sensible. Those are
the ones we're worried about.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, June 10</NOTE>
