<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0705EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv03   06-02 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 03,0852</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, June 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Christians Flock To Atheist Land To Salute Faith</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By some odd twists of place and history, church
leaders of the world converge next week in a land of official
atheism to celebrate the original flowering there of Christianity.
   It's a peculiar combination. In the seemingly incompatible
setting of the Soviet Union, whose government disavows existence of
God, an enduring faith marks its 1,000th birthday.
   Taking part there in June 5-16 celebrations are prominent church
figures from many countries, ranging from top Vatican officers to
evangelist Billy Graham to the Archbishop of Canterbury.
   To a curious extent, the occasion brings together chieftains of
belief in a climate against it, where the Communist government's
efforts to stamp it out have gone on for 70 years.
   But signs of change circulated and the Rev. Bruce Rigdon, a
Presbyterian scholar of Chicago and specialist on Soviet church
life, says ``all kinds of amazing things are happening'' to improve
religious conditions.
   ``We want to show our solidarity with churches there, to express
our hopes for them and let the government know that they're not
isolated and alone but part of a worldwide community that holds
them in esteem and cares for them.''
   The Rev. John Wilkes of the Baptist World Alliance in
Washington, also among those attending, says, ``This worldwide
gathering can be helpful in overcoming barriers to Christianity and
making it better understood.''
   The affair comes at a time of moderations in Soviet domestic
policies, including opening of additional churches, large-scale
printing and importing of Bibles and promised easing of religious
restrictions.
   Some even see latent religious potentialities in Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev, reportedly raised in a Russian Orthodox family
and who says laws are being revised to recognize religious concerns.
   ``We are praying that he will become a Christian and, if
possible, a Methodist,'' the Rev. Olay Parnaments, a Methodist
pastor in Soviet Estonia told the United Methodist general
conference in St. Louis in May.
   Gorbachev in April met with Patriarch Pimen in the Kremlin and
called for more tolerant attitudes toward religion, the first such
meeting between top church and government leaders in 40 years.
   Bishop Clement, U.S. representative of Russian Orthodoxy, says
about 450 foreign church leaders are attending the celebrations
there, including about 60 from the United States.
   Roman Cathoilicism is sending a high-level, 10-member
delegation, headed by the Vatican Secretary of State, Cardinal
Agostino Casaroli, the pope's top aide.
   He and Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, leader of the
world-wide Anglican communion, including U.S. Episcopalians, are
among speakers for special ``Jubilee'' ceremonies June 10 at
Resurrection Church of the newly restored St. Daniel Monastery in
Moscow.
   Other speakers at that time are to include Graham and Rabbi
Arthur Schneier of New York, president of the interfaith Appeal of
Conscience Foundation, which works internationally to promote
religious freedom.
   Pope John Paul II issued a pastoral letter on the rise and
endurance of Christianity in the Soviet Union, expressing hopes for
`` full communion in Christ with these sister churches.''
   The Lutheran World Federation hailed the Russian church for its
creative influence in the country's history.
   Among American church leaders attending:
   The Rev. Avery Post, president of the United Church of Christ;
the Rev. Arie Brouwer, chief executive of the National Council of
Churches; Metropolitan Theodosius, head of the Orthodox Church in
America; Roman Catholic Cardinal John O'Connor of New York; the
Rev. Joe Hale, general secretary of the World Methodist Conference;
Bishop Herbert Chilstrom, head of the Evangelical Lutheran Church
in America; Episcopal Bishop David Reed of Louisville, Ky.;
Presbyterian William P. Thompson of the World Conference on
Religion and Peace; Neal Wilson, president of Seventh-day
Adventists, and the Rev. Donald Miller, general secretary of the
Church of the Brethren.
   The 10-day celebration starts with all-night vigils at Moscow
churches, followed the next day, June 5, by a liturgy at the
Patriarchal Cathedral of the Epiphany led by Patriarch Pimen.
   Russian Orthodoxy holds a council June 6-9 at the nearby
theological center at Zagorsk, with various intervening events at
theaters and churches prior to the ``Jubilee'' ceremonies June l0.
   Another all-night vigil was set June ll at Moscow churches.
   Other special services commemorating saints, and recognizing
some new ones, were set for June 12 in Trinity Cathedral, with a
reception afterward, hosted by Pimen and other Orthodox prelates.
   On following days, and also interspersing previous events,
visits were to be made to churches in other cities, including
Leningrad, Kiev and Vladimir.
   It was in A.D. 988 that Prince Vladimir, newly converted to
Christianity, got the pagan subjects of his principality then known
as Kievan Rus to join in a mass baptism of thousands in the Dnieper
river at Kiev.
   The faith penetrated a people and a culture, and despite
hardships it has encountered, the imprint remains.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, June 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
