<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Capitalism Visits Communism for Superpower Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From Cajun food to cable television, the
journalists, Kremlinologists, presidential aides and party
functionaries involved in the Moscow summit got a glimpse of
capitalism in the core of communist power.
   While the summit was short on substance, it broke down some of
the stereotypes the two leaders had on life in the other
superpower, stirring up a ``feel-good'' atmosphere that was visible
on the streets and sidewalks of this infamously grim city.
   Media madness and commercial hype are unfamiliar experiences in
Moscow, and for the most part Soviet citizens were excluded from
the fray that unfolded at the summit media center. Roadblocks set
up a half-mile from the site at the International Hotel steered
away all without special passes.
   But for the Westerners in town for the meetings between Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and President Reagan, a few touches of
home made their stay more comfortable and in conformance with
similar events held abroad.
   The island of consumerism established at the hotel, known as the
``Mezh'' among the foreign community here, drew dozens of prominent
Soviet pundits and politicians.
   Instant coffee and caviar sandwiches were sold from linen-spread
tables in the Congress Hall, alongside kiosks selling Gorbachev's
book ``Perestroika'' and stacks of Moscow postcards.
   Officials in the vanguard of the glasnost and perestroika
campaigns milled around the cavernous press room, where many of the
5,000 journalists covering the event set up telephones, typewriters
and portable computers. They gave impromptu interviews, surveyed
the souvenirs and watched the live Cable News Network feed on huge
television monitors set up throughout the center.
   The White House press center issued texts of the president's
speeches and comments, and the Soviet Foreign Ministry responded
with summit briefing packets and a desk that took applications for
private interviews with Soviet officials.
   CNN beamed its 24-hour service into central Moscow for the
summit, but only foreign-made televisions like those at the Mezh
were able to tune in the American programming.
   A mobile pizza van brought in to Moscow two months ago parked
along the Moscow River embankment across from the hotel and did a
whopping business with the busy journalists.
   A Louisiana chef, John Folse, shipped his Cajun cooking
operation _ lock, stock and catfish _ to Moscow for the summit,
taking over the Mercury restaurant at the Mezh in a weeklong
joint-venture that hit some snags. The restaurant gave out free
hamburgers and fries to the working press as a means of eating up
some of its profits that could not be taken out of the country.
   Rival T-shirt and souvenir kiosks sprung up at the press center,
dispensing ``Moscow Summit-88'' memorabilia for hard currency. Even
the official Tass news agency got in on the act, producing shirts,
buttons, records and tapes with the help of an American marketing
firm.
   Summit spinoffs that reached the general public were at times
more hindrance than help. Roadblocks were set up at intersections
leading to all summit sights _ the press center, the American
ambassador's residence where the Reagans stayed and along motorcade
routes. The traffic diversions frustrated some Soviets trying to
get to home or work in areas around the president's path.
   But the spruced-up city and the excitement of a visit by the
American president who once called the Soviet Union an ``evil
empire'' made Muscovites proud and brought them out in droves for
walks about the summit showcase.
   American and Soviet flags stemmed from light poles along the
motorcade routes and Red Square, with its famous and garish
landmarks, was floodlit throughout the summit for the benefit of
American television viewers who saw the historic setting as the
backdrop on evening news programs.
   The Arbat pedestrian mall, always thronged with street artists
and strollers, took on a more political focus with murals depicting
abstract concepts of superpower relations and buttons commemorating
the five-day event.
   But almost simultaneously with the takeoff of the presidential
plane, the barriers came down and the power plugs were pulled.
   Some summit preparations may have longer term effects, like the
frenetic painting and repaving done before the event. But for most
Muscovites, the signs of the superpower conference were a memory
before Reagan's plane crossed out of Soviet airspace.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Carol J. Williams has been a correspondent for
The Associated Press in Moscow since July 1984
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 5</NOTE>
