<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0559</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ran up a sharp gain for the
second straight session as fears of rising interest rates and
inflation continued to abate on Wall Street.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 32.89 points
Wednesday to 2,064.01, bringing its gain over the past two sessions
to 107.57 points.
   Seasoned market watchers expressed surprise at the buying spree
following the long Memorial Day weekend. Many analysts said the
rally once again proved the adage that you cannot outguess the
market.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said its chief economic
forecasting gauge rose a modest 0.2 percent in April, an increase
analysts said signaled continued healthy economic growth for the
rest of the year.
   Wednesday's report marked the third consecutive monthly increase
in the Commerce Department's Index of Leading Indicators, following
an identical 0.2 percent rise in March and a giant 1.5 percent
February surge, which had been the largest gain in more than two
years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories surged for the second
consecutive month in April, the government said, indicating that
U.S. manufacturing plants will be humming in the months ahead.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that orders for durable
and non-durable goods rose a strong 1.2 percent to a seasonally
adjusted $218.7 billion in April. The advance followed an even
bigger 1.6 percent increase in March.
   ``The boom-like conditions in factory America continue pretty
much unabated,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist of Boston Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending advanced 0.1 percent in
April as a boom in factory construction helped offset weakness in
government projects, the Commerce Department reported.
   The department said Wednesday that building activity rose to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $401.8 billion in April, up 1.4
percent from a year earlier.
   But analysts tended to discount the weak overall change and
instead focus on a big 8.8 percent rise in spending on industrial
plants, which put activity in this sector up a remarkable 39.8
percent above where it was a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. dropped its fierce resistance to a
hostile takeover bid, succumbing to a $1.7 billion offer from
British industrialist Brian C. Beazer and abruptly ending a
three-month battle that caught congressional attention.
   The sudden collapse of Koppers' opposition to the takeover
spelled the end of independence for the construction materials and
chemicals company, one of the largest U.S. road repair companies.
   ``We set out to keep the company independent, but business as it
is currently conducted didn't give us that opportunity,'' Koppers
Chairman Charles Pullin said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines cut 29 flights from its southern
hub in Atlanta and said it will transfer workers and sharply limit
hiring this summer to avoid new layoffs.
   The reduction in flights from the Atlanta hub announced
Wednesday was intended to cut costs. Eastern lost $182 million last
year.
   The airline began stepped-up negotiations this week under
federal mediation with its largest union, the International
Association of Machinists, while a spokesman for the Air Line
Pilots Association said his union is preparing proposals for talks
on amending its contract.
</TEXT>
