<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission decided
to give securities industry officials a month to press their
objections to a proposal aimed at protecting investors' option to
sue their brokers.
   The SEC had been scheduled to vote Wednesday to ask Congress to
pass a law barring brokerage firms from requiring customers to
agree in advance to submit disputes to stock exchange-sponsored
arbitration panels.
   But the vote was postponed after commissioners Charles Cox,
Edward Fleischman and Joseph Grundfest said the matter required
more deliberation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. farm exports in March climbed to a
3{-year high of 14.8 million tons valued at $3.3 billion, the
Agriculture Department announced.
   ``Agriculture is making an important contribution to the trade
balance of the United States,'' Agriculture Secretary Richard E.
Lyng said in a speech Wednesday before the figures were released.
   In his remarks, Lyng predicted around $33 billion in export
sales this year and a positive farm trade balance of perhaps $12
billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who died of lung cancer after
smoking for 40 years knew the risks but chose to smoke anyway, a
tobacco company lawyer said as final arguments began in the product
liability trial of three cigarette manufacturers.
   The companies are charged with misleading the public about the
dangers of cigarettes and contributing to the 1984 death of Rose
Cipollone, 58.
   Wednesday's defense summations came exactly four months after
the case opened in federal court with a lawyer for widower Antonio
Cipollone outlining the case against Liggett Group Inc., Lorillard
Inc. and Philip Morris Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aviation industry stunned by the in-flight
breakup of an Aloha Airlines jet in April began a formal
re-examination of how to ensure that aging aircraft are kept safe.
   More than 350 representatives from airlines, aircraft
manufacturers, government agencies and aviation safety groups
launched a three-day conference Wednesday by debating whether the
industry's approach to maintaining the safety of older planes is
adequate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having taken his potshots at the White House,
former Treasury Secretary Donald Regan is now zinging Merrill Lynch
& Co., the giant investment firm he headed during its rapid growth
in the 1970s.
   In the June 20 issue of Fortune magazine, Regan blasts the
current management at Merrill Lynch and suggests the company be
taken over.
   ``How long does it take to get your act together?'' Regan asked.
``You guys have had over three years.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ran up a sharp gain for the second straight
session Wednesday as fears of rising interest rates and inflation
continued to abate. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed
32.89 points to 2,064.01, bringing its gain over the past two
sessions to 107.57 points.
   A post-holiday rally in the U.S. financial markets sustained the
