<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Germany-SovietTrade Bjt   06-02 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Soviet Trade, Bjt,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Germans Rushing To Boost Trade With Soviets; Washington Concerned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German businesses, lured in
part by promises of economic reform in the Soviet Union, are
rushing to boost their trade with the Kremlin.
   They range from the mighty Deutsche Bank, which recently
arranged a $2 billion line of credit for the Kremlin, to the
sporting goods company Adidas, which already is making products in
the Soviet Union but is looking to expand.
   While a string of new collaborations were announced in May, the
growing trend has sparked some criticism from Washington.
   Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., without referring by name to Deutsche
Bank, said the Soviets ``are using these loans to finance military
mischief, I fear, around the world.''
   But Soviet economists say that is unlikely.
   ``Soviet consumers want better products,'' said Helmut Giesecke,
an economist with the Bonn Industry and Trade Conference office.
``Once they have them, they're not going back to the old ways.''
   Still, Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci, who appeared with
Sasser at a recent senate committee hearing, said U.S. defense
officials had discussed the situation ``in general terms because
they put an added defense burden on the NATO allies.''
   The allies, however, could also complain about U.S. trade with
the Soviets, Carlucci noted.
   West Germany, which serves as NATO's front line of defense
against the Soviet-led Warsaw pact, has seen its trade with the
Soviets decline for the past three years.
   West German imports from the Soviets have nearly halved to $4.27
billion since 1984, and exports to the Soviets are down to $4.6
billion, from $6.3 billion three years ago.
   Seventy percent of Soviet exports to West Germany are natural
gas and oil products, which are purchased with U.S. dollars. But a
low dollar and cheap oil prices have taken their toll, cutting into
the foreign currency supplies the Soviets need import goods.
   Increased ties to West Germany fit Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's program to improve conditions at home, Soviet
economists say. To encourage foreign investment, the Soviet Union
has begun allowing Western concerns to own a share of Soviet
industries.
   Deutsche Bank economist Hans Dettmar said that it is too early
to tell how the line of credit will be used by the Soviets, but
``it is intended for light industry consumer products, such as
shoes and foodstuffs, and joint venture projects to expand that
market with the Soviet Union.''
   Any business deals will be announced by the companies taking
part, not the bank. ``We and the other banks involved only make the
money available,'' he said.
   Among the German companies that announced deals last month were:
   _Salamander, West Germany's largest shoe producer, which already
produces shoes in Leningrad, said it would up its production with a
new plant in Vitebsk.
   _Lurgi GmbH said it was heading a consortium of companies
awarded a $294 million contract to build two new oil and gas plants
to expand production in the Tengiuz oil fields near the Caspian Sea.
   _Adidas will begin making sports textiles in Tbilis by the end
of this year. The company has been making shoes in Moscow since
1978 and in Kiev since 1984.
   _MAN, producer of heavy vehicles, announced a joint venture with
the Soviets to produce long-haul trucks.
   To help finance the deals the Soviets are looking West for hard
currency. Frankfurt bank sources said the Soviets are planning to
sell $294 million in Eurobonds in West Germany.
   That sale would follow a $70 million bond the Soviets floated
five months ago in Switzerland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
