<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-Trade     06-02 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Trade,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slowdown Reported In Export Growth In May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's exports in May rose 16
percent to $4.67 billion but appear to be slowing from the brisk
pace set in the first four months of the year, the Trade and
Foreign Ministry said Thursday.
   Exports totaled $4.67 billion last month, compared with $4.02
billion a year ago.
   But they increase fell short of the 32.5 percent average boost
during the first four months of the year.
   The setback was attributed to recent labor disputes over wage
hikes in auto and some other export-sensitive industries as well as
the appreciation of the Korean won against the U.S. dollar. The won
has risen about 8 percent in value since January.
   Imports in May totaled $4.23 billion, up 16.6 percent from $3.63
billion a year ago.
   The trade surplus in May amouted to $435 million, compared with
$437 million in April and $395 million in May 1987. The May surplus
was the smallest since February.
   For the past five months, exports totaled $22.1 billion, up 28.6
percent from a year ago, while imports rose 30.7 percent to $19.83
billion, according to the ministry's preliminary figures.
</TEXT>
