<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Soviet-Alcoholism     06-02 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Alcoholism,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Rolls Back Some Anti-Alcohol Measures, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has relaxed curbs on the production
of alcohol and lifted some restrictions on the sale of booze in a
slackening of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's anti-drunkenness drive, a
weekly newspaper reports.
   Moscow News, which is at the forefront of the Soviet leader's
campaign for ``glasnost,'' or openness, did not say what
restrictions on sales were removed.
   But the labor newspaper Trud reported last month that Moscow
city authorities had recently allowed an expansion of the number of
stores selling alcoholic beverages to 772. It did not give the
previous figure.
   Moscow News, in its Wednesday editions, and Trud gave two
reasons for the easing of Gorbachev's anti-alcoholism campaign: to
try to discourage moonshining and stop a run on sugar. The
moonshiners, who Trud said are outproducing the legal alcohol
industry, use sugar to make alcohol.
   Sugar is being rationed in several Soviet cities, but Moscow
News said it is not in short supply, adding that sugar supplies
were greater in 1988 than last year.
   Increased sales of alcohol and the stabilization of alcohol
production should reduce the use of sugar by moonshiners, Moscow
News said.
   Gorbachev's anti-alcohol campaign, his first major initiative
after taking power in March 1985, included raising the drinking
age, shortening the hours of liquor stores and cutting liquor
production.
   Soviet officials have credited the campaign with increasing the
life expectancy and cutting drunkenness on the job.
   but Nikolai Shmelev, a prominent economist, told reporters last
week Gorbachev has been going about trying to reduce alcoholism the
wrong way.
   He said the campaign has encouraged moonshiners and taken
revenue from liquor sales away from the government.
   Instead, said Shmelev, the government should improve consumer
supplies ``so a man could use his ruble to buy a bottle of vodka or
a good shirt.''
   The Communist Party daily Pravda reported late last year that
more than 4.5 million of the Soviet Union's 284 million people are
``registered alcoholics,'' 1 million of whom require compulsory
care.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
