<HEAD>Schering Drops Deal to Buy Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schering-Plough Corp. says it has
terminated its revised agreement to buy Cooper Companies Inc.'s
worldwide contact lens and lens solution businesses for $195
million.
   Schering said Wednesday it ended the deal because it did not
believe a speedy review would be forthcoming from the Federal Trade
Commission.
   Schering and Cooper reached a definitive agreement in March, but
terminated it in May after the FTC threatened a suit. The FTC said
at the time the deal might reduce competition in the manufacture
and sale of soft contact lenses.
   A few weeks later, the companies entered a revised agreement and
submitted it for FTC review.
   The transaction would have doubled the size of Schering's
Wesley-Jessen vision care business.
</TEXT>
