<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NabiscoReorganization     06-02 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nabisco Reorganization,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nabisco To Grant More Freedom to its Operating Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST HANOVER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nabisco Brands Inc. says it will
reorganize into a holding company with four autonomous operating
companies in a move designed to make the food company more
responsive to its market.
   Domestically, the Biscuit Division has been renamed the Nabisco
Biscuit Company and the Grocery Products Division will now be
called the Nabisco Foods Company.
   Nabisco's two international operating companies, London-based
International Nabisco Brands Inc. and Toronto-based Nabisco Brands
Ltd., will be relatively unaffected, Nabisco said Wednesday.
   Nabisco expects the reorganization to be complete by the end of
the year. All but about 400 of the current 2,000 workers on Nabisco
Brands' corporate staff will be assigned to the operating companies.
   The company said it did not know if any layoffs will be
necessary.
   ``Our goal with this new corporate structure is to give our
operating companies full responsibility for their key functional
areas as well as all the resources necessary to fulfill this
responsibility,'' said H. John Greeniaus, president and chief
executive officerf of Nabisco Brands.
   In the first quarter of 1988, Nabisco had net income of $273
million, up 24 percent from $220 million during the same time
period in 1987, company spokeswoman Caroline Fee said.
</TEXT>
