<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PostalService-Perot     06-02 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Postal Service-Perot,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Expert to Aid Mail Delivery</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postmaster General Anthony Frank is turning to
Texas billionaire H. Ross Perot for help in improving the nation's
postal service.
   Perot, a pioneer in computer services, is expected to be asked
to study the massive Postal Service and recommend ways to improve
efficiency.
   Frank, who became postmaster general March 1, reportedly first
met Perot at about that time and began discussing the possibility
of having the Texan help improve postal efficiency.
   Details of the plan, including the cost of Perot's work, were
not immediately available, but is was expected that Perot and
associates from his computer firm would undertake an analysis of
postal operations, including automation and labor relations.
   The Postal Service lost $635 million in the quarter from
December to March, but higher rates put into effect April 3 are
expected to pull the agency back into the black.
   When it was made an independent agency in the early 1970s, the
postal subsidy was eliminated and the service was directed to break
even, which it has done, on average, over the last decade.
   Perot founded Electronic Data Systems Co., a pioneer computer
services company, and later worked to help restructure General
Motors Co., before clashing with GM chairman Roger B. Smith. Frank
was president of a California bank that became part of Ford Motor
Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 0926EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Koppers 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koppers Succumbs To Beazer in $1.7 Billion Deal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS last graf to show tender offer was extended to June
15 rather than deal expected to close by that date.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After three months of lawsuits, talk of a
recapitalization plan and a flurry of political support, Koppers
Co. succumbed to a $1.7 billion takeover bid from British
industrialist Brian C. Beazer.
   The construction materials and chemicals company, one of the
largest U.S. road repair concerns, agreed Wednesday to be acquired
for $61 a share by BNS Inc., a company formed by Beazer, Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. and National Westminster Bank PLC.
   ``We set out to keep the company independent, but business as it
is currently conducted didn't give us that opportunity,'' Koppers
Chairman Charles Pullin said after the board unanimously approved
the merger.
   Beazer's struggle to acquire Koppers aroused intense hostility
in Pennsylvania, where Koppers is a major employer. It led to legal
wrangling in federal court and compelled local members of Congress
to introduce anti-takeover measures.
   The battle also ignited sharp criticism over Shearson's role in
participating in a hostile takeover while helping to finance it.
   Koppers' congressional allies were quick to note that Beazer's
victory does not quiet those concerns.
   ``The question for the Congress remains about the role of the
investment bankers, where they were essentially both soliciting the
deal and providing the wherewithall,'' said Rep. Doug Walgren, D-Pa.
   ``That to me is something that we ought to remain concerned
about,'' said Walgren, one of 15 congressmen who petitioned the
Energy and Commerce Committee for an investigation.
   ``It's not approprite for securities firms and foreign
corporations with banking interests to be involved in hostile
takeovers,'' said Rep. Tom Ridge, R-Pa., who vowed to support new
regulations.
   Ridge and Walgren co-sponsored a bill barring foreign banks and
domestic financial services firms from hostile takeovers. But their
efforts, like a bill introduced by Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., fell
short of helping Koppers.
   A key feature of the merger agreement is job guarantees for
Koppers employees. About 7,000 salaried workers will be guaranteed
jobs for at least one year or get a year's pay, and hourly
employees are covered by contracts that remain in force, Koppers
said.
   In addition, payments from a 32-year-old deferred compensation
plan will be accelerated to some of Koppers' 460 active and retired
managers, but ``nobody is going to get more under this merger than
they had when Koppers was ... totally independent,'' Pullin said.
   Beazer said he would delay for 45 days plans to sell the
chemicals business, giving managers a chance to make an offer. He
agreed that Koppers will remain headquartered in Pittsburgh for at
least three years.
   Pullin said Koppers' greatest hope of surviving on its own was a
recapitalization plan it claimed would compete with Beazer's offer.
But management's deal collapsed last week when an unidentified
prospective buyer backed out of purchasing part of the construction
materials business, he said.
   Koppers opposition to Beazer traces back to March 3, when BNS
launched a $45-a-share tender offer. BNS boosted the offer to $60 a
share on March 25 and sweetened it by $1 during weekend
negotiations.
   Koppers won anti-takeover injunctions in U.S. District Courts in
Los Angeles and Pittsburgh. The California ruling, concerning
antitrust issues, fell last week on appeal, and the judge in
Pittsburgh offered BNS options for overcoming apparent violations
of securities laws.
   On Wall Street, Koppers stock closed Wednesday at $60.50 a
share, up $1.50.
   Analysts were satisfied with the $61-a-share payout. ``That's a
good value for Koppers shareholders,'' said analyst Christopher H.
Willis of Brown Brothers Harriman in New York.
   In the end, Pullin insisted that the merger agreement was
reached ``with my complete cooperation'' and that the takeover
fulfills management's commitment to enhance shareholder value.
   ``Now that the drama has ended, we are looking forward to
getting on with the job, putting together a world class aggregates
company and beating the competition,'' Beazer said.
   The tender offer was extended until June 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
