<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined broadly today, giving
up some of its recent gains as interest rates turned upward.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 11.56 to 2,052.45
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 2 to 1 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 301 up, 718
down and 414 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 23.15 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Interest rates rose in the credit markets this morning,
reversing a sharp decline Tuesday and Wednesday. Analysts also
noted an increase in British interest rates.
   That prompted many traders to sell stocks in order to cash in on
the gains of the past two sessions, brokers said.
   The upswing in stock prices since the start of the week was met
with considerable skepticism on Wall Street, given continued signs
of upward pressure on commodity prices.
   Texaco fell 1{ to 50~. Financier Carl Icahn said he would
probably sell his large stake in the company if he should lose his
bid to gain control of five seats on the board of directors.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.69 to 149.65. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .68 at 297.61.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 32.89 to
2,064.01, bringing its gain over the past two sessions to 107.57
points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by nearly 4 to 1 on the
NYSE, with 1,287 up, 323 down and 360 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 234.56 million shares, against 247.61 million in the
previous session.
