<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FirstCity-Dividend     06-02 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-First City-Dividend,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First City Announces First Dividend Since Bailout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First City Bancorporation of Texas Inc. says it
plans to pay partial second-quarter dividends to stockholders June
30.
   At a monthly board meeting Wednesday, First City's board of
directors voted to pay roughly $1.085 on each share of Series B
convertible preferred stock that was sold to finance part of the
$1.5 billion, federally-assisted restructuring of the Houston-based
holding company.
   After overcoming weeks of delays spurred by hesitant
debtholders, the transaction was completed April 19. The dividend,
the first to be paid by the restructured company, will be paid to
stockholders of record June 15.
   The Series B preferred bears a $5.50 annual dividend rate, and
the partial dividend will cover the period between April 19 and
June 30, First City officials said.
   The restructuring was completed using $500 million of private
capital, including the sale of 2.45 million preferred shares, a
$970 million note from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., and a
$108 million loan from a group of banks.
   First City spokesman Jim Day said the company has been
profitable since April 19, when the transaction was completed.
</TEXT>
