<HEAD>Diamond Star Motors Begins Production of Pilot Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diamond-Star Motors Corp. has begun
production of about 100 pilot cars at its new factory, testing the
coordinated work of robots and humans, a company spokeswoman said
today.
   The assembly line began rolling slowly on Wednesday, giving some
400 auto workers their first experience working with robots in the
new $650 million plant, a joint venture between Chrysler Corp. and
Mitsubishi Motors of Japan.
   But the first pilot cars won't roll off the assembly line until
mid-June, said spokeswoman Chris Ziehmann.
   ``Production did begin yesterday. Understanding that it is a
very slow, careful beginning, everything that was scheduled
yesterday went fine,'' Ms. Ziehmann said today.
   ``This is the start of tying everything together, making sure
everything works right,'' she added.
   The state-of-the-art auto plant features high-technology
machinery, including robotics on the final assembly line.
   Diamond-Star is scheduled to begin full-scale production of
sporty coupes at the new plant in the first week of September.
Chrylser will market the car as the Plymouth Laser.
   Mitsubishi Motor Sales of America, which has 205 dealerships in
the United States, also will distribute the sports car, but it
hasn't announced the name it will use.
</TEXT>
