<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Fisher-Riser     06-02 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fisher-Riser,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fisher-Riser Merger Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fisher Foods' shareholders have approved a
merger with Riser Foods Inc. that will give Riser 63 grocery stores
and one of the largest wholesale grocery operations in the Midwest.
   The vote came Thursday, a day after Cuyahoga County Common Pleas
Judge Michael Corrigan denied a request by three Fisher Foods
shareholders to prevent the grocery firm from holding a special
meeting of shareholders to vote on the merger proposal.
   Fisher said in a news release that it expects the merger to go
into effect June 13. The new company will be the largest retail
employer in Greater Cleveland with about 6,500 employees and
estimated revenues of about $1 billion, Fisher said.
   Under the merger, each share of Fisher common stock will be
exchanged for one share of Riser Class A common stock, and each
share of preferred will also be evenly exchanged.
   Even though the special meeting was not delayed, Corrigan will
still consider the suit filed by William Steiner and Charles Miller
of Great Neck, N.Y., and Edith Citron, of Pompano Beach, Fla.
   The three shareholders alleged that the parties to the merger
are scheming to acquire a disproportionately high amount of
Fisher's stock at the expense of Fisher shareholders.
   Brian K. Garson, Fisher president, said: ``We are very pleased
with Judge Corrigan's decision to allow Fisher shareholders the
right to vote on the erger proposal.''
   He said the lawsuit's allegations ``are totally without merit.''
   A similar suit, filed by the same shareholders, against Fisher
is pending in U.S. District Court.
</TEXT>
