<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Advance In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower, then
quickly turned mixed to higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The lower opening reflected the tail end of Wednesday's
profit-taking and reports of light rain in the eastern Corn Belt,
analysts said.
   New buying interest surfaced in response to the National Weather
Service's prediction of below-normal rainfall in most
grain-producing areas for the period June 7-11.
   The early gains ``make sense given the six-to-10 day forecast,''
said Katharina Zimmer, a grain analyst in New York with Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets Inc. ``We need rain now; we don't need
another six to 10 days of dry weather.''
   Rain is badly needed in the Midwest, where the corn crop is
entirely planted and soybean planting is nearing completion.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to \ cent higher with
July at $3.48 a bushel; corn was { cent to } cent higher with July
at $2.21{ a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 3\ cents higher with July
at $1.81{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher
with July at $8.01} a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher while pork futures were mostly lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .30 cent higher with June at 72.37
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .48 cent higher with
August at 76.70 cents a pound; hogs were .38 cent lower to .18 cent
higher with June at 54.12 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.40 cent to .98 cent lower with July at 57 cents a pound.
   Frozen pork bellies settled sharply higher on Wednesday while
livestock futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
