<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Rally Falters, Major Retailers Post Lackluster May Sales</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 7 new grafs with morning market activity, retail
sales reports. Picks up 6th graf pvs, The Commerce ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pulled back today after rising sharply over the
past two sessions, and the nation's largest general retailers
reported May sales that analysts described as lackluster.
   At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials,
which had climbed 107.57 points Tuesday and Wednesday, was off 6.76
at 2,057.25.
   Analysts said some traders sold stocks to cash in on the gains
of the past two sessions. They noted that interest rates, which had
fallen earlier this week, turned higher today.
   In the latest round of retail sales reports, major storeowners
reported their sales were marginally higher or actually fell last
month.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest retailer, said its
overall sales last month rose 5.1 percent from May 1987 levels,
while sales from stores open at least a year _ also known as
same-store sales _ rose only 0.2 percent.
   K mart Corp. said its overall sales rose 6 percent last month,
while same-store sales rose only 2.3 percent. J.C. Penney Co. Inc.
said its overall sales fell 1.2 percent last month and same-store
sales fell 1.4 percent.
   On Wednesday, the government reported April gains in its chief
economic forecasting gauge as well as in factory orders and
construction spending.
   The Commerce Department reported its Index of Leading Indicators
rose 0.2 percent in April, following rises of 0.2 percent rise in
March and 1.5 percent in February.
   The March increase in the leading index originally was reported
as a much stronger 0.8 percent rise. However, weakness in consumer
and business borrowing pulled the index down sharply.
   The government also reported that orders to U.S. factories for
manufactured goods climbed 1.2 percent in April to a seasonally
adjusted $218.7 billion following an even bigger 1.6 percent March
increase.
   Most economists had been forecasting only modest growth in new
orders of 0.5 percent in April. The bigger-than-expected number
likely will do little to alleviate concern among some analysts that
strong demand, particularly for exports, will trigger greater
inflation.
   The strength in new orders in April came in electrical
machinery, lumber and wood products and in petroleum, chemicals and
paper.
   In a third report, the Commerce Department said construction
spending rose 0.1 percent in April to an annual rate of $401.8
billion, following a 1.3 percent jump in March and a 0.4 percent
February increase.
   Analysts tended to discount the weak overall change and focused
on a big 8.8 percent rise in spending on industrial plants, which
put activity in this sector up 39.8 percent from where it was a
year earlier.
   Jerry Jasinowski, chief economist of the National Association of
Manufacturers, said the gain reflected the boom in export sales,
which has meant plants in many industries are operating near full
capacity.
   Government construction fell by 3.1 percent in April to an
annual rate of $79.3 billion. Residential construction posted a 0.4
percent advance in April to an annual rate of $191.9 billion, while
non-residential construction climbed 2.1 percent in April to an
annual rate of $94.4 billion.
   In another economic report Wednesday, the Agriculture Department
said U.S. farm exports climbed to a 3{-year high of 14.8 million
tons valued at $3.3 billion in March. A year earlier, farm exports
were 11.4 million tons valued at $2.4 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880602-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Mexico-Oil     06-02 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico-Oil,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Begins Marketing New Light Crude</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico's state oil monopoly Pemex has begun
marketing a new high-grade crude in the international petroleum
market, the government newspaper El Nacional reported.
   Abundio Juarez Mendez, deputy director of primary production for
Pemex, said the company last month exported 250,000 42-gallon
barrels of the new crude, called Olmeca. He did not identify the
purchaser.
   He said the new crude can be priced a dollar more a barrel than
the Isthmus brand, which previously was the nation's superior oil.
Mexico also exports a heavy crude, called Maya.
   ``(Olmeca) is much finer than Isthmus (and) it is superior to
Arab light,'' Juarez Mendez told local reporters at an oil
conference on Latin American drilling, according to the article,
which was published Thursday.
   Mexico, he said, has the capacity to eventually export 125,000
barrels to 150,000 barrels a day of the new crude, which is being
extracted from fields in the southeastern state of Tabasco along
the coast of the Gulf of Mexico.
   Juarez Mendez said the new oil has a density of between 38 and
40 on the American Petroleum Institute scale, compared to a density
of 32 to 34 for Isthmus.
   The English-language daily Mexico City News quoted an
unidentified Pemex official as saying the government ``is not yet
sure how much light oil it has. Pemex is still exploring.''
   ``There is probably not much Olmeca in Mexico,'' he was quoted
as saying.
   Pemex, meanwhile, reported that prices to Japanese clients for
Isthmus and Maya crudes were held steady in May
   The price for Isthmus was $15.30 a barrel in May to Japan, the
same as in April, and for Maya, $12.60 a barrel.
   ``This reflects the stability that prevails in the general level
of prices in the international oil market,'' Pemex said in a
statement.
   Mexico has a contract with Japanese customers to supply 180,000
barrels of oil a day, the statement said.
   Mexico's prices vary according to geographical area. The oil
company did not give the May prices for U.S. and European customers.
   In April, the price of the Isthmus brand to U.S. customers was
$16 a barrel and $12.77 for the heavy type.
   Mexico maintains an export platform of 1.36 million barrels a
day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
