<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-StockMargins     06-02 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Stock Margins,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stock Exchange To Raise Margin Requirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange said Thursday it would
raise its margin requirement for stock purchases from 60 percent to
70 percent as of June 3 because of recent gains in share prices and
volume.
   A substantial rise in margin transactions also prompted the
move, exchange officials said.
   Traders however said the action was likely to have little effect
on the market and added that changes in the margin requirement in
the past had failed to have strong impact on the exchange.
   The margin requirement represents the down payment needed for
investors who purchase stock with borrowed money.
   On May 16, the TSE raised the margin requirement to the current
60 percent from 50 percent. The next day, the Nikkei Stock Average
of 225 selected issues rose 167.86 points to top its close on the
day before the October crash. It rose another 93 points the day
after that and then surged 1,001 points over three sessions early
the next week to surpass its pre-crash high.
   Over the past four sessions this week, the main market barometer
has risen 906.86 points. It closed Thursday at a record high
27,869.36 points.
   Volume, meanwhile, this week has averaged around 1.8 billion
shares a day, compared with around 1.1 billion shares a day last
week. On Wednesday, volume in terms of shares traded reached the
highest level since the market crash after 2.561 billion shares
were traded for the second highest one-day volume ever.
   On Tuesday, the TSE announced that in the week ended May 28, the
balance of margin buying rose 208.1 billion yen to 6.485 trillion
yen. It was the fourth consecutive weekly rise, and a historical
high balance of long positions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
