<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-InterestRates     06-02 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Interest Rates,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Banks Raise Base Rate to 8 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's major commercial banks, heeding a signal
from the Bank of England, announced they would raise their base
lending rate by half a percentage point to 8 percent.
   Barclays Bank PLC, Midland Bank PLC, National Westminster Bank
PLC and Lloyds Bank PLC said Thursday they would increase the
benchmark rate, effective Friday.
   The Bank of England, apparently responding to the slumping
British pound, sent its signal at noon local time by announcing it
would raise a key money-market intervention rate.
   The pound has fallen sharply against the dollar and the West
German mark in the last few days as the market's attention has
shifted away from sterling into the dollar and other major
currencies.
   The British base rate was last changed on May 17, when it was
cut to 7.5 percent from 8 percent as British authorities attempted
to estrain a strong rise in the pound.
   Corporate borrowers can obtain loans from commercial banks at
one percentage point above the base rate.
</TEXT>
