<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1524EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TexasAir 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Air, 1st Ld-Writethru,0721</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern, Continental Operated Safely, Feds Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and Continental Airlines are
being operated safely but labor turmoil at Eastern raises the risk
of safety problems there, an investigation by the Transportation
Department concluded today.
   The report said that a close inspection of Texas Air Corp., the
parent company of the two airlines, showed no serious management or
financial problems, but that labor strife at Eastern may have a
future impact on public safety.
   As a result of the continuing labor problems, the Federal
Aviation Administration planned to continue close scrutiny of
Eastern's operations and former Labor Secretary William Brock will
attempt to work with Eastern management and labor to ease tensions.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor told a news conference that ``an
unsafe condition does not currently exist'' at either Eastern or
Continental.
   But McArtor and Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley voiced
concerns that safety may be jeopardized at Eastern in the future by
the ``extreme labor-management tensions'' at the airline.
   Burnley said that the department's investigation of Texas Air
and its two major airline subsidiaries showed no safety problems at
Continental. It did, however, find a serious lack of communication
between labor and management at Eastern.
   The department also said it found no evidence that Texas Air
Corp.'s extensive financial losses last year posed any serious
financial problems, saying the company had adequate resources and
its management was found to be ``fit, willing and able'' to run an
airline.
   Burnley said that Brock's role will be to ``work for ways to
de-escalate the (labor-management) tensions'' at Eastern.
   Brock said he had been in contact with most of the parties
involved in the Eastern turmoil but that he had not yet developed a
game plan on how to ease those tensions.
   McArtor said that an in-depth, plane-by-plane inspection at both
Eastern and Continental had not shown anything that would warrant
extreme safety concerns.
   Frank Lorenzo, Texas Air's chairman, repeatedly has blamed labor
unons at Eastern Airlines for his two airlines' problems, accusing
the unions of waging a campaign against the airline to discredit
its safety record.
   The Transportation Department announced its two-pronged
investigation of Texas Air on April 13, including a plane-by-plane
examination of Eastern's aircraft by FAA inspectors. Five days
later the FAA safety inspection was broaded to include Continental
as well.
   In conjunction with the announcement of the investigation, the
FAA disclosed that it was proposing a $823,000 fine against Eastern
because of safety violations found in special reviews of the
Miami-based airline last year.
   During the 30-day inspections of Eastern and Continental, FAA
officials repeatedly examined each aircraft at airport gates to
determine if they were following federal air safety requirements.
   The separate probe of the parent company focused on possible
management and financial concerns. DOT investigators wanted to
determine if the executives of the Houston-based holding company
are ``fit, willing and able'' to operate an airline according to
federal aviation laws.
   There had been pressure from Congress for the department to open
an investigation of Texas Air in light of the company's huge
losses, including $466 million last year, and its continuing labor
turmoil at Eastern.
   A resolution calling for a such an investigation gained the
support of 150 congressmen.
   In announcing the special probe, officials cited a pattern of
safety violations at Eastern reflected by the latest $823,000 fine,
which came
   on top of a $9.5 million civil penalty from earlier Eastern
safety violations.
   The department also had raised concern about recent financial
transactions involving Texas Air and Eastern, including attempts by
the airline to spin off Eastern's lucrative Northeast shuttle. The
shuttle spinoff has been blocked by the courts.
   These transactions raised quetions about whether the managers of
Texas Air Corp., have complied with federal safety and economic
practices that are required of commercial air carriers under
federal aviation law, DOT officials said in April.
   Eastern Airlines and Continental Airlines are the key airlines
under Texas Air Corp. It also owns Rockey Mountain Airways, Britt
Airways, Bar Harbor Airlines and Provincetown-Boston Airlines. None
of the smaller carriers specifically was subject to the DOT or FAA
investigations.
</TEXT>
