<HEAD>Soybeans Soar; Grains Close Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS final graf to CORRECT direction of oats trading.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices surged Thursday on the
Chicago Board of Trade and grain futures posted moderate gains on
forecasts for continued warm, dry weather in the Midwest.
   The soybean market, already more sensitive than the grains to
weather factors because of tight-supply concerns, got an additional
boost from indications the Soviet Union had recently purchased more
than 1 million metric tons of soybean meal from South American
processors and was looking for more.
   ``There was tremendous strength coming out of the meal market,''
said Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research Department Inc. in
Chicago. ``I think the bean rally was due to the rally in meal more
than anything else.''
   Soybean meal futures posted near-limit gains with the contract
for delivery in July closing $7.30 higher at $253 a ton.
   The chances for widespread rains in the Corn Belt remained slim,
and the National Weather Service predicted below-normal rainfall in
most grain-producing areas for most of next week.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 3\ cents higher with July at
$3.51 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 3} cents higher with July
at $2.24{ a bushel; oats were 7\ cents to 8} cents higher with July
at $1.86{ a bushel; soybeans were .01 cent lower to 18\ cents
higher with July at $8.20 a bushel.
