<1ST_LINE>u f AM-IBMPCs     06-02 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM PCs,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Announces New Models Of PCs, Including Fastest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. fleshed
out its 14-month-old Personal System-2 line of personal computers
Thursday with reliable new models that include what would be the
world's fastest PC.
   But Compaq Computer Corp., IBM's top rival in speedy personal
computers, hinted it would strike back with one even faster that
would reach the market before IBM's. Compaq has scheduled a product
announcement for June 20.
   ``In the time frame that IBM has indicated they might deliver
their product, we will continue to have the highest performance
386-based machines in the marketplace,'' said Michael Swavely, vice
president for marketing at Houston-based Compaq.
   IBM said the fastest version of its new Model 70, to be
available in the July-September period, will be up to 50 percent
faster than the Model 80, its fastest currently available computer.
Its price will be $11,295.
   IBM also announced two other versions of the Model 70 available
immediately, starting at $5,995, and a version of its Model 50
starting at $3,995 that is up to 35 percent faster than the current
model.
   Also introduced was a version of the Model 25, the smallest and
cheapest member of the Personal System-2 family, that is designed
for use in office networks. Hard disk drives are also available for
the Model 25 for the first time. Those products are available this
month.
   IBM said the new computers are up to five times more reliable
than the original PC, introduced in 1981. It said its one-year
maintenance contract on a Model 60 is about $200 a year, compared
to the $600 to $800 a year charged by competitors for computers of
similar power.
   IBM reduced prices on the Model 60 and Model 80 by 5 to 18
percent to keep them in line with the improved new models. Analysts
are expecting announcements of improvements in those products in
coming months.
</TEXT>
