<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WestPoint-Pepperell     06-02 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-West Point-Pepperell,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textile Giant Strengthens Its Takeover Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. announced steps
to strengthen its ``poison pill'' takeover defense Thursday, a
little more than a week after it revealed plans by Farley Inc. to
purchase up to 25 percent of its common stock.
   The Georgia-based textile company announced that its board had
amended its share purchase rights plan, which allows existing
stockholders to purchase additional shares at reduced prices in the
event of a takeover bid. The plan is designed to make a hostile
takeover more expensive.
   Previously, the plan was effective when a person or group
acquired 20 percent or more of Pepperell's common stock or
announced a tender offer. Under the amendment, the threshold is 10
percent.
   Pepperell announced May 25 it had been notified of Farley's
filing with the Federal Trade Commission for permission to purchase
up to 25 percent of Pepperell's approximately 32 million
outstanding shares.
   Farley, a conglomerate privately owned by William F. Farley,
includes in its holdings Fruit of the Loom Inc., the underwear
manufacturer.
   Pepperell recently became the nation's largest publicly owned
textile company when it acquired J.P. Stevens & Co. in a joint
buyout with Odyssey Partners Inc.
   Pepperell officials declined to confirm Thursday's action was in
response to the Farley disclosure.
   But Patricia Ryan, a textile industry analyst with Raymond James
in St. Petersburg, Fla., said the directors probably took the
action to protect stockholders if Farley does buy a significant
portion of Pepperell stock.
   ``Apparently it's to dilute the ownership of the outside group
that's trying to buy stock,'' added Kay Norwood, a textile analyst
with Interstate Securities in Charlotte, N.C.
   In a statement issued by the company, Pepperell Chairman Joseph
L. Lanier Jr. said the amendment will expire in two years if the 10
percent threshold has not been crossed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
