<HEAD>Oil Company Sells Restaurants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OIL CITY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quaker State Corp., a major refiner of
engine lubricants, said Thursday it signed a definitive agreement
to sell its Western chain of 102 Arctic Circle restaurants to a
Pittsburgh-based investment fund.
   Quaker State acquired the restaurants in 1985 in order to get
Arctic Circle's chain of motor oil changing shops, which have been
renamed Quaker State Minute Lube Inc.
   The sale, for undisclosed terms to the Maverick Fund, was
planned before New York investors led by Ardshiel Inc. made an
unsolicited bid in April of $26.50 per share, or $675 million, for
the company, said Quaker State spokesman Benton H. Faulkner.
   ``Our position continues to be one of silence'' on the takeover
bid, Faulkner said.
