<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 1745EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     06-02 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Supply Up in Late May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's money supply rose in the week ended
May 23, the Federal Reserve Board reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose
to a seasonally adjusted $769.3 billion from a revised $768.1
billion the previous week.
   A broader measure of the money supply, M2, rose to a seasonally
adjusted $3.009 trillion from $3.003 trillion.
   An even broader measure, M3, increased to a seasonally adjusted
$3.782 trillion from $3.775 trillion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In setting its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M1 averaged $766.5 billion, a 5.5
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous
13 weeks.
   The Fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for
M2 and M3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly
lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent. The Fed
has not set a specific target range for M1 since early 1987.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks rose $96 million,
compared with a decline of $1.1 billion a week earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System averaged $776 million, up from $388 million.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $276.7 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, up from $275.6 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
