<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Polo-SEC     06-02 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polo-SEC,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Files Civil Action Against Roberto Polo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission sought a
court order Thursday to force high-living investment adviser
Roberto C. Polo to produce business records.
   The SEC action accused Polo, 37, and his Private Asset
Management Group Inc., a registered investment advising firm, of
failing to keep books and records as required by federal securities
law.
   The agency launched an investigation following published reports
last week that some of Polo's clients are suing him in state court,
alleging that he diverted $110 million from their accounts to
support a lavish lifestyle.
   The day after a May 26 Wall Street Journal article on the
lawsuits against Polo, federal officials went to check the books of
Private Asset Management at the Fifth Avenue address listed on
public documents as the firm's offices.
   Instead, they found Miguel Cruz International, a fashion design
firm owned by Polo, and were told the investment adviser business
had moved to Geneva, Switzerland ``sometime in 1986.''
   The manager of Miguel Cruz also told federal officials,
according to court papers, that all of the investment records had
been moved to Switzerland and that she and other Cruz employees had
not been paid in several months.
   In its civil complaint, filed at federal court in Manhattan, the
SEC claimed the withholding of books and records ``thwarted'' the
commission's efforts to check whether the law had been broken.
   In other court papers, Charles Padgett, associate regional
administrator for the SEC in New York, said the agency had been
unable to locate Polo or learn who his current attorney is.
   The front-page article in the Wall Street Journal described the
Cuban born Polo as a voracious art collector with an expensively
furnished apartment in Paris.
   According to the article, 13 of Polo's investors filed civil
suit in New York state court, claiming he diverted $110 million
from their accounts. A state court has barred him from disposing of
his assets, French authorities have seized the Paris apartment and
Swiss and French police are searching for Polo on financial fraud
charges in Switzerland.
</TEXT>
