<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Drugs-Lilly 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Lilly, 1st Ld-Writethru,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Company Still Considering Selling Herbicide for Drug War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead, 6th, 12th grafs to uppercase Spike to reflect
trade name; also moving general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eli Lilly & Co. has not ruled out a sale of
its herbicide ``Spike'' to the State Department for aerial spraying
of coca crops in Peru, a House subcommittee chairman said Thursday.
   Rep. Glenn English, whose House Government Operations panel is
reviewing the U.S. battle against illegal drugs, said the use of
the chemical is still possible even though Lilly has expressed
environmental and safety concerns.
   English, who spoke Wednesday to Lilly officials, did not repeat
his Wednesday statement that the Indianapolis-based corporation was
a ``deserter'' in the war on drugs.
   The Oklahoma Democrat used that critical description after Ann
B. Wrobleski, assistant secretary of state for international
narcotics matters, complained to the subcommittee that the company
refused to cooperate in the coca spraying program.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley also had said Lilly
apparently was worried about possible retaliatory measures by
``traffickers or terrorists.''
   Speaking at a hearing Thursday, English said Lilly officials
have objected to use of the chemical tebuthiuron, sold under the
name ``Spike,'' because ``they have not done the proper testing of
application by air over a wide section of countryside. They have no
data. They have not seen data from (the) State (Department), and
cannot assume responsibility or liability.''
   But he added, ``We will continue discussions. We need to acquire
a herbicide against coca bushes as quickly as possible. At this
point, my own perception is the door is open, discussions will
continue, and hopefully a solution can be found to this particular
problem.''
   Later, in an interview, English expanded his remarks to say
there had not been proper aerial testing in the coca producing
region of Peru, where the chemical would be sprayed. He said the
area has considerable groundwater, and therefore is much different
from the dry, brush areas where the herbicide is used in the United
States.
   English added that the company also was concerned that the coca
area in Peru ``may not be in friendly hands, and you may not have a
pilot totally concentrating on the accuracy of spraying.''
   Ted McKinney, a Lilly spokesman, had no immediate comment on
English's statement on Thursday.
   But he did say the chemical is applied both by air and on the
ground in the United States.
   He described ``Spike'' as ``a broad-spectrum, soil-applied
herbicide for brush and weed control on non-cropland, pasture and
rangeland.'' The herbicide is ``approved for use in grazing lands,
wildlife openings along ditchbanks, and utility rights of way. It
is safe for humans, livestock, wildlife and the environment when
used according to label directions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
