<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     06-02 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurer Postpones Announcement of Proxy Tally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Insurance Group Inc., which is
fighting a hostile $4.5 billion takeover offer by Batus Inc.,
postponed Thursday's scheduled announcement of the results of a
shareholder vote on the issue.
   Counting of the proxy vote taken at Farmers' annual meeting May
20 was incomplete, said Charles L. Schultz, senior vice president
for finance.
   The annual meeting was reconvened Thursday in the expectation of
announcing the count, then adjourned until June 10 when results are
expected to be available, Schultz said.
   The tally, conducted by Corporation Trust Co. of America, was
difficult because both sides in the protracted fight sent out
numerous statements seeking shareholders' permission to cast their
votes in proxy, he said. The counting firm, based in Delaware, has
yet to offer a preliminary count.
   ``It's not a surprise, it is simply a question of the mechanics
of making a count when the two sides are sending out repeated
mailings with repeated proxy cards,'' Schultz said. ``The counter
has to sort them out to see which is the latest.''
   The vote was on a resolution introduced by Louisville, Ky.-based
Batus urging Farmers' board to reconsider its opposition a
$63-a-share buyout offer.
   Farmers is the nation's third-ranking home and auto insurer and
seventh-largest property and casualty insurer.
   Batus, a tobacco, retailing and paper company whose best-known
operations include Kool cigarettes and Saks Fifth Avenue, is a
subsidiary of BAT Industries PLC, a British conglomerate.
</TEXT>
