<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankFailures 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Failures, 1st Ld-Writethru,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Regulators Shut Five Banks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 1st graf to clarify banks.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Over-extended lending and a slumping economy
forced regulators on Thursday to shut down three banks in Texas and
two in Colorado. Guaranty Bank of Dallas, Williamstown Bank N.A. of
Houston and River Plaza National Bank of Fort Worth were declared
insolvent, pushing the state's 1988 bank-failure tally to 32.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. was named receiver for the
three banks, all of which will open Friday after being assumed by
other banks, said FDIC spokesman Bill Olcheski. Depositors of the
failed banks automatically become depositors of the assuming banks.
   Guaranty had about $81.8 million in assets and will be acquired
by the Red Oak State Bank of Red Oak; Williamstown Bank had total
assets of about $23.6 million, and will reopen as a branch of City
National Bank of Houston, and River Plaza, which had assets of
$43.5 million and one office, will reopen Friday as a branch of
Tarrant Bank of Fort Worth.
   In Colorado, Security Bank of Boulder, with total assets of
$13.4 million, will be acquired by the First National Bank in
Boulder.
   The Security Bank of Aurora was taken over by Security Bank of
Colorado in Aurora, a newly chartered subsidiary of First United
Bancorporation Inc.
   They are the fourth and fifth banks to fail in Colorado.
   The failures bring the national total to 75 failed banks and 13
assistance transactions. Texas accounts for nearly half those
failures and both federal and state regulators are predicting that
the Lone Star total will reach 70 by year's end.
</TEXT>
