<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-88 2312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WritersStrike     06-02 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scriptwriters' Strike Tactic Ignites Old Feud With Directors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 21-year-old Hollywood feud between
scriptwriters and directors over who gets top credit for a movie is
flaring anew over a tactic writers are using in their bitter strike
against movie and TV producers.
   Negotiations between the writers' union and the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers, representing management,
were scheduled to resume Friday, following an unsuccessful
nine-hour session Wednesday.
   In making a separate labor peace with 80 small producers this
week, the Writers Guild of America used a contract that requires a
film be credited to the writer rather than the director.
   The Directors Guild of America on Thursday threatened legal
action against producers who sign the union's model contract, which
also allows writers to encroach on directors' prerogatives in
several other areas.
   The warning by the directors' guild, made in an advertisement
published in Hollywood trade journals, is the latest complication
in the writers' 13-week strike, which has already forced delays in
the start of fall television season.
   The writers' independent contract with small producers who have
broken ranks with the management group gives writers ``possessory
credit,'' the right to have their name associated with the film
title.
   Other objectionable provisions, said directors' spokesman Chuck
Warn, require ``meaningful consultation'' with the writer on choice
of director, actors and location, and give the writer a voice on
script changes made during filming.
   Warn declined to discuss possible legal action, other than to
say directors' lawyers were studying the matter. The unions fought
in court over possessory credit in 1967 and the directors won.
   Writers Guild spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden refused to comment on
the directors' threat or the possessory credit issue.
   ``It shows their demands are not realistic,'' Herb Steinberg, a
spokesman for the producers, said of the writers. ``They're just as
unrealistic when it comes to the residuals for one-hour shows and
foreign production,'' he continued, referring to the two main
issues in the strike.
   The independent producers who have signed independent contracts
with the union employ only about 100 of the union's 3,000 active
writers, Steinberg said.
   The Writers Guild called the strike March 7, largely because the
producers sought to reduce their compensation for reruns of
one-hour television shows. With the demand for reruns of one-hour
shows slipping, the producers sought to tie the writers' payments,
called residuals, to a show's success in reruns.
</TEXT>
