<HEAD>City Asks Court To Block Koppers Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City attorneys Thursday asked a U.S. District
Court to delay the $1.7 billion sale of Koppers Co. to an
investment group headed by British industrialist Brian Beazer.
   Beazer won a three-month battle to take over the construction
materials and chemicals company when Koppers agreed earlier this
week to be acquired for $61 a share by BNC Inc., a company he
formed with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and National Westminster
Bank PLC.
   In court papers filed Thursday, the city argued it should be
allowed time to review the latest findings in the case before an
injuction blocking the sale is lifted.
   Mayor Sophie Masloff sharply criticized Koppers, saying, ``I
think they sold us down the river.... I thought we had an agreement
with them that there wouldn't be a sellout yet, but apparently they
didn't pay any attention to that.''
   City officials said they are concerned about the fate of 1,150
employees the company has in the Pittsburgh area. All but 40 of
Koppers' local workforce is attached to chemicals operations Beazer
plans to sell.
   Allegheny County Commissioner Tom Foerster on Thursday asked the
city and the state to join the county in helping Koppers' employess
put together a plan to buy the company's chemical and allied
products operations from BNS Inc.
