<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices turned downward Thursday, giving up
some of their recent gains as interest rates rose.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 107.57 points
Tuesday and Wednesday, dropped back 11.56 to 2,052.45.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by slightly less than 3
to 2 in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed
stocks, with 614 up, 888 down and 476 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 193.54 million shares,
down from 234.56 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
222.89 million shares.
   Interest rates rose in the credit markets, reversing a sharp
decline Tuesday and Wednesday. Analysts also noted an increase in
British interest rates.
   That prompted many traders to sell stocks in order to cash in on
the gains of the past two sessions, brokers said.
   The upswing in stock prices since the start of the week was met
with considerable skepticism on Wall Street, given continued signs
of upward pressure on commodity prices.
   Futures prices for commodities ranging from soybeans to gold
climbed in Thursday's activity.
   Next on the market agenda is the Labor Department's monthly
report Friday on the employment situation. The figures will get a
close look from Wall Streeters watching for evidence of the pace of
economic activity.
   Burlington Northern gained 1} to 69[. The company reported plans
to sell a 13 percent interest in its Burlington Resources operation
to the public.
   Texaco fell 1} to 50|. Financier Carl Icahn said he would
probably sell his large stake in the company if he should lose his
bid to gain control of five seats on the board of directors.
   Other losers among the blue chips included American Telephone &
Telegraph, down } at 27; Exxon, down 1 at 44[; General Motors, down
| at 76\, and DuPont, down | at 84~.
   In the precious metals group, ASA Ltd. rose 1{ to 46[; Battle
Mountain Gold ~ to 18[; Hecla Mining 1] to 15}; Callahan Mining 2
to 19, and Sunshine Mining | to 4}.
   Elsewhere in the metals sector, Alcoa gained 1\ to 47}; Asarco
1\ to 26, and Phelps Dodge 1\ to 41~.
   Circus Circus, which reported higher quarterly profits, climbed
1| to 29|.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $6.39 billion, or 0.24
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .67 to 149.67.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell 1.68 to 306.36, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was down 1.36 at 265.33.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
slipped .16 to 374.65. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 299.08, up .79.
</TEXT>
